[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hello and welcome to the Chessable course about the Open Sicilians for White.   First, let me introduce myself. I'm GM Ivan Šarić, European Champion  (2018)  , World Champion U18  (2008)  , European Champion U18  (2007)  , multiple Croatian champion and regular top 100 player with current ELO of 2678  (peak ELO: 2703)  .   I have been playing 1. e4 whole my life, almost exclusively, and I have gathered a lot of experience which I'm going to present in this course. Many lines which are in this course have served me well during my chess career.   As the name suggests, this course is all about open and active play from White side, so you won't be seeing boring alternatives such as 3. Bb5, 3. b3, 3. g3 or whatever. Against the best Sicilians our answer is always the same: 3. d4! This is by far the most principled and critical move.    Short explanation of content Chapter 1: is about2...a6 O'Kelly variation. I'm suggesting the move 3. c3 because 3. d4 now doesn't work so well. The move 3. c3 had the best reputation for years and White had always enjoyed edge there.   When I started working on my course, this was my first task, which is one of the reasons why it is such a big chapter. I might have gone too much into the details, but I guess there is no harm in it. In the end, it was pointed out to me that its size even surpasses the Najdorf chapters.   Another reason is that after move 3. c3, Black has many different setups and plans which lead to all kinds of pawn structures which makes the whole 2...a6 variation unique. In other Sicilians you will most likely always see the same or similar pawn structures with similar plans.    2... Nf6 is another move that stops 3. d4, since Black attacks pawn on e4, but allows White to gain space with 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 which is covered inChapter 2.    In chapters3 and4 we are dealing with the 2...g6 systems which include the Accelerated Dragon. There I'm recommending the classical Maroczy setup with a few exceptions, such as castling queenside in some specific positions.  Then, we are finally moving towards three main moves 2...e6, 2...d6 and 2...Nc6. First, I'm covering 2...Nc6 3.d4 4.cxd4 Nxd4. Before going for the criticalKalashnikov andSveshnikov variations, inChapter 5 I'm showing you the way how to 'refute' 4...d5.   Chapter 6 is about the Grivas variation 2...Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6 5. Nb3 Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. Qe2 which is a smart way for White to castle queenside and go for the attack on the kingside.   We are continuing with the 2...Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 in chapters7 and8 by examining 4...e5 5. Nb5: Loewenthal and Kalashnikov variations. Against the Kalashnikov I'm going for the classical 6. Nc3.    Chapters9 and10 cover dubious lines for Black, such as the Pin variation 2...e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. e5 where White almost wins by force.    Then, we are finally examining the main Sicilians.Chapters 11-14 are about the Kan variation 2...e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6. I'm recommending 5. Bd3 which is usually followed by c4 against the hedgehog setups, and White castling kingside.    Chapter 15 covers the Paulsen variation with alternatives to the main Taimanov variation.   Against the Taimanov, inChapter 16 I'm recommending something completely different. It is universally accepted that 6. Be3 is the most critical setup against the Taimanov, but on move 7, White has many different choices: the classical 7. Qd2, the popular 7. Qf3, or the newest invention: 7. g4. However, I have something else in mind, the modest-looking 7. a3. White's idea is to castle queenside and to develop pieces as quickly as possible.      Chapter 17 is about the Keres variation where 6. g4 is kind of expected and secures White small advantage.    The currently and highly popular Four Knights variation is covered inChapter 18, and I believe that White's critical response is 6. Nxc6.     The Dragon defense is in Chapters19 and20. White should go for the queenside castling if he wants to achieve anything against the Dragon. There has always been theoretical discussion for White whether to play Bc4 before castling or to leave that bishop to f1. I prefer it on f1, not being a target for Black queenside pieces. In most of the cases, White has a slightly better endgame.    Chapter 21 is about some offbeat lines on move 5 for Black after 2...d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3. Black has big troubles in those lines and I wouldn't recommend them to anyone.    Against the Sveshnikov variation inChapter 22 I'm going for the 7. Nd5, currently the most popular move, and the one which doesn't give Black an easy play. Positions are extremely complicated, and both sides have their chances.     Chapter 23 is for the Rauzer variation which invites 6. Bg5. Most of the lines are well known, but against the main line, the move 10. Kb1 is kind of new. White is flexible about the f-pawn which can go to f3, but also to f4, depending on the Black's response.    Finally, we reach the finalChapter 24 which is reserved for the Najdorf variation. It has not been an easy task to recommend something against 'my own opening'. I decided for the most principled move 6. f3 which suits perfectly into our repertoire which is based on the English attack. In a few lines, Black is OK, but he needs to be heavily prepared just to equalize.    I highly recommend examining theReference Games andModel Games. This will help you understand the ideas furthermore.   I hope you will enjoy this Course and learn something new which will help you in your chess improvement!   GM Ivan Šarić }
