[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Katalimov: 2...b6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 b6
{ From all playable Sicilians this one gives White the easiest play. Black wants to fianchetto his bishop as soon as possible, but there are a few obvious drawbacks.   First, the 2...b6 move doesn't really fight for the centre, the pressure on the e4 is neglectable since White can easily defend the e4-pawn.   Secondly, when dealing against the kingside attack in Sicilian, Black always wants to create counterplay with b5-b4, which means that b7-b6 is practically a loss of tempo.   Finally, White has a couple of promising lines @@StartBracket@@6.Bg5, 6.Bf4, 6.g3, 6.Be3, 6.f3@@EndBracket@@ against it, but 6.Bg5 is the most concrete one. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7 5. Nc3 a6
{ Black has to play this move to cover b5 square. Now, White will already have 3 developed pieces compared to the single black one.   5...e6?!  6.Ndb5!  is the reason why you have to play a6 first. }
6. Bg5 { Stopping e6. } 6... Qc7
{ 6...Nf6  7.e5  creates only more troubles for Black;   6...h6  7.Bh4  doesn't help him much either. The bishop is no longer hanging on g5 in some lines and after Qc7 it can harass the black queen from g3. }
7. Nd5
{ Concrete play. White doesn't allow Black to play e6, and make some sort of Taimanov setup. }
7... Qe5 { Double attack. } 8. Be3 Bxd5
{ The only move, everything else loses.  8...e6?  9.Nf3  Qxe4  10.Nc7+  wins a rook. }
9. exd5 Qxd5 10. Be2 { Developing and creating a threat. } 10... e5
{ Black must react concretely.   10...Qb7?  11.Bf3  Nc6  12.Nxc6  dxc6  13.Qd4±  White will return one pawn and his two bishops are powerful and ideally placed. This secures him almost winning advantage. }
11. Nf5
{ Black has too many weaknesses, and White doesn't mind entering the endgame with the bishop pair. }
11... Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 g6 { Black will have to play this move sooner or later. }
13. Nd6+ { The knight shouldn't go backward. } 13... Bxd6 14. Rxd6 Nc6 15. O-O
{ Finishing the development. White is not hurrying to restore the material balance.   If Black goes for  15...Nge7  then  16.g4  , stopping any counterplay connected with Nf5.  For the purpose of the QuickStarter we end the line here; the variation is examined in more detail in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch: 2...Nf6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch variation, but it is more appropriate to call it the Rakhmanov variation since the Russian GM played a huge number of games in it, and proved that the variation itself is better than its reputation. }
3. e5
{ The most principled response. There is a seemingly easier option to play lazy  3.Nc3  and after  3...Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  transpose into the well known lines.   However, Black can play  3...d5  which is a completely independent line, but gives White a slight edge.   Surprisingly, after  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.d4  , Black can even deviate with  4...d5  where White has to enter the endgame with tripled pawns @@StartBracket@@he is pawn up@@EndBracket@@ in order to prove some advantage:  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.dxc5  Nxc3  7.Qxd8+  Nxd8  8.bxc3  f6  , etc.   To conclude, not only do I believe that 3. e5 is a better option, but also it requires less work and memorization. }
3... Nd5 4. Nc3 Nxc3
{ I guess the main reason why  4...e6  is more popular than  4...Nxc3  is because White players basically don't have to know any theory after 4...Nxc3 to gain an advantage. You can simply play normal developing moves and have a comfortable position.   After developing all the pieces, everything looks great for White. When you look at the position a bit deeper, you realize that White's pawn structure is almost fixed, and there isn't much to do about it. Then, the right problem arises for White: how to proceed? }
5. dxc3 Nc6 6. Bf4
{ White first develops the dark-squared bishop to stop any kind of d7- d5 @@StartBracket@@or d6@@EndBracket@@ ideas. }
6... e6 7. h4
{ This move is always useful for White who postpones his decision about where to put his queen and light-squared bishop. }
7... b6 8. Ng5
{ Pretending to attack the f7-pawn, but actually going for e4-square. } 8...
Qc7
{ 8...h6  9.Ne4  Bb7  10.Qg4  --  and  11.Nd6  followed by the intermediate move Qg7 is a threat. }
9. Qh5
{ Provoking g6 which creates a hook for h4-h5 and the f6 weakness as well. }
9... g6 10. Qf3 h6 11. Ne4 Nxe5 12. O-O-O
{ Smart move, stronger than  12.Nf6+  immediately. } 12... Bg7
{ 12...Nxf3?  13.Bxc7+-  and the knight is trapped. } 13. Nd6+
{ White can also continue attacking with  13.Qg3  , but text move is simpler. }
13... Qxd6 14. Qxa8 Qc7 15. Qe4
{ White won an exchange and Black knight is still pinned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "O'Kelly: 2...a6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6
{ Before stepping into the deep woods of Najdorf, Dragon, Sveshnikov, or Rauzer first we need to cover some less popular lines. It seemed natural for me to start from the left side @@StartBracket@@queenside@@EndBracket@@, and the first decent alternative to main Sicilians is the 2...a6.   The so-called O'Kelly variation has never been a popular choice in classical chess, but currently has a strong supporter, Russian GM Vladislav Artemiev. In the last few years, he has been playing it regularly, especially at the faster time controls.   The simplest explanation of this move would be that it makes 3.d4 ineffective. However, there are some hidden subtleties behind it. White has two good options, the first one is 3.c4, but in those pawn structures, a6 is always useful for Black. Therefore, I have always preferred c3 since it asks the question: how does 2...a6 fight for the centre? }
3. c3
{ Black again has a couple of options, the critical ones are 3...e6 and 3...d5, in my opinion, but 3...Nf6 and 3...g6 are not trivial.   Black's main idea is to counter  3.d4  with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  followed by Bb4 and/or d5 with comfortable equality. In case you forgot this trick or simply premove 3.d4 then I would advise you to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...cxd4  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  with the following plan: Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1 @@StartBracket@@h3@@EndBracket@@, etc.  Also, 4. c3 might be very interesting since White will get a favourable version of Morra gambit. }
3... d6 { Totally useless in combination with a6. } 4. d4 Nf6
{ 4...cxd4  5.cxd4  Nf6  6.Nc3±  White has full control of the centre. Bd3, h3, O-O are White next moves. }
5. dxc5
{ Possibly stronger than  5.Bd3  which also gives an advantage to White. } 5...
Nc6 6. Nbd2
{ 6.cxd6  Nxe4  is what Black wants, but I'm not even sure it works. } 6...
dxc5 7. e5 Nd5 8. Ne4 e6 9. Be2 { Simply developing pieces. } 9... Be7 10. c4
{ The knight doesn't have a good square after c4. } 10... Nb6 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8
12. Bf4
{ White has a much better endgame and a nice outpost on d6. His pieces are harmoniously placed. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "O'Kelly: 2...a6  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6 3. c3 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Bg4
{ Black wants to activate his bishop before playing e6. In his ideal scenario, he will manage to develop all his pieces: Nf6, e6, Nc6, Be7, and finally castle. However, White will not allow that. }
6. Be2 e6 7. O-O
{ White plays first the simplest moves, before deciding what to do in the centre. }
7... Nf6 8. h3
{ Before taking any concrete decisions it is always useful to include h3 because giving the bishop pair is not an option for Black. }
8... Bh5 9. c4
{ This move has been played rarely, mostly because White players didn't have the right follow-up.  9.Be3  has always been considered as slightly better for White. It is true, but I believe White can strive for more. }
9... Qd8 10. d5
{ The point of 9.c4 and the idea which can refute the whole 5...Bg4 concept. }
10... exd5 11. cxd5
{ If Black doesn't accept the pawn sacrifice he is worse, he lacks space and White d-pawn is strong. }
11... Qxd5 12. g4
{ 12.Re1  is also possible and should transpose, but I don't want to allow Bxf3 at some point although it doesn't help Black. }
12... Bg6 { 12...Qxd1  13.Bxd1  Bg6  14.Re1+  transposes. } 13. Re1 Qxd1 14.
Bxd1+
{ At first sight, it looks completely ridiculous why would White play like this. He gave up a pawn and has all pieces besides one knight on the first rank.   It is a temporary illusion because all those pieces in one move will acquire ideal squares. Even more surprising is that he has a dangerous attack.   For the purpose of the QuickStarter, we end the line here. The variation is analyzed in more detail in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Accelerated Dragon: 2...g6 3.d4 Bg7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 Bg7
{ I think this is the only 'Sicilian' where Black doesn't take on d4 which means this line is closer to Pirc/Modern setups. It can be reached via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  2.d4  Bg7  3.Nf3  c5  . }
4. dxc5 { Taking the free pawn. } 4... Qa5+
{ 4...Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  6.Bd3  keeps an extra pawn. } 5. c3 Qxc5
{ Black has to take the pawn, otherwise White plays b4. } 6. Na3
{ Key move which puts doubt on Black's opening concept. } 6... Nf6 7. Nb5
{ 7.e5  Ng4  8.Qd4  Qxd4  9.cxd4  is alternative which gives White slight advantage, but I believe that  7.Nb5  is stronger. }
7... b6 8. b4
{ All what White does in whole line is attacking Black pieces one by one. }
8... Qc6 9. e5 { Attacking again. } 9... Ne4
{ 9...Nh5  definitely not a square for a knight  10.g4  Bb7  11.Be2  and the knight drops.   9...Nd5?  10.Qxd5  with classical fork Nc7+ next. }
10. Nfd4 { And again. } 10... Qb7 11. Bd3 { 12. Qe2 and 12. Qf3 are threats. }
11... a6 12. Qe2
{ Creating a stronger threat. The knight from e4 has nowhere to go. } 12... Nc5
{ Only move. } 13. bxc5 axb5 14. Be4
{ Attacking again, all White moves starting from 7. Nb5 were attacking ones. }
14... Nc6 15. Qf3
{ 16. Nxc6 is an unstoppable threat and Black has to give up an exchange.   For the purpose of the QuickStarter, we end the line here; the variation is examined in more detail in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...e6 with 4...Nf6 5.Nc3 Bb4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ An old line, nowadays practically refuted by engines.   5...d5?  is too early because of  6.exd5  Nxd5  7.Bb5+!  Bd7  8.Nxd5  exd5  9.O-O  and Black will lose the d5-pawn soon. }
6. e5 Nd5 { The only move for Black. } 7. Bd2 Nxc3 8. bxc3
{ The bishop pair advantage is more valuable here than the doubled pawns. }
8... Be7
{ 8...Bc5  and  8...Ba5  don't make much sense after typical  9.Qg4  . } 9. Qg4
g6 { 9...Kf8  and  9...O-O  are examined in the course. } 10. h4 Nc6
{ 10...h5  11.Qg3  weakens the g6 square and improves white queen. } 11. Qg3
Nxd4 12. cxd4
{ White has better structure and better pieces, so Black tries to create concrete problems. }
12... Qb6 13. c3 { Protecting central pawns. } 13... Qb2 14. Rd1 Qxa2
{ The pawn shouldn't be relevant here, because black king will remain in the centre. }
15. Bd3 b6 16. O-O
{ White has a huge advantage in the development.  Once again, for the purpose of the QuickStarter we end the line here; the variation is examined in more detail in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...e6 - Four Knights: 4...Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Four knights defence. Black follows the basic opening principles and develops both his knights, before deciding where should queen go @@StartBracket@@d8, c7, b6 or sometimes even a5@@EndBracket@@ and dark squared bishop @@StartBracket@@e7, c5 or b4@@EndBracket@@.   Without wasting time on playing a7-a6 Black is already prepared to strike in the centre with move d7-d5 with possible inclusion of the move Bb4. Currently, this variation is highly popular, played by majority of the top players, and some Sveshnikov players use it as alternative @@StartBracket@@for some players it is even first choice@@EndBracket@@ way of reaching the Sveshnikov.   After  6.Ndb5  d6  7.Bf4  e5  8.Bg5  Black has avoided numerous Rossolimo lines and the trendy 7. Nd5 variation which is also my recommendation against Sveshnikov. Therefore, instead of 6. Ndb5 we must choose the another principled @@StartBracket@@and probably the best@@EndBracket@@ move, 6. Nxc6. }
6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Practically, the forced recapture. Taking with other pawn leads to bad endgame for Black.  6...dxc6  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  8.e5  Nd5  9.Ne4  followed by Bd2, c4 and O-O-O gives White nice edge thanks to the spatial advantage, and bad light-squared bishop in Black's camp. }
7. e5
{ The point of Nxc6, playing quickly e5. That pawn will trouble Black in many lines. You will see that most of White moves are based on chasing black knight which won't be safe on d5. }
7... Nd5 8. Ne4
{ The d6 is the weakest square in Black's position, and knight from e4 controls it nicely. This move also creates a threat of playing c2-c4. Now, Black has couple of different moves to choose, two of them are having solid reputation.   First one is  8...Bb7  which leads to a slightly inferior but defendable endgame, and another one is the main move  8...Qc7  . }
8... Qc7 { The main move. Before playing Qb6 Black weakens the e3 square. } 9.
f4 { Forced, the pawn must be protected. } 9... Qb6
{ With the inclusion of the move Qc7 Black has provoked weakening of the g1-a7 diagonal and secured the e3 square for his knight. }
10. c4
{ Attacking the knight. Black is at the crossroads now:  10...Bb4+  or  10...Ne3  . }
10... Bb4+ { The main move, and currently more popular than the  10...Ne3  . }
11. Ke2 { Forced reply. Otherwise, White loses material. } 11... f5
{ Practically, the only move for Black. } 12. exf6
{ White has two equally good moves:  12.Nf2  and  12.exf6  . It is hard to say which one is better, but the text move helps White to develop pieces quicker. }
12... Nxf6 13. Be3 Qa5 14. Nxf6+
{ Only good move for White, but gives more than enough advantage. } 14... gxf6
15. Kf2 { Gives White a nice edge. His king is safe on f2 unlike black one. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...e6 - Paulsen: 4...Nc6 5. Nc3 Bc5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ The most natural move in the current position. Black develops the knight and attacks the d4 square. }
5. Nc3
{ First the knights, the bishops afterwards. There are three major lines for Black here:   a@@EndBracket@@  5...a6  ,  b@@EndBracket@@  5...Nf6  theFour Knights variation and  c@@EndBracket@@  5...Qc7  theTaimanov variation, and some minor moves. }
5... Bc5 { The first 'minor' move. } 6. Nb3
{ 6.Ndb5  Nf6  is a common variation that occurs from the 4 Knights variation @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Ndb5  Bc5  . Since I'm not recommending 6. Ndb5 there, I would like to avoid that variation.   In case of  6.Be3  Qb6  is the point, with a messy position. The recommended move attacks the bishop with tempo and immediately asks questions. }
6... Bb4 7. Qg4
{ The most principled move, attacking the weakness.   It is possible to play simply  7.Bd3  Nge7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Qh5  and White should have an advantage here. }
7... Qf6
{ This was played in some games, the queen doesn't belong on the f6 square.   7...Nf6  , a novelty and the best move for Black, is taken in exams in Chapter 15, startingfrom here. }
8. Bd2 Qg6 9. Qe2
{ 9.Qg3  is also good, but it is a pity to trade such a misplaced queen. } 9...
Nf6 10. f3 O-O 11. a3
{ White is much better. The queen on g6 is a target for White's pieces. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...e6 - Paulsen: 4...Nc6 5. Nc3 a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3
{ First the knights, the bishops afterwards. There are three major lines for Black here:   a@@EndBracket@@  5...a6  ,  b@@EndBracket@@  5...Nf6  theFour Knights variation and  c@@EndBracket@@  5...Qc7  theTaimanov variation, and some minor moves. }
5... a6
{ To understand this move, you have to know what's happening after  5...Qc7  . In that case White can play  6.Be3  and choose English attack systems which were quite unpleasant for Black.   Here, the difference in case of  6.Be3  Nf6  7.Qd2  Bb4  8.f3  is  7...d5  or even  7...e5  with the idea to play d5 after Nf5. }
6. a3
{ 6.Nxc6  has always been considered as the most principled reaction against the 5... a6 variation. In general, I believe that White's chances are better in the aforementioned line, but it is very far from simple.   Therefore, I am proposing a much simpler solution. The main point behind the move  6.a3  is that Black doesn't have anything better than playing  6...Qc7  and transposing to the Taimanov variation }
6... d6 { Going for the Scheveningen setup. } 7. g4
{ Black doesn't create any pressure in the centre, so White can carelessly expand on the kingside. }
7... Nge7
{ The knight on f6 would invite g5, and it makes more sense for Black to play Nge7. Or  7...Nxd4  8.Qxd4  Ne7  . }
8. Be3 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Nc6 10. Qd2 b5
{ Black did everything that he wanted, however, it is still not good enough for equality. }
11. g5 { Gaining space and escaping Ne5 with tempo. } 11... Qa5 12. Rd1
{ The most flexible move. White will castle kingside but still hasn't decided which pawns he will push first @@StartBracket@@h or f@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Ne5 13. Be2 { We will not blunder the queen. } 13... Qc7 14. f4 Nc4 15.
Bxc4 Qxc4 16. f5
{ Should be better for White, Black has only one developed piece. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...e6 - Taimanov: 4...Nc6 5.Nc3 Qc7 with 7...b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ The Taimanov variation. Slightly more flexible than  5...a6  .   Black is not afraid of  6.Ndb5  because of  6...Qb8  and a6 on the next move. In some lines Black can even play without a6 @@StartBracket@@Nf6 and quickly Bb4@@EndBracket@@.   This move also makes  6.Nxc6  harmless. }
6. Be3 { White develops the bishop and prepares for the English attack. } 6...
a6 7. a3
{ Semi-waiting move which is not the most popular reaction against the Taimanov variation, but full of venom and very practical. It avoids tons of variations. The most popular moves are classical  7.Qf3  and  7.Qd2  with English attack setup.   The problem of  7.Qd2  line is that Black has found a good antidote almost a decade ago and White still hasn't found the way to pose Black big problems.   Currently, the 'main' move  7.Qf3  , is the most aggressive option for White. However, this move has already been covered in some books and also Chessable courses, and I don't want to repeat the same recommendations from the other authors. }
7... b5
{ Current state of the theory says that this is the best move for Black and it is a recommendation of Harikrishna in his Taimanov course. }
8. Nxc6
{ When the bishop is on c8, and Black no longer has a possibility of taking with b-pawn on c6, it is the right time to capture on c6. Now, Black has to make a decision, to capture with a pawn or with a queen. }
8... Qxc6 { In the spirit of the Taimanov. } 9. Bd3
{ The bishop on d3 guards biggest weaknesses in White's camp, the pawns on c2 and e4. }
9... Bb7 10. Qd2
{ Playing simple moves. White wants to castle queenside. Here, Black has many different setups.  10...Nf6  runs into the  11.e5  Ng4  12.Bd4  , so Black must develop his kingside accurately. }
10... Be7
{ 10...Qc7  11.Bf4!  e5  12.Bg3  this will most likely transpose to the main line  12...Nf6  13.O-O-O  Be7  14.Kb1  O-O  15.f4  . }
11. O-O-O Qc7 { Preparing Nf6 and b4 simultaneously. } 12. Bf4 e5
{ In case of  12...Qb6  Black has to consider  13.Bxb5  and wild complications afterward. Everything is purely tactical, and it is hard for me to explain all the moves. }
13. Bg3
{ White lost some time with this maneouvre, but has provoked e6-e5 which gave him the d5-square. }
13... Nf6 14. Kb1 { The usual move. } 14... O-O 15. f4 d6 16. Rhe1
{ Including last piece into the play. } 16... Rad8 17. Nd5
{ Gives White an advantage. His pieces are ideally placed. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...e6 - Taimanov: 4...Nc6 5.Nc3 Qc7 with 7...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ The Taimanov variation. Slightly more flexible than  5...a6  .   Black is not afraid of  6.Ndb5  because of  6...Qb8  and a6 on the next move. In some lines Black can even play without a6 @@StartBracket@@Nf6 and quickly Bb4@@EndBracket@@.   This move also makes  6.Nxc6  harmless. }
6. Be3 { White develops the bishop and prepares for the English attack. } 6...
a6 7. a3
{ A semi-waiting move which is not the most popular reaction against the Taimanov variation, but full of venom and very practical. It avoids tons of variations. The most popular moves are the classical  7.Qf3  and  7.Qd2  with the English attack setup.   The problem of the  7.Qd2  line is that Black has found a good antidote almost a decade ago and White still hasn't found the way to pose Black big problems.   Currently, the 'main' move  7.Qf3  , is the most aggressive option for White. However, this move has already been covered in some books and also Chessable courses, and I don't want to repeat the same recommendations from the other authors. }
7... Nf6 { A natural move which allows White to show his idea. } 8. f4
{ More powerful than  8.f3  . Instead of playing in the English attack style @@StartBracket@@f3, Qd2, O-O-O, g4...@@EndBracket@@ White aims for the more aggressive setup with a pawn on f4, queen on f3, followed by O-O-O and g4. }
8... d6
{ Forcing Black to Scheveningen setups can be considered as a small success for White, especially when he has a possibility to castle queenside. The problem for Black is that he has to stop the move e5, and everything else is worse. }
9. Qf3 { The queen on f3 guards all White pawns on the fourth rank. } 9... Be7
10. O-O-O O-O { Last few moves were natural and easy to understand. } 11. Nxc6
{ White would love to play  11.g4  but this runs into  11...Nxd4  followed by 12... e5 and the pawn on g4 is hanging. Therefore, White gives Black the b-file, but in return advances his kingside pawns faster. }
11... bxc6
{ Black has an open b-file but it turns out that White's attack is faster. }
12. g4 d5
{ It is very logical to open up the bishop and the queen. Black can start with  12...Rb8  first, but at some point, he will have to play d5. }
13. g5 Nd7 14. h4
{ Pushing pawns. After  14...Rb8  15.h5  Qa5  Bf2  , to defend along the third rank, both sides will try to build an attack. For the purpose of the QuickStarter we end the line here; the variation is examined in more detail in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Kan Sicilian: 5...Qb6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps knight from b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterwards.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White best choices are positional  5.c4  and concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3 Qb6
{ Against all opening principles, Black still hasn't developed any light piece. }
6. Be3
{ Voluntarily offering the b2 pawn. The only problem White could have in this line is that he needs to remember many forced variations. If you succeed, in return you should get a winning position. }
6... Qxb2
{ If Black wants to take that pawn, he should take it as soon as possible. } 7.
Nd2 Qc3 8. O-O Qc7
{ Black must return the queen to a safe place to cover all the weaknesses. } 9.
e5 { Another 'pawn sacrifice' which prevents Black from developing. } 9... d6
10. f4 dxe5 11. fxe5 { Now the f-file is open. } 11... Qxe5
{ Black's best chance is to take as much as material possible. } 12. Nc4 Qc7
13. Rb1
{ White includes the last piece into the game.   Now  13...b5  , as you can see in Chapter 11, loses immediately after  14.Qf3!  bxc4  15.Nxe6!  Bxe6  16.Qxa8  .   While  13...Bc5  14.Qg4!?  is examined in more detail in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Kan Sicilian: 5...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps knight from b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterwards.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White best choices are positional  5.c4  and concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3 Nc6
{ Black challenges knight on d4 and practically forces White to trade knights. }
6. Nxc6 dxc6
{ This can be evaluated as a slightly safer but more passive option than bxc6. Black chooses the symmetrical pawn structure to fight for an equality, but his problem is lag in development. }
7. Bf4
{ Very interesting idea stands behind this move, unfairly neglected by top grandmasters. It is common knowledge that  7.Nd2  or  7.O-O  lead to slightly better positions for White, but the move  7.Bf4  is more ambitious and direct.   Obviously, White's idea is to stop e6-e5. If he succeeds, he will have a big advantage. Black can prepare e6-e5 with Ne7-Ng6 or Qf6. However, both these moves are responded in the same manner, White retreats bishop to e3 and says that Black no longer can put knight to his ideal square f6. }
7... Qf6 { Double attack, seems like the most natural move. } 8. Be3
{ In case of  8.Qc1  Black gets comfortable position after  8...e5  . } 8... e5
{ was played twice in the only games we have after 8. Be3. } 9. Nd2 Be6 10. O-O
Bd6 11. Nc4 { Now we can see why Black should have a queen on d8. } 11... Bc7
12. Bc5 { Preparing Nd6. } 12... Rd8 13. Qe1
{ Unpinning and eyeing the queenside. } 13... Bxc4 14. Bxc4 Bd6 15. Bb6
{ White has two bishops advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Kan Sicilian: 5...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps knight from b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterwards.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White best choices are positional  5.c4  and concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3 Nf6 6. O-O Qc7
{ The most flexible move for Black. His queen belongs to c7 in almost every line, but he waits a bit before playing d6.   6...Be7?!  7.e5  Nd5  8.Qg4  and Black must weaken his kingside.   6...Nc6?!  7.Nxc6  dxc6  8.e5  is the type of the position which Black should avoid at all costs.   6...Qb6  7.Be3!  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qb6  6.Be3  . }
7. Qe2 d6 8. c4 g6
{ With white queen on e2 the fianchetto makes more sense since Black can immediately put pressure on the d4 knight, and White is not really targeting pawn on d6. }
9. Nc3 Bg7 10. Be3
{ The simplest possible way for White to play. Plan is to put rooks on c1 an d1, fortify pawn on e4 with f3, and then decide. }
10... O-O 11. Rac1 Nbd7 { Going for the classical hedgehog setup. } 12. Rfd1 b6
13. f3 Bb7
{ Up to here it was easy. Here, White has couple of interesting plans. } 14.
Qf2 { Eyeing the pawn on b6. } 14... Rac8
{ 14...Ne5  15.Bf1  , and the pawn on c4 is untouchable. } 15. Bf1
{ The best square for the bishop in this structure. } 15... Qb8 16. b4
{ Getting c5 square under control. White plays on the queenside in this type of the hedgehog. }
16... Rfe8 17. Nb3
{ Targeting black pawns.   If Black continues with  17...d5!?  then after  18.exd5  exd5  19.c5  bxc5  20.bxc5  the pawn on  c5  is stronger than the pawn on  d5  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Kan Sicilian: 5...Bc5 and 6...Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps knight from b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterwards.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White best choices are positional  5.c4  and concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3 Bc5
{ We have reached the final chapters of the Kan variation in which we are covering the most natural and logical move for Black after 5. Bd3, 5...Bc5.   The drawback of 5. Bd3 is that it leaves knight unprotected on d4, and with his last move Black asks some questions. }
6. Nb3
{ The knight goes from the centre because time is more important to White. }
6... Be7
{ Black has two good squares to retreat the bishop, to e7, the classical one or to more active a7 which is part of the next chapter. }
7. Qg4 { Important move, provokes weakening of the black kingside. } 7... Bf6
{ I never believed in such moves. Playing twice with the bishop early in the opening without developing the knights. Other reason is even more obvious, the bishop doesn't belong to f6, that is the square for the knight. }
8. f4 d6 9. Nc3 { White develops pieces in the most natural way. } 9... Nc6 10.
Be3
{ White should go for the most aggressive setup. I'm not impressed by the position of the black dark-squared bishop. }
10... Nge7 11. O-O-O
{ We have finished developing, and move e5 is in the air.   After  11...Qc7  12.Kb1  Bxc3  13.bxc3  O-O  14.Qh5  White targets Black's weakest point, the  h7  pawn.  For the purpose of the QuickStarter we end the line here; the variation is examined in more detail in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Kan Sicilian: 5...Bc5 and 6...Ba7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps knight from b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterwards.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White best choices are positional  5.c4  and concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3 Bc5 6. Nb3 Ba7
{ Placing bishop on a7 is more active reply from Black. The first visible plus for Black is that after  7.Qg4  Nf6  is now completely different compared to the Be7 since pawn on f2 will hang in many variations. }
7. Qe2
{ White sometimes plays  7.O-O  Nc6  8.Qg4  and grabs a pawn on g7, but I believe that  7.Qe2  is a simpler and safer solution. The idea is to trade dark-squared bishops and have some pressure on the d6 pawn in the middlegame. Also, White can in some lines even castle queenside. }
7... Nc6 8. Be3 { The bishop on a7 needs to be exchanged. } 8... d6
{ In general Black has a choice, to take on e3, or to let White to take on a7. The latter one gives him few more possibilities. }
9. O-O
{ Once Black has played d6, and no longer can play d7-d5, White can castle kingside. In the mentioned case White plan is to play c4 and Nc3 to control the centre.   In case of  9.Nc3  Black should play  9...b5!  with the idea b4. }
9... Nf6
{ Developing knight to the most natural square.   9...Bxe3  10.Qxe3  Nf6  11.c4  O-O  12.Nc3  will transpose to  9...Nf6  10.c4  O-O  . }
10. c4
{ Before playing Nc3 White gains some space, and prevents Black from playing d5. }
10... O-O { Black can try to play without e6-e5. } 11. Nc3 Bxe3 12. Qxe3 b6 13.
Rad1 Qc7 14. Be2
{ White has a spatial advantage and can harass black pawns. We end the line here; the variation is examined in more detail in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Accelerated Dragon: Maroczy Bind 5.c4 Bg7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ 2...g6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Bg7  5.c4  doesn't have independent value   5...Qb6  6.Nb3  Nc6  7.Be3  is the position we will reach via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  g6  5.c4  Bg7  6.Be3  Qb6  7.Nb3  .  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  O-O  7.Be2  d6  8.O-O  transposes to the main line of the Maroczy Bind. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ This move represents the starting position for the Accelerated Dragon. Compared to the classical Dragon, Black restricts the most critical possibilities for White. For example, the line which I'm recommending against the Dragon @@StartBracket@@White castling queenside and avoiding to play Bc4@@EndBracket@@.   First big decision for White. After  4...g6  White can choose to play ambitious  5.Nc3  and enter into the lines of Accelerated Dragon, and Dragon or play  5.c4  which is more positional choice.  In the repertoire which I'm recommending playing  5.Nc3  doesn't fit into our plans because against Dragon my choice is O-O-O without Bc4. Also, I believe that Maroczy type of positions are constant suffering for Black, and suit less to players who are comfortable with wild Dragon type positions. }
5. c4
{ We are entering into one of the most known structures in chess, named after Hungarian master Geza Maroczy. Before developing knight on c3, White plays c4, obtains more space and with pawns on e4 and c4 in long run prevents Black from playing d5.   Black has Dragon / KID setup which is characterized by g6, Bg7, Nf6, Nc6, d6, O-O often with Bd7, Qa5 to follow. In general, White has an easier play because Black always has to find ways to create counterplay to avoid passive position. }
5... Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 Ng4
{ Black uses small tactics to exchange pair of the knights and open up the long diagonal.   7...d6  8.Be2  O-O  9.O-O  is a transposition. }
8. Qxg4
{ Forced response from White.  8.Nxc6?  is bad after  8...Nxe3  when Black obtains a strong bishop pair advantage. }
8... Nxd4 9. Qd1
{ This has been known for ages as a right response against 7... Ng4 line. Here, Black is again at the crossroads: to retreat the knight or to fortify it with e5 but give d5-square. }
9... e5
{ This is recommendation in one of the most recent books about Accelerated Dragon. I honestly don't believe this setup can bring full equality to Black because of the weak d5 square which Black can't compensate with his knight on d4.   The difference is that White can get rid of d4-knight, while Black can't solve the problem of the d5-square and weakness on d6. On the other hand 9... e5 seems like the best option for Black in current situation. }
10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O d6 12. Qd2 { Playing simple and natural moves. } 12... Be6
13. b3
{ Here Black has couple of possible moves  13...a6  ,  13...Rc8  ,  13...Qa5  , but most likely they will transpose to each other. }
13... a6 14. Rfd1 Rc8 15. Rac1 Qa5 16. h3
{ White keeps slight edge because of the d5-square. Qb2 is possible follow up, and also Nd5 or Ne2 could come into consideration.   16...Bxh3?  is boomerang tactics after  17.Nd5  Qxd2  18.Rxd2  when White wins exchange. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Accelerated Dragon: Maroczy Bind 5.c4 Nf6 with 7...Nxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ This move represents the starting position for the Accelerated Dragon. Compared to the classical Dragon, Black restricts the most critical possibilities for White. For example, the line which I'm recommending against the Dragon @@StartBracket@@White castling queenside and avoiding to play Bc4@@EndBracket@@.   First big decision for White. After  4...g6  White can choose to play ambitious  5.Nc3  and enter into the lines of Accelerated Dragon, and Dragon or play  5.c4  which is more positional choice.  In the repertoire which I'm recommending playing  5.Nc3  doesn't fit into our plans because against Dragon my choice is O-O-O without Bc4. Also, I believe that Maroczy type of positions are constant suffering for Black, and suit less to players who are comfortable with wild Dragon type positions. }
5. c4
{ We are entering into one of the most known structures in chess, named after Hungarian master Geza Maroczy. Before developing knight on c3, White plays c4, obtains more space and with pawns on e4 and c4 in long run prevents Black from playing d5.   Black has Dragon / KID setup which is characterized by g6, Bg7, Nf6, Nc6, d6, O-O often with Bd7, Qa5 to follow. In general, White has an easier play because Black always has to find ways to create counterplay to avoid passive position. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 d6
{ The best move order for Black. First, it stops  7.Be3  because of  7...Ng4  . So, White can play either 7. Be2 or 7. f3.   After  7.Be2  Nxd4!  8.Qxd4  Bg7  9.Be3  @@StartBracket@@or 9.Bg5@@EndBracket@@  9...O-O  10.Qd2  a5  Black will manage to play a4, Qa5, Be6, Rfc8, a well known plan which gives him an easy play.   On the other hand when White plays  7.f3  he will no longer have flexibility to play h3 at some point, but since I'm choosing f3 in the main line anyway this doesn't concern us much. }
7. f3 Nxd4
{ Black takes on d4 immediately, forcing White to recapture with queen. } 8.
Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 { Queen must return, Ng4 was a threat. } 10... Be6
11. Rc1 { Typical Maroczy move, rook is escaping from the long diagonal. }
11... Qa5 12. b3
{ Setup which is quite easy to remember. Pieces on dark squares form an 'X' and pawns are on the light squares. }
12... Rfc8
{ Black is preparing to anticipate Nd5 and possible opening of the c-file.  12...a6  invites  13.Nd5  . }
13. Bd3
{ Compared to the  13.Be2  which has more than thousand games in the database, this is a rarely played move. I believe it is not inferior to 13. Be2. The idea is simply to jump Nd5 in the next move and after exchanges on d5 bishop is more active on d3. }
13... a6 14. Nd5
{ Forcing an endgame.   For the purpose of the QuickStarter, we end the line here; the variation is examined in more detail in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
