1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ This move represents the starting position for the Accelerated Dragon. Compared to the classical Dragon, Black restricts the most critical possibilities for White. For example, the line which I'm recommending against the Dragon @@StartBracket@@White castling queenside and avoiding to play Bc4@@EndBracket@@.   First big decision for White. After  4...g6  White can choose to play ambitious  5.Nc3  and enter into the lines of Accelerated Dragon, and Dragon or play  5.c4  which is more positional choice.  In the repertoire which I'm recommending playing  5.Nc3  doesn't fit into our plans because against Dragon my choice is O-O-O without Bc4. Also, I believe that Maroczy type of positions are constant suffering for Black, and suit less to players who are comfortable with wild Dragon type positions. }
5. c4
{ We are entering into one of the most known structures in chess, named after Hungarian master Geza Maroczy. Before developing knight on c3, White plays c4, obtains more space and with pawns on e4 and c4 in long run prevents Black from playing d5.   Black has Dragon / KID setup which is characterized by g6, Bg7, Nf6, Nc6, d6, O-O often with Bd7, Qa5 to follow. In general, White has an easier play because Black always has to find ways to create counterplay to avoid passive position. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 d6
{ The best move order for Black. First, it stops  7.Be3  because of Ng4. So, White can play either  7.Be2  or  7.f3  .   After  7.Be2  Nxd4!  8.Qxd4  Bg7  9.Be3   or  9.Bg5  9...O-O  10.Qd2  a5  Black will manage to play a4, Qa5, Be6, Rfc8, a well known plan which gives him an easy play.   On the other hand when White plays  7.f3  he will no longer have flexibility to play h3 at some point, but since I'm choosing f3 in the main line anyway this doesn't concern us much. }
7. f3 Bg7 8. Be3 O-O 9. Be2
{ This position can be reach via move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  g6  5.c4  Bg7  6.Be3  Nf6  7.Nc3  O-O  8.Be2  d6  9.f3  . }
9... Bd7 10. Qd2
{ This is a move White has to play anyway, but unlike  10.O-O  , White is flexible about castling. }
10... Nxd4
{ The most typical way for Black to handle this position.   10...Rc8  11.O-O  playing Rc8 early reduces Black possibilities. }
11. Bxd4 a5
{ 11...Bc6  is usually played against O-O together with a5 and Nd7. Here it is premature. }
12. h4 { White plays on 'his' side. } 12... a4 { Allows h5. } 13. h5 Qa5
{ Taking the pawn on h5 usually leads to checkmate:  13...Nxh5?  14.Bxg7  Kxg7  15.g4  followed by 16. Qh6+ and 17. Nd5 wins on the spot. }
14. h6
{ Positional decision.  14.g4  is also possible for those who like to attack. }
14... Bh8 15. O-O-O
{ White can aim for a better endgame with Kb1 and Nd5 thanks to the strong pawn on h6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...Nc6 - Grivas Sicilian"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6
{ The Grivas variation. Personally, I'm always happy to see my opponent making an early queen move. Black wants to play some sort of classical Sicilian setup @@StartBracket@@d6, e6, a6 - b5, Nf6 - Nd7, Nc6, Be7, Qc7@@EndBracket@@.   Before placing queen to c7 he provokes Nb3, dragging our knight from the centre. This, however is not that bad for White at all. Just to make my point I will mention that against Najdorf, move 6. Nb3 became popular recently. }
5. Nb3 Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. Qe2
{ Since classical English attack setup @@StartBracket@@Be3, Qd2@@EndBracket@@ runs into Bb4 followed by quick d5 White has to be more subtle. The text move is known as the right antidote to the Qb6 line. White is preparing to play e5. }
7... d6 { Black goes for the classical setup. } 8. g4 a6
{ 8...Be7  9.g5  Nd7  10.Be3  Qc7  11.O-O-O  a6  12.f4  transposes. } 9. Be3
Qc7 10. g5 { White moves are simple and good. } 10... Nd7 11. O-O-O b5 12. f4
{ Here Black has couple of different plans, but none of them gives him enough counterplay for equality. I've realized that Black should keep his bishop on c8 to keep pawn on e6 protected and his best chance to create some counterplay should be connected with b4-Rb8 etc.   Actually, it would even make some sense to stop my analysis here because White has so many different promising plans and moves that it was hard for me to pick one.   However, you can explore the lines I've analyzed in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...Nc6 - Loewenthal: 4...e5 5. Nb5 a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 a6
{ Black claims that White has played too many moves in the early stage with his knight and he doesn't care if his bishop from f8 gets traded. In return for bishop pair Black gets development advantage.   Other reasonable moves are  5...d6  which is covered in the next chapter, Kalashnikov variation, and  5...Nf6  6.N1c3  isSveshnikov variation. }
6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6
{ Black has couple of choices, but only two of them are playable:  7...Qf6  or  7...Qe7  . Everything else is clearly worse for Black. }
7... Qf6 8. Qd2
{ My initial idea was  8.Qd1  , but the variation becomes just too long and complex.  8.Qd2  is much simpler solution. White indeed blocks bishop from c1, but his plan is to play b3-Bb2 and O-O-O and queens on d2 fits perfectly there.   8.Qxf6  Exchanging queens is another simple possibility and leads  to quiet endgame where White puts his hopes into bishop pair, while Black  parries it with harmonious piece setup. I believe Black can hold that position  without much worries.  8...Nxf6  9.Nc3  Nb4  10.Kd2  d6  11.a3  Nc6  12.Ke1  Be6  13.f3  Ke7  14.Be3  Rhc8  . }
8... Nge7 { 8...d6  9.Nc3  Nge7  10.b3  has no independent value. } 9. Nc3 d6
{ The most natural move. } 10. b3
{ White continues with his plan. Slow play usually favours the side with bishop pair. }
10... O-O 11. Bb2 Be6
{ We were following Leko - Vallejo Pons, Linares 2005. Now the most natural and logical move seems to be: }
12. O-O-O Rac8 13. f3
{ White shouldn't hurry with Kb1 because it gives Black possibility of playing d5 because rook on d1 becomes unprotected. }
13... Rfd8 { Black wants to play d5, so next move is practically forced. } 14.
Nd5 Bxd5 15. exd5 Nb8 16. Kb1
{ White is much better due to his bishop pair. One thing in which bishops are particularly better than knights are the positions with opposite side castling. Bishops can at the same time attack and defend while knights don't have that possibility. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...Nc6 - Kalashnikov: 7...Be6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6
{ The Kalashnikov variation. Younger brother of the more popular Sveshnikov. Black is flexible about move Nf6 since he doesn't want to get pinned with Bg5 @@StartBracket@@which happens in Svehnikov@@EndBracket@@. This however has some drawbacks, obvious one is that it allows Nd5 jump. }
6. N1c3
{ 6.c4  is another way to deal with Kalashnikov, but  6.N1c3  fits better in our repertoire. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ Here we have another branching point. Black can play  7...b5  to stop  8.Nc4  or he can play some developing move:   a@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  transposes tothe Sveshnikov,   b@@EndBracket@@  7...Be6  transposes tothe Kalashnikov and   c@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7  transposes tothe Kalashnikov too. }
7... Be6 8. Nc4 { Improving our worst piece. } 8... b5
{ Black should chase this knight immediately.   8...Nf6  9.Bg5  will be covered inSveshnikov chapter. }
9. Ne3 { The only square. } 9... Nf6
{ 9...Be7  10.a4!?  b4  11.Ncd5  Nf6  12.Bd3  transposes to 9...Nf6. } 10. Bd3
{ Covering pawn on e4. } 10... Nb4
{ Covering d5 and attacking bishop at the same time. } 11. a4
{ The light-squared bishop is not that important. } 11... Nxd3+
{ 11...bxa4?!  12.Rxa4  only improves White pieces. } 12. Qxd3 b4 13. Ncd5
{ Black has to exchange those powerful knights. } 13... Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15.
Qxd5
{ The position is simplified, but White controls the d5-square and the light squares. His bishop should be better than the Black one.   For the purpose of the QuickStarter we end the variation here; the line is examined in more detail in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...Nc6 - Kalashnikov: 7...b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6
{ The Kalashnikov variation. Younger brother of the more popular Sveshnikov. Black is flexible about move Nf6 since he doesn't want to get pinned with Bg5 @@StartBracket@@which happens in Svehnikov@@EndBracket@@. This however has some drawbacks, obvious one is that it allows Nd5 jump. }
6. N1c3
{ 6.c4  is another way to deal with Kalashnikov, but  6.N1c3  fits better in our repertoire. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ Here we have another branching point. Black can play  7...b5  to stop  8.Nc4  or he can play some developing move:   a@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  transposes to Sveshnikov,   b@@EndBracket@@  7...Be6  and   c@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7  . }
7... b5 8. Nd5 { This is the starting point of the main line Kalashnikov. }
8... Nge7 9. Bd3
{ Relatively new idea with small number of games. White doesn't give up the d4 square so easily and develops bishop instead. Current state of theory suggest that the ball is in black's court.   9.c4  is the main move where Black has couple of ways to give up a pawn for quick development. }
9... Nxd5 10. exd5 { Black has to decide where to put his knight. } 10... Ne7
11. c4
{ Only now, when black knight is on passive square, and far away from d4, White plays c4. Practically speaking, White has tricked Black with 9. Bd3 move order.   After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/4nppp/p1np4/1p1Np3/4P3/N7/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.c4  Nxd5  10.exd5  no one puts the knight on e7. }
11... g6 12. O-O
{ White can also take on b5 first, but Black can't do anything about it anyways. }
12... Bg7 13. cxb5 O-O 14. Re1
{ An useful move before taking on a6.   14.bxa6  is the simplest move which gives  White advantage, but he can strive for more.   Here we should follow the example of the 1.b3 expert who sometimes tries the extravagant 1.e4:  14...Bb7  15.bxa6  Bxd5?  16.Bf1  Be6  17.b4  d5  18.b5  was already winning for White in Adhiban - Fawzy, Khanty-Mansiysk 2017. }
