[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...Nc6 - Sveshnikov with 8...Nb8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ The Sveshnikov variation. Since many new ideas were found in the 70's and the 80's it gained a reputation as one of the best Sicilians for Black.   It was pet line of many top class players including two World champions: Magnus Carlsen and Vladimir Kramnik who played it quite often before unfortunate discovery of the Berlin defense. }
6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5
{ This move was never considered critical, but the World Championship match Caruana - Carlsen from 2018 has completely changed the course of the current theory. The main problem for White is that after  7.Bg5  Black was successfully equalizing in most of the lines, so White players were somehow forced to create something new.   The move  7.Nd5  gives up fight for the d5 square, which is success for Black and leads to the pawn structures which are typical for the Najdorf. The positive side for White with or the move Nd5 is that the knight from b5 doesn't have to retreat to the a3 square and quite often goes back to c3 after the pawn goes c4. Also, Black has to decide where to place his knight. }
7... Nxd5 8. exd5
{ Black here has a choice between Nb8 and Ne7. The first one had a better reputation, but the World Champion revived the whole Ne7 line. }
8... Nb8 9. a4
{ White has two ways to solve the problem of the b5-knight, he can play  9.c4  and return the knight to c3, or play in a modern way  9.a4  and return the knight to a3 where it can reach his ideal square in this pawn structure, the c4 square. }
9... Be7
{ Black develops his kingside first, and is not in a hurry to play a6. } 10.
Be2 { White also develops, before pushing on the queenside with a5. } 10... O-O
11. Bd2
{ The most common move is  11.O-O  but after  11...Nd7  12.Bd2  a6  13.Na3  a5  practice has shown that Black has good chances there. With this move order @@StartBracket@@Bd2 before castling@@EndBracket@@ White fights against the mentioned plan @@StartBracket@@a6 followed by a5@@EndBracket@@ and doesn't spoil his position.   The bishop goes to d2, to guard the pawn on a5, or to attack the black pawn depending on our opponents reaction. }
11... f5
{ Usually, the best plan for Black is to play on the kingside, and postpone playing a6 as long as possible. }
12. a5 { Improving on the queenside and waiting for reply. } 12... Nd7
{ Black continues with the developing. } 13. O-O
{ Easy move for White, finishing the development. } 13... a6
{ If Black plays  13...Nf6  too soon, then  14.c4  is a strong reply, usually followed by Nc3 and pawn expansion on the queenside. }
14. Na3 e4 { Creating square for the knight. } 15. Nc4
{ Of course, knight is on its ideal square. } 15... Ne5
{ Black challenges it. } 16. Nb6 { It is too early to trade those knights. }
16... Rb8 17. f4
{ White has to open up the position for his pieces on the kingside. } 17...
exf3 18. Bxf3
{ This position was reached via a different move order in the 8th game of the World Championship match Caruana - Carlsen, London 2018. The challenger was arguably having a winning advantage at some point which shows how tricky this position is for the Black side. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...Nc6 - Sveshnikov with 8...Ne7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ The Sveshnikov variation. Since many new ideas were found in the 70ies and the 80ies it gained a reputation as one of the best Sicilians for Black.   It was pet line of many top class players including two World champions: Magnus Carlsen and Vladimir Kramnik who played it quite often before unfortunate discovery of the Berlin defense. }
6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5
{ This move was never considered critical, but the World Championship match Caruana - Carlsen from 2018 has completely changed the course of the current theory. The main problem for White is that after  7.Bg5  Black was successfully equalizing in most of the lines, so White players were somehow forced to create something new.   The move  7.Nd5  gives up fight for the d5 square, which is success for Black and leads to the pawn structures which are typical for the Najdorf. The positive side for White with or the move Nd5 is that the knight from b5 doesn't have to retreat to the a3 square and quite often goes back to c3 after the pawn goes c4. Also, Black has to decide where to place his knight. }
7... Nxd5 8. exd5 Ne7
{ The modern way of playing this position. It has brought many victories to the current World Champion. It seems as if Black is on the verge of losing a pawn in this line, but somehow always manages to find some compensation for it. }
9. c4 Ng6 { If Black could castle he would have a great position. } 10. Qa4
{ Creating a deadly threats. } 10... Bd7 { Only move. } 11. Qb4
{ White is annoying Black and constantly attacking some pawns. Here Black has choice between two approximately similar options: Bf5 and Qb8. }
11... Qb8 { Defending pawn, and keeping the option of playing f7-f5. } 12. Be3
{ White players are automatically including h4 and h5, and only then playing Be3, but I have realized that this only helps Black to create some counter chances. White wants to play c5 on the next move if Black doesn't do anything. }
12... a6
{ Black can hardly play without this move,  12...Be7  allows  13.c5  , so he has to include a6 first. }
13. Nc3 Be7
{ 13...f5  isn't  something White should be afraid of. Move f4 is not really a threat since it  gives the e4 square, and White can continue expanding on the queenside.  14.a4  and White has an easier play. }
14. Na4
{ Going for Nb6. It is important that in many lines pawn on h4 isn't hanging. That is the difference compared to the 13. h4. }
14... Qc7 { Giving rook air to breathe. } 15. Qb6
{ In general, the endgame should be favourable for White with the pawn majority on the queenside. }
15... Qb8 { Or  15...Qc8  is responded in the same manner. } 16. Qb3
{ As we have seen in the Bf5 line, White queen is better played on b3 than on b4 since it participates in the defence over the third rank. In some lines playing c5 also becomes option, especially when Black pushes f5. }
16... Qc7 17. Nb6
{ White will take the bishop on d7 and obtain the bishop pair advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d6 - Dragodorf with 7...b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 a6
{ Sooner or later Black will have to play Bg7, and I don't see much sense if Black avoids it.   7...Nbd7  is always responded with  8.g4!  b5  9.Qd2  Bb7  10.O-O-O  and we are back in the main line. }
7. f3 b5 8. Qd2 { Preparing to castle. } 8... Bb7 9. a4
{ White's pieces are not only prepared for the queenside castling, but also for the kingside castling. White changes the usual plan and decides to play more positionally since Black will have weaknesses on the queenside. }
9... e5
{ 9...bxa4  10.Nxa4  certainly favours White, he will continue Be2 and O-O, with advantage on the queenside.   9...b4  10.Na2  e5  11.Nb3  is a transposition. }
10. Nb3 b4
{ Black is avoiding  10...bxa4  and trying to strike in the centre. } 11. Na2
d5 { 11...a5  12.c3  and Black can't really afford to give up b5-square. } 12.
Bg5 { Stops dxe4 and creates pressure on the d5-pawn. } 12... Nbd7 13. exd5
{ Simply taking pawn. } 13... Bxd5 14. Qxd5
{ 14.O-O-O  also looks promising, but this is the simplest. } 14... Nxd5 15.
Bxd8 Kxd8 { Forced recapture, since pawn on a6 is hanging. } 16. O-O-O
{ Finishing development with tempo. Rook is perfect on the d-file. } 16... Ne3
17. Rd3 Bh6 18. Kb1 { King is safe, and pawn on b4 is under attack. } 18... a5
19. c3
{ White will win a pawn at least. Knight from a2 will be returned into the action and Black will have to give up some material. }
