[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d6 - Dragodorf with 7...a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6
{ Playing a6 is almost never an idea for Black in Dragon, so this opening looks like some hybrid between Dragon and Najdorf, which explains its name.   7...h5  has no independent value,  8.Qd2  will either transpose to h5-Dragon or the usual Dragodorf.  8...Nbd7  9.Be2  a6  10.h3  . }
8. Qd2 { Useful move for White, but also a waiting one, too. } 8... Nbd7
{ Whenever knight from b8 lands to d7, White should play g4 if he can. } 9. g4
{ White should play g4 before castling to avoid h5 response. } 9... b5 10.
O-O-O Bb7
{ 10...Nb6?  would be an error because of  11.Nc6  attacking the queen  11...Qc7  12.Nxe7!  Kxe7  13.e5!  dxe5  14.Nxb5!  axb5  15.Qb4+  Ke6  16.Bxb6  Qxb6  17.Bc4+  and White has a strong attack against Black's king. }
11. h4 { Simple and good, the idea is h5 and h6. } 11... h5
{ 11...Ne5  12.h5  Rc8  13.h6  is a disaster for Black. } 12. g5
{ Black knight will have to go back. } 12... Nh7 13. f4
{ Very direct play. White is trying to breakthrough with f5. } 13... Nc5 14. f5
{ White can play calm Bg2, but 14. f5 is much stronger and direct. } 14... b4
15. fxg6 { Intermezzo, which opens black king. } 15... fxg6
{ Or  15...bxc3  16.fxg7+  , where the Black king comes out. See thefollowing variation. }
16. Nd5 Nxe4 17. Qxb4
{ Both pieces were hanging, which is not important. Black king is very weak. }
17... Bxd5 18. Bb5+
{ This is the last move you need to remember. Now, White is collecting everything.   Black can continue with  18...axb5  or  18...Kf8  . We end the line here; both variations are examined in more detail in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black " 2...d6 - Dragon with 9.O-O-O Bd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon variation. One of the most aggressive Sicilians, which was used by many great players in history including two greatest ones: Garry Kasparov and Magnus Carlsen.   Nowadays, it is not as popular as it used to be on the top level since White found the ways to soothe the Dragon. }
6. Be3
{ Going for the typical English attack setup, in this case known as Yugoslav attack. }
6... Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O
{ The main move and the best one. The alternatives are not very promising. } 9.
O-O-O
{ Through the history there was a long debate whether White should play  9.Bc4  or  9.O-O-O  . In the early ages of Dragon  9.Bc4  has always been considered as the critical move, since castling gave Black opportunity to strike with  9...d5  .   However, the main difference between 9. Bc4 and 9. O-O-O is that if Black wants to create some counter chances he will have to comply with an inferior position in the 9. O-O-O line. }
9... Bd7
{ Before analyzing the main and the strongest move  9...d5  we will cover some other options for Black. }
10. g4 Rc8 { Here White has a pleasant choice between  11.h4  and  11.Kb1  . }
11. Kb1 { Typical useful move for White. } 11... Ne5
{ If  11...h5  12.h3  is strong, keeping both g5 and gxh5 as an option. It shows why Kb1 was a strong semi-waiting move. }
12. Be2 { Prevents some desperate sacrifices on f3 and c3 followed by Nxe4. }
12... Qc7 13. h4 { White has prepared everything for pushing pawns. } 13... b5
14. h5
{ We don't care about pawns on the queenside, checkmating is more important. }
14... b4 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. exd5
{ The knight on d4 is a powerful defender, and White has free hands on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d6 - Dragon with 9.O-O-O Nxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon variation. One of the most aggressive Sicilians, which was used by many great players in history including two greatest ones: Garry Kasparov and Magnus Carlsen.   Nowadays, it is not as popular as it used to be on the top level since White found the ways to soothe the Dragon. }
6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 9. O-O-O
{ Throughout history there was a long debate whether White should play  9.Bc4  or  9.O-O-O  . In the early ages of Dragon  9.Bc4  has always been considered as the critical move since castling gave Black the opportunity to strike with  9...d5  .   However, the main difference between 9. Bc4 and 9. O-O-O is that if Black wants to create some counter-chances he will have to comply with an inferior position in the 9. O-O-O line. }
9... Nxd4
{ This line is equally good @@StartBracket@@or bad@@EndBracket@@ as  9...Bd7  . }
10. Bxd4 Be6 11. Kb1 { This move is crucial since it stops  11...Qa5  . } 11...
Qc7
{ One or two decade@@StartBracket@@s@@EndBracket@@ ago computers were not so strong and some people were still believing that it is possible to waste one tempo in such a position and still have a decent game. Today, things are different, and the engines are already giving a winning advantage for White here. }
12. h4 { White's moves are simple. } 12... Rfc8 13. h5
{ The logical continuation of the previous moves. } 13... Qa5 14. hxg6 hxg6
{ Black can't really sacrifice an exchange on c3 since White's king will have an escape route via d2. }
15. a3 { Before continuing the attack, prophylaxis. } 15... Rab8 16. Bd3
{ Connecting the rooks, covering c2, and eyeing g6.   Black can now continue with  16...Bc4  , which we examine inthis variation;   or with the more aggressive  16...b5  , transposing into theMainline. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d6 - Dragon with 9.O-O-O d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon variation. One of the most aggressive Sicilians, which was used by many great players in history including two greatest ones: Garry Kasparov and Magnus Carlsen.   Nowadays, it is not as popular as it used to be on the top level since White found the ways to soothe the Dragon. }
6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 9. O-O-O
{ Throughout history there was a long debate whether White should play  9.Bc4  or  9.O-O-O  . In the early ages of Dragon  9.Bc4  has always been considered as the critical move since castling gave Black the opportunity to strike with  9...d5  .   However, the main difference between 9. Bc4 and 9. O-O-O is that if Black wants to create some counter-chances he will have to comply with an inferior position in the 9. O-O-O line. }
9... d5 { Literally, the only move. } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4
{ White shows his real intentions with this move. He wants to kill any counterplay Black has in this position, trade the dark-squared bishops, and play for the better endgame. }
12... Bxd4
{ This move was recommended by Gawain Jones in his books about Dragon. Until recently, @@StartBracket@@read Anish Giri Dragon course@@EndBracket@@ the whole line has been considered as the best option for Black. }
13. Qxd4 Qb6
{ Black generally doesn't want to trade queen unless it improves his pawn structure and opens the a-file. }
14. Na4 { Black wanted to take on d4 and c3, thus White has to react. } 14...
Qc7
{ More popular than the  14...Qa5  , although it is hard to say which move is better one for Black. }
15. Bc4 Rd8 16. Nc5
{ Improving the knight.   We end the line here; the variation is analyzed in great detail in the corresponding theoretical chapter, starting fromthis variation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
