[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d6 - Dragon with 9.O-O-O d5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon variation. One of the most aggressive Sicilians, which was used by many great players in history including two greatest ones: Garry Kasparov and Magnus Carlsen.   Nowadays, it is not as popular as it used to be on the top level since White found the ways to soothe the Dragon. }
6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 9. O-O-O
{ Throughout history there was a long debate whether White should play  9.Bc4  or  9.O-O-O  . In the early ages of Dragon  9.Bc4  has always been considered as the critical move since castling gave Black the opportunity to strike with  9...d5  .   However, the main difference between 9. Bc4 and 9. O-O-O is that if Black wants to create some counter-chances he will have to comply with an inferior position in the 9. O-O-O line. }
9... d5 { Literally, the only move. } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4
{ White shows his real intentions with this move. He wants to kill any counterplay Black has in this position, trade the dark-squared bishops, and play for the better endgame. }
12... e5 { The most fighting move. } 13. Bc5 Re8
{ Before, everyone was playing  13...Be6  inviting White to  14.Bxf8  . The problem with  13...Be6  is that if White doesn't accept the sacrifice he has an easy play.   Currently this move is gaining population and it will probably surpass the 13...Be6 in the future. It is recommendation of Anish Giri in his excellent Dragon course. }
14. Ne4 f5 15. Nd6 Bf8
{ Indirectly stopping  16.Nxe8  . White has brilliant refutation. } 16. Bb5
{ Such a powerful move. } 16... Bxd6 17. Bxc6
{ Too many black pieces are hanging. } 17... Bxc5 18. Bxd5+ Be6 19. Bxe6+
{ White wins a pawn, which should be enough for victory. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d6 - Rauzer with 6...h6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Rauzer variation, known also as the Classical Sicilian. Black develops knights to the most natural squares, f6 and c6.   He will follow it up with e6, Be7, a6, Bd7 which seems as beginners way to play chess. However, this keeps flexibility and often Black castles queenside, or keeps king in the centre which makes typical English attack less effective.   Also,  6.Be3  is responded by Ng4, while  6.f3  e5  gives Black a more favourable position than in Najdorf. Unlike some other Sicilians, if White wants to achieve anything from the opening he must castle kingside. }
6. Bg5 h6
{ I have never been fan of this move for Black, since White wants to take on f6 anyway.   6...Bd7  7.Qd2  h6  8.Bxf6  gxf6  is a different move order. }
7. Bxf6 gxf6 8. Qd2 { Getting ready for the long castle. } 8... Bd7
{ Black has to develop the queenside first. } 9. O-O-O Nxd4
{ White already can play Nf5 on the next move, so Black destroys the knight. }
10. Qxd4 Qa5 11. f4 { Must move for White in the Richter-Rauzer attack. } 11...
Rc8 12. Kb1
{ This calm move is always useful in Sicilians. Here it prevents exchange sacrifice ideas for Black @@StartBracket@@Rxc3@@EndBracket@@ . }
12... Qc5
{ With the bishop pair advantage and weak king Black would definitely love to trade queens. Actually this is one of the reasons why Classical Sicilian or Rauzer doesn't lose its popularity.   Black often has a very favourable endgame, and in the 90% of the cases when Black has bishop pair, White should avoid trade of the queens }
13. Qd3
{ White won't trade queens, and the only question is where does the queen go, d3 or d2? I prefer it on d3 since it is more useful on the third rank and more importantly, it doesn't stand on the c1-h6 diagonal which will be occupied by black bishop. }
13... e6 { Not really compatible with the h6-system in general. } 14. Be2
{ Simple and good. } 14... h5
{ After  14...Be7  or  14...Bc6  White can play  15.f5  . } 15. Rhf1 Bc6 16. f5
Qe5 17. Qh3
{ White has a favourable version of the Richer-Rauzer attack. Normally Black pawns would already be on the fifth or fourth rank. }
