[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d6 - Rauzer with 6...e6 and 7...Be7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Rauzer variation, known also as the Classical Sicilian. Black develops knights to the most natural squares, f6 and c6.   He will follow it up with e6, Be7, a6, Bd7 which seems as beginners way to play chess. However, this keeps flexibility and often Black castles queenside, or keeps king in the centre which makes typical English attack less effective.   Also,  6.Be3  is responded by Ng4, while  6.f3  e5  gives Black a more favourable position than in Najdorf. Unlike some other Sicilians, if White wants to achieve anything from the opening he must castle kingside. }
6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ Natural follow up to the 6...e6. This means Black will castle kingside. } 8.
O-O-O O-O
{ 8...Bd7?  9.Ndb5  this is why Black has to play a6 before Bd7.   8...a6  9.Bxf6!   9.f4  Bd7  would transpose into very fashionable line which I'm trying to avoid.  9...gxf6  10.f4  and Black will have to play  10...Nxd4  which will be  covered in theline 8...Nxd4. }
9. h4
{ My initial idea was to recommend  9.Nb3  but I realized that  9.h4  fits more into our repertoire. The idea behind this move is to secure the bishop on g5 and prevent possible tactics.   Also, it makes move h6 less appealing for Black.  Black's best replyis 8...Nxd4 which is covered later. }
9... a6 10. Nxc6
{ This reaction is more typical for Taimanov. Other normal moves are  10.f4  or  10.Kb1  . }
10... bxc6 11. Rh3 { The rook comes into the play. } 11... d5 12. Rg3 Rb8
{ Very natural move, but White here has strong reply. } 13. e5 Nd7 14. Bh6 g6
15. f4
{ No need to take the rook yet, White can have a dangerous attack instead. He can parry Black threats on the queenside with the simple b3. If Black takes the pawn on h4 then h-file will be opened for white rooks. }
