[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d6 - Rauzer with 6...e6 and 7...Be7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Rauzer variation, known also as the Classical Sicilian. Black develops knights to the most natural squares, f6 and c6.   He will follow it up with e6, Be7, a6, Bd7 which seems as beginners way to play chess. However, this keeps flexibility and often Black castles queenside, or keeps king in the centre which makes typical English attack less effective.   Also,  6.Be3  is responded by Ng4, while  6.f3  e5  gives Black a more favourable position than in Najdorf. Unlike some other Sicilians, if White wants to achieve anything from the opening he must castle kingside. }
6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7 8. O-O-O Nxd4
{ One can say this is a more precise move order for Black than  8...O-O  since it avoids the  9.Nb3  line. }
9. Qxd4 O-O 10. h4
{ 10.f4  is by far the most popular move, but  10.h4  is trickier and I believe more precise. }
10... Qa5 11. Kb1
{ Here is the main difference between moves 10. f4 and 10. h4. The Black queen will soon be misplaced on a5.   When you compare this line withthe main line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2nppn2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...a6  8.O-O-O  Bd7  it is visible that Black got an inferior version of it, with early castling and will lose the whole tempo with Qa5-Qc7. }
11... h6 12. Bc1
{ 12.Bd2  is also interesting, Black has to play  12...Qc5  and enter into an inferior endgame. }
12... Bd7 13. f3 h5
{ Probably the only move which keeps Black in the game. Allowing g4 would lead to a disaster. }
14. Bd2
{ Forcing the Black queen to a more passive square. Queen trades @@StartBracket@@on e5 and c5@@EndBracket@@ leave Black with a damaged pawn structure. }
14... Qc7 15. Bg5
{ We can improve our bishop now. With the Black queen on a5, b5 would be the best move. Here it just loses material. }
15... Rac8 16. Qd2 { Securing the c2-pawn, preventing b7-b5 once again. } 16...
Rfd8 17. Bd3 { White has done all the preparations for a kingside attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d6 - Rauzer with 6...e6 and 7...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Rauzer variation, known also as the Classical Sicilian. Black develops knights to the most natural squares, f6 and c6.   He will follow it up with e6, Be7, a6, Bd7 which seems as beginners way to play chess. However, this keeps flexibility and often Black castles queenside, or keeps king in the centre which makes typical English attack less effective.   Also,  6.Be3  is responded by Ng4, while  6.f3  e5  gives Black a more favourable position than in Najdorf. Unlike some other Sicilians, if White wants to achieve anything from the opening he must castle kingside. }
6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6
{ Since we have seen that Black can't really get enough counterplay without a6-b5 plan it seems logical to start with this move. }
8. O-O-O h6
{ This line was popular until discovery of 9. Nxc6. After that it was all going downhill for Black. More popular andbetter 8...Bd7 will be part of this chapter. }
9. Nxc6
{ In case of  9.Bh4  Nxe4  is a well known trick, although White can claim some compensation there. }
9... bxc6 10. Bf4
{ Forcing Black to play d5, since  10...e5?  loses pawn to  11.Bxe5  . } 10...
d5 11. Qe3
{ Avoiding possible pin, and making the most out of the queen and the rook. White queen is doing great job on the third rank.   White next move is Be2 and he will have all his pieces developed by 12th move. If we look at Black pieces, we see completely different picture. }
11... Bb4 { Over the last couple of years this moves gave Black most success. }
12. Be2 { Finishing development. } 12... O-O 13. e5
{ Black has to decide where to put his knight. On d7 it looks more natural, but it blocks his bishop and prevents black queenside from developing. }
13... Nd7
{ 13...Nh7  is a serious alternative, discussed starting fromthis variation. }
14. Qg3
{ The only move which keeps initiative.  14.h4  f6!  and Black gets decent position. }
14... Qc7 15. a3
{ Black has created some counterplay because of the e5 pawn, but we can take the bishop pair. }
15... Bxc3 16. Qxc3 f6 17. Qg3
{ On the other hand White wins pawn on h6. Yes, the central pawns are usually more important than the ones on the edge of the board, but White dark-squared bishop has no opponent which is more than enough for White to claim advantage.  For the purpose of the QuickStarter we end the line here; the variation is examined in more detail in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
