1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Rauzer variation, known also as the Classical Sicilian. Black develops knights to the most natural squares, f6 and c6.   He will follow it up with e6, Be7, a6, Bd7 which seems as beginners way to play chess. However, this keeps flexibility and often Black castles queenside, or keeps king in the centre which makes typical English attack less effective.   Also,  6.Be3  is responded by Ng4, while  6.f3  e5  gives Black a more favourable position than in Najdorf. Unlike some other Sicilians, if White wants to achieve anything from the opening he must castle kingside. }
6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7
{ We have reached the main move in the Rauzer. Since after  8...Be7  9.Bxf6  Black has to recapture with the pawn on f6, Black first develops light-squared bishop. And he is ready to play b5. }
9. Kb1
{ Before explaining why I'm choosing 9. Kb1 I have to mention the main move and the most aggressive one,  9.f4  . After  9.f4  Black has two different options, one is to play  9...b5  which has always been considered as the main line. Another one is  9...Be7  , modern way of handling the position.   In both cases White can claim some advantage according to the computers, but variations are long and complicated, and sometimes difficult to understand.   Also, White gives dark-squared bishop in order to compromise black pawn structure, which means that Black always has some counter chances, even in dubious positions. The move  9.Kb1  is very similar to the  9.f3  , and often we will just transpose to the 9. f3 lines, with few small differences which favour White in my opinion.   For example, on case of  9.f3  Nxd4  10.Qxd4  h6  11.Be3  Bc6  12.Qd2  d5  13.e5  Nd7  14.f4  g5!  15.f5  Qc7  Black gets enough counterplay. Also, we are freeing the c1 square for dark-squared bishop in some lines. 9. Kb1 has been tried more than once by Giri, Dominguez Perez and Nakamura. }
9... Be7 10. Nxc6 { The usual. } 10... Bxc6
{ With bishop on d7, it makes no sense for Black to capture on c6 with a pawn. }
11. f3
{ Fortifying e4, and preparing for the kingside attack. White light squared bishop is best placed on the d3, g and h pawns must be pushed as far as possible.   The knight on c3 is placed well there, but sooner or later Black will attack it with b5-b4, and then we move it to e2 where it go to centre @@StartBracket@@d4@@EndBracket@@, defend queenside @@StartBracket@@c1@@EndBracket@@ or to the kingside @@StartBracket@@f4, g3 later h5@@EndBracket@@ to join the attack. }
11... b5 12. h4
{ Advancing the kingside pawns, and securing the bishop. White has to be careful and not fall into the trap by playing  12.Ne2??  too early because of  12...Nxe4!  trick. }
12... Rc8 13. Ne2 { Before doing anything, White improves his knight. } 13...
Bb7 14. Nd4 h6 15. Be3 Nd7
{ Black tries to postpone castling on the kingside, which could put off White's attack. }
16. g4 Qc7 17. Bd3 { Finishing development and overprotecting the pawns. }
17... d5 18. g5
{ The simplest reaction. Another promising move is  18.Bf4  provoking e5 which weakens the f5 square. Black is forced to open up the h-file because everything else is clearly worse for him. }
