[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d6 - Najdorf English Attack: Rare Black Setups, 6...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf. One of the most popular and best systems against 1. e4 in general. There was a hardly any modern World Champion who hasn't played the Najdorf. It was a first choice against 1. e4 of many great players in history, such as Bobby Fischer, Gari Kasparov, Veselin Topalov...   Nowadays people usually connect the Najdorf with the name of Maxime Vachier-Lagrave who plays it almost exclusively. I also have to mention that the Najdorf is currently the first choice against 1. e4 of your author. }
6. f3
{ White has tried almost every legal move against the Najdorf. It wasn't an easy call to decide what to recommend against 'my own opening'.  6.Bg5  is the most aggressive and principled move, but it requires White to know a ton of theory, and in majority of lines such as  7...Qb6  theory tends to lead into forced draw.   I decided for the classical English attack setup, starting with  6.f3  . When comparing  6.f3  and  6.Be3  , the latter one is more flexible against  6...e6  and  6...e5  since it gives White more options.   But  6.f3  has one major plus. It avoids  6...Ng4  variation where White failed to prove any advantage as far as I know. To conclude, I choose  6.f3  because it leads to fighting play, and it is one of the most principled setups. }
6... e6
{ In the nineties  6...e6  was more popular than the  6...e5  , but this was general trend, Scheveningen schemes were more appreciated. }
7. Be3 { White begins developing pieces. } 7... b5
{ Black starts pushing queenside pawns, sometimes his idea is to immediately challenge knight on c3 with b4, and then quickly play e5 followed by d5. Black needs to first develop pieces on the queenside. For example playing  7...Be7  is not very precise here due to  8.g4  . }
8. a3
{ Stopping all kinds of ideas connected with b4.  8.Qd2  or  8.g4  are more popular, but lead to massive theoretical duels which can be avoided. }
8... h5
{ I believe Black's best chance is to prevent White from playing g4 when he can't create counterattack with b5-b4. }
9. Qd2 { Going for the queenside castling is the most critical. } 9... Nbd7 10.
O-O-O Bb7 11. Kb1
{ Both sides are playing typical moves, sometimes the move order can change slightly, but you should know where to put your pieces. }
11... Be7 12. Rg1 { One day White will play g4. } 12... Rc8 13. Be2
{ Connecting rooks. White has developed all his pieces. } 13... Nb6
{ The main move by far.  13...Qc7  might be too early because of  14.Bg5  . Black must play Nb6 at some point while queen is useful on some other squares.   Also, queen on c7 blocks the rook, and takes away the typical possibility of exchange sacrifice on c3, as well as move Rc5 which creates pressure on the bishop on g5. }
14. Bg5
{ Pinning the knight and not allowing Nfd7.   14.Qe1  leads to a very forced variation, which is draw according to the engines:  14...Nfd7  15.g4  hxg4  16.Rxg4  g6  17.Rxg6!?  Rxc3!  18.Nxe6  Qc8!  19.Ng7+  Kf8  20.Rh6!  Rxh6  21.Bxh6  Rxc2  22.Nf5+  Ke8  23.Nxe7  Kxe7  24.Qh4+  f6  25.Bf4  Rxb2+  26.Kxb2  Na4+  27.Kb1  Nc3+  28.Ka1  Nxd1  29.Qh7+  Kd8  30.Qg8+  Ke7  31.Qh7+  Kd8  32.Qg8+  Ke7  33.Qh7+  1/2-1/2 Alekseenko - Vachier Lagrave,  Candidates 2020. }
14... Rc5
{ As I mentioned in the notes on move 13th, Black creates pressure on the bishop on g5. }
15. h4 { Bishop needs to be secured. } 15... O-O { It is safe to castle now. }
16. Rde1
{ This strange looking move, allows White to reroute the knight from c3 to e3 via d1. }
16... Qc7 17. Nd1 Rc8 18. Ne3
{ White has prepared everything for the g4 push. } *

