[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d6 - Najdorf English Attack: Main without 8..h5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf. One of the most popular and best systems against 1. e4 in general. There was a hardly any modern World Champion who hasn't played the Najdorf. It was a first choice against 1. e4 of many great players in history, such as Bobby Fischer, Gari Kasparov, Veselin Topalov...   Nowadays people usually connect the Najdorf with the name of Maxime Vachier-Lagrave who plays it almost exclusively. I also have to mention that the Najdorf is currently the first choice against 1. e4 of your author. }
6. f3
{ White has tried almost every legal move against the Najdorf. It wasn't an easy call to decide what to recommend against 'my own opening'.  6.Bg5  is the most aggressive and principled move, but it requires White to know a ton of theory, and in majority of lines such as  7...Qb6  theory tends to lead into forced draw.   I decided for the classical English attack setup, starting with  6.f3  . When comparing  6.f3  and  6.Be3  , the latter one is more flexible against  6...e6  and  6...e5  since it gives White more options.   But  6.f3  has one major plus. It avoids  6...Ng4  variation where White failed to prove any advantage as far as I know. To conclude, I choose  6.f3  because it leads to fighting play, and it is one of the most principled setups. }
6... e5 7. Nb3 Be6
{ Black can't play this system without placing bishop to e6, where it naturally belongs.   For example  7...Be7  8.Be3  O-O  9.Qd2  b5?!  10.O-O-O  with Nd5 on the next move or  10.a4  both give White a pleasant advantage. }
8. Be3 Nbd7 9. g4
{ This is the only case in the whole Najdorf where we play g4 before Qd2. So, what would happen after  9.Qd2?  Black's idea is to play  9...b5  and after  10.O-O-O  h5  . Maybe White can claim some tiny advantage there, but 9. g4 seems more critical and principled. }
9... Nb6
{ This move wouldn't be even remotely strong if White had played 9. Qd2, but you can't have everything. Black wants to play d5, and White is not in time to stop it with Qd2 and O-O-O. Instead he must attack the f6-knight. }
10. g5 { White must play like this, the threat was  10...d5  . } 10... Nh5 11.
Qd2 { Continuing with our setup. } 11... Be7 12. O-O-O
{ Both sides are playing usual developing moves. } 12... O-O 13. Kb1
{ You can hardly play Sicilian with White pieces without this move. } 13... Rc8
14. Rg1
{ Rook is always useful on g1, protects the g5 pawn, and anticipates the opening of the g-file.   For the purpose of the QuickStarter, we end the line here. The variation is analyzed in more detail in the corresponding theoreticalchapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d6 - Najdorf English Attack: Main without 8..h5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf. One of the most popular and best systems against 1. e4 in general. There was a hardly any modern World Champion who hasn't played the Najdorf. It was a first choice against 1. e4 of many great players in history, such as Bobby Fischer, Gari Kasparov, Veselin Topalov...   Nowadays people usually connect the Najdorf with the name of Maxime Vachier-Lagrave who plays it almost exclusively. I also have to mention that the Najdorf is currently the first choice against 1. e4 of your author. }
6. f3
{ White has tried almost every legal move against the Najdorf. It wasn't an easy call to decide what to recommend against 'my own opening'.  6.Bg5  is the most aggressive and principled move, but it requires White to know a ton of theory, and in majority of lines such as  7...Qb6  theory tends to lead into forced draw.   I decided for the classical English attack setup, starting with  6.f3  . When comparing  6.f3  and  6.Be3  , the latter one is more flexible against  6...e6  and  6...e5  since it gives White more options.   But  6.f3  has one major plus. It avoids  6...Ng4  variation where White failed to prove any advantage as far as I know. To conclude, I choose  6.f3  because it leads to fighting play, and it is one of the most principled setups. }
6... e5 7. Nb3 Be6
{ Black can't play this system without placing bishop to e6, where it naturally belongs.   For example  7...Be7  8.Be3  O-O  9.Qd2  b5?!  10.O-O-O  with Nd5 on the next move or  10.a4  both give White a pleasant advantage. }
8. Be3 Be7 9. Qd2
{ 9.g4?  would be a mistake because of  9...d5  when Black is much better. }
9... O-O 10. O-O-O a5
{ Instead of the typical Najdorf setup with the knight on d7, Black is trying to immediately cause troubles for White by pushing the a-pawn.   White shouldn't allow a4, which means that sooner or later he will have to play a4 himself, which will leave square b4 available for the black knight. Black will get a nice outpost on b4, but we should not forget that White will also get a nice square on b5. }
11. a4 { Stopping a4. } 11... Nc6 12. g4
{ White needs to have option of playing g5 available to spot Black from quickly playing d5 @@StartBracket@@after Nb4@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Nb4 13. Kb1 { King is much safer on b1. White waits for Black response. }
13... Rc8 { Activating the rook. } 14. g5
{ Black was threatening d5, and this is perfect time for g5. } 14... Nd7
{ The knight could have future on the queenside, but this move allows White to play f4. }
15. f4 exf4 16. Bxf4
{ The knight from b3 got the d4 square, and the White pieces are simply too active. }
*

