[Black "2...d6 - Najdorf English Attack: Main with 8...h5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf. One of the most popular and best systems against 1. e4 in general. There was a hardly any modern World Champion who hasn't played the Najdorf. It was a first choice against 1. e4 of many great players in history, such as Bobby Fischer, Gari Kasparov, Veselin Topalov...   Nowadays people usually connect the Najdorf with the name of Maxime Vachier-Lagrave who plays it almost exclusively. I also have to mention that the Najdorf is currently the first choice against 1. e4 of your author. }
6. f3
{ White has tried almost every legal move against the Najdorf. It wasn't an easy call to decide what to recommend against 'my own opening'.  6.Bg5  is the most aggressive and principled move, but it requires White to know a ton of theory, and in majority of lines such as  7...Qb6  theory tends to lead into forced draw.   I decided for the classical English attack setup, starting with  6.f3  . When comparing  6.f3  and  6.Be3  , the latter one is more flexible against  6...e6  and  6...e5  since it gives White more options.   But  6.f3  has one major plus. It avoids  6...Ng4  variation where White failed to prove any advantage as far as I know. To conclude, I choose  6.f3  because it leads to fighting play, and it is one of the most principled setups. }
6... e5 7. Nb3 Be6
{ Black can't play this system without placing bishop to e6, where it naturally belongs.   For example  7...Be7  8.Be3  O-O  9.Qd2  b5?!  10.O-O-O  with Nd5 on the next move or  10.a4  both give White a pleasant advantage. }
8. Be3 Be7 { or  8...h5  9.Qd2  Be7  . } 9. Qd2
{ 9.g4?  would be a mistake because of  9...d5  when Black is much better. }
9... h5 10. Be2
{ The main line is  10.Nd5  which is heavily covered in Anish Giri Najdorf course. With the Be2 move White is aiming to obtain the bishop pair advantage. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nd5 { Now it is time to jump. } 11... Nxd5 12. exd5 Bf5 13. O-O
{ 13.Na5  would allow Black to include a check on h4 and weaken white kingside  13...Bh4+  14.g3  Bf6  . }
13... O-O 14. Na5 { Once this knight lands on a5 White has a nice advantage. }
14... Qc7 15. c4
{ White enjoys a nice advantage here. The plan is b4, Rac1, Rfd1 and pushing c5 at the right moment. }
