[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ The simplest way to respond most of those queen's moves is to play 3. d4 and transpose into the well-known lines or to play 3. Nc3 first, if necessary. However, I will mention possible ways to punish those queen moves. }
2... Qb6
{ Is the strangest looking move in my opinion. I guess Black wants to play Grivas variation without allowing  3.Bb5  . }
3. c3
{ Going for the Alapin setup and a full centre.   In case of  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nc6  5.Nb3  transposes toChapter 6. }
3... Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4
{ The typical reaction to the Nf6 move in Alapin works very well here. } 5...
cxd4 6. cxd4 e6 7. Nc3
{ Will give White attacking motifs on the kingside, because of the pawn on e5 and space advantage. Also, Black's queen is misplaced on b6, since it will become a target after an exchange on c3 @@StartBracket@@Rb1@@EndBracket@@, and Black would normally like to play b6 and develop his bishop to b7 in this type of structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Rare 2nd Moves"]
[Black "Odd queen moves  #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ The simplest way to respond most of those queen's moves is to play 3. d4 and transpose into the well-known lines or to play 3. Nc3 first, if necessary. However, I will mention possible ways to punish those queen moves. }
2... Qb6
{ Is the strangest looking move in my opinion. I guess Black wants to play Grivas variation without allowing  3.Bb5  . }
3. c3
{ Going for the Alapin setup and a full centre.   In case of  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nc6  5.Nb3  transposes toChapter 6. }
3... e6 4. d4 d5
{ In case Black inserts  4...cxd4  5.cxd4  d5  White can react in the same manner: take on d5 followed by Nc3, Bd3 and O-O or play  6.e5  and enter into a very favourable version of the Advance Variation in the French defense since Black has exchanged the c-pawns too early and allowed White to develop the knight on c3. }
5. exd5
{ Here we take on d5, we don't want to play e5 and transpose to the advanced variation of the French which is fine for Black. }
5... exd5 6. Bd3 { White continues to develop. } 6... Nf6 7. O-O Be7
{ If at any point Black plays c4 then Bc2 followed by b3 opens the a-file for the white rook and brings the white pawns closer to the centre. }
8. dxc5
{ Forcing Black to take on c5 with the queen so we can develop the dark-squared bishop. }
8... Qxc5 9. Bf4 O-O 10. Re1 { Putting a rook on the open file. } 10... Re8 11.
Nbd2
{ White has slight advantage because he has a favorable version of the 'isolani'. Black practically wasted two moves with the queen and will have to move it again. }
*

