1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ The simplest way to respond most of those queen's moves is to play 3. d4 and transpose into the well-known lines or to play 3. Nc3 first, if necessary. However, I will mention possible ways to punish those queen moves. }
2... d5
{ This fits into odd queen moves since Black will follow up with 2 queen moves. Simply a bad version of the Scandinavian. }
3. exd5 Qxd5
{ if  3...f6  then  4.Bb5+  Bd7  5.Bxd7+  Qxd7  6.c4  e6  7.Qe2  and White ends up with an extra pawn. }
4. Nc3 Qd8 5. d4 cxd4 6. Qxd4
{ Taking with the knight is good, but this is even stronger. Black's queenside becomes very vulnerable after a trade of queens. }
6... Qxd4 7. Nxd4
{ White is already winning on move 7. Black can't control the white knights.   As information for the user, the line can continue like this: }
7... Bd7 8. Ndb5 Kd8 9. Be3 Nc6 10. O-O-O Nf6 11. Be2 Kc8 12. Rd2 a6 13. Na4
axb5 14. Nb6+ Kb8 15. Nxd7+ Nxd7 16. Rxd7 Rxa2 17. Kb1 Ra5 18. Rhd1 g6 19. Bb6
{ Finishes the game. } *

