[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Katalimov: 2...b6 / Nimzowitsch: 2..Nf6"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch: 2...Nf6 3.e5!  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch variation, but it is more appropriate to call it the Rakhmanov variation since the Russian GM played a huge number of games with it, and proved that the variation itself is better than its reputation. }
3. e5
{ The most principled response. There is a seemingly easier option to play lazy  3.Nc3  and after  3...Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  transpose into the well known lines.   However, Black can play  3...d5  which is a completely independent line, but gives White a slight edge.   Surprisingly, after  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.d4  , Black can even deviate with  4...d5  where White has to enter the endgame with tripled pawns @@StartBracket@@he is pawn up@@EndBracket@@ in order to prove some advantage:  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.dxc5  Nxc3  7.Qxd8+  Nxd8  8.bxc3  f6  , etc.   To conclude, not only do I believe that 3. e5 is the better option, but also it requires less work and memorization. }
3... Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Ne4
{ Less known than the main move  5.Nxd5  , but more venomous. My feeling is that players who are playing 4...e6 exactly want to play the 5. Nxd5 line where Black gets nice activity for a sacrificed pawn.  I want to add that amongst others, 5. Ne4 was played by Levon Aronian, Anish Giri and Alireza Firouzja. They certainly didn't play it by coincidence.   The move  5.Nxd5  exd5  6.d4  Nc6  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.Qxd5  d6  9.exd6  Qb6  10.Qe4+  Be6  is only the starting point of the variation and I fear that hardworking players might analyze this position 'till the end' and easily make a draw with Black. }
5... d6 { Plays into White hands. } 6. exd6 Bxd6 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. O-O O-O 9. Bxc6
{ Spoiling Black's pawn structure. } 9... bxc6 10. Nxd6
{ Eliminating Black's bishop pair. } 10... Qxd6 11. Re1
{ We have a better structure and a long-term advantage. The pawn on c5 will always be a problem for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Katalimov: 2...b6 / Nimzowitsch: 2..Nf6"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch: 2...Nf6 3.e5!  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch variation, but it is more appropriate to call it the Rakhmanov variation since the Russian GM played a huge number of games with it, and proved that the variation itself is better than its reputation. }
3. e5
{ The most principled response. There is a seemingly easier option to play lazy  3.Nc3  and after  3...Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  transpose into the well known lines.   However, Black can play  3...d5  which is a completely independent line, but gives White a slight edge.   Surprisingly, after  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.d4  , Black can even deviate with  4...d5  where White has to enter the endgame with tripled pawns @@StartBracket@@he is pawn up@@EndBracket@@ in order to prove some advantage:  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.dxc5  Nxc3  7.Qxd8+  Nxd8  8.bxc3  f6  , etc.   To conclude, not only do I believe that 3. e5 is the better option, but also it requires less work and memorization. }
3... Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Ne4
{ Less known than the main move  5.Nxd5  , but more venomous. My feeling is that players who are playing 4...e6 exactly want to play the 5. Nxd5 line where Black gets nice activity for a sacrificed pawn.  I want to add that amongst others, 5. Ne4 was played by Levon Aronian, Anish Giri and Alireza Firouzja. They certainly didn't play it by coincidence.   The move  5.Nxd5  exd5  6.d4  Nc6  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.Qxd5  d6  9.exd6  Qb6  10.Qe4+  Be6  is only the starting point of the variation and I fear that hardworking players might analyze this position 'till the end' and easily make a draw with Black. }
5... f5 6. Nc3
{ White has provoked f5 and now he goes back. The main point is that Nxd5 now is a much bigger threat than on move 5. }
6... Nxc3 7. dxc3
{ Compared to the 4...Nxc3 line White lost two tempi, but Black lost forever the possibility of playing f7-f6, thus undermining the e5-pawn. Also, if he ever manages to play d6, the pawn on e6 will be weak. }
7... Be7 8. Bf4 O-O
{ Kingside castling is quite dangerous for Black and it should be avoided. } 9.
Qd2 Nc6 10. h4 { White has many attacking possibilities. } *

