[White "2) Katalimov: 2...b6 / Nimzowitsch: 2..Nf6"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch: 2...Nf6 3.e5!  #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch variation, but it is more appropriate to call it the Rakhmanov variation since the Russian GM played a huge number of games with it, and proved that the variation itself is better than its reputation. }
3. e5
{ The most principled response. There is a seemingly easier option to play lazy  3.Nc3  and after  3...Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  transpose into the well known lines.   However, Black can play  3...d5  which is a completely independent line, but gives White a slight edge.   Surprisingly, after  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.d4  , Black can even deviate with  4...d5  where White has to enter the endgame with tripled pawns @@StartBracket@@he is pawn up@@EndBracket@@ in order to prove some advantage:  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.dxc5  Nxc3  7.Qxd8+  Nxd8  8.bxc3  f6  , etc.   To conclude, not only do I believe that 3. e5 is the better option, but also it requires less work and memorization. }
3... Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Ne4
{ Less known than the main move  5.Nxd5  , but more venomous. My feeling is that players who are playing 4...e6 exactly want to play the 5. Nxd5 line where Black gets nice activity for a sacrificed pawn.  I want to add that amongst others, 5. Ne4 was played by Levon Aronian, Anish Giri and Alireza Firouzja. They certainly didn't play it by coincidence.   The move  5.Nxd5  exd5  6.d4  Nc6  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.Qxd5  d6  9.exd6  Qb6  10.Qe4+  Be6  is only the starting point of the variation and I fear that hardworking players might analyze this position 'till the end' and easily make a draw with Black. }
5... f5 6. Nc3
{ White has provoked f5 and now he goes back. The main point is that Nxd5 now is a much bigger threat than on move 5. }
6... Ne7
{ Black prepares to create pressure on e5-pawn.   6...Nc7?!  this is rarely a good square for knights in Sicilians, it usually belongs to the queen.  7.d4  cxd4  8.Bg5  is trading the dark-squared bishops to emphasize weakness on d6  8...Be7  9.Bxe7  Qxe7  10.Qxd4  Nc6  11.Qd6  and White has a huge advantage, the knight on c7 is big trouble for Black. }
7. Nb5
{ The right follow-up. White's plan is to take the dark squared bishop at the cost of a pawn, and prove that f5 is a serious weakness. }
7... Ng6 8. b3
{ Simple and good, but if you like @@StartBracket@@Evans@@EndBracket@@ gambits, then  8.b4  with idea  8...cxb4  9.h4!  is certainly worth investigating. My feeling tells me that it must be good for White. }
8... a6 9. Nd6+ Bxd6 10. exd6 Qb6
{ Black should at least take a pawn in exchange for the weak dark squares. If  10...O-O  11.d4  White will have an advantage without sacrificing. }
11. Bb2
{ White can play  11.d4  Qxd6  12.Ba3  Qc7  13.Qd2  Just don't hurry to return the material and blunder with   13.dxc5??  Qa5+  A. Giri - T. Le, chess.com 2020.  13...cxd4  14.O-O-O  Qc3  15.Qxd4  Qxd4  16.Nxd4  White has more than enough compensation, but I would try to keep the queens on the board as long as possible. That is the reason why I prefer 11. Bb2 over 11. d4. }
11... O-O { 11...Qxd6  12.h4  O-O  13.h5  transposes tothis line. } 12. h4 Qxd6
13. h5
{ White's attack is progressing quickly. Black has a tough choice, where to put his knight. On e7 it doesn't have a bright future, on h8 it looks extremely ugly. }
13... Ne7 { Better no future than ugly :P } 14. h6 g6
{ Up to this moment we were following another blitz encounter between Giri and T. Le. }
15. d4 { It is time to open up the files and the diagonals. } 15... cxd4
{ 15...Nbc6?!  16.dxc5  Qxc5  17.Qd2  it is too dangerous for Black to leave the queens on the board. }
16. Bxd4 Nbc6 17. Bg7 Qxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Re8 19. c4
{ Black has managed to trade queens, but his position remains passive. The dark squares are terribly weak, the bishop on c8 is a problem, and White only gave up a pawn. }
