6... e6 7. h4
{ This move is always useful for White who postpones his decision about where to put his queen and light-squared bishop. }
7... b6 8. Ng5
{ Pretending to attack the f7 pawn, but actually going for the e4 square. }
8... Qc7
{ 8...h6  9.Ne4  Bb7  10.Qg4  and 11. Nd6 followed by the intermediate move Qg7 is a threat. }
9. Qh5
{ Provoking g6 which creates a hook for h4-h5 and a weakness on f6 as well. }
9... g6 10. Qf3 h6 11. Ne4 Nxe5 12. O-O-O
{ Smart move, stronger than the immediate  12.Nf6+  . } 12... Bg7
{ 12...Nxf3?  13.Bxc7+-  and the knight is trapped. } 13. Nd6+
{ White can also continue attacking with  13.Qg3  , but the text move is simpler. }
13... Qxd6 14. Qxa8 Qc7 15. Qe4
{ White won an exchange and Black's knight is still pinned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Katalimov: 2...b6 / Nimzowitsch: 2..Nf6"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch: 2...Nf6 3.e5!  #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch variation, but it is more appropriate to call it the Rakhmanov variation since the Russian GM played a huge number of games with it, and proved that the variation itself is better than its reputation. }
3. e5
{ The most principled response. There is a seemingly easier option to play lazy  3.Nc3  and after  3...Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  transpose into the well known lines.   However, Black can play  3...d5  which is a completely independent line, but gives White a slight edge.   Surprisingly, after  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.d4  , Black can even deviate with  4...d5  where White has to enter the endgame with tripled pawns @@StartBracket@@he is pawn up@@EndBracket@@ in order to prove some advantage:  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.dxc5  Nxc3  7.Qxd8+  Nxd8  8.bxc3  f6  , etc.   To conclude, not only do I believe that 3. e5 is the better option, but also it requires less work and memorization. }
3... Nd5 4. Nc3 Nxc3
{ I guess main reason why  4...e6  is more popular than  4...Nxc3  is because White players basically don't have to know any theory after 4...Nxc3 to gain an advantage. You can simply play normal developing moves and have a  comfortable position.   After developing all the pieces, everything looks great for White. When you look at the position a bit deeper, you realize that White's pawn structure is almost fixed, and there isn't much to do about it. Then, the right problem arises for White, how to proceed? }
5. dxc3 Nc6 6. Bf4
{ White first develops the dark-squared bishop to stop any kind of d7- d5 @@StartBracket@@or d6@@EndBracket@@ ideas. }
6... Qc7 { seems inferior compared to 6...Qb6 to my eyes. } 7. Bd3 e6 8. Qe2
{ Preparing for queenside castling. } 8... b6
{ 8...a6  9.a4  I prefer stopping counterplay with b5, and castle kingside, while Black can't castle queenside. }
9. O-O-O Bb7 10. h4 h6 11. h5 { Gaining space. } 11... O-O-O
{ White's chances are better because playing d7-d5 doesn't solve all the problems for Black. For example }
12. Be4 d5 { 12...f5  13.Bd3!  After f5 Black will never play d5. } 13. exd6
Bxd6 14. Bxd6 Rxd6 15. Rxd6
{ White gives away the d-file because there isn't much he can do there. However, he can create pressure on g7 with the Rh3-Rg3 maneuvre. }
15... Qxd6 16. b3 { First, let's secure the king. } 16... Rd8 17. Kb2
{ Black can't move the knight from c6 because Ne5 is quite a strong response after the exchange of bishops and Nxf7 is a crushing threat. }
17... f6 18. Rh3 Rd7 19. Rg3
{ In this relatively simple position White keeps better chances, his king is safer and Black has to worry about the weaknesses on g7 and e6. }
*

