[White "2) Katalimov: 2...b6 / Nimzowitsch: 2..Nf6"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch: 2...Nf6 3.e5!  #17"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch variation, but it is more appropriate to call it the Rakhmanov variation since the Russian GM played a huge number of games with it, and proved that the variation itself is better than its reputation. }
3. e5
{ The most principled response. There is a seemingly easier option to play lazy  3.Nc3  and after  3...Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  transpose into the well known lines.   However, Black can play  3...d5  which is a completely independent line, but gives White a slight edge.   Surprisingly, after  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.d4  , Black can even deviate with  4...d5  where White has to enter the endgame with tripled pawns @@StartBracket@@he is pawn up@@EndBracket@@ in order to prove some advantage:  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.dxc5  Nxc3  7.Qxd8+  Nxd8  8.bxc3  f6  , etc.   To conclude, not only do I believe that 3. e5 is the better option, but also it requires less work and memorization. }
3... Nd5 4. Nc3 Nxc3
{ I guess main reason why  4...e6  is more popular than  4...Nxc3  is because White players basically don't have to know any theory after 4...Nxc3 to gain an advantage. You can simply play normal developing moves and have a  comfortable position.   After developing all the pieces, everything looks great for White. When you look at the position a bit deeper, you realize that White's pawn structure is almost fixed, and there isn't much to do about it. Then, the right problem arises for White, how to proceed? }
5. dxc3 Nc6 6. Bf4
{ White first develops the dark-squared bishop to stop any kind of d7- d5 @@StartBracket@@or d6@@EndBracket@@ ideas. }
6... Qb6
{ Is the preferred choice of the line specialist Alexander Rakhmanov. Before playing Qc7 Black wants to provoke Rb1 or b3, to make White castling queenside risky or impossible. }
7. b3 Qc7
{ The queen has done its task on b6 and goes back to the most natural square. }
8. Bd3 { Developing the bishop to its natural square. } 8... e6
{ 8...b6  9.Qe2  Bb7  10.h4  e6  transposes to 8...e6 } 9. Qe2
{ The queen is ideally placed on e2 in this line, and White keeps flexibility with his king. }
9... b6 10. h4
{ Another useful move which postpones the decision about castling. } 10... Bb7
11. h5 { Is another semi-waiting move. } 11... c4
{ An unexpected resource.   If Black waits with h6 then we can play Rh3 and get into a favourable version of 11.Rh3 variation:  11...h6  12.Rh3  O-O-O  13.O-O-O  d5  14.exd6  Bxd6  15.Bxd6  Rxd6  16.Rg3  . }
12. bxc4 f5
{ Black aims to have some sort of positional compensation since there isn't any good way for White to use those tripled pawns. However, I believe they are somehow useful since they control central squares. }
13. Nd4 Nxd4
{ Black regains the pawn, but improves White's pawn structure.   13...a6  14.Rh3  doesn't change much. }
14. cxd4 Bxg2 15. Rg1
{ The rook gets to the g-file, and although material is equal White is better. He still has a space advantage and better control of the centre. }
15... Qc6 16. Qe3 { Don't play  16.d5?  Bxd5! } 16... Be4 17. Ke2
{ Connecting the rooks. The king on e2 is safe and White has much better rooks. }
