{ 8...b6  9.Qe2  Bb7  10.h4  e6  transposes to 8...e6 } 9. Qe2
{ The queen is ideally placed on e2 in this line, and White keeps flexibility with his king. }
9... b6 10. h4
{ Another useful move which postpones the decision about castling. } 10... Bb7
11. Rh3
{ White activates his rook, and now it is clear that he won't castle kingside.   White shouldn't hurry with castling queenside  11.O-O-O  a6!  with b5-c4 ideas to follow shows the point of 6...Qb6. }
11... O-O-O 12. O-O-O d5
{ 12...h6  13.h5  only helps White, the pawn on g7 will remain there for a very long time. }
13. exd6
{ White's pieces are better prepared for the opening of the position. } 13...
Bxd6 14. Bxd6 Rxd6
{ It may look like Black has solved all opening problems, and even has a potential pawn majority on the kingside. The truth is however, bit different.   White's doubled pawns control squares on the queenside and are securing the white king. Black's pieces are mostly situated on the queenside which means that the kingside pawns can become vulnerable. }
15. Rg3 { Immediately targeting the g7-pawn. } 15... g6 16. h5
{ With Rh1 to follow, White keeps the initiative because his pieces are more active. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Katalimov: 2...b6 / Nimzowitsch: 2..Nf6"]
[Black "Katalimov: 2...b6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 b6
{ From all playable Sicilians this one gives White the easiest play. Black wants to fianchetto his bishop as soon as possible, but there are few obvious drawbacks.   First, the 2...b6 move doesn't really fight for the centre, the pressure on the e4 is neglectable since White can easily defend the e4-pawn.   Secondly, when dealing against the kingside attack in Sicilian, Black always wants to create counterplay with b5-b4, which means that b7-b6 is practically a loss of tempo.   Finally, White has couple of promising lines @@StartBracket@@6. Bg5, 6. Bf4, 6. g3 , 6. Be3, 6. f3@@EndBracket@@ against it, but the 6. Bg5 is the most concrete one. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ Not very compatible with the b6-Bb7 setup. } 6. Bf4
{ Eyeing the weak diagonal in Black's position. 6. Bg5 is also a good developing move, but the text move is more concrete. }
6... Nf6 7. Nxc6 dxc6 8. Qf3
{ With a pawn being on c6, the bishop on b7 is unhappy. } *

