[Black "Katalimov: 2...b6  #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 b6
{ From all playable Sicilians this one gives White the easiest play. Black wants to fianchetto his bishop as soon as possible, but there are few obvious drawbacks.   First, the 2...b6 move doesn't really fight for the centre, the pressure on the e4 is neglectable since White can easily defend the e4-pawn.   Secondly, when dealing against the kingside attack in Sicilian, Black always wants to create counterplay with b5-b4, which means that b7-b6 is practically a loss of tempo.   Finally, White has couple of promising lines @@StartBracket@@6. Bg5, 6. Bf4, 6. g3 , 6. Be3, 6. f3@@EndBracket@@ against it, but the 6. Bg5 is the most concrete one. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Bg5
{ Power play. White develops and gives up a pawn to gain time. } 6... Nxe4
{ if  6...Nc6  then  7.f4  is the simplest, and White has a very good version of the Rauzer attack.  8. e5 or 8. Bxf6 is coming next. }
7. Nxe4 Bxe4
{ Taking the pawn on e4 only helps White to gain time and develop all his pieces. It only brings more troubles for Black. }
8. Qg4 Bd5 { Blocks the d-file, but bishop on d5 will be a target. } 9. O-O-O
Qc8 { Anticipating the Nb5-Nd6 idea. } 10. Nb5 Be6 11. Qe4 Nc6
{ 11...Na6  12.Be2  with Bf3 coming next.  12...Nc5  is impossible because of  13.Qxa8!  Qxa8  14.Nc7+  and White wins a rook. }
12. Bf4 d6 13. Nxd6+ { This is crushing and much stronger than anything else. }
13... exd6 14. Bb5 Kd7 15. Rxd6+
{ White had this move in mind when 13. Nxd6 was played. } 15... Bxd6 16. Rd1
{ Currently White is a rook and a knight down, but Black has no defence and he is completely lost. The bishop on d6 falls, then the knight on c6 and eventually the rook on a8. }
16... f5 17. Qf3 { The bishop from d6 won't go anywhere. } 17... Ke7 18. Bxd6+
Kf7 19. Bxc6
{ White has restored the material balance, and will have an extra pawn at least. Black is in some sort of zugzwang. }
19... h5 { Black needs to cover the h5 square. } 20. Be5
{ Don't hurry! First we improve our pieces and later we'll collect material. }
20... Qf8 21. Bxa8 Qxa8 22. Qg3 Rg8 23. Bc3
{ Black has too many weak squares around his king and the position is dead lost. }
