[White "2) Katalimov: 2...b6 / Nimzowitsch: 2..Nf6"]
[Black "Katalimov: 2...b6  #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 b6
{ From all playable Sicilians this one gives White the easiest play. Black wants to fianchetto his bishop as soon as possible, but there are few obvious drawbacks.   First, the 2...b6 move doesn't really fight for the centre, the pressure on the e4 is neglectable since White can easily defend the e4-pawn.   Secondly, when dealing against the kingside attack in Sicilian, Black always wants to create counterplay with b5-b4, which means that b7-b6 is practically a loss of tempo.   Finally, White has couple of promising lines @@StartBracket@@6. Bg5, 6. Bf4, 6. g3 , 6. Be3, 6. f3@@EndBracket@@ against it, but the 6. Bg5 is the most concrete one. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7 5. Nc3 a6
{ Black has to play this move to cover the b5 square. Now, White will already have 3 developed pieces compared to single black one.   5...e6?!  6.Ndb5!  is the reason why you have to play a6 first. }
6. Bg5 { Stopping e6. } 6... Qc7
{ 6...Nf6  7.e5  creates only more troubles for Black, and   6...h6  7.Bh4  doesn't help him much either. Bishop is no longer hanging on g5 in some lines and after Qc7 it can harass black queen from g3. }
7. Nd5
{ Concrete play. White doesn't allow Black to play e6, and make some sort of Taimanov setup. }
7... Qe5 { Double attack. } 8. Be3 Bxd5
{ Only move, everything else loses.  8...e6?  9.Nf3  Qxe4  10.Nc7+  wins a rook. }
9. exd5 Qxd5 10. Be2 { Developing and creating a threat. } 10... e5
{ Black must react concretely.   10...Qb7?  11.Bf3  Nc6  12.Nxc6  dxc6  13.Qd4±  White will regain one pawn and his two bishops are powerful and ideally placed. This secures him almost a winning advantage. }
11. Nf5
{ Black has too many weaknesses, and White doesn't mind to enter into the endgame with the bishop pair. }
11... Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 g6 { Black will have to play this move sooner or later. }
13. Nd6+ { The knight shouldn't go backwards. } 13... Bxd6 14. Rxd6 Ne7
{ Black gives back material, in order to take the bishop pair. However, this is not enough for equality because the white rook is too active. }
15. Rxb6 Nd5 16. Rb7 Nxe3 17. fxe3
{ Both sides need to finish development and bring the remaining pieces into the play. }
17... Ke7 18. Kf2 Nc6 19. Rd1 Rhd8 20. a3 { Preparing b4. } 20... a5
{ The b5 square is weak now. } 21. Bb5
{ White's pieces are much more active, the bishop is dominant over the knight, and White can easily create a passed pawn which gives him much better chances in this endgame. }
