[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) O'Kelly: 2...a6"]
[Black "2...a6 3.c3 g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Before stepping into the deep woods of Najdorf, Dragon, Sveshnikov, or Rauzer first we need to cover some less popular lines. It seemed natural for me to start from the queenside, and the first decent alternative to the main Sicilians is the  2...a6  .  The so-called O'Kelly variation has never been a popular choice in classical chess, but currently has a strong supporter, the Russian GM Vladislav Artemiev. In the last few years, he has been playing it regularly, especially at the faster time controls.  The simplest explanation of this move would be that it makes  3.d4  ineffective. However, there are some hidden subtleties behind it. White has two good options, the first one is 3.c4, but in those pawn structures, a6 is always useful for Black. Therefore, I have always preferred c3 since it asks the question: how does 2...a6 fights for the centre? }
2... a6 3. c3
{ Black again has a couple of options, the critical ones are  3...e6  and  3...d5  , in my opinion, but  3...Nf6  and  3...g6  are not trivial.   Black's main idea is to counter  3.d4  with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  followed by Bb4 and/or d5 with comfortable equality.   In case you forgot this trick or simply premove 3.d4 then I would advise you to play  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  with the following plan: Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1 @@StartBracket@@h3@@EndBracket@@, etc. Also, 4.c3 might be very interesting since White will get a favourable version of the Morra gambit. }
3... g6
{ The first playable option for Black, although White has many different ways to obtain the advantage.   3...b5  in the spirit of A. Miles, gives up the centre and any hopes to equalize.  4.d4  Bb7  5.Bd3  We can stop here. White has many interesting plans which give him better chances. The most classical one is to castle, play  Re1  , reroute the knight from  b1  , probably to  g3  .   3...Nc6  A perfect example of a natural move that is not good; now a6 just becomes a waste of time.  4.d4  cxd4?!   4...d5  is objectively the best.  5.exd5  Qxd5  6.Be3  transposes to 3...d5 after 4.exd5 Qxd5 5.d4 Nc6.  5.cxd4  Is already a big trouble for Black.  5...e6  6.d5!  Bb4+  7.Nc3  Nce7  8.Qd4  White has a big advantage. Black has to give up the bishop pair and he has problems with the dark squares.   3...d6  Totally useless in combination with a6.  4.d4 }
4. d4 {  } 4... cxd4
{ 4...Bg7  is just bad. Black loses a pawn and would be happier with the pawn being on a7.   This is an inferior version of the line starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  g6  3.d4  Bg7  which will be covered in Chapter  3.  5.dxc5  Nf6  6.Be3!  Nxe4  7.Nbd2  Nxd2   7...Nf6  8.Nc4  That's the problem with  a6!  8.Qxd2  White has an overwhelming advantage. He controls the central squares @@StartBracket@@note how the pawn on c5 stops b6 and d6 and restricts the black pieces@@EndBracket@@, has more active pieces and his plan is simple: O-O-O, h4 and attack on the kingside.   4...d5  This is not how chess works.  5.dxc5  Nf6  6.exd5  Qxd5  7.Qxd5  Nxd5  Black has absolutely no compensation for the pawn. }
5. cxd4
{ The only problem I'm having in this position with the white pieces is too many good options. However, I must warn you that White only has a slight advantage in most of the lines, and to win the game you will have to play good moves.   5.Bc4!?  is an interesting alternative, a pawn sacrifice that helps White to control the centre and obtain the initiative. For example  5...e6  6.Bb3!?   6.cxd4  d5  is good for Black.  6...dxc3  7.Nxc3  Bg7  8.h4!?  Nf6  9.h5  Nxh5  10.e5  f5  11.Bg5  Qa5  12.Qe2  Nc6  13.O-O-O  with huge attacking chances. In a practical game, only a miracle can save Black. This line is not forced and it serves as an illustration of what might happen. }
5... d5
{ The only move that fights for the centre.   5...Bg7  6.Nc3  d6  7.h3  Nf6  8.Bd3  O-O  9.O-O  White gets the typical advantage due to his central pawns. }
6. e5
{ Probably the simplest and the best solution.   Eventually, I gave up on  6.exd5  Nf6  7.Nc3  Bg7  8.Qb3  Nbd7  followed by Nb6-Nbxd5 gives Black a decent position, although White still keeps some pressure.   I really wanted to refute the line with  6.Qa4  but Black has some amazing resources.  6...Bd7  7.Qb3  dxe4   7...e6  8.exd5  exd5  9.Qxd5  is a pawn up for White.  8.Ng5  e6  9.d5  Nf6  10.dxe6  fxe6  11.Qxb7  Bc5!  12.Nc3  O-O  13.Bc4  Kh8  and this is only the beginning of the craziness. }
6... Nc6 7. Be2
{ 7.h3  and  7.Bd3  are equally good alternatives. I've chosen  7.Be2  because it anticipates the Bg4 pin and develops the bishop, basically has the function of both alternatives. }
7... Bg7 8. O-O Bg4
{ When the opponent has a spatial advantage, it is a good idea to trade a few pieces. Black's light-squared bishop is his worst piece and he is happy to exchange it.   8...f6  9.Nc3  is another reason why the bishop is good on e2. Black can't afford himself to open up the position and trade the e5 pawn for the d5 since he lags in development. }
9. Nbd2 { Before playing h3 we want to recapture on f3 with the knight. } 9...
e6 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 Nge7 12. Bd3
{ The bishop has done its job on the d1-h5 diagonal and now we are improving it. Also, in the case of Nf5 Black always has to consider Bxf5. }
12... O-O 13. Re1 { White has excellent attacking chances on the kingside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) O'Kelly: 2...a6"]
[Black "2...a6 3.c3 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Before stepping into the deep woods of Najdorf, Dragon, Sveshnikov, or Rauzer first we need to cover some less popular lines. It seemed natural for me to start from the queenside, and the first decent alternative to the main Sicilians is the  2...a6  .  The so-called O'Kelly variation has never been a popular choice in classical chess, but currently has a strong supporter, the Russian GM Vladislav Artemiev. In the last few years, he has been playing it regularly, especially at the faster time controls.  The simplest explanation of this move would be that it makes  3.d4  ineffective. However, there are some hidden subtleties behind it. White has two good options, the first one is 3.c4, but in those pawn structures, a6 is always useful for Black. Therefore, I have always preferred c3 since it asks the question: how does 2...a6 fights for the centre? }
2... a6 3. c3
{ Black again has a couple of options, the critical ones are  3...e6  and  3...d5  , in my opinion, but  3...Nf6  and  3...g6  are not trivial.   Black's main idea is to counter  3.d4  with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  followed by Bb4 and/or d5 with comfortable equality.   In case you forgot this trick or simply premove 3.d4 then I would advise you to play  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  with the following plan: Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1 @@StartBracket@@h3@@EndBracket@@, etc. Also, 4.c3 might be very interesting since White will get a favourable version of the Morra gambit. }
3... Nf6
{ When playing against the Alapin - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.c3  ,  2...Nf6  is one of the best black responses, and personally my favorite. However, with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  included this is not the case. White gets the development advantage and can quickly materialize it. }
4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 e6 6. c4 { There are no good squares for the black knight. }
6... Ne7
{ 6...Nb6  7.Be3  The knight is feeling loose on  b6  already.  7...cxd4  8.Qxd4  Na4  9.Qd1!  We keep harassing the knight.  9...Qa5  10.Bd2  Bb4  11.Qc2  White's pieces will be harmoniously developed, and Black still hasn't solved the problem with his knight. He doesn't have time to take on e5, because after a3-b4 he will lose a piece. }
7. dxc5 { 7.d5  is an equally good alternative. } 7... Nbc6 8. Nc3 Ng6 9. Be3
{ The e5-pawn can't be defended in a good way, so we protect the c5-pawn and prepare for harmonious development. }
9... Ncxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. f4 Nc6 12. Qd2 d6 13. cxd6 Qxd6 14. Qf2
{ The dark squares are weak in the black camp, and his queen is a target. }
14... e5 15. Rd1
{ With a clear advantage for White, Black has too many weak squares on the queenside. }
*

