{ When playing against the Alapin - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.c3  ,  2...Nf6  is one of the best black responses, and personally my favorite. However, with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  included this is not the case. White gets the development advantage and can quickly materialize it. }
4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 e6 6. c4 { There are no good squares for the black knight. }
6... Ne7
{ 6...Nb6  7.Be3  The knight is feeling loose on  b6  already.  7...cxd4  8.Qxd4  Na4  9.Qd1!  We keep harassing the knight.  9...Qa5  10.Bd2  Bb4  11.Qc2  White's pieces will be harmoniously developed, and Black still hasn't solved the problem with his knight. He doesn't have time to take on e5, because after a3-b4 he will lose a piece. }
7. dxc5 { 7.d5  is an equally good alternative. } 7... Ng6 8. Be3 Qc7 9. Nc3
{ White simply develops his pieces. } 9... Bxc5 10. Bxc5 Qxc5 11. Qd6
{ The weak dark squares are something Black can't get rid of. In the endgame, it could even become more obvious. }
11... b6 12. b4 Qxd6 13. exd6 Nc6 14. a3
{ The pawn on d6 is too strong, and Black will have to be careful on the queenside, for example,  14...Bb7  runs into  15.Na4  . White is clearly better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) O'Kelly: 2...a6"]
[Black "2...a6 3.c3 Nf6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Before stepping into the deep woods of Najdorf, Dragon, Sveshnikov, or Rauzer first we need to cover some less popular lines. It seemed natural for me to start from the queenside, and the first decent alternative to the main Sicilians is the  2...a6  .  The so-called O'Kelly variation has never been a popular choice in classical chess, but currently has a strong supporter, the Russian GM Vladislav Artemiev. In the last few years, he has been playing it regularly, especially at the faster time controls.  The simplest explanation of this move would be that it makes  3.d4  ineffective. However, there are some hidden subtleties behind it. White has two good options, the first one is 3.c4, but in those pawn structures, a6 is always useful for Black. Therefore, I have always preferred c3 since it asks the question: how does 2...a6 fights for the centre? }
2... a6 3. c3
{ Black again has a couple of options, the critical ones are  3...e6  and  3...d5  , in my opinion, but  3...Nf6  and  3...g6  are not trivial.   Black's main idea is to counter  3.d4  with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  followed by Bb4 and/or d5 with comfortable equality.   In case you forgot this trick or simply premove 3.d4 then I would advise you to play  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  with the following plan: Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1 @@StartBracket@@h3@@EndBracket@@, etc. Also, 4.c3 might be very interesting since White will get a favourable version of the Morra gambit. }
3... Nf6
{ When playing against the Alapin - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.c3  ,  2...Nf6  is one of the best black responses, and personally my favorite. However, with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  included this is not the case. White gets the development advantage and can quickly materialize it. }
4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4
{ Before playing anything else, Black always includes cxd4, so he doesn't have to worry about any c3-c4 ideas.   5...d6?!  is also bad, Black shouldn't allow  6.c4 }
6. Bc4
{ We really aren't afraid of this pawn sacrifice, actually, we would prefer that Black accepts it since it gives big attacking prospects, sometimes even gives White a forced win. }
6... Nb6
{ The text move is played way more often, but gives White tremendous attacking chances. The general problem Black faces in most of the following lines is that knight on b6 has no future, and with the pawn being on a6 it often becomes a target. }
7. Bb3 e6
{ This move neutralizes the white bishop on b3, but weakens the important d6 square. }
8. Bg5 Qc7
{ 8...Be7?!  Weakens the dark squares more and leaves the knight on  b6  hanging.  9.Bxe7  Qxe7  10.Qxd4  Capturing with a tempo.  10...Qd8  11.Nbd2  O-O  12.Ne4  f6  13.O-O-O  White is dominating. He has ideally placed pieces, unlike Black. Just take a look at Black's queenside. }
9. O-O Nc6
{ Is the lesser evil.   9...dxc3?!  The queen on c7 isn't thrilled about the opening of the c-file. Also, White gets an extra developing tempo.  10.Nxc3  Nc6  11.Ne4!  Going for the  d6  square; currently, the pawns aren't important.  11...Nxe5  12.Nxe5  Qxe5  13.Re1  Black doesn't have a good square for his queen.  13...Qa5  14.Bd2  Bb4  15.Nd6+  Ke7  16.Re5!!  Deflection, a beautiful finish. }
10. cxd4 d5 11. exd6 Bxd6 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Re1
{ With a typical 'isolani' type of position, where the black pieces are a bit too far from his king. }
*

