3... Nf6
{ When playing against the Alapin - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.c3  ,  2...Nf6  is one of the best black responses, and personally my favorite. However, with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  included this is not the case. White gets the development advantage and can quickly materialize it. }
4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4
{ Before playing anything else, Black always includes cxd4, so he doesn't have to worry about any c3-c4 ideas.   5...d6?!  is also bad, Black shouldn't allow  6.c4 }
6. Bc4
{ We really aren't afraid of this pawn sacrifice, actually, we would prefer that Black accepts it since it gives big attacking prospects, sometimes even gives White a forced win. }
6... Nb6
{ The text move is played way more often, but gives White tremendous attacking chances. The general problem Black faces in most of the following lines is that knight on b6 has no future, and with the pawn being on a6 it often becomes a target. }
7. Bb3 d5
{ 7...dxc3?  Such greediness must lose by force.  8.Ng5!  The most direct.   8.Nxc3  is also good.  8...e6   8...d5  9.exd6  e6  10.Qh5!  Creating further weaknesses @@StartBracket@@the f6-square@@EndBracket@@ on the kingside.  10...g6  11.Qf3  Black can't parry all the threats.  9.Qh5  Qe7  10.Nxc3  Regaining one pawn and preparing to jump on d6.  10...g6  11.Qh3  Bg7  12.f4  White's attack is too powerful: the weak squares d6 and f6, the inability to castle, and the unstable position of the knight on b6 are the obvious reasons.   7...d6  8.exd6  is the same thing as 7...d5. }
8. exd6 { Is the same thing as 7...d5 } 8... e6
{ 8...exd6  9.Nxd4  and the d6-pawn will remain an eternal weakness. White will have a very favourable version of the isolani structure. }
9. Nbd2
{ A novelty! I really like this move, White postpones his decision about taking on d4. More important is to improve the knight from b1.   9.cxd4  is usually played, with the typical attacking chances in an isolani type of position.  9...Bxd6  10.Nc3  Nc6  11.O-O  O-O  12.Qd3!?  White is better here. }
9... Bxd6
{ 9...dxc3?  The pawn on d6 is too important. We can conclude that in the whole system with 3...Nf6 it is almost always bad for Black to capture on c3.  10.Ne4  N8d7  11.Bg5  Nf6  12.Qd4  White is dominating, and the d6 pawn is too powerful. }
10. Ne4 O-O 11. Bg5
{ 11.Nxd6  Qxd6  12.Qxd4  Qxd4  13.Nxd4  is also possible, with the typical bishop pair advantage in the endgame. }
11... Be7 { Otherwise 12. Qxd4 } 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Qxd4
{ We took on d4 with tempo and Black has to move his knight again. } 13... Nd5
{ Four moves with the g8-knight and 0 with the b8-knight. } 14. O-O-O Nc6 15.
Qc5 { Going into a clearly better endgame. } 15... Qxc5 16. Nxc5
{ With a risk-free advantage in the endgame. White controls the d-file, and the biggest problem for Black is his bishop on the initial square. The position looks like a bad version of the 3...dxe4 French for Black. }
