[Round "?"]
[White "3) O'Kelly: 2...a6"]
[Black "2...a6 3.c3 d5 with 4...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Before stepping into the deep woods of Najdorf, Dragon, Sveshnikov, or Rauzer first we need to cover some less popular lines. It seemed natural for me to start from the queenside, and the first decent alternative to the main Sicilians is the  2...a6  .  The so-called O'Kelly variation has never been a popular choice in classical chess, but currently has a strong supporter, the Russian GM Vladislav Artemiev. In the last few years, he has been playing it regularly, especially at the faster time controls.  The simplest explanation of this move would be that it makes  3.d4  ineffective. However, there are some hidden subtleties behind it. White has two good options, the first one is 3.c4, but in those pawn structures, a6 is always useful for Black. Therefore, I have always preferred c3 since it asks the question: how does 2...a6 fights for the centre? }
2... a6 3. c3
{ Black again has a couple of options, the critical ones are  3...e6  and  3...d5  , in my opinion, but  3...Nf6  and  3...g6  are not trivial.   Black's main idea is to counter  3.d4  with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  followed by Bb4 and/or d5 with comfortable equality.   In case you forgot this trick or simply premove 3.d4 then I would advise you to play  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  with the following plan: Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1 @@StartBracket@@h3@@EndBracket@@, etc. Also, 4.c3 might be very interesting since White will get a favourable version of the Morra gambit. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Nf6 5. d4
{ 5.Qa4  is equally good.  The thing about the lines arising after 4...Nf6 is that White will probably be a pawn up at some point and the variations that arise after 5.d4 have a bigger tendency of queen trading than the ones after 5.Qa4.   As we have all learned from the beginner books, if you have a material advantage you should trade pieces, especially queens. Therefore, from a practical point of view, I chose 5.d4 over 5.Qa4. }
5... Nxd5 6. dxc5 { Whenever the c5-pawn is hanging, you should take it. } 6...
e6 7. b4 a5
{ A typical reaction to b4, undermining White's pawn structure and opening the a-file. }
8. Qb3
{ Defending the pawn and developing the queen. Note that a3 doesn't defend the pawn due to a pin along the a-file. }
8... Be7 9. Bb5+
{ Developing with a check, we also have a material advantage and we don't mind trading a few pieces. }
9... Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. a3 { Overprotecting b4 and preparing for c3-c4. }
11... axb4 12. cxb4 b6 13. Nbd2
{ White could try to keep the pawn, but he has a better solution. He gives back material in order to have two connected passed pawns and to gain some time to develop the queenside. }
13... bxc5
{ Black has returned the material balance, but we are having two outside passed pawns.   13...Qb5  14.cxb6  Nxb6  15.Bb2  O-O  16.Rc1  N8d7  17.Nd4  I don't see any compensation for Black. }
14. b5 Nb6 15. Bb2
{ If  15.a4  c4!  16.Nxc4  Qd5  gives Black counter chances. } 15... Qd5
{ Black must stop a3-a4 at any cost. In case of  15..O-O  16.a4  White has a big advantage because of his passed pawns. }
16. Qc2 { We will trade the queens only under favourable circumstances. } 16...
Qf5 { 16...O-O  17.a4  As Ivanchuk would say, the pawns just go. } 17. Qxf5
exf5 18. Bxg7 Rg8 19. Be5 N8d7
{ 19...Rxg2  20.Bg3  and Kf1 next, so Black doesn't have an alternative. } 20.
O-O
{ Engines are claiming that White is only slightly better, but to me, it looks like a huge advantage. White is still a pawn up and his pressure on the e-file could mean something. }
