{ White would like to take on c4 with the bishop and develop one more piece, but Black has Nb6 which regains the material balance. }
10... Nc5 11. Nxd4
{ We have entered into an endgame almost by force where White is a pawn up. Black has some compensation, but not enough. }
11... e6 12. Nc3 Nfe4
{ 12...exd5  I wouldn't recommend it because it frees the c4 square for the white bishop.  13.Nxd5!  Nxd5  14.cxd5  Bb7  15.Bc4  Rd8  16.Nc6  and the pawn now really makes the difference. Black will have to take that knight, and then the bishop from c4 becomes strong. }
13. Nxe4 Nxe4
{ Trading pieces looks counterintuitive for Black, but he has created the threat of Bb4. }
14. f3 Bb4+ 15. Ke2
{ 15...Bc3  16.Rb1  doesn't change much, because both knights are hanging. }
15... Nc3+ 16. Kd3
{ White keeps an extra pawn.   16...exd5  loses to  17.Bd2  dxc4  18.Kxc4  and Black has no checks. }
