[Black "2...a6 3.c3 d5 with 4...Qxd5 and 5...Nc6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Before stepping into the deep woods of Najdorf, Dragon, Sveshnikov, or Rauzer first we need to cover some less popular lines. It seemed natural for me to start from the queenside, and the first decent alternative to the main Sicilians is the  2...a6  .  The so-called O'Kelly variation has never been a popular choice in classical chess, but currently has a strong supporter, the Russian GM Vladislav Artemiev. In the last few years, he has been playing it regularly, especially at the faster time controls.  The simplest explanation of this move would be that it makes  3.d4  ineffective. However, there are some hidden subtleties behind it. White has two good options, the first one is 3.c4, but in those pawn structures, a6 is always useful for Black. Therefore, I have always preferred c3 since it asks the question: how does 2...a6 fights for the centre? }
2... a6 3. c3
{ Black again has a couple of options, the critical ones are  3...e6  and  3...d5  , in my opinion, but  3...Nf6  and  3...g6  are not trivial.   Black's main idea is to counter  3.d4  with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  followed by Bb4 and/or d5 with comfortable equality.   In case you forgot this trick or simply premove 3.d4 then I would advise you to play  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  with the following plan: Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1 @@StartBracket@@h3@@EndBracket@@, etc. Also, 4.c3 might be very interesting since White will get a favourable version of the Morra gambit. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Nc6 6. Be3 cxd4
{ 6...Bg4  7.dxc5  A free pawn.  7...Qxd1  8.Kxd1  O-O-O  9.Kc1  Nf6  10.Nbd2  White is a clear pawn up. }
7. cxd4 e5
{ Swapping the central pawns doesn't solve black troubles.  7...e6  8.Nc3  transposing into 5...e6 is the best choice for Black. }
8. Nc3 Bb4 9. dxe5 Nge7
{ Now we just play simple moves.  9...Qxd1  10.Rxd1  gives White a pawn. } 10.
Be2 Qa5 11. O-O O-O 12. Ne4
{ Not a simple move, but with a simple threat, @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p2nppp/p1n5/q3P3/1b2N3/4BN2/PP2BPPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 6 12@@EndFEN@@  13.a3  . }
12... Ng6
{ 12...Nf5  13.Bf4  Rd8  14.Bd3  White keeps the pawn and has some tactical motifs connected with Nd6.   12...Nxe5??  13.a3  wins the bishop. }
13. a3 Be7 14. b4 { Gaining some time and space. } 14... Qc7 15. Nc3
{ Takes the bishop pair by force, in a way it converts one advantage into another.  15.Rc1  or  15.Nfd2!?  followed by f4 are alternatives. }
15... Be6
{ Only move, Black can't take the pawn immediately.   15...Ngxe5?  16.Nd5  Nxf3  17.Bxf3  Qe5  18.Nxe7  Nxe7  19.Bc5  Re8  20.Re1  Qc7  21.Qd6+- }
16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. Qxd5 Rad8 { Before taking on e5 Black activates his rook. }
18. Qe4 Ngxe5 19. Nxe5
{ It is also possible to play  19.Rac1  , but the text move is the simplest solution. }
19... Qxe5 20. Qxe5 Nxe5 21. Rac1
{ Black has an unpleasant task defending this seemingly simple endgame. The queenside pawns on the light squares are an ideal target for the white bishop. }
