{ Before stepping into the deep woods of Najdorf, Dragon, Sveshnikov, or Rauzer first we need to cover some less popular lines. It seemed natural for me to start from the queenside, and the first decent alternative to the main Sicilians is the  2...a6  .  The so-called O'Kelly variation has never been a popular choice in classical chess, but currently has a strong supporter, the Russian GM Vladislav Artemiev. In the last few years, he has been playing it regularly, especially at the faster time controls.  The simplest explanation of this move would be that it makes  3.d4  ineffective. However, there are some hidden subtleties behind it. White has two good options, the first one is 3.c4, but in those pawn structures, a6 is always useful for Black. Therefore, I have always preferred c3 since it asks the question: how does 2...a6 fights for the centre? }
2... a6 3. c3
{ Black again has a couple of options, the critical ones are  3...e6  and  3...d5  , in my opinion, but  3...Nf6  and  3...g6  are not trivial.   Black's main idea is to counter  3.d4  with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  followed by Bb4 and/or d5 with comfortable equality.   In case you forgot this trick or simply premove 3.d4 then I would advise you to play  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  with the following plan: Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1 @@StartBracket@@h3@@EndBracket@@, etc. Also, 4.c3 might be very interesting since White will get a favourable version of the Morra gambit. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Bg4
{ Black wants to activate his bishop before playing e6. In his ideal scenario, he will manage to develop all his pieces with Nf6, e6, Nc6, Be7, and finally castle. However, White will not allow that. }
6. Be2 e6 7. O-O
{ White plays the simplest moves first before deciding what to do in the centre. }
7... Nf6 8. h3
{ Before taking any concrete decisions it is always useful to include h3, because giving the bishop pair is not an option for Black. }
8... Bh5
{ 8...Bf5  is as bad as it looks.  9.Nbd2!  Nc6  10.Nc4  Qd8  When the opponent plays backward moves in the opening, it's the right time for active moves.  11.Nfe5!  cxd4  12.Nxc6  bxc6  13.Qa4  Rc8  14.cxd4  White will collect the a6-pawn. }
9. c4
{ This move has been played rarely, mostly because White players didn't have the right follow-up.  9.Be3  has always been considered as slightly better for White. It is true, but I believe White can strive for more. }
9... Qd8 10. d5
{ The point of 9. c4 and the idea which can refute the whole 5...Bg4 concept. }
10... exd5 11. cxd5
{ If Black doesn't accept the pawn sacrifice he is worse, he lacks space, and White's d-pawn is strong. }
11... Qxd5
{ 11...Nxd5??  12.Qb3  is already winning for White; 13.Qxb7 and 13.Rd1 are deadly threats.  12...b5   12...Nb6  13.Bg5  Qc7  14.Re1  So many tactical shots are undefendable.  13.Rd1  c4  14.Bxc4!  bxc4  15.Qxc4  Bxf3  16.gxf3  White will at least be a pawn up. Just take a look at Black's pieces on the back rank. }
12. g4
{ 12.Re1  is also possible and should transpose, but I don't want to allow Bxf3 at some point although it doesn't help Black. }
12... Bg6 { 12...Qxd1  13.Bxd1  Bg6  14.Re1  transposes. } 13. Re1 Qxd1
{ 13...Be7  14.Nc3  Qxd1  15.Bxd1  also transposes. } 14. Bxd1+
{ At first sight it looks completely ridiculous why would White play like this. He gave up a pawn and has all pieces besides one knight on the first rank. It is a temporary illusion because all those pieces in one move will acquire their ideal squares. Even more surprising is that he has a dangerous attack. transposes. }
14... Be7
{ 14...Kd8  Black avoids the pin along the e-file but puts his king to an unfortunate square.  15.Bf4  Nd5  16.Bg3  Nd7  17.Bb3  Nb4  18.Nc3  White's rooks are killing it, in fact, all White's pieces are active. }
15. Nc3 Nc6 16. Ba4
{ The key move which makes the whole white concept starting from 9.c4 effective. With every single move from this moment, White stops Black from castling. }
16... Kf8 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Ne5 Bd6
{ 18...Rc8!  19.f4!  h5  20.f5  Bh7  The bishop is spiritually dead.  21.Bg5  hxg4  22.hxg4  Everyone's dream position, but not for Black! Now you just need to trade all your pieces. }
19. Nxc6
{ It is time to return the pawn.   19.f4  h5  20.f5  Bh7  isn't effective now, the g4-pawn is hanging. }
19... Rc8 20. Ne5 Bxe5 21. Rxe5 h5 22. g5
{ We don't want to allow an opening of the h-file, but 22.f3 is worth considering because it restricts Black's light pieces. }
22... Nd7 23. Rd5 Nb6 24. Rd6 Nc4 25. Rxa6
{ With a healthy @@StartBracket@@passed!@@EndBracket@@ pawn advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) O'Kelly: 2...a6"]
[Black "2...a6 3.c3 d5 with 4...Qxd5 and 5...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Before stepping into the deep woods of Najdorf, Dragon, Sveshnikov, or Rauzer first we need to cover some less popular lines. It seemed natural for me to start from the queenside, and the first decent alternative to the main Sicilians is the  2...a6  .  The so-called O'Kelly variation has never been a popular choice in classical chess, but currently has a strong supporter, the Russian GM Vladislav Artemiev. In the last few years, he has been playing it regularly, especially at the faster time controls.  The simplest explanation of this move would be that it makes  3.d4  ineffective. However, there are some hidden subtleties behind it. White has two good options, the first one is 3.c4, but in those pawn structures, a6 is always useful for Black. Therefore, I have always preferred c3 since it asks the question: how does 2...a6 fights for the centre? }
2... a6 3. c3
{ Black again has a couple of options, the critical ones are  3...e6  and  3...d5  , in my opinion, but  3...Nf6  and  3...g6  are not trivial.   Black's main idea is to counter  3.d4  with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  followed by Bb4 and/or d5 with comfortable equality.   In case you forgot this trick or simply premove 3.d4 then I would advise you to play  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  with the following plan: Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1 @@StartBracket@@h3@@EndBracket@@, etc. Also, 4.c3 might be very interesting since White will get a favourable version of the Morra gambit. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6
{ The main move and Artemiev's favorite choice.   5...e6  6.Be3  cxd4  7.cxd4  Ng6  8.Nc3  transposes to 5...Nf6.   5...Bf5  f5  is not the right square for the black bishop.  6.Nbd2!  e6   6...cxd4?!  7.Bc4  Qd6  8.Qb3  White wins material.  7.Nc4  Nc6   7...Qd8  8.Bg5  8.Ne3  Planning to take the bishop on f5.  8...Qe4  9.Nd2  We keep attacking the queen to force Black to recapture with the pawn on f5.  9...Qh4  10.Nxf5  exf5  11.Nf3  Qe7+  12.Be2  The bishop pair, better development, and a passed d-pawn guarantee a big advantage. }
6. Be3
{ We are threatening 7.dxc5 and forcing Black to capture on d4, so that we can put a knight on c3, and develop the bishop on d3 without worries about the d4 pawn. }
6... Bg4 { Loses a pawn. } 7. dxc5 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Nd5
{ 8...e5 9.h3 is similar, White keeps an extra pawn. } 9. h3
{ Grabbing the bishop first, before taking any future decisions. } 9... Bxf3+
10. gxf3 e6 11. b4 a5 12. Bc4
{ The knight on d5 is the strongest black piece and needs to be removed. Indirectly, White defends the b4-pawn. }
12... Nxe3+
{ 12...Nc6  13.Bxd5  exd5  14.Re1  Indirectly defending the pawn and bringing the rook into the game.  14...O-O-O  15.a3  and similarly to the previous lines, White is a pawn up. Now,  axb4  is almost never an option for Black, since it opens the a-file for the white rook.   12...axb4  13.Bxd5  Taking off the strong knight.  13...exd5  14.cxb4  Nc6  15.Bd2!  Followed by a4-Na3; White is a pawn up, and will certainly create a passed pawn on the queenside. }
13. fxe3 axb4 14. Bb5+
{ An important intermezzo.   14.cxb4  Nc6  15.Bb5  O-O-O  is the reason why we play 14.Bb5+ first. }
14... Nc6 15. Bxc6+ { The knight has to be destroyed with check. } 15... bxc6
16. cxb4 { Leaves White a pawn up. } *

