6. Be3
{ We are threatening 7.dxc5 and forcing Black to capture on d4, so that we can put a knight on c3, and develop the bishop on d3 without worries about the d4 pawn. }
6... e6 7. dxc5 { A free pawn. } 7... Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Nc6 9. Nbd2
{ 9.b4  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2Pq4/8/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  8.b4  Qxd1+  9.Kxd1  . }
9... Nd5
{ 9...Ng4?  The bishop on e3 is not that important.  10.b4  a5  11.Bb5  White is not only a pawn up, but his pieces are also better placed. His rooks will be connected soon @@StartBracket@@Ke2 or Kc2@@EndBracket@@, and he practically has a winning position. }
10. Bd4 { An important move, otherwise White's advantage is small. } 10... Nxd4
{ 10...f6  with the idea of playing e5 11.Bc4! Afterwards, White can simply take on d5 with a clear advantage. }
11. cxd4 b6 12. cxb6 Rb8 13. Rc1 Nxb6 14. Bd3
{ We are a pawn up in the endgame. } *

