[White "3) O'Kelly: 2...a6"]
[Black "2...a6 3.c3 d5 with 4...Qxd5 and 5...Nf6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Before stepping into the deep woods of Najdorf, Dragon, Sveshnikov, or Rauzer first we need to cover some less popular lines. It seemed natural for me to start from the queenside, and the first decent alternative to the main Sicilians is the  2...a6  .  The so-called O'Kelly variation has never been a popular choice in classical chess, but currently has a strong supporter, the Russian GM Vladislav Artemiev. In the last few years, he has been playing it regularly, especially at the faster time controls.  The simplest explanation of this move would be that it makes  3.d4  ineffective. However, there are some hidden subtleties behind it. White has two good options, the first one is 3.c4, but in those pawn structures, a6 is always useful for Black. Therefore, I have always preferred c3 since it asks the question: how does 2...a6 fights for the centre? }
2... a6 3. c3
{ Black again has a couple of options, the critical ones are  3...e6  and  3...d5  , in my opinion, but  3...Nf6  and  3...g6  are not trivial.   Black's main idea is to counter  3.d4  with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  followed by Bb4 and/or d5 with comfortable equality.   In case you forgot this trick or simply premove 3.d4 then I would advise you to play  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  with the following plan: Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1 @@StartBracket@@h3@@EndBracket@@, etc. Also, 4.c3 might be very interesting since White will get a favourable version of the Morra gambit. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6
{ The main move and Artemiev's favorite choice.   5...e6  6.Be3  cxd4  7.cxd4  Ng6  8.Nc3  transposes to 5...Nf6.   5...Bf5  f5  is not the right square for the black bishop.  6.Nbd2!  e6   6...cxd4?!  7.Bc4  Qd6  8.Qb3  White wins material.  7.Nc4  Nc6   7...Qd8  8.Bg5  8.Ne3  Planning to take the bishop on f5.  8...Qe4  9.Nd2  We keep attacking the queen to force Black to recapture with the pawn on f5.  9...Qh4  10.Nxf5  exf5  11.Nf3  Qe7+  12.Be2  The bishop pair, better development, and a passed d-pawn guarantee a big advantage. }
6. Be3
{ We are threatening 7.dxc5 and forcing Black to capture on d4, so that we can put a knight on c3, and develop the bishop on d3 without worries about the d4 pawn. }
6... cxd4 7. cxd4 e6 8. Nc3
{ Black has to decide where to put his queen: d6, d8, or a5. Just like in the Scandinavian. They all have equal value according to silicon monsters, so it is a matter of taste. Black can also play Bb4, but eventually, he will have to give up bishop pair with almost no compensation for it. }
8... Qd6
{ Normally, the black bishop goes to e7, so this looks like the most logical follow-up. The queen on d6, together with the knight on c6 controls the e5 square which is important since White would like to jump on e5. Also, the pawn on a6 is useful since it stops Nb5 and Black will often play b5 followed by Bb7. }
9. Bd3 Nc6
{ 9...Be7  10.O-O  Nbd7  Black wants the Nbd7-b5-Bb7 setup, but the knight on c6 looks more natural. The knight on d7 doesn't target the d4 pawn and we can use that by playing  11.Ng5!?  Ne4 is the idea, and the queen can go to f3.  11...O-O  12.Qf3  Stopping b5 and bringing the queen closer to the black king. White has nice attacking prospects on the kingside. }
10. Ne4
{ This move probably has an equal value as  10.O-O  ,  but I want to provoke Black to take on b2. It is a matter of taste, if you don't want to give the pawn on b2 then 10.O-O is your option.   The positional background of this move is that it exchanges an important defender in Black's camp @@StartBracket@@the knight on f6@@EndBracket@@ for the knight on c3, which is a bit far from the black king. Also, when the knight disappears from c3, the c-file becomes open to the white rook. }
10... Nxe4
{ 10...Qb4?!  looks dubious to me, so many queen moves in the opening shouldn't pass unpunished.  11.Bd2  Qxb2  12.Nxf6  gxf6  13.O-O  All White's pieces are developed and Black still has 5 passive pieces on the starting rank. White is probably winning here. }
11. Bxe4 Qb4+
{ White has a pleasant choice: the safer  12.Nd2  , or the ambitious  12.Bd2 }
12. Bd2
{ 12.Nd2!?  doesn't give up the pawn.  12...Qxb2?  13.O-O  With the knight on d2, Nc4 is a serious threat.  13...Na5  The knight on the edge of the board sounds alarming.  14.Rb1  Qa3  15.Qh5  Be7  16.Rfc1  White has too much for the price of a meaningless pawn. }
12... Qxb2
{ The reason I'm giving so many options for White is to prove that White can almost play anything and have more than enough compensation for the pawn. }
13. Rc1
{ With the idea of Rxc6.   13.O-O  Castling is also good.  13...Be7  14.Qa4!?   14...Qb5  15.Qc2  ,  b5  is an awkward square for the queen.  14...O-O  15.Rab1  Qa3  16.Qc2  h6  17.Bxc6  bxc6  18.Rb3  No need to hurry with capturing the pawns.  18...Qd6  19.Ne5  gives White nice attacking chances, his pieces are much more active. }
13... Qb6
{ 13...Nxd4?!  loses by force.  14.Rb1  Nxf3  15.Qxf3  Now it is a good thing that we have the king on e1 defending the bishop on d2!  15...Qxa2  16.Bxc6!  bxc6  17.Qxc6  Ke7  18.Rd1!   A silent move that creates a couple of threats: 19.Bg5 is the first, while taking the rook is the second; and  18...Qd5  loses after  19.Bb4+  . Black has no defence.  18...Rb8  19.Bg5+  f6  20.Qc7  Ke8  21.Rd8 }
14. O-O
{ White has finished his development while Black hasn't done anything. } *

