{ 9...Be7  10.O-O  Nbd7  Black wants the Nbd7-b5-Bb7 setup, but the knight on c6 looks more natural. The knight on d7 doesn't target the d4 pawn and we can use that by playing  11.Ng5!?  Ne4 is the idea, and the queen can go to f3.  11...O-O  12.Qf3  Stopping b5 and bringing the queen closer to the black king. White has nice attacking prospects on the kingside. }
10. Ne4
{ This move probably has an equal value as  10.O-O  ,  but I want to provoke Black to take on b2. It is a matter of taste, if you don't want to give the pawn on b2 then 10.O-O is your option.   The positional background of this move is that it exchanges an important defender in Black's camp @@StartBracket@@the knight on f6@@EndBracket@@ for the knight on c3, which is a bit far from the black king. Also, when the knight disappears from c3, the c-file becomes open to the white rook. }
10... Nxe4
{ 10...Qb4?!  looks dubious to me, so many queen moves in the opening shouldn't pass unpunished.  11.Bd2  Qxb2  12.Nxf6  gxf6  13.O-O  All White's pieces are developed and Black still has 5 passive pieces on the starting rank. White is probably winning here. }
11. Bxe4 Be7 12. O-O Nb4
{ Before castling Black improves his knight first. The knight is great on d5, but it doesn't control the e5 square. }
13. Ne5 { White pieces are kingside-oriented. } 13... O-O
{ 13...Nd5?  Black shouldn't avoid castling for too long.  14.Qh5  Provoking another weakness.  14...g6  15.Qf3  f5  16.Nc4!  An intermediate move that prevents Black from recapturing on d5 with the queen, because of Nb6.  16...Qd8  17.Bxd5  exd5  18.Ne5  is strategically winning for White. The dark squares, the weak king, the c- and e-files, everything works in White's favour. }
14. Re1
{ More patient than Qf3, slowly improving pieces.   14.Qf3!?  is a decent possibility as well, but maybe Black can claim some compensation after  14...f5  15.Bxb7  Bxb7  16.Qxb7  Rab8 }
14... Nd5
{ 14...f5?  makes no sense now.  15.Bf3  Black is left with a long-term weakness on e6. }
15. Qd3 { Connecting the rooks with a gain of tempo. } 15... Nf6 16. Rac1
{ The rook to the open file.  16.Bf3  , not giving the bishop pair is also good. }
16... Nxe4 17. Qxe4
{ White has a strong knight on e5 and domination on the c-file. Black still hasn't solved the problem of the c8-bishop. }
