{ Before stepping into the deep woods of Najdorf, Dragon, Sveshnikov, or Rauzer first we need to cover some less popular lines. It seemed natural for me to start from the queenside, and the first decent alternative to the main Sicilians is the  2...a6  .  The so-called O'Kelly variation has never been a popular choice in classical chess, but currently has a strong supporter, the Russian GM Vladislav Artemiev. In the last few years, he has been playing it regularly, especially at the faster time controls.  The simplest explanation of this move would be that it makes  3.d4  ineffective. However, there are some hidden subtleties behind it. White has two good options, the first one is 3.c4, but in those pawn structures, a6 is always useful for Black. Therefore, I have always preferred c3 since it asks the question: how does 2...a6 fights for the centre? }
2... a6 3. c3
{ Black again has a couple of options, the critical ones are  3...e6  and  3...d5  , in my opinion, but  3...Nf6  and  3...g6  are not trivial.   Black's main idea is to counter  3.d4  with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  followed by Bb4 and/or d5 with comfortable equality.   In case you forgot this trick or simply premove 3.d4 then I would advise you to play  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  with the following plan: Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1 @@StartBracket@@h3@@EndBracket@@, etc. Also, 4.c3 might be very interesting since White will get a favourable version of the Morra gambit. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6
{ The main move and Artemiev's favorite choice.   5...e6  6.Be3  cxd4  7.cxd4  Ng6  8.Nc3  transposes to 5...Nf6.   5...Bf5  f5  is not the right square for the black bishop.  6.Nbd2!  e6   6...cxd4?!  7.Bc4  Qd6  8.Qb3  White wins material.  7.Nc4  Nc6   7...Qd8  8.Bg5  8.Ne3  Planning to take the bishop on f5.  8...Qe4  9.Nd2  We keep attacking the queen to force Black to recapture with the pawn on f5.  9...Qh4  10.Nxf5  exf5  11.Nf3  Qe7+  12.Be2  The bishop pair, better development, and a passed d-pawn guarantee a big advantage. }
6. Be3
{ We are threatening 7.dxc5 and forcing Black to capture on d4, so that we can put a knight on c3, and develop the bishop on d3 without worries about the d4 pawn. }
6... cxd4 7. cxd4 e6 8. Nc3
{ Black has to decide where to put his queen: d6, d8, or a5. Just like in the Scandinavian. They all have equal value according to silicon monsters, so it is a matter of taste. Black can also play Bb4, but eventually, he will have to give up bishop pair with almost no compensation for it. }
8... Qd6
{ Normally, the black bishop goes to e7, so this looks like the most logical follow-up. The queen on d6, together with the knight on c6 controls the e5 square which is important since White would like to jump on e5. Also, the pawn on a6 is useful since it stops Nb5 and Black will often play b5 followed by Bb7. }
9. Bd3 Nc6
{ 9...Be7  10.O-O  Nbd7  Black wants the Nbd7-b5-Bb7 setup, but the knight on c6 looks more natural. The knight on d7 doesn't target the d4 pawn and we can use that by playing  11.Ng5!?  Ne4 is the idea, and the queen can go to f3.  11...O-O  12.Qf3  Stopping b5 and bringing the queen closer to the black king. White has nice attacking prospects on the kingside. }
10. O-O
{ Was my initial idea, I don't want to play a3 as they usually do in these lines, if I really don't have to. 10.O-O is a move White has to make, a3 isn't. }
10... Be7 { 10...Nb4  11.Ne4  and White keeps the advantage and the bishops. }
11. Ne4 Qd5
{ This can be the only major difference compared to 10.Ne4.   11...Nxe4  12.Bxe4  transposes into 10.Ne4. }
12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Rc1 O-O 14. Rc5
{ Activating the rook and asking black a question, where will your queen go? }
14... Qd6
{ 14...Qxa2?  15.Qc2  Black will lose the queen or get into a mating net after Bxh7 and Rh5. }
15. Ne5
{ Not the only move which gives White an advantage, but the most spectacular one. }
15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 Bxe5 17. Bxh7+ { The tactical point behind 15.Nxe5 } 17...
Kxh7 18. Qh5+ Kg8 19. Rd1
{ It was possible to return the bishop, but this intermediate move is stronger. White practically sacrifices a piece. }
19... Bxh2+ 20. Kf1 g6
{ 20...Qb8  21.Rg5  with  Rxg7+  Kxg7  Bh6  as an undefendable threat.   20...Qe7  21.Qxh2  White has a dangerous attack. }
21. Rxd6 { White goes into a favourable endgame. } 21... gxh5 22. Rg5+ Kh7 23.
Rxh5+ Kg6 24. Rh6+ { Forcing the black king to the dark square. } 24... Kg7 25.
Rxh2
{ Although the material is equal, the black king is weak, and the white bishop is much stronger than its counterpart. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) O'Kelly: 2...a6"]
[Black "2...a6 3.c3 e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Before stepping into the deep woods of Najdorf, Dragon, Sveshnikov, or Rauzer first we need to cover some less popular lines. It seemed natural for me to start from the queenside, and the first decent alternative to the main Sicilians is the  2...a6  .  The so-called O'Kelly variation has never been a popular choice in classical chess, but currently has a strong supporter, the Russian GM Vladislav Artemiev. In the last few years, he has been playing it regularly, especially at the faster time controls.  The simplest explanation of this move would be that it makes  3.d4  ineffective. However, there are some hidden subtleties behind it. White has two good options, the first one is 3.c4, but in those pawn structures, a6 is always useful for Black. Therefore, I have always preferred c3 since it asks the question: how does 2...a6 fights for the centre? }
2... a6 3. c3
{ Black again has a couple of options, the critical ones are  3...e6  and  3...d5  , in my opinion, but  3...Nf6  and  3...g6  are not trivial.   Black's main idea is to counter  3.d4  with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  followed by Bb4 and/or d5 with comfortable equality.   In case you forgot this trick or simply premove 3.d4 then I would advise you to play  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  with the following plan: Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1 @@StartBracket@@h3@@EndBracket@@, etc. Also, 4.c3 might be very interesting since White will get a favourable version of the Morra gambit. }
3... e6
{ Black wants to play some sort of French Defence. Once upon a time  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.  e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  wasn't considered critical against French, when both  3.Nc3  and  3.Nd2  had a better reputation, but recently because of the efforts of MVL, Shirov, and other top players, the  3.e5  enjoys increasing popularity.   The difference here is that White has Nf3, which is a must move, while Black has a6, a move which almost no one plays in the advanced variation of the French Defence. However, the move a6 has some function and makes the Bd7-Bb5 idea possible. }
4. d4 d5
{ The only consistent move.   4...cxd4  5.cxd4  b5  It may be better for Black to play like this without the exchange of the c-pawns. Giving up the centre can rarely bring you equality in the opening phase.  6.Bd3  Bb7  7.O-O  White simply develops his pieces.  7...Nf6  8.Re1  Be7  9.Nc3  White has achieved everything in the opening. His pieces are developed and he has full control of the centre. }
5. e5
{ 5.exd5  is the recommendation of Wesley So in his course, but I don't want to repeat the same lines and I believe that the move  5.e5  is more ambitious. }
5... Ne7 { Black first develops the g8 knight. } 6. Bd3 Nf5
{ 6...cxd4  This capture is usually premature since it allows White to develop the knight on c3.  7.cxd4  Nf5  8.Nc3  Nc6  9.Bc2  With the white knight on c3, the move Qb6 is never possible because of Bxf5. The plan is to castle, secure the b4 square with the move a3, and then deal with the knight on f5 with g2-g4 or Ne2-Ng3. }
7. dxc5
{ It makes sense to release the tension because the knight on f5 is misplaced in the arising pawn structure. }
7... Bxc5 8. Nbd2 Nc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nb3 Ba7 11. Re1
{ White is better, the pawn on e5 allows him to create attacking chances on the kingside. With the knight being on f5 Black normally can't play f6 because of Bxf5 exf5 e6, followed by Nd4. }
*

