[White "3) O'Kelly: 2...a6"]
[Black "2...a6 3.c3 e6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Before stepping into the deep woods of Najdorf, Dragon, Sveshnikov, or Rauzer first we need to cover some less popular lines. It seemed natural for me to start from the queenside, and the first decent alternative to the main Sicilians is the  2...a6  .  The so-called O'Kelly variation has never been a popular choice in classical chess, but currently has a strong supporter, the Russian GM Vladislav Artemiev. In the last few years, he has been playing it regularly, especially at the faster time controls.  The simplest explanation of this move would be that it makes  3.d4  ineffective. However, there are some hidden subtleties behind it. White has two good options, the first one is 3.c4, but in those pawn structures, a6 is always useful for Black. Therefore, I have always preferred c3 since it asks the question: how does 2...a6 fights for the centre? }
2... a6 3. c3
{ Black again has a couple of options, the critical ones are  3...e6  and  3...d5  , in my opinion, but  3...Nf6  and  3...g6  are not trivial.   Black's main idea is to counter  3.d4  with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  followed by Bb4 and/or d5 with comfortable equality.   In case you forgot this trick or simply premove 3.d4 then I would advise you to play  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  with the following plan: Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1 @@StartBracket@@h3@@EndBracket@@, etc. Also, 4.c3 might be very interesting since White will get a favourable version of the Morra gambit. }
3... e6
{ Black wants to play some sort of French Defence. Once upon a time  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.  e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  wasn't considered critical against French, when both  3.Nc3  and  3.Nd2  had a better reputation, but recently because of the efforts of MVL, Shirov, and other top players, the  3.e5  enjoys increasing popularity.   The difference here is that White has Nf3, which is a must move, while Black has a6, a move which almost no one plays in the advanced variation of the French Defence. However, the move a6 has some function and makes the Bd7-Bb5 idea possible. }
4. d4 d5
{ The only consistent move.   4...cxd4  5.cxd4  b5  It may be better for Black to play like this without the exchange of the c-pawns. Giving up the centre can rarely bring you equality in the opening phase.  6.Bd3  Bb7  7.O-O  White simply develops his pieces.  7...Nf6  8.Re1  Be7  9.Nc3  White has achieved everything in the opening. His pieces are developed and he has full control of the centre. }
5. e5
{ 5.exd5  is the recommendation of Wesley So in his course, but I don't want to repeat the same lines and I believe that the move  5.e5  is more ambitious. }
5... Bd7
{ is the only real alternative to 5...Nc6, since other moves normally transpose. 5...Bd7 has an independent idea of playing Bb5 before developing the knight. }
6. Bd3 cxd4
{ 6...Nc6  7.a3  transposes into the mainline.   6...Bb5?!  The bishop trade leaves Black with weak pawns.  7.Bxb5+  axb5  8.dxc5  White is playing directly, trying to isolate the pawn on b5.  8...Bxc5  9.b4!  Attacking the bishop and fixing the pawn on b5.  9...Ba7  10.Na3  White wins the b5 pawn. }
7. cxd4 Bb5
{ This is a better version for Black than in 6...Bb5 since after exchanging on b5 Black can push the pawn to b4. }
8. Bc2 { Therefore, White avoids the trade of the bishops. } 8... Bb4+ 9. Bd2
a5
{ 9...Bxd2  10.Qxd2  The trade-off of the dark-squared bishops in a French-type pawn structure is not really a success for Black.  10...a5  11.Nc3  Ba6  12.h4  We have too much space on the kingside and excellent attacking prospects. }
10. Nc3 Ba6 11. a3
{ 11.h4  is interesting also, but I like to see what is Black planning with his bishop. }
11... Bxc3 12. Bxc3
{ Normally, in the French Defence when you give up the dark-squared bishop you at least spoil the white pawn structure. Here, Black didn't even manage to do that. }
12... Nc6 13. h4 Nge7 14. h5 h6 15. Rh3
{ White has a considerable advantage, and I don't see how should Black proceed. In general, White's king is safe on e1. }
