[White "5) Accelerated Dragon: Maroczy Bind"]
[Black "Maroczy 5...Bg7  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ 2...g6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Bg7  5.c4  doesn't have independent value   5...Qb6  6.Nb3  Nc6  7.Be3  is the position we will reach via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  g6  5.c4  Bg7  6.Be3  Qb6  7.Nb3  .  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  O-O  7.Be2  d6  8.O-O  transposes to the main line. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ This move represents the starting position for the Accelerated Dragon. Compared to the classical Dragon, Black restricts the most critical possibilities for White. For example, the line which I'm recommending against the Dragon @@StartBracket@@White castling queenside and avoiding to play Bc4@@EndBracket@@.   First big decision for White. After  4...g6  White can choose to play the ambitious  5.Nc3  and enter into the lines of the Accelerated Dragon, and the Dragon or play  5.c4  which is a more positional choice.  In the repertoire which I'm recommending playing  5.Nc3  doesn't fit into our plans because against the Dragon my choice is O-O-O without Bc4. Also, I believe that Maroczy type of positions are constant suffering for Black, and suit less to players who are comfortable with wild Dragon type positions. }
5. c4
{ We are entering one of the most known structures in chess, named after Hungarian master Geza Maroczy. Before developing the knight on c3, White plays c4, obtains more space and with pawns on e4 and c4 in the long run prevents Black from playing d5.   Black has a Dragon / KID setup which is characterized by g6, Bg7, Nf6, Nc6, d6, O-O often with Bd7, Qa5 to follow. In general, White has easier play because Black always has to find ways to create counterplay to avoid a passive position. }
5... Bg7 6. Be3 Qb6
{ Pet line of GM Rauf Mamedov, who is an expert from the Black side. Targeting the knight and the b2 pawn. }
7. Nb5 { Attacking the queen and saving the knight. } 7... Qa5+
{ 7...Qd8  8.N1c3  forcing Black to play  8...a6  9.Nd4  White got Nc3 while Black got a6, which is in White's favour. }
8. N5c3
{ White's pieces are a bit disrupted from an ideal setup, but the black queen will have to retreat after a few moves.   We don't play  8.N1c3  Nf6  9.f3  a6  10.Nd4  Nxd4  11.Bxd4  d6  because it fits very well into Black's plans. Be6, O-O and Rfc8 is coming. In general, White tries to avoid exchanges of the light pieces. }
8... d6
{ This line is recommended by Kamil Plichta in his course Lifetime Repertoires: Accelerated Dragon. Black waits with Nf6 to keep the dark-squared bishop active. }
9. Be2
{ The most flexible and useful move for White, finishing the  development. }
9... Qb4 10. Qc1 { 10.Qc2  allows Nd4. } 10... Bd4
{ Strange at first  sight, but Black's positional idea is to trade the pieces since he lacks space. }
11. O-O Nf6 12. Na3
{ Developing the knight. If you don't like to spoil pawn structure, you can try  12.b3  , but White's advantage is only minimal. }
12... Bxc3
{ The critical move. Black gives up the bishop and spoils White's pawn  structure.   If  12...Bxe3  then  13.Qxe3  and White gets nice spatial  advantage as usual. }
13. bxc3 Qa5 14. f3 { Defending the vital pawn on e4. } 14... O-O 15. Rb1
{ The most logical and natural move in the position, activating the rook. }
15... Nd7 { Black wants to place the knight to its ideal square: c5. } 16. Rb5
Qc7 17. f4 { White starts pushing pawns. } 17... b6
{ If  17...Nf6  then  18.Qb1!  defends the pawn on  e4  and keeps an eye on the b7-pawn. }
18. Rg5 Nc5 19. Bf3
{ 19.Nb5  is really a tempting option, but we can always do that. } 19... Bb7
20. Rg3 { White has prepared everything for a kingside attack. } *

