3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ This move represents the starting position for the Accelerated Dragon. Compared to the classical Dragon, Black restricts the most critical possibilities for White. For example, the line which I'm recommending against the Dragon @@StartBracket@@White castling queenside and avoiding to play Bc4@@EndBracket@@.   First big decision for White. After  4...g6  White can choose to play the ambitious  5.Nc3  and enter into the lines of the Accelerated Dragon, and the Dragon or play  5.c4  which is a more positional choice.  In the repertoire which I'm recommending playing  5.Nc3  doesn't fit into our plans because against the Dragon my choice is O-O-O without Bc4. Also, I believe that Maroczy type of positions are constant suffering for Black, and suit less to players who are comfortable with wild Dragon type positions. }
5. c4
{ We are entering one of the most known structures in chess, named after Hungarian master Geza Maroczy. Before developing the knight on c3, White plays c4, obtains more space and with pawns on e4 and c4 in the long run prevents Black from playing d5.   Black has a Dragon / KID setup which is characterized by g6, Bg7, Nf6, Nc6, d6, O-O often with Bd7, Qa5 to follow. In general, White has easier play because Black always has to find ways to create counterplay to avoid a passive position. }
5... Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 Ng4
{ Black uses small tactics to exchange pair of the knights and open up the long diagonal.   7...d6  8.Be2  O-O  9.O-O  is a transposition. }
8. Qxg4
{ Forced response from White.  8.Nxc6?  is bad after  8...Nxe3  when Black obtains a strong bishop pair advantage. }
8... Nxd4 9. Qd1
{ This has been known for ages as a right response against 7... Ng4 line. Here, Black is again at the crossroads: to retreat the knight or to fortify it with e5 but give d5-square. }
9... Nc6 10. Qd2
{ is a inferior version compared to the main line for Black. The knights d4 and f6 have been exchanged which favors White since Black can't control d5 square well. }
10... d6 11. Be2 Qa5 12. Rc1 O-O
{ The good thing about playing Maroczy with White is that you almost play same moves against everything Black does @@StartBracket@@Be2, Rc1, O-O, b3, etc.@@EndBracket@@ }
13. O-O Be6 14. b3 { Continuing with the typical plan. } 14... Rac8 15. f4
{ With Black bishop on e6, and no knight on f6 White doesn't have to play f3. He can immediately start attacking with f4. }
15... f5 16. exf5 Bxf5 17. Bf3
{ White controls the centre, has more space, and d6-e7 pawns are potential weaknesses. }
