5. c4
{ We are entering one of the most known structures in chess, named after Hungarian master Geza Maroczy. Before developing the knight on c3, White plays c4, obtains more space and with pawns on e4 and c4 in the long run prevents Black from playing d5.   Black has a Dragon / KID setup which is characterized by g6, Bg7, Nf6, Nc6, d6, O-O often with Bd7, Qa5 to follow. In general, White has easier play because Black always has to find ways to create counterplay to avoid a passive position. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 d6
{ The best move order for Black. First, it stops  7.Be3  because of  7...Ng4  . So, White can play either 7. Be2 or 7. f3.   After  7.Be2  Nxd4!  8.Qxd4  Bg7  9.Be3  @@StartBracket@@or 9.Bg5@@EndBracket@@  9...O-O  10.Qd2  a5  Black will manage to play a4, Qa5, Be6, Rfc8, a well-known plan which gives him an easy play.   On the other hand when White plays  7.f3  he will no longer have the flexibility to play h3 at some point, but since I'm choosing f3 in the mainline anyway this doesn't concern us much. }
