13. Bd3
{ Compared to the  13.Be2  which has more than a thousand games in the database, this is a rarely played move. I believe it is not inferior to 13. Be2. The idea is simply to jump with Nd5 in the next move and after some exchanges on d5 the bishop is more active on d3. }
13... a6 { Move which Black almost always plays, to have b7-b5 ideas in mind. }
14. Nd5 { Forcing an endgame. } 14... Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Nxd5 16. exd5
{ In case of  16.cxd5  , Black will trade both pair of rooks and he should make a draw despite having a lack of space. }
16... Bd7 17. a4
{ With a5 ideas in mind, and more importantly, b7-b5 needs to be stopped. }
17... Bb2 { Removing white rook from the c-file. } 18. Rb1 Ba3
{ Transferring the bishop to the other diagonal doesn't work well. It was played in a blitz game between Grischuk - Guseinov, chess.com 2020. and White could have punished Black with }
19. b4 a5 20. bxa5 Rxa5 21. Rxb7 Bxa4 22. Bd4
{ Black has too many pieces on the a-file and they do nothing. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Accelerated Dragon: Maroczy Bind"]
[Black "Maroczy 5...Nf6   7...Nxd4  #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ This move represents the starting position for the Accelerated Dragon. Compared to the classical Dragon, Black restricts the most critical possibilities for White. For example, the line which I'm recommending against the Dragon @@StartBracket@@White castling queenside and avoiding to play Bc4@@EndBracket@@.   First big decision for White. After  4...g6  White can choose to play the ambitious  5.Nc3  and enter into the lines of the Accelerated Dragon, and the Dragon or play  5.c4  which is a more positional choice.  In the repertoire which I'm recommending playing  5.Nc3  doesn't fit into our plans because against the Dragon my choice is O-O-O without Bc4. Also, I believe that Maroczy type of positions are constant suffering for Black, and suit less to players who are comfortable with wild Dragon type positions. }
5. c4
{ We are entering one of the most known structures in chess, named after Hungarian master Geza Maroczy. Before developing the knight on c3, White plays c4, obtains more space and with pawns on e4 and c4 in the long run prevents Black from playing d5.   Black has a Dragon / KID setup which is characterized by g6, Bg7, Nf6, Nc6, d6, O-O often with Bd7, Qa5 to follow. In general, White has easier play because Black always has to find ways to create counterplay to avoid a passive position. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 d6
{ The best move order for Black. First, it stops  7.Be3  because of  7...Ng4  . So, White can play either 7. Be2 or 7. f3.   After  7.Be2  Nxd4!  8.Qxd4  Bg7  9.Be3  @@StartBracket@@or 9.Bg5@@EndBracket@@  9...O-O  10.Qd2  a5  Black will manage to play a4, Qa5, Be6, Rfc8, a well known plan which gives him easy play.   On the other hand when White plays  7.f3  he will no longer have flexibility to play h3 at some point, but since I'm choosing f3 in the main line anyway this doesn't concern us much. }
7. f3 Nxd4
{ Black takes on d4 immediately, forcing White to recapture with queen. } 8.
Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 { The queen must return, Ng4 was a threat. } 10...
Be6 11. Rc1
{ A typical Maroczy move, the rook is escaping from the long diagonal. } 11...
Qa5 12. b3
{ A setup which is quite easy to remember. Pieces on the dark squares form an 'X' and pawns are on the light squares. }
12... Rfc8
{ Black is preparing to anticipate Nd5 and a possible opening of the c-file.  12...a6  invites  13.Nd5  . }
13. Bd3
{ Compared to the  13.Be2  which has more than a thousand games in the database, this is a rarely played move. I believe it is not inferior to 13. Be2. The idea is simply to jump with Nd5 in the next move and after some exchanges on d5 the bishop is more active on d3. }
13... a6 { Move which Black almost always plays, to have b7-b5 ideas in mind. }
14. Nd5 { Forcing an endgame. } 14... Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Nxd5 16. exd5
{ In case of  16.cxd5  , Black will trade both pair of rooks and he should make a draw despite having a lack of space. }
16... Bd7 17. a4
{ With a5 ideas in mind, and more importantly, b7-b5 needs to be stopped. }
17... Bb2 { Removing white rook from the c-file. } 18. Rb1 Ba3
{ Transferring the bishop to the other diagonal doesn't work well. It was played in a blitz game between Grischuk - Guseinov, chess.com 2020. and White could have punished Black with }
19. b4 Bxa4 20. Bb6 { Stopping a5 } 20... e6 21. dxe6 fxe6 22. Kc3 a5
{ Black must give some pawns, otherwise he will lose the bishop. } 23. Bxa5 b5
24. Ra1 Rxa5 { Otherwise the bishop drops. } 25. bxa5 b4+ 26. Kd4
{ Returning the exchange, but centralizing the king. } 26... Ra8 27. Rxa3 bxa3
28. Ra1 Rxa5 29. Rxa3 Ra8 30. Bc2 Bc6 31. Rxa8+ Bxa8 32. Be4
{ Wins for White. That's why we play 26. Kd4, if the White king was instead on d2 this would only lead to a draw. }
*

