7. f3 Bg7 8. Be3 O-O 9. Be2
{ This position can be reach via move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  g6  5.c4  Bg7  6.Be3  Nf6  7.Nc3  O-O  8.Be2  d6  9.f3  . }
9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Be6
{ Black is trying to exchange light pieces. When bishop is on e6, White should castle kingside. }
11. O-O Qa5 12. f4
{ Typical move against the bishop on e6. Not giving time for Black to play Nd7. }
12... Rac8 13. b3 Ng4 { Black wants to exchange few pieces. } 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15.
Bxg4
{ Bad things can happen on the long diagonal, and White destroys dangerous knight. }
15... Bxg4 16. Qd4+
{ White doesn't mind exchanges, he wants to prove that knight is dominant to the light-squared bishop in such pawn structure. }
16... f6 17. f5 { Preparing trap for the bishop. } 17... g5 18. Nd5
{ Creating a double threat: 19. Ne7 and 19. e5. } 18... Qc5
{ Only move, which indirectly defends e7 and prevents e4-e5. } 19. Qxc5 Rxc5
20. a4
{ Stops b5. White can slowly improve his king @@StartBracket@@to d4@@EndBracket@@, play h4 to open the h-file and try to create additional weaknesses in Black's position. }
