[White "6) 2...e6 with 4...Qb6 and 4...Bc5 5.Be3 Qb6"]
[Black "4...Qb6 5.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ Sicilians with 2...e6 are often characterized as the positional Sicilians, which doesn't mean they aren't full of tactics.   The most common ones are Taimanov @@StartBracket@@4...Nc6 and 5...Qc7@@EndBracket@@ and Kan @@StartBracket@@4...a6@@EndBracket@@. First we will cover some less known and dubious lines. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ In this chapter  4...Bc5  and  4...Qb6  will be covered together because they often transpose to each other and I am recommending the same response against both of them  5.Be3  .  It is hard to say what the real idea behind mentioned moves is, but in my experience it is primarily to confuse the opponent. }
4... Qb6 5. Be3
{ There is nothing wrong with  5.Nc3  or  5.Nb3  , but with this move, White wants to punish Black for the unprincipled opening move, developing the queen before a light piece. }
5... Qxb2 { What else? } 6. Nd2
{ White develops one more piece and Nb5 is a serious threat. } 6... Qb6
{ 6...a6  is the only move, after  7.Bd3  we have the position which is usually reached via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  5.Bd3  Qb6  6.Be3  Qxb2  7.Nd2  . }
7. Nb5 Qd8 8. Bf4 Na6 9. Nc4
{ Almost every white piece attacks the d6 square. } 9... Nf6 10. Nbd6+ Bxd6 11.
Nxd6+ Kf8 12. Qf3 Qa5+ 13. c3 { White has a winning attack. } *

