1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ Sicilians with 2...e6 are often characterized as the positional Sicilians, which doesn't mean they aren't full of tactics.   The most common ones are Taimanov @@StartBracket@@4...Nc6 and 5...Qc7@@EndBracket@@ and Kan @@StartBracket@@4...a6@@EndBracket@@. First we will cover some less known and dubious lines. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ In this chapter  4...Bc5  and  4...Qb6  will be covered together because they often transpose to each other and I am recommending the same response against both of them  5.Be3  .  It is hard to say what the real idea behind mentioned moves is, but in my experience it is primarily to confuse the opponent. }
4... Bc5 5. Be3 Qb6 6. Na3
{ Developing knight with the Nc4 idea. Evans style  6.b4  is among top computer choices, but here we don't have to sacrifice a pawn. }
6... d5 7. Bb5+ { Developing with tempo. } 7... Bd7
{ Here, White can simply take on d5, then castle and have a slightly better position due to the isolated pawn on d5, but there is one line which I must mention. }
8. O-O e5 9. Nf5 d4 { Black plays aggressively. } 10. Nc4
{ Bishop can't be taken thanks to the Nd6 fork. } 10... Qf6 11. f4
{ Powerful move, wins by force. White wants to land with knight on d6 at any cost. }
11... dxe3 12. Qd5 { Escaping from e2 check. } 12... e2+ 13. Qxc5 exf1=Q+ 14.
Rxf1 { White is rook down, but his threats are deadly. } *

