[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 2...e6 - Four Knights: 4...Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6"]
[Black "4 Knights  #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Four knights defence. Black follows the basic opening principles and develops both his knights, before deciding where should the queen go @@StartBracket@@d8, c7, b6 or sometimes even a5@@EndBracket@@ and his dark squared bishop @@StartBracket@@e7, c5 or b4@@EndBracket@@.   Without wasting time on playing a7-a6 Black is already prepared to strike in the centre with the move d7-d5 with the possible inclusion of the move Bb4. Currently, this variation is highly popular, played by majority of the top players, and some Sveshnikov players use it as an alternative @@StartBracket@@for some players it is even first choice@@EndBracket@@ way of reaching the Sveshnikov.   After  6.Ndb5  d6  7.Bf4  e5  8.Bg5  Black has avoided numerous Rossolimo lines and the trendy 7. Nd5 variation which is also my recommendation against Sveshnikov.   Therefore, instead of  6.Ndb5  we must choose the another principled @@StartBracket@@and probably the best@@EndBracket@@ move,  6.Nxc6  . }
6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Practically, the forced recapture. Taking with the other pawn leads to a bad endgame for Black.  6...dxc6  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  8.e5  Nd5  9.Ne4  followed by Bd2, c4 and O-O-O gives White a nice edge thanks to the space advantage, and the bad light-squared bishop in Black's camp. }
7. e5
{ The point of Nxc6, playing e5 quickly. That pawn will trouble Black in many lines. You will see that most of White's moves are based on chasing black's knight which won't be safe on d5. }
7... Nd5 8. Ne4
{ The d6 is the weakest square in Black's position, and knight from e4 controls it nicely. This move also creates a threat of playing c2-c4. Now, Black has couple of different moves to choose, two of them are having solid reputation.   First one is  8...Bb7  which leads to a slightly inferior but defendable endgame, and another one is the main move  8...Qc7  . }
8... Bb7
{ In many lines in the Four Knights defence, the biggest problem for Black is the light-squared bishop. With this move Black tries to solve that issue. }
9. Be2
{ Best by the current state theory. Before chasing the knight White wants to finish developing. If we go  9.c4  Nb4  , the move  10.a3  is strongly answered with  10...Qa5  , attacking the pawn on e5 and creating a deadly threat of discovered check. Instead, White usually plays 10. c5, but this loses control over the d5-square. }
9... c5
{ Obviously, Black wants to open up his light-squared bishop. Attacking the e5 pawn doesn't give Black anything except troubles. For example,  9...Qc7   9...Qb8  doesn't change much,  10.Nd6+  Bxd6  11.exd6  and the pawn can't be taken because Black loses the knight after 12. c4. }
10. O-O Qc7
{ Black is now ready for Qc7. Here White has two options  11.c4  and  11.Nd6  , and I chose 11. Nd6+ since it is the more ambitious one. }
11. Nd6+ { The main move. White gets the bishop pair advantage. } 11... Bxd6
12. exd6 Qc6
{ Again, the pawn on d6 is untouchable because of c4. With his last move, Black shows the whole idea behind playing Bb7, c5. He creates a strong threat on the diagonal. White must do something about it. }
13. f3
{ An important move, the White's bishop needs to stay on the f1-a6 diagonal. The king is not in danger because Black doesn't have the dark-squared bishop anymore. }
13... c4
{ The forced decision, almost. If White manages to play c4, the position becomes difficult for Black. }
14. Qd4
{ Black has achieved some strategic goals, so White must act quickly. Basically, the only move for White. }
14... O-O 15. Bxc4 Rfc8 16. b3 { Defending the bishop. } 16... Qxd6 17. Rf2
{ Interesting idea: White covers the c2 square and also closes the g1-a7 diagonal. }
17... Qb6 18. Qh4
{ White avoids the queen trade since all Black's pieces are on the queenside, far away from the Black king. Black will have to be very careful when parrying all the threats. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 2...e6 - Four Knights: 4...Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6"]
[Black "4 Knights  #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Four knights defence. Black follows the basic opening principles and develops both his knights, before deciding where should the queen go @@StartBracket@@d8, c7, b6 or sometimes even a5@@EndBracket@@ and his dark squared bishop @@StartBracket@@e7, c5 or b4@@EndBracket@@.   Without wasting time on playing a7-a6 Black is already prepared to strike in the centre with the move d7-d5 with the possible inclusion of the move Bb4. Currently, this variation is highly popular, played by majority of the top players, and some Sveshnikov players use it as an alternative @@StartBracket@@for some players it is even first choice@@EndBracket@@ way of reaching the Sveshnikov.   After  6.Ndb5  d6  7.Bf4  e5  8.Bg5  Black has avoided numerous Rossolimo lines and the trendy 7. Nd5 variation which is also my recommendation against Sveshnikov.   Therefore, instead of  6.Ndb5  we must choose the another principled @@StartBracket@@and probably the best@@EndBracket@@ move,  6.Nxc6  . }
6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Practically, the forced recapture. Taking with the other pawn leads to a bad endgame for Black.  6...dxc6  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  8.e5  Nd5  9.Ne4  followed by Bd2, c4 and O-O-O gives White a nice edge thanks to the space advantage, and the bad light-squared bishop in Black's camp. }
7. e5
{ The point of Nxc6, playing e5 quickly. That pawn will trouble Black in many lines. You will see that most of White's moves are based on chasing black's knight which won't be safe on d5. }
7... Nd5 8. Ne4
{ The d6 is the weakest square in Black's position, and knight from e4 controls it nicely. This move also creates a threat of playing c2-c4. Now, Black has couple of different moves to choose, two of them are having solid reputation.   First one is  8...Bb7  which leads to a slightly inferior but defendable endgame, and another one is the main move  8...Qc7  . }
8... Bb7
{ In many lines in the Four Knights defence, the biggest problem for Black is the light-squared bishop. With this move Black tries to solve that issue. }
9. Be2
{ Best by the current state theory. Before chasing the knight White wants to finish developing. If we go  9.c4  Nb4  , the move  10.a3  is strongly answered with  10...Qa5  , attacking the pawn on e5 and creating a deadly threat of discovered check. Instead, White usually plays 10. c5, but this loses control over the d5-square. }
9... c5
{ Obviously, Black wants to open up his light-squared bishop. Attacking the e5 pawn doesn't give Black anything except troubles. For example,  9...Qc7   9...Qb8  doesn't change much,  10.Nd6+  Bxd6  11.exd6  and the pawn can't be taken because Black loses the knight after 12. c4. }
10. O-O Qc7
{ Black is now ready for Qc7. Here White has two options  11.c4  and  11.Nd6  , and I chose 11. Nd6+ since it is the more ambitious one. }
11. Nd6+ { The main move. White gets the bishop pair advantage. } 11... Bxd6
12. exd6 Qc6
{ Again, the pawn on d6 is untouchable because of c4. With his last move, Black shows the whole idea behind playing Bb7, c5. He creates a strong threat on the diagonal. White must do something about it. }
13. f3
{ An important move, the White's bishop needs to stay on the f1-a6 diagonal. The king is not in danger because Black doesn't have the dark-squared bishop anymore. }
13... c4
{ The forced decision, almost. If White manages to play c4, the position becomes difficult for Black. }
14. Qd4
{ Black has achieved some strategic goals, so White must act quickly. Basically, the only move for White. }
14... O-O 15. Bxc4 Qxd6 16. b3 Qb6 17. Qxb6 Nxb6
{ If  17...axb6  18.a4  White keeps the typical edge. } 18. Bd3 Rfc8
{ Up to this moment we were following the blitz game Carlsen - Artemiev, chess24.com 2021 and the classical one Navara-Grachev, EU-cup 2019. The simplest move to my eye seems to be 19. Bd2. }
19. Bd2 { White has an edge thanks to the bishop pair. } *

