6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Practically, the forced recapture. Taking with the other pawn leads to a bad endgame for Black.  6...dxc6  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  8.e5  Nd5  9.Ne4  followed by Bd2, c4 and O-O-O gives White a nice edge thanks to the space advantage, and the bad light-squared bishop in Black's camp. }
7. e5
{ The point of Nxc6, playing e5 quickly. That pawn will trouble Black in many lines. You will see that most of White's moves are based on chasing black's knight which won't be safe on d5. }
7... Nd5 8. Ne4
{ The d6 is the weakest square in Black's position, and knight from e4 controls it nicely. This move also creates a threat of playing c2-c4. Now, Black has couple of different moves to choose, two of them are having solid reputation.   First one is  8...Bb7  which leads to a slightly inferior but defendable endgame, and another one is the main move  8...Qc7  . }
8... Bb7
{ In many lines in the Four Knights defence, the biggest problem for Black is the light-squared bishop. With this move Black tries to solve that issue. }
9. Be2
{ Best by the current state theory. Before chasing the knight White wants to finish developing. If we go  9.c4  Nb4  , the move  10.a3  is strongly answered with  10...Qa5  , attacking the pawn on e5 and creating a deadly threat of discovered check. Instead, White usually plays 10. c5, but this loses control over the d5-square. }
9... c5
{ Obviously, Black wants to open up his light-squared bishop. Attacking the e5 pawn doesn't give Black anything except troubles. For example,  9...Qc7   9...Qb8  doesn't change much,  10.Nd6+  Bxd6  11.exd6  and the pawn can't be taken because Black loses the knight after 12. c4. }
10. O-O Qc7
{ Black is now ready for Qc7. Here White has two options  11.c4  and  11.Nd6  , and I chose 11. Nd6+ since it is the more ambitious one. }
11. Nd6+ { The main move. White gets the bishop pair advantage. } 11... Bxd6
12. exd6 Qc6
{ Again, the pawn on d6 is untouchable because of c4. With his last move, Black shows the whole idea behind playing Bb7, c5. He creates a strong threat on the diagonal. White must do something about it. }
13. f3 Qb6 14. Rf2
{ The idea behind Rf2 is to play the move c4 without allowing  Black's knight to jump on b4. Which will White prevent by playing the move a3,  but first he needs to prevent the c4 check.   If  14.c4  then  14...Nb4  15.Be3  a5!   15...Nc6?  is a mistake due to  16.b4  where Black loses material.  16.Qa4!  the only way for White to fight for the advantage  16...Qxd6   16...Bc6  17.Qb3  a4  18.Qc3  shows exactly the idea behind 16. Qa4, the bishop on c6  takes  away an important square which belong to the knight.  17.Qb5  and White wins the  c5  pawn  17...Ba6  18.Qxc5  Qxc5  19.Bxc5  Rc8  20.Bb6  a4  21.b3  Ke7  22.Rfc1  and White has a better endgame thanks to the bishop pair advantage but Black’s position seems holdable. }
14... O-O 15. a3
{ The b4 square is under control and White is finally ready to play c4. } 15...
a5
{ Always a useful move for  Black. Stopping the b4 ideas and the rook can attack on d6 via the a6 square. }
16. c4 Nf6 17. Rb1 { Supporting the b2 pawn. } 17... e5 18. Be3
{ The threat is b4. } 18... Qc6 19. Bf1 Rfe8 20. Rd2
{ White has secured the d6-pawn and keeps control.  When the position finally opens, the bishop pair will prove to be stronger. }
