8... Qc7 { The main move. Before playing Qb6 Black weakens the e3 square. } 9.
f4 { Forced, the pawn must be protected. } 9... Qb6
{ With the inclusion of the move Qc7 Black has provoked the weakening of the g1-a7 diagonal and secured the e3 square for his knight. }
10. c4
{ Attacking the knight. Black is at the crossroads now:  10...Bb4+  or  10...Ne3  . }
10... Ne3 11. Qd3 { Forced reply, but good enough. } 11... Bb4+
{ Black has weak squares, which he tries to compensate with quick development. }
12. Bd2 O-O
{ 12...Rb8  is too early, after  13.b3  the rook is misplaced on the b-file. }
13. Rc1 { Covering the c2 square, and preparing to capture on b4. } 13... f5
14. exf6 Ng4
{ Black uses tactical motifs to keep knight in the game since he doesn't want to change it for the undeveloped bishop from f1. }
15. c5 { Closing diagonals and fixing black pawn on d7. } 15... Qa5 16. a3
{ Forcing exchanges. } 16... Bxd2+ 17. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 18. Kxd2 Nxf6 19. Nd6
{ White has nice edge thanks to the strong knight on d6. } *

