f4 { Forced, the pawn must be protected. } 9... Qb6
{ With the inclusion of the move Qc7 Black has provoked the weakening of the g1-a7 diagonal and secured the e3 square for his knight. }
10. c4
{ Attacking the knight. Black is at the crossroads now:  10...Bb4+  or  10...Ne3  . }
10... Ne3 11. Qd3 { Forced reply, but good enough. } 11... Nf5
{ Black is trying to place the knight to its ideal square: d4.  However, he loses a lot of time in the opening just to improve one piece. }
12. Bd2
{ Developing the queenside.  12.g4  is more popular but this allows Black to  create some counterplay connected with the move h5. }
12... c5 13. O-O-O Bb7 14. Ba5
{ Interesting idea which forces the Black queen to move to a worse square. White usually chooses  14.Bc3  but after  14...Rd8  15.Be2  d5  I don’t know how big White’s advantage is. }
14... Qc6 15. Be2 Nd4 16. Bf3
{ The whole point of playing Ba5. We are  threatening a discovered attack once again. Giving up the strong knight on d4  which blocks the d-file is not a good option for Black. }
16... Qa4 { Or  16...Qa6  17.Bc3  . } 17. Bc3 { The knight on d4 has to go. }
17... Qxa2 18. Bxd4 cxd4 19. Nc3
{ Before capturing on d4 White has an intermediate move. Both the bishop and the queen are hanging. }
19... Qa6 { 19...Qa1+  20.Kc2  only improves White’s king. } 20. Qxd4 Bc6 21.
Nb5
{ With the idea of Nc7.  White has the initiative. Black still hasn’t developed the kingside. }
