[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Four knights defence. Black follows the basic opening principles and develops both his knights, before deciding where should the queen go @@StartBracket@@d8, c7, b6 or sometimes even a5@@EndBracket@@ and his dark squared bishop @@StartBracket@@e7, c5 or b4@@EndBracket@@.   Without wasting time on playing a7-a6 Black is already prepared to strike in the centre with the move d7-d5 with the possible inclusion of the move Bb4. Currently, this variation is highly popular, played by majority of the top players, and some Sveshnikov players use it as an alternative @@StartBracket@@for some players it is even first choice@@EndBracket@@ way of reaching the Sveshnikov.   After  6.Ndb5  d6  7.Bf4  e5  8.Bg5  Black has avoided numerous Rossolimo lines and the trendy 7. Nd5 variation which is also my recommendation against Sveshnikov.   Therefore, instead of  6.Ndb5  we must choose the another principled @@StartBracket@@and probably the best@@EndBracket@@ move,  6.Nxc6  . }
6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Practically, the forced recapture. Taking with the other pawn leads to a bad endgame for Black.  6...dxc6  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  8.e5  Nd5  9.Ne4  followed by Bd2, c4 and O-O-O gives White a nice edge thanks to the space advantage, and the bad light-squared bishop in Black's camp. }
7. e5
{ The point of Nxc6, playing e5 quickly. That pawn will trouble Black in many lines. You will see that most of White's moves are based on chasing black's knight which won't be safe on d5. }
7... Nd5 8. Ne4
{ The d6 is the weakest square in Black's position, and knight from e4 controls it nicely. This move also creates a threat of playing c2-c4. Now, Black has couple of different moves to choose, two of them are having solid reputation.   First one is  8...Bb7  which leads to a slightly inferior but defendable endgame, and another one is the main move  8...Qc7  . }
8... Qc7 { The main move. Before playing Qb6 Black weakens the e3 square. } 9.
f4 { Forced, the pawn must be protected. } 9... Qb6
{ With the inclusion of the move Qc7 Black has provoked the weakening of the g1-a7 diagonal and secured the e3 square for his knight. }
10. c4
{ Attacking the knight. Black is at the crossroads now:  10...Bb4+  or  10...Ne3  . }
10... Bb4+ { The main move, and currently more popular than  10...Ne3  . } 11.
Ke2
{ Forced reply. Otherwise, White loses material:  11.Bd2  Qe3+  12.Qe2  Bxd2+  13.Nxd2  Qxe2+  14.Bxe2  Nxf4  . }
11... f5 { Practically, the only move for Black. } 12. exf6
{ White has two equally good moves:  12.Nf2  and  12.exf6  . It is hard to say which one is better, but the text move helps White to develop pieces quicker. }
12... Nxf6 13. Be3 Qa5 14. Nxf6+
{ The only good move for White, but gives more than enough advantage. } 14...
gxf6 15. Kf2
{ Gives White a nice edge. His king is safe on f2 unlike the black one. } *

