{ White wants to play Bg4, forcing Black to react quickly and give up a pawn on e6. After  21...d6  both  21.Qxe6  and  21.Bxe6  are equally good, and I will leave this very instructive queen sacrifice as an example of White ideas. }
21... d6 22. Qxe6+ Kh8 23. Rgf1 Rb6 24. b3 Ra6 25. Rd2 d5 26. Qe5 Re8 27. cxd5
Rxe5 28. fxe5 Bxd5 29. Bg2 c4 30. Bxd5 c3 31. Bb7 cxd2 32. Bxa6 Qe8 33. Bc4 g6
34. e6 { 1-0 Wei Yi - A.Fier, Moscow 2019. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 2...e6 - Paulsen: 4...Nc6 5. Nc3 Bc5 and 5...a6"]
[Black "Paulsen 5...Bc5  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ The most natural move in the current position. Black develops the knight and attacks the d4 square. }
5. Nc3
{ First knights, bishops afterwards. There are three major lines for Black here:   a@@EndBracket@@  5...a6  ,  b@@EndBracket@@  5...Nf6  theFour Knights variation and  c@@EndBracket@@  5...Qc7  theTaimanov variation, and some minor moves. }
5... Bc5 { The first 'minor' move. } 6. Nb3
{ 6.Ndb5  Nf6  is a common variation that occurs from the 4 Knights variation @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Ndb5  Bc5  . Since I'm not recommending 6. Ndb5 there, I would like to avoid that variation.   In case of  6.Be3  Qb6  is the point, with a messy position. The recommended move attacks the bishop with tempo and immediately asks questions. }
6... Bb6
{ The only square for the bishop which makes the move Qg4 ineffective. However, the bishop is no longer covering the a3-f8 diagonal which is the biggest weakness in black's position. }
7. Bf4
{ 7.Nb5  looks very tempting  d5  8.exd5  exd5  9.Bf4  Nge7  10.Nd6+  Kf8  11.Qh5  Be6  Black's king is in the center, but I'm not sure how to continue the attack. }
7... e5
{ Practically forced, Black can't allow the bishop to land on d6.  7...Nge7  8.Bd6  would give White a big advantage. }
8. Bg3 d6 { A normal move which gives White a pleasant advantage after } 9. Nb5
Bc7 10. Bh4 { Small tactics help White to achieve a positional goal. } 10...
Nf6 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Bc4
{ Black has a weak pawn structure, a weak d5 square and there is hardly anything good in his position. }
*

