[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 2...e6 - Paulsen: 4...Nc6 5. Nc3 Bc5 and 5...a6"]
[Black "Paulsen 5...a6 6.a3  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3
{ First knights, bishops afterwards. There are three major lines for Black here:   a@@EndBracket@@  5...a6  ,  b@@EndBracket@@  5...Nf6  theFour Knights variation and  c@@EndBracket@@  5...Qc7  theTaimanov variation, and some minor moves. }
5... a6
{ To understand this move, you have to know what's happening after  5...Qc7  . In that case White can play  6.Be3  and choose English attack systems which were quite unpleasant for Black.   Here, the difference in case of  6.Be3  Nf6  7.Qd2  Bb4  8.f3  is  7...d5  or even  7...e5  with the idea to play d5 after Nf5. }
6. a3
{ 6.Nxc6  has always been considered as the most principled reaction against the 5... a6 variation. In general, I believe that White's chances are better in aforementioned line, but it is very far from simple.   Therefore, I am proposing a much simpler solution. The main point behind the move  6.a3  is that Black doesn't have anything better than playing  6...Qc7  and transposing to the Taimanov variation }
6... Nf6
{ Bad move, because it leads to the 4 knights variation with a3 and a6 included. There, a3 is a very useful move for White, and a6 is just nonsense and weakening for Black. }
7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 Nd5 9. Ne4
{ The b4-square is covered and half of the lines which are working in the 4 knights aren't even playable here for Black. }
*

