6... Nge7 { Preparing to capture on d4 and put the other knight on c6. } 7. Bf4
{ Developing move must be good. White has also other interesting options here:  a@@EndBracket@@  7.Nb3  is the typical reaction against Nge7 avoiding the exchange on d4 and  b@@EndBracket@@  7.h4!?  just gaining space on the kingside. After exchanges on d4, white's queen will go to e3, followed by Bd2 and O-O-O. }
7... d5 { If  7...Ng6  then  8.Be3  and the knight on g6 is a bit misplaced. }
8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Nxc6 Qxc6
{ Taking with pawn is much worse for Black  10...bxc6  11.Be2  and he will have to passively defend the c6-pawn. }
11. Qd3
{ White can hope for something here because of the black bishop on c8. } 11...
Be7 12. O-O-O O-O
{ Both sides have castled and the position might seem equal. However, white's bishops are stronger and his attack is faster. }
13. Be2 Bf6
{ Taking on g2 is obviously very dangerous, because you open the g-file in front of Black's king. }
14. h4
{ We still don't care about the f2 and g2 pawns. White has promising attack. }
*

