[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) 2...e6 - Taimanov: 4...Nc6 5.Nc3 Qc7"]
[Black "Taimanov 6...Nf6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ The Taimanov variation. Slightly more flexible than  5...a6  .   Black is not afraid of  6.Ndb5  because of  6...Qb8  and a6 on the next move. In some lines Black can even play without a6 @@StartBracket@@Nf6 and quickly Bb4@@EndBracket@@.   This move also makes  6.Nxc6  harmless. }
6. Be3 { White develops the bishop and prepares for the English attack. } 6...
Nf6
{ You can make an argument that this is even an imprecise move, since it allows White to play f4. The main move  6...a6  will be covered in the next chapter with theKeres variation. }
7. f4 { White can allow Bb4 here because he threatens e5. } 7... Nxd4
{ This was used as a surprise weapon a decade ago, but nowadays has completely gone out of practice. }
8. Qxd4
{ Even  8.Bxd4  is possible for White, but here White doesn't have to give up the pawn. }
8... Ng4 9. Nb5
{ Before moving the bishop, White has to drive away the queen from the f4-pawn. }
9... Qc6 10. Bg1 a6 11. Nc3 b5 12. Be2
{ With Bf3 next, White's pieces are well developed. } *

