{ A semi-waiting move which is not the most popular reaction against the Taimanov variation, but full of venom and very practical. It avoids tons of variations. The most popular moves are the classical  7.Qf3  and  7.Qd2  with English attack setup.   The problem of the  7.Qd2  line is that Black has found a good antidote almost a decade ago and White still hasn't found the way to pose Black big problems.   Currently, the 'main' move is  7.Qf3  , the most aggressive option for White. However, this move has already been covered in some books and also Chessable courses, and I don't want to repeat the same recommendations from the other authors. }
7... Nf6 { A natural move which allows White to show his idea. } 8. f4
{ More powerful than  8.f3  . Instead of playing in the English attack style @@StartBracket@@f3, Qd2, O-O-O, g4...@@EndBracket@@ White aims for the more aggressive setup with the pawn on f4, queen on f3, followed by O-O-O and g4. }
8... Nxd4
{ 8...d5  9.e5  Nd7  10.Qd2  White gets a slightly favourable version of the French defense, since Black's queen on c7 is a bit misplaced there. }
9. Bxd4 { This pawn sacrifice secures an advantage for White. } 9... Qxf4 10.
g3 Qg5 { Looks as a much worse square for the queen. } 11. e5 Nd5 12. Ne4 Qh6
13. c4 Ne3 14. Qe2 Nf5 15. Bb6 Be7 16. Bg2
{ Black's queenside is horrible. For the price of one pawn White has everything else. }
*

