[Round "?"]
[White "10) 2...e6 - Taimanov: 4...Nc6 5.Nc3 Qc7"]
[Black "Taimanov 7.a3 Nf6  #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ The Taimanov variation. Slightly more flexible than  5...a6  .   Black is not afraid of  6.Ndb5  because of  6...Qb8  and a6 on the next move. In some lines Black can even play without a6 @@StartBracket@@Nf6 and quickly Bb4@@EndBracket@@.   This move also makes  6.Nxc6  harmless. }
6. Be3 { White develops the bishop and prepares for the English attack. } 6...
a6 7. a3
{ A semi-waiting move which is not the most popular reaction against the Taimanov variation, but full of venom and very practical. It avoids tons of variations. The most popular moves are the classical  7.Qf3  and  7.Qd2  with English attack setup.   The problem of the  7.Qd2  line is that Black has found a good antidote almost a decade ago and White still hasn't found the way to pose Black big problems.   Currently, the 'main' move is  7.Qf3  , the most aggressive option for White. However, this move has already been covered in some books and also Chessable courses, and I don't want to repeat the same recommendations from the other authors. }
7... Nf6 { A natural move which allows White to show his idea. } 8. f4
{ More powerful than  8.f3  . Instead of playing in the English attack style @@StartBracket@@f3, Qd2, O-O-O, g4...@@EndBracket@@ White aims for the more aggressive setup with the pawn on f4, queen on f3, followed by O-O-O and g4. }
8... d6
{ Forcing Black to Scheveningen setups can be considered as a small success for White, especially when he has the  possibility to castle queenside. The problem for Black is that he has to stop the move e5, and everything else is worse. }
9. Qf3 { The queen on f3 guards all White's pawns on the fourth rank. } 9...
Be7 10. O-O-O O-O { Last few moves were natural and easy to understand. } 11.
Nxc6
{ White would love to play  11.g4  but this runs into  11...Nxd4  followed by 12... e5 and the pawn on g4 is hanging. Therefore, White gives Black the b-file, but in return advances his kingside pawns faster. }
11... bxc6
{ Black has an open b-file but it turns out that the White attack is faster. }
12. g4 d5
{ It is very logical to open up the bishop and the queen. Black can start with  12...Rb8  first, but at some point he will have to play d5. }
13. g5 Nd7 14. h4 { Pushing pawns. } 14... Rb8 15. h5 Qa5
{ Both sides are improving pieces, and Black has created a threat. } 16. Bf2
{ White is defending along third rank. } 16... Rxb2
{ Tempting move, which doesn't work. } 17. Kxb2 Qxa3+ 18. Kb1 Nc5 19. Bxc5 Bxc5
20. Rh3
{ White's king has an escape route via d2, and also White can give back one knight since he has an extra rook. See thenext variation. }
