7... Nf6 { A natural move which allows White to show his idea. } 8. f4
{ More powerful than  8.f3  . Instead of playing in the English attack style @@StartBracket@@f3, Qd2, O-O-O, g4...@@EndBracket@@ White aims for the more aggressive setup with the pawn on f4, queen on f3, followed by O-O-O and g4. }
8... d6
{ Forcing Black to Scheveningen setups can be considered as a small success for White, especially when he has the  possibility to castle queenside. The problem for Black is that he has to stop the move e5, and everything else is worse. }
9. Qf3 { The queen on f3 guards all White's pawns on the fourth rank. } 9...
Be7 10. O-O-O O-O { Last few moves were natural and easy to understand. } 11.
Nxc6
{ White would love to play  11.g4  but this runs into  11...Nxd4  followed by 12... e5 and the pawn on g4 is hanging. Therefore, White gives Black the b-file, but in return advances his kingside pawns faster. }
11... bxc6
{ Black has an open b-file but it turns out that the White attack is faster. }
12. g4 d5
{ It is very logical to open up the bishop and the queen. Black can start with  12...Rb8  first, but at some point he will have to play d5. }
13. g5 Nd7 14. h4 { Pushing pawns. } 14... Rb8 15. h5 Qa5
{ Both sides are improving pieces, and Black has created a threat. } 16. Bf2
{ White is defending along third rank. } 16... e5
{ Tricky move.   16...f6  17.exd5  cxd5  18.h6  Followed by attack on  e6  is too dangerous for Black.   16...Rd8  Is probably the best option for Black. Taking on  b2  becomes a serious option for him since the rook is prepared for the opening of the d-file.  17.Nb1!  Amazing defensive move. Protecting the weak pawn on  a3  .  17...Qc7  18.Nd2  . White has better attacking chances. If  18...Nb6  19.exd5!  Black doesn’t have a good way to recapture on  d5  .  19...cxd5  allows  20.Bd3  . If  19...exd5  20.Bd4!  White bishop controls everything. Taking on  d5  with the piece gives White  e4  and  c4  squares. }
17. h6 Rxb2 { Black tries his luck. } 18. hxg7 Bxa3 19. Rd3
{ This precise move decides the game.  19.Rxd5!  is also powerful, giving one extra square to White's king before playing Qh5.   The point is that taking on f8 only helps Black to improve his pieces:  19.gxf8=Q+  Nxf8  20.Rd3  Rb1+  21.Kd2  dxe4  22.Qxe4  Bc1+  The bishop comes to g4 where White loses material. }
19... Rb1+ { 19...Kxg7  20.Rxh7+!!  Kxh7  21.Qh5+  Kg7  22.Rh3+- } 20. Kd2
{ Not entering into the checkmate. } 20... dxe4 21. Qxe4 Bc1+ 22. Ke2
{ White threatens checkmate in one and Black doesn't have any check. Note that Black doesn't have the Bg4 check which exists after 19. gxf8=Q+. }
