[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) 2...e6 - Taimanov: 4...Nc6 5.Nc3 Qc7"]
[Black "Taimanov 7.a3 b5  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ The Taimanov variation. Slightly more flexible than  5...a6  .   Black is not afraid of  6.Ndb5  because of  6...Qb8  and a6 on the next move. In some lines Black can even play without a6 @@StartBracket@@Nf6 and quickly Bb4@@EndBracket@@.   This move also makes  6.Nxc6  harmless. }
6. Be3 { White develops the bishop and prepares for the English attack. } 6...
a6 7. a3
{ A semi-waiting move which is not the most popular reaction against the Taimanov variation, but full of venom and very practical. It avoids tons of variations. The most popular moves are the classical  7.Qf3  and  7.Qd2  with English attack setup.   The problem of the  7.Qd2  line is that Black has found a good antidote almost a decade ago and White still hasn't found the way to pose Black big problems.   Currently, the 'main' move is  7.Qf3  , the most aggressive option for White. However, this move has already been covered in some books and also Chessable courses, and I don't want to repeat the same recommendations from the other authors. }
7... b5
{ Current state of theory says that this is the best move for Black and it is a recommendation of Harikrishna in his Taimanov course. }
8. Nxc6
{ When the bishop is on c8, and Black no longer has the possibility of taking with b-pawn on c6, it is the right time to capture on c6. Now, Black has to make a decision, to capture with a pawn or with a queen. }
8... dxc6
{ Might look like a safer option, but on the other hand, Black will lack counterplay in this line. He will have to comply with the slightly inferior endgame with almost no winning chances. }
9. Qg4
{ White's queen wants to go to g3, but needs to stop Bd6 which is possible in case of  9.Qf3  . }
9... e5 10. Qg3 h5
{ Black takes advantage of the exposed white queen with the typical reaction ...h5. }
11. Bd4 f6 { Only move, otherwise Black loses a pawn. } 12. Be3 h4
{ Black can play something like  12...Be6  which can be answered with  13.Be2  , but it is best for him to force the trade of queens immediately. }
13. Qg6+ Qf7 14. Qxf7+ Kxf7 15. a4 Rb8
{ Since playing  15...b4  is a serious positional mistake which leaves weaknesses on the queenside, Black is forced to play a defensive move. }
16. Be2 Bb4 17. O-O
{ White has finished his development. Black has a spatial advantage on the kingside thanks to the pawn on h4, but he is considerably weaker on the queenside and his pawns are targets for white pieces. }
*

