{ The best chance for White is the endgame with the opposite-coloured bishops. }
19... exf4 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. Rxd5
{ How to evaluate this position? Material is completely equal. However, White has a very active rook, control over the d-file, pawn majority on the queenside which has more potential than the black one on the kingside.   Also, black's pawns @@StartBracket@@f4, a6, b5, f7@@EndBracket@@ are easier targets than White pawns. Objectively, Black should hold this endgame, and I have no doubt that 2700 player will hold it, but that task is far from easy for an average player. }
21... Re8 22. Rhd1
{ Including the rook into the game. No need to hurry with e4-e5. } 22... g6 23.
Bf3 Kg7 24. e5 Bf8 25. c3
{ There is no clear way for Black to force a draw. In the meantime White can improve his king and start attacking pawns. }
