[Black "Keres  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6
{ Sometimes Black plays like this to make g4 less effective. However, White can play g4 anyway. }
6. g4 a6 7. Be3 Nge7
{ Black doesn't want to allow White to push g5 with tempo. } 8. Nb3
{ Avoiding the exchange of the knights. } 8... b5 9. h4 Bb7 10. Rh3
{ Removing the rook from the h1-a8 diagonal and covering the third rank. White has a simple attacking plan: Qd2, O-O-O and pushing pawns on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 2...e6 -Scheveningen: Keres attack 4...Nc6 5.Nc3 d6"]
[Black "Keres  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6
{ The Keres variation. And old line, which is out of fashion these days, but still has its supporters. The main idea behind this move order is to make  6.Bg5  less playable. After  6...h6  7.Bh4  Be7  , Black already has a threat of Nxe4 which isn't possible in the Najdorf.   The obvious drawback of this move order compared to the Najdorf is that Black made his decision of not playing e7-e5, which is a big deal. This gives White free hands to launch a typical kingside attack, and to play 6. g4 immediately, which isn't possible in the Najdorf. }
6. g4 { 6...--  7.g5  is a threat. } 6... e5 7. Nf5
{ White shouldn't hurry with Bb5+. } 7... h5
{ The only attempt to justify previous play. In the case of 8...g6 White returns the knight to e3 with full control over the d5 square. }
8. Bg5 hxg4 9. Nd5 { Active play beats everything. } 9... Bxf5 10. Bxf6 gxf6
11. exf5
{ After some trades, the position is a bit clarified. Black is temporary a pawn up, but has a terrible pawn structure and weak light squares. His king is not better either. }
11... Bh6 12. h4
{ The key move which you should remember.  12.c3  allows Bg5 with Rh4 next, where Black's position is not bad at all. }
12... Kf8 { Now White can capture on g4 with the rook. } 13. Rg1 Nc6 14. Rxg4
Ne7 15. Nxe7 Qxe7 16. Bg2 { Total domination on the light squares. } *

