[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 2...e6 -Scheveningen: Keres attack 4...Nc6 5.Nc3 d6"]
[Black "Keres  #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6
{ The Keres variation. And old line, which is out of fashion these days, but still has its supporters. The main idea behind this move order is to make  6.Bg5  less playable. After  6...h6  7.Bh4  Be7  , Black already has a threat of Nxe4 which isn't possible in the Najdorf.   The obvious drawback of this move order compared to the Najdorf is that Black made his decision of not playing e7-e5, which is a big deal. This gives White free hands to launch a typical kingside attack, and to play 6. g4 immediately, which isn't possible in the Najdorf. }
6. g4 { 6...--  7.g5  is a threat. } 6... h6 7. Rg1 Nc6 8. Be3
{ The main move is  8.h4  but this allows  8...d5  where Black has shown some new defensive ideas. The point of Be3 is to first develop the queenside @@StartBracket@@Qd2 or Qe2 and castle@@EndBracket@@ to make d6-d5 impossible and only then push the kingside pawns. }
8... Be7 9. Qe2
{ The queen goes to e2, because the pawn on g4 needs to be protected. Again, playing  9.h4  allows  9...d5  and it is not clear how White achieves an advantage there. }
9... Nxd4
{ Since all other setups are passive, Black must do something concrete. } 10.
Bxd4 e5 11. Be3 Be6
{ Planning to counter the h4-g5 march with the typical exchange sacrifice Rc8-Rxc3 @@StartBracket@@and Nxe4@@EndBracket@@. }
12. O-O-O Rc8 { 12...a6  allows  13.h4  which gives White d5-square. } 13. Qb5+
{ Black's queenside pawns are weak, which is quite unusual for the Sicilians. This move forces the trade of queens and leaves White with a better endgame. }
13... Qd7
{ 13...Nd7  is the engine’s first suggestion. We can simply grab the pawn on  b7  .  14.Qxb7  O-O  Black has some compensation for the pawn but I doubt it is enough for equality.  15.Nd5!?  White has many other moves as well  15.g5!? or 15.Qxa7!?.  Bg5  16.Kb1  Securing the king and the queenside pawns.  Bxd5  17.Qxd5  Bxe3  18.fxe3  Qc7  Last couple of moves starting from  15.Nd5  were forced. White can play  19.c3  Rb8  20.Ka1  At some point Black will return pawn and take on  e4  , but white light-squared bishop will be superior to the knight. }
14. Bxa7 { Taking a pawn. } 14... Bxg4 15. Qxd7+ Bxd7
{ Practically a forced recapture. } 16. f3 { Now, the g7 pawn is hanging. }
16... Kf8 17. Be3 Be6 18. a4 g5 19. Be2
{ White's pawn majority on the queenside should be stronger than the black one on the kingside. Also, White has the d5 square and pressure on the d6-pawn, which secures him a slight advantage. }
