1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps the knight on b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterward.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack.  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White's best choices are the positional  5.c4  and the concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3
{ In this chapter we will check some rare variations, mostly pawn moves. } 5...
Ne7
{ Black prepares for Nc6 and wants to recapture on c6 with the knight, not with the pawn. }
6. O-O Nbc6 7. c3 { White can trade knights, but only when he wants. } 7... Ng6
{ 7...e5?!  8.Nf3!  d5  Otherwise White will play c4, Nc3, and obtain full control over the d5 square.  9.exd5  Qxd5  10.Qe2  The knight on e7 stands awkward, and Black has problems here. }
8. Be3 Be7 9. Nd2 O-O
{ Last few moves were easy for both sides. Here White has many possible continuations. }
10. Qh5
{ Allowing d5 is also possible:  10.a4  d5  11.exd5  exd5  12.N2f3  And White has a good isolani structure. }
10... d6 11. Rad1 Nxd4 12. cxd4 e5 13. Bb1
{ White has a very good version of Ruy Lopez's pawn structure. } *

