1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps the knight on b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterward.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack.  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White's best choices are the positional  5.c4  and the concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3
{ In this chapter we will check some rare variations, mostly pawn moves. } 5...
Qb6
{ Against all opening principles, Black still hasn't developed any light piece. }
6. Be3
{ Voluntarily offering the b2 pawn. The only problem White could have in this line is that he needs to remember many forced variations. If you succeed, in return you should get a winning position. }
6... Bc5 7. c3 { Defending the knight. } 7... Nc6
{ Instead of taking the poisoned pawn, Black attacks the knight on d4. } 8. Nd2
{ White simply doesn't care about Black's threats. } 8... Qxb2
{ There is a reason why the b2-pawn is called poisoned. } 9. O-O
{ Before chasing the queen we secure the king, connect the rooks and avoid all kinds of checks. }
9... Ne5 { Looks logical, but it has a fantastic refutation. } 10. Nxe6
{ Not the only move which wins  @@StartBracket@@  10.Rb1  or  10.Be2  are good also.@@EndBracket@@ but the strongest and the most effective one. }
10... dxe6
{ 10...Bxe3  11.Nxg7!  Kf8  12.fxe3  Black can choose which piece to capture, but he loses anyway.  12...Kxg7   12...Nxd3  loses to  13.Rxf7!  followed by Qh5, or 13.Qh5 immediately.  13.Nc4  Qxc3   If  13...Qb5  14.Rf5  White wins back material and wins the game too.  14.Rc1!  Qxd3  15.Rxf7!  It can't be more brutal than this. If Black takes on f7 he loses the queen.  15...Kh6  16.Nxe5  White can now trade queens.  16...Qxd1  17.Rxd1  The black king is probably getting checkmated. }
11. Bxc5 Qxc3
{ 11...Nxd3  Looks like Black gained a whole knight.  12.Bd4  A nasty double attack. White is either taking the queen with Nc4, or the rook after Bxg7 and Bxh8. }
12. Nc4 { Wins in more beautiful way. } *

