{ 9...Qxe5?  Taking the pawn loses by force.  10.Nc4  Qc7  11.Nxe6!  dxe6  12.Nb6  White wins the rook.  12...Nd7  13.Nxa8  Qb8  14.Nb6  Black is still lagging in development.   9...b5  Stops Nc4, only temporarely.  10.c4  b4  11.c5!  is crushing. }
10. f4 dxe5 11. fxe5 { Now the f-file is open. } 11... Qxe5
{ 11...Ne7  12.Qf3  Nd5  here White has many good moves @@StartBracket@@13.Ne4/Bg5/Bf2/Rae1@@EndBracket@@ to keep the attack going. The following line is instructional:  13.Rae1  Nxe3  14.Rxe3  Bc5  15.c3  Nc6  16.Ne4  Nxe5  17.Qg3  and White has too many threats. }
12. Nc4 Qc7
{ It is move 12, and Black still hasn't developed any light piece. } 13. Rb1
{ White includes the last piece into the game. } 13... Bc5
{ 13...Nd7?  loses after  14.Nxe6  fxe6  15.Qh5+   13...b5?  Loses brutally after  14.Qf3!  bxc4  15.Nxe6!  An important zwischenzug.  15...Bxe6  16.Qxa8  Bd6  17.Bf4!  White has to destroy the b8-defender at all costs.  17...Bxf4  18.Rxf4  Qxf4  19.Rxb8  Ke7  20.Re8+  Kf6  21.Qd8  White will win the queen. }
14. Qg4 f5 15. Bxf5
{ White has other options as well, but this one seems the most forcing. } 15...
exf5 16. Nxf5 Bxf5 17. Qxf5 Bxe3+ 18. Kh1
{ It is quite easy to miss such moves. } 18... Nf6 19. Qe6+ Kd8 20. Rxf6 Qd7
21. Qe5
{ 21.Nxe3  Qxe6  22.Rxe6  Should also be winning for White, although Black has traded the queens. }
21... Nc6 22. Rxc6 Qxc6 23. Qxe3 Qxc4 24. Qg5+ Kd7 25. Qxg7+ Kd6 26. Rb6+
{ White will win the queen and the b7-pawn which should be more than enough for victory. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Kan Sicilian: Various 5th Moves"]
[Black "5...Qb6 with 6...Qxb2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps the knight on b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterward.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack.  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White's best choices are the positional  5.c4  and the concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3
{ In this chapter we will check some rare variations, mostly pawn moves. } 5...
Qb6
{ Against all opening principles, Black still hasn't developed any light piece. }
6. Be3
{ Voluntarily offering the b2 pawn. The only problem White could have in this line is that he needs to remember many forced variations. If you succeed, in return you should get a winning position. }
6... Qxb2
{ If Black wants to take that pawn, he should take it as soon as possible.   6...Nf6  7.Nd2  Qc7  Is just too deep for my understanding of chess.  8.O-O  Be7  9.f4  O-O  10.g4  Give White excellent attacking chances compared to the Scheveningen lines. White is about 4-5 tempi faster. }
7. Nd2 Qc3
{ 7...Nc6?!  8.Rb1  Qa3  9.Nxc6  dxc6  10.e5  As usual Black is undeveloped and has too many weak squares in his camp. }
8. O-O Qc7
{ Black must take the queen to a safe place to cover all the weaknesses. } 9.
e5 { Another 'pawn sacrifice' which prevents Black from developing. } 9... d6
{ 9...Qxe5?  Taking the pawn loses by force.  10.Nc4  Qc7  11.Nxe6!  dxe6  12.Nb6  White wins the rook.  12...Nd7  13.Nxa8  Qb8  14.Nb6  Black is still lagging in development.   9...b5  Stops Nc4, only temporarely.  10.c4  b4  11.c5!  is crushing. }
10. f4 dxe5 11. fxe5 { Now the f-file is open. } 11... Qxe5
{ 11...Ne7  12.Qf3  Nd5  here White has many good moves @@StartBracket@@13.Ne4/Bg5/Bf2/Rae1@@EndBracket@@ to keep the attack going. The following line is instructional:  13.Rae1  Nxe3  14.Rxe3  Bc5  15.c3  Nc6  16.Ne4  Nxe5  17.Qg3  and White has too many threats. }
12. Nc4 Qc7
{ It is move 12, and Black still hasn't developed any light piece. } 13. Rb1
{ White includes the last piece into the game. } 13... Bc5
{ 13...Nd7?  loses after  14.Nxe6  fxe6  15.Qh5+   13...b5?  Loses brutally after  14.Qf3!  bxc4  15.Nxe6!  An important zwischenzug.  15...Bxe6  16.Qxa8  Bd6  17.Bf4!  White has to destroy the b8-defender at all costs.  17...Bxf4  18.Rxf4  Qxf4  19.Rxb8  Ke7  20.Re8+  Kf6  21.Qd8  White will win the queen. }
14. Qg4 f5 15. Bxf5
{ White has other options as well, but this one seems the most forcing. } 15...
Nf6 16. Qg5 exf5 { 16...O-O?  loses after both  17.Nxe6  or  17.Bxe6+  . } 17.
Nxf5 Bxf5 18. Rxf5 Be7
{ 18...Bxe3  19.Qxe3  Kd8  20.Nb6  Qxh2  A nice trick, that doesn't save Black.  21.Kxh2  Ng4  22.Kh3!  The knight must be restricted.  22...Nxe3  23.Rf7  Ra7  24.Rb3!  The knight on e3 has no good squares.  24...Nxc2   After  24...Nd1  25.Kg3!  is the most precise.   While  24...Re8  runs into checkmate after  25.Rd3  25.Rc3  Nc6  26.Rd7  Ke8  27.Rxc2  White will win another knight. }
19. Nb6 O-O
{ The best practical chance for Black.   19...Ra7  Loses directly.  20.Bf4  Qxc2  21.Rc1  Qb2  22.Nd5!  Nxd5  Runs into checkmate.  23.Rc8  Kd7  24.Rxd5  Kxc8  25.Qf5  Nd7  26.Qxd7  . }
20. Nxa8 Qxc2 21. Rff1
{ White is an exchange up, and still has very good attacking chances. } *

