[Black "5...Qc7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps the knight on b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterward.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack.  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White's best choices are the positional  5.c4  and the concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3
{ In this chapter we will check some rare variations, mostly pawn moves. } 5...
Qc7 6. O-O Nc6
{ 6...Bc5  7.Nb3  and  6...d6  7.c4  will transpose to other chapters.   6...Bd6  7.Kh1  With f4 next, asking Black the question about what is the bishop doing on d6. }
7. Nxc6
{ There are 3 possible ways for Black to recapture, but none leads to equality. }
7... dxc6 8. f4 e5
{ 8...Nf6  9.e5  Nd5  10.c4  Nb4  11.Be4  c5  12.Qf3  Leads to a very passive position for Black.   8...Bc5  9.Kh1  e5  is an inferior version of 8...e5, since White will play Kh1 anyway.  10.Qe1  Nf6  11.a4!?  Gaining some space on the queenside, and making ...b5 less appealing.  11...O-O  12.a5  exf4  13.Bxf4  Qe7  14.Bg5  Qe5  15.Bxf6  gxf6  16.Nd2  White has a much better pawn structure and a safer king. }
9. Kh1 Nf6
{ 9...Bd6  10.Nd2!?  exf4  is dubious after  11.Nc4  Be6  12.Nxd6  Qxd6  13.Bxf4  when White's bishop pair is very strong. }
10. Qe1 { White queen naturally belongs to the kingside. } 10... Bd6 11. Nd2 b5
{ 11...exf4??  loses the bishop after  12.e5  Bxe5  13.Nc4  Nd7  14.Bxf4  f6  15.Qg3  O-O  16.Nxe5  fxe5  17.Bc4  Kh8  18.Bxe5  . }
12. Nf3 Nd7 13. f5 { White will have attacking prospects on the kingside. } *

