[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Kan Sicilian: Various 5th Moves"]
[Black "5...Nc6 with 6...dxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps the knight on b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterward.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack.  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White's best choices are the positional  5.c4  and the concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3
{ In this chapter we will check some rare variations, mostly pawn moves. } 5...
Nc6
{ Black challenges the knight on d4 and practically forces White to trade knights. }
6. Nxc6 { White doesn't waste time on retreating. } 6... dxc6 7. Bf4
{ A very interesting idea stands behind this move, unfairly neglected by top grandmasters. It is common knowledge that  7.Nd2  or  7.O-O  lead to slightly better positions for White, but the move  7.Bf4  is more ambitious and direct. Obviously, White's idea is to stop e6-e5. If he succeeds, he will have a big advantage.   Black can prepare e6-e5 with Ne7-Ng6 or Qf6. However, both these moves are responded in the same manner, White retreats the bishop to e3 and says that Black no longer can put the knight to his ideal square: f6. }
7... Ne7 { The only real alternative to  7...Qf6 } 8. Be3
{ 8.Nd2  Ng6  9.Be3  is almost the same. } 8... e5
{ If  8...Ng6  White can play  9.Nd2  and transpose, but he can also try  9.f4!?  . }
9. Nd2 Ng6 10. g3 { Restricting Black's knight and preparing h4. } 10... Bd6
11. h4 { 11...h5?  is very bad, after simple  12.Be2  Black loses a pawn. }
11... b5 12. Nb3 Nf8 13. Qd2 Ne6 14. a4 Rb8 15. axb5 axb5 16. Be2 O-O 17. O-O
{ Is clearly better for White, he controls the a-file and has threats on the d-file. }
*

