{ In this chapter we will check some rare variations, mostly pawn moves. } 5...
Nc6
{ Black challenges the knight on d4 and practically forces White to trade knights. }
6. Nxc6 { White doesn't waste time on retreating. } 6... bxc6 7. O-O d5 8. c4
Nf6
{ All other moves are dubious.   8...dxe4?!  Leaves Black with a weak pawn on c6.  9.Bxe4  Qxd1  10.Rxd1  Bb7  11.Nc3  Nf6  12.Bf3  Be7  13.Bf4  White's pieces are dominating, Black's kingside is weak.   8...dxc4?!  Also creates weaknesses on c6.  9.Bxc4  Qxd1   Keeping the queens on the board doesn't help Black:  9...Qc7  10.Qe2  White has a couple of plans, the simple one is Nc3, Be3, Rac1, Rfd1 etc.  10.Rxd1  Nf6  11.Nc3  Bb4  12.f3  Black has no counterplay and too many weaknesses. }
9. Qa4
{ A rarely played move, but very logical. The positional threat of taking on d5 becomes quite strong now.   Both  9.Nc3  and  9.cxd5  can lead to the famous model game Fischer - Petrosian, Candidates 1971, but Black is not forced to enter that position.   For example, after  9.Nc3  d4  can be played, and after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1p1pn2/3p4/2P1P3/3B4/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.cxd5  cxd5  10.exd5  Black should recapture on d5 with a piece. }
9... d4
{ Is better for Black than on the previous move, but doesn't equalize. } 10. e5
Nd7 11. Qxc6 Rb8 12. Qe4 Nc5 13. Qe2 Qc7 14. Nd2 Bb7 15. Nb3 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 Qxe5
17. Qxd4
{ White is a pawn up again, but Black has some hopes due to the bishop pair. }
