{ A rarely played move, but very logical. The positional threat of taking on d5 becomes quite strong now.   Both  9.Nc3  and  9.cxd5  can lead to the famous model game Fischer - Petrosian, Candidates 1971, but Black is not forced to enter that position.   For example, after  9.Nc3  d4  can be played, and after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1p1pn2/3p4/2P1P3/3B4/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.cxd5  cxd5  10.exd5  Black should recapture on d5 with a piece. }
9... Bd7
{ 9...Nxe4  Black wins the bishop pair but loses a pawn.  10.Bxe4  dxe4  11.Qxc6  Bd7  12.Qxe4  I don't see enough compensation for the pawn. }
10. e5
{ The bishop has occupied the d7-square and Black has to make an awkward decision. }
10... Ng4
{ 10...Ng8  11.Nd2  is clearly better for White.   10...c5  An intermediate move that doesn't solve the problem of the f6-knight.  11.Qc2  dxc4  12.Bxc4  Nd5  13.Nc3  Nb6  14.Bd3  The pawn on e5 secures White a spatial advantage and attacks prospects on the kingside. }
11. cxd5 { The tactical justification of White's play. } 11... Nxe5 12. dxe6
Nxd3
{ 12...Bxe6  Capturing on e6 leaves Black with worse pawn structure and weakness on c6 which can be targeted immediately with  13.Be4  . }
13. exd7+ Qxd7 { The smoke has cleared a bit. } 14. Rd1
{ White only needs to develop the queenside to keep the advantage. } 14... Nc5
15. Qc2
{ 15.Rxd7  Nxa4  16.Rc7  Bd6  17.Rxc6  Be5  Might just be enough for Black to save the game. }
15... Qc7 16. Be3 Ne6 17. Nd2 Be7 18. Rac1 Rc8
{ The last few moves were forced, and here White has a pleasant choice. } 19.
Nc4 O-O 20. Nb6 Rcd8 { The only move, otherwise Black loses an exchange. } 21.
Nd5 cxd5 22. Qxc7 Nxc7 23. Rxc7 Bf6 24. b3
{ We have only a few pieces remaining on the board, but these positions are very tricky for the defending side. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Kan Sicilian: Mainline with 5...Nf6 / 5...Bc5"]
[Black "5...Nf6 6.O-O Qc7 with 7...h5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps the knight on b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterward.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack.  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White's best choices are the positional  5.c4  and the concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3 Nf6
{ When Black plays  5...Nf6  it becomes clear that we will enter the 'hedgehog' type of position. After  6.O-O  Black can play immediately  6...d6  which is responded by  7.c4  or first include @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p3pn2/8/3NP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qc7  7.Qe2  and then go for the 'hedgehog' with  7...d6  8.c4  . }
6. O-O Qc7 7. Qe2 h5
{ Could be effective against 8.e5, but if White plays smarter it will only restrict Black possibilities, such as castling kingside. }
8. h3 d6 9. c4 Nbd7 10. f4
{ We have a 'normal' position with h3 and h5 included. } 10... h4 11. Nc3 Nh5
{ I guess this is the only way for Black to exploit the inclusion of h3 and h5. }
12. Rd1 Be7 13. Be3
{ Black can land his knight on g3, but what next? White pieces are developed and better prepared for the action. }
*

