5. Bd3 Nf6
{ When Black plays  5...Nf6  it becomes clear that we will enter the 'hedgehog' type of position. After  6.O-O  Black can play immediately  6...d6  which is responded by  7.c4  or first include @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p3pn2/8/3NP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qc7  7.Qe2  and then go for the 'hedgehog' with  7...d6  8.c4  . }
6. O-O Qc7 7. Qe2 d5 8. e5 Nfd7
{ This isn't that bad for Black. We have transposed to some sort of French defense.   8...Ne4?  9.c4!  Qxe5  10.Nf3  Qh5  11.cxd5  Black is on the verge of collapse. }
9. Bf4 { White just continues to develop. } 9... Nc5 10. Nd2 Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6
12. c4
{ Creates escape route for white light-squared bishop, forcing Black to trade off a pair of pieces. }
12... Rb8 13. b3 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Ba3 15. Qg3 O-O 16. Rae1
{ The pawn on e5 gives White attacking possibilities on the kingside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Kan Sicilian: Mainline with 5...Nf6 / 5...Bc5"]
[Black "5...Nf6 6.O-O Qc7 with 7...Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps the knight on b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterward.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack.  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White's best choices are the positional  5.c4  and the concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3 Nf6
{ When Black plays  5...Nf6  it becomes clear that we will enter the 'hedgehog' type of position. After  6.O-O  Black can play immediately  6...d6  which is responded by  7.c4  or first include @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p3pn2/8/3NP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qc7  7.Qe2  and then go for the 'hedgehog' with  7...d6  8.c4  . }
6. O-O Qc7 7. Qe2 Bc5 { Isn't compatible with Qc7. } 8. Nb3 Be7
{ 8...Ba7  9.e5  Nd5  10.Nc3!  Is quite powerful. If Black takes on c3, the a3-f8 diagonal will be opened for the white bishop. On the other hand, going backward clearly indicates an opening defeat. }
9. e5 Nd5 10. c4 Nb4 11. Bf4
{ Black takes the bishop pair in many lines, but spends too much time and allows White to develop all his pieces. Also, the d6-square remains a huge problem for him. }
11... Nxd3 12. Qxd3 Nc6 13. Nc3 { The pawn on e5 is taboo, because of Qg3. }
13... g5 { Black can try to expand on the kingside first. } 14. Bg3 h5 15. h3
h4 16. Bh2 Nxe5 17. Qe3 f6 18. c5
{ Completely paralyzes Black's queenside. White is strategically winning here. }
