18... Nc6 { Otherwise, Black is much worse. } 19. Bb3 Nd4 20. Qd1 O-O 21. Nc3
Ne5 22. Bf4 { White is a pawn up. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Kan Sicilian: Mainline with 5...Nf6 / 5...Bc5"]
[Black "5...Nf6 6.O-O Qc7 with 7...d6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps the knight on b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterward.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack.  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White's best choices are the positional  5.c4  and the concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3 Nf6
{ When Black plays  5...Nf6  it becomes clear that we will enter the 'hedgehog' type of position. After  6.O-O  Black can play immediately  6...d6  which is responded by  7.c4  or first include @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p3pn2/8/3NP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qc7  7.Qe2  and then go for the 'hedgehog' with  7...d6  8.c4  . }
6. O-O Qc7 7. Qe2 d6
{ 7...Nc6?!  Allows White to play e5.  8.Nxc6  followed by 9.e5. } 8. c4
{ White finally plays c4 and aims for the setup Nc3-Bd2-f4-Kh1-Rae1 with the e5 and f5 pawn breaks. }
8... Nbd7
{ This move together with  8...Be7  or  8...b6  often transpose into each other and in my experience in 99% of the games you will get the position from the mainline. However, Black can sometimes play too originally.   8...Nc6  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.Nc3  is usually reached via a different move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nxc6  bxc6  . }
9. f4 { This move is more precise than  9.Nc3  since it prevents 9...Ne5. }
9... Be7 10. Nc3 Nc5 { Is premature. } 11. Bc2 e5 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. exf5
{ Here Black must play 13...h5. After the natural  13...O-O?  14.g4!  he is already lost because g5 followed by Nd5 is crushing. }
13... h5 14. h3 { White has the bishop pair advantage. } *

