{ 7...Nc6?!  Allows White to play e5.  8.Nxc6  followed by 9.e5. } 8. c4
{ White finally plays c4 and aims for the setup Nc3-Bd2-f4-Kh1-Rae1 with the e5 and f5 pawn breaks. }
8... Nbd7
{ This move together with  8...Be7  or  8...b6  often transpose into each other and in my experience in 99% of the games you will get the position from the mainline. However, Black can sometimes play too originally.   8...Nc6  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.Nc3  is usually reached via a different move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nxc6  bxc6  . }
9. f4 { This move is more precise than  9.Nc3  since it prevents 9...Ne5. }
9... Be7 10. Nc3 O-O
