11. Kh1 b6
{ 11...Re8  is not advisable. White can play  12.Bd2  and Black has nothing better than  12...b6  returning to the main line, but also White can try 12.Nf3 or more aggressive 12. g4 which I like and start asking some serious questions.   11...Nc5  12.Bc2  e5  Works well against some other setups, but so far White has done everything to make this shot less effective.  13.Nf3  Bg4  14.f5  White will take the bishop pair and have a nice spot on the d5-square. }
12. Bd2 Re8
{ Played way less often than the common  12...Bb7  , but the more precise move in my opinion. }
13. Rac1
{ This is a critical moment for White. Before making this course I was convinced that  13.Rae1  is the best move for White. Now, my opinion is a bit different. I have checked all the interesting squares where the rook from a1 can go @@StartBracket@@c1,d1,e1@@EndBracket@@ and concluded that c1 might be the best one. In some strange way 13.Rac1 is a semi-waiting move.   13.Rae1  Bb7  14.Nf3  is the recommendation of Sethuraman in his course, but I don't know exactly what to do with the white pieces after  14...Nf8!?  which makes  15.e5  ineffective after  15...Nfd7  .  If White plays anything else, then Black can play Rad8 and Ng6 and I don't see a way of improving White's position. }
13... Bf8
{ 13...Bb7  14.f5  and Black doesn't have anything better than  14...Bf8  transposing into the 13...Bf8. }
14. f5 Ne5 { Black can include the text move, followed by ...Bb7. } 15. b3 Bb7
16. Bb1 Rac8 17. Rcd1
{ However, the knight on e5 blocks his rook and also makes 18.Bg5 a threat. } *

