[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Kan Sicilian: Mainline with 5...Nf6 / 5...Bc5"]
[Black "5...Nf6 6.O-O d6 with 7...Nc7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps the knight on b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterward.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack.  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White's best choices are the positional  5.c4  and the concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3 Nf6
{ When Black plays  5...Nf6  it becomes clear that we will enter the 'hedgehog' type of position. After  6.O-O  Black can play immediately  6...d6  which is responded by  7.c4  or first include @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p3pn2/8/3NP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qc7  7.Qe2  and then go for the 'hedgehog' with  7...d6  8.c4  . }
6. O-O d6
{ 6...Bc5  7.Nb3  Bd6  Not a great square for the bishop, but the only one that stops e5.  8.f4  e5  9.Nc3  O-O  10.Nd5!  Opens up White's bishop.  10...Nxd5  11.exd5  g6  12.c4  b6  13.Qe2  Re8  14.fxe5  Black's queenside is chronically undeveloped.   6...Qb6  7.Be3!  is a transposition to 5...Qb6 6.Be3. }
7. c4
{ There are many different plans here for Black, but none of them gives him enough for equality. }
7... Nc6 8. Nxc6 { ...Nc6 is always responded in the same way. } 8... bxc6 9.
Nc3 Be7 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qe2
{ With the last two moves White is being flexible about his plans. He can continue with f4, and expansion on the kingside, or he can switch to the queenside play with Rfd1, Rac1, b3 preparing the c4-c5 shot at the right moment. }
11... e5
{ 11...Qc7  allows White to continue attacking the kingside:  12.f4  Bb7  13.Bc2 }
12. Rfd1 { Now, White prepares to undermine black pawns with c4-c5. } 12... Rb8
13. h3 Qc7 14. Rac1 a5 15. b3
{ White is better, Black has a very passive position while White controls every side of the board. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Kan Sicilian: Mainline with 5...Nf6 / 5...Bc5"]
[Black "5...Nf6 6.O-O d6 with 7...Bd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps the knight on b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterward.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack.  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White's best choices are the positional  5.c4  and the concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3 Nf6
{ When Black plays  5...Nf6  it becomes clear that we will enter the 'hedgehog' type of position. After  6.O-O  Black can play immediately  6...d6  which is responded by  7.c4  or first include @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p3pn2/8/3NP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qc7  7.Qe2  and then go for the 'hedgehog' with  7...d6  8.c4  . }
6. O-O d6
{ 6...Bc5  7.Nb3  Bd6  Not a great square for the bishop, but the only one that stops e5.  8.f4  e5  9.Nc3  O-O  10.Nd5!  Opens up White's bishop.  10...Nxd5  11.exd5  g6  12.c4  b6  13.Qe2  Re8  14.fxe5  Black's queenside is chronically undeveloped.   6...Qb6  7.Be3!  is a transposition to 5...Qb6 6.Be3. }
7. c4
{ There are many different plans here for Black, but none of them gives him enough for equality. }
7... Bd7
{ Black wants to prepare Nc6 and recapture on c6 with the bishop to keep his structure solid. }
8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Nxc6 Bxc6 10. b4
{ White gains space, but also creates the possibility of playing b4-b5 at the right moment. }
10... b6
{ 10...Be7  11.b5   There is nothing wrong with  11.Bb2  followed by Qe2 and Rad1, but the text move is principled.  11...Bd7  12.a4  O-O  13.Ba3  White has some pressure on the d-file and a space advantage on the queenside. }
11. Bb2 Be7
{ 11...g6  12.b5  axb5  13.cxb5  Bb7  14.Na4  The threat is Bd4 which forces Black to play e5, thus weakening the d5-square.  14...e5  15.Nc3  Be7  16.Bc4  White has a very nice outpost on d5 and more space which gives him an advantage. }
12. Qe2 O-O 13. Rad1
{ Gives White a nice advantage with an easy plan to follow up which usually ends spectacularly after White plays Nd5 at the right moment. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Kan Sicilian: Mainline with 5...Nf6 / 5...Bc5"]
[Black "5...Nf6 6.O-O d6 with 7...g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps the knight on b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterward.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack.  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White's best choices are the positional  5.c4  and the concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3 Nf6
{ When Black plays  5...Nf6  it becomes clear that we will enter the 'hedgehog' type of position. After  6.O-O  Black can play immediately  6...d6  which is responded by  7.c4  or first include @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p3pn2/8/3NP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qc7  7.Qe2  and then go for the 'hedgehog' with  7...d6  8.c4  . }
6. O-O d6
{ 6...Bc5  7.Nb3  Bd6  Not a great square for the bishop, but the only one that stops e5.  8.f4  e5  9.Nc3  O-O  10.Nd5!  Opens up White's bishop.  10...Nxd5  11.exd5  g6  12.c4  b6  13.Qe2  Re8  14.fxe5  Black's queenside is chronically undeveloped.   6...Qb6  7.Be3!  is a transposition to 5...Qb6 6.Be3. }
7. c4
{ There are many different plans here for Black, but none of them gives him enough for equality. }
7... g6
{ This is a safer setup for Black in terms of not getting checkmated, but the big problem for Black in this variation will be the pawn on d6.   Playing e6 and g6 is usually not very compatible and this line is no exception. White has a couple of plans which give him a slight edge. }
8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Nb3 O-O 10. Be2
{ Black has a couple of moves here, and all are responded in the same manner, 11. Bf4. }
10... b6 11. Bf4 e5 { If  11...Ne8  12.e5  is strong. } 12. Be3 Be6 13. Qd2 Nc6
14. Rfd1 { White has clearly better position. } *

