7... Nc6 8. Be3 d6
{ 8...Bxe3  9.Qxe3  Now, White will play 10.Nc3 and castle queenside.  9...Nf6  10.Nc3  d6  11.O-O-O  White can soon start a kingside attack.   8...Nf6  9.Nc3  Whenever White plays Nc3 before c4 he should castle queenside.  9...d6  10.O-O-O  b5  11.Bxa7  Rxa7  12.g4  with a nice attack. }
9. O-O
{ Once Black has played d6, and no longer can play d7-d5, White can castle kingside. In the aforementioned case, White's plan is to play c4 and Nc3 to control the centre. }
9... Nf6 { 9...Bxe3  10.Qxe3  Nf6  11.c4  O-O  12.Nc3  will transpose. } 10. c4
O-O { Black can try to play without e6-e5. } 11. Nc3 Bxe3 12. Qxe3 b6 13. Rad1
Qc7 14. Be2 { White has a spatial advantage and can harass the black pawns. }
14... Bb7 15. Na4 Nd7 16. Rd2 { It is time to double the rooks. } 16... Rad8
17. Rfd1 Nc5 18. Nc3
{ With knight on c5 Black can't create counterplay against the c4-pawn. } *

