1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation. Black delays Nc6 and keeps the knight on b8 flexible. Also, the knight doesn't stand in way and blocks the queen on c7 or the bishop on b7 afterward.   This point can be seen best if White tries to deploy a typical English attack.  5.Nc3  Qc7  6.Be3?!  Bb4  7.Qd2?!  Nf6  8.f3  d5  where Black already has a more pleasant position.   The drawback of the move  4...a6  is that it doesn't develop anything nor fights for the centre. Therefore, White's best choices are the positional  5.c4  and the concrete and more flexible  5.Bd3  which I'm recommending. }
5. Bd3 Bc5
{ Black immediately challenges the knight on d4, forcing White's reaction.   5...b5  is a decent option when White plays 5.Nc3 because b5-b4 is always played with tempo, but here it doesn't make sense.  6.a4!  b4  This leaves a weak square in Black's camp.   6...bxa4  7.O-O  Bb7  8.Rxa4  is great for White. The pawn on a6 will be forever weak, and White will dominate the queenside.  7.O-O  Bb7  8.Nd2  The knight is headed toward c4, or even b6, if White manages to include a4-a5.  8...Qc7   8...Nc6  is always answered by  9.Nxc6  Bxc6  10.a5  9.Re1  Supporting e4-e5 ideas.  9...Nc6  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.a5  Be7  12.Nc4  Nf6  13.Nb6  White has a huge advantage. He can play 14.e5 with 15.Qg4 and attack on both wings.   5...e5  Looks odd, and it really is.  6.Nf5  g6  7.Ne3  Nf6  8.O-O  d6  9.Nc3!?  White can play without c4.  9...Be6  10.Bc4  Black has a tough choice.   5...b6  6.O-O  Bb7  7.c4  will most likely transpose to some classical 'hedgehog' lines which will be covered later. }
6. Nb3 Be7 { The most solid retreat. } 7. Qg4
{ Causing the weakening of the kingside. } 7... Bf6
{ I never believed in such moves. } 8. f4 d6
{ 8...d5  9.e5  Nh6  10.Qe2  Nh4  11.g3  Be7  12.N1d2  White has a very favourable French-type structure. }
9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Be3
{ White should go for the most aggressive setup. I'm not impressed by the position of the black dark-squared bishop. }
10... Nge7 11. O-O-O Qc7
{ 11...Bxc3  12.bxc3  O-O  13.Qh4  The two bishops are more dangerous than a spoiled pawn structure. }
12. Kb1 Bxc3 { 12...O-O  13.Qh5  and Black will have to give up the bishop. }
13. bxc3 O-O 14. Qh5 a5 15. a4 Bd7 16. e5 g6 17. exd6 Qxd6 18. Qh6
{ The plan is to push h-pawn. } 18... Nd5 19. Bc5 Nxc3+ 20. Ka1 Qc7 21. h4
{ Black king can't hide. } *

