{ 9...Nf6  is usually responded with  10.Bh6  , preventing O-O.   9...Nc6  10.Nc3  Qc7  11.a4  Black will play Ne5 at some point, thus transposing. }
10. a4
{ Not the main move, but quite logical. White wants to stop b5 and have an option to challenge the pawn on b6 with a4-a5. }
10... b6 11. a5 b5 12. c4 bxc4
{ 12...b4  13.Bd2  Ne5  14.Bc2  Qc7  15.Bxb4  Qxc4  16.Qxc4  Nxc4  17.N1d2  Nxd2  18.Nxd2  The endgame is unpleasant for Black. He lags in development and has more weaknesses. }
13. Bxc4 Bb7
{ 13...Ne5  14.Nc3  Nf6  15.Na4  The weak b6-square is a big problem for Black. }
14. Nc3 Ngf6 15. Bh6 Ne5 16. Rfd1
{ Black's king is the centre and something bad will happen. } *

