{ The queen has done its task on g4. } 8... d6 9. O-O Nd7
{ 9...Nf6  is usually responded with  10.Bh6  , preventing O-O.   9...Nc6  10.Nc3  Qc7  11.a4  Black will play Ne5 at some point, thus transposing. }
10. a4
{ Not the main move, but quite logical. White wants to stop b5 and have an option to challenge the pawn on b6 with a4-a5. }
10... Ne5 11. Nc3 { 11.a5  is also possible, but it will not run away. } 11...
Nf6 { If  11...Bd7  12.a5 } 12. a5 Bd7
{ Stopping 13. Na4.   12...O-O  allows  13.Na4  Bd7  14.Nb6  Rb8  15.Be3  The knight on b6 restricts Black's pieces. }
13. f4 Nxd3 14. cxd3
{ Black took the bishop pair which is usual for this line. White got the b6-square and strong center. }
14... O-O 15. Be3 Bc6 16. Nd4 { Bringing back the knight to the center. } 16...
Re8 17. h3
{ White is in no hurry, he can slowly improve his pieces and prepare some breakthroughs @@StartBracket@@f4-f5, e4-e5@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) 2...Nc6 with 4...d5"]
[Black "4...d5  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 d5
{ Black strikes in the centre, but the practice has shown that it doesn't work well. }
5. exd5
{ Much stronger than the more popular alternative. In some chess books, the recommended move is  5.Bb5  with the point that White has a better endgame. After forcing sequence  5...dxe4  6.Nxc6  Qxd1  7.Kxd1  a6  8.Ba4  Bd7  9.Nc3  Bxc6  10.Bxc6+  bxc6  11.Nxe4  e5  12.Ke2  f5  13.Nd2  Nf6  14.Nc4  O-O-O!  White's advantage doesn't impress me. }
5... Qxd5 6. Be3
{ Protecting the knight and preparing to gain a tempo with 7. Nc3. Playing too early with the queen always has its drawbacks. Here, unlike in the Scandinavian, Black has to be extra careful about Nb5-Nc7 ideas. }
6... Nxd4 { This exchange only helps White to develop. } 7. Nc3 Nf3+
{ 7...Nxc2+? is even worse, after 8.Qc2 everything opens for White pieces. If Black retreats queen on 7th move, White can even trade queens because afterwards Black can't parry both 10.Nb5 and 10. Nd5. }
8. Qxf3 Qxf3 9. gxf3 Bd7 10. O-O-O
{ White has a winning advantage in the endgame. Almost all his pieces are developed and Black can't stop all the threats. }
10... Nf6 11. Nb5 Kd8 12. Bxa7
{ White is not only a pawn up, but has dangerous attack as well. } *

