1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 d5
{ Black strikes in the centre, but the practice has shown that it doesn't work well. }
5. exd5
{ Much stronger than the more popular alternative. In some chess books, the recommended move is  5.Bb5  with the point that White has a better endgame. After forcing sequence  5...dxe4  6.Nxc6  Qxd1  7.Kxd1  a6  8.Ba4  Bd7  9.Nc3  Bxc6  10.Bxc6+  bxc6  11.Nxe4  e5  12.Ke2  f5  13.Nd2  Nf6  14.Nc4  O-O-O!  White's advantage doesn't impress me. }
5... Qxd5 6. Be3
{ Protecting the knight and preparing to gain a tempo with 7. Nc3. Playing too early with the queen always has its drawbacks. Here, unlike in the Scandinavian, Black has to be extra careful about Nb5-Nc7 ideas. }
6... e5
{ doesn't stop 7. Nc3, it just makes the d5-square and the queen on d5 more vulnerable. }
7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Nb5
{ White keeps attacking with each move, not giving time for Black to breathe. }
8... Qxd1+ 9. Rxd1 Kf8 10. Nc7 Rb8 11. Bb5 { Developing and attacking! } 11...
Bf5 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Na6
{ White achieved his goal, he will take the dark-squared bishop which leaves the black king exposed. }
13... Bxc3+ 14. bxc3
{ The black rook must protect the first rank and leave the b-file. Once White connects his rooks and one them enters the 7th rank the game could be over. }
