[White "14) 2...Nc6 with 4...d5"]
[Black "4...d5  #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 d5
{ Black strikes in the centre, but the practice has shown that it doesn't work well. }
5. exd5
{ Much stronger than the more popular alternative. In some chess books, the recommended move is  5.Bb5  with the point that White has a better endgame. After forcing sequence  5...dxe4  6.Nxc6  Qxd1  7.Kxd1  a6  8.Ba4  Bd7  9.Nc3  Bxc6  10.Bxc6+  bxc6  11.Nxe4  e5  12.Ke2  f5  13.Nd2  Nf6  14.Nc4  O-O-O!  White's advantage doesn't impress me. }
5... Qxd5 6. Be3
{ Protecting the knight and preparing to gain a tempo with 7. Nc3. Playing too early with the queen always has its drawbacks. Here, unlike in the Scandinavian, Black has to be extra careful about Nb5-Nc7 ideas. }
6... e6 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Qg4
{ The natural  8.Qd2  is also good, but  8.Qg4  looks stronger. It is basically a double threat: the g7-pawn is hanging, and the bishop on b4 isn't safe either. }
8... Qe5
{ Defending the g7 square.  8...Bxc3+  9.bxc3  Qe5  is a transposition. } 9.
O-O-O Nge7
{ If Black doesn't take on c3 immediately he will not have a second chance. }
10. Bf4 Qf6 { The queen must stay close to g7-pawn. } 11. Ne4
{ Another tempo. } 11... Qg6 12. Qxg6 hxg6 13. a3
{ The bishop is ridiculous on b4, but if Black moves it, then Nd6+ is crushing. }
13... Nd5 14. Nxc6
{ Simplifying the position, and spoiling Black's pawn structure. } 14... bxc6
15. Nd6+ { Grabbing the bishop pair. } 15... Bxd6 16. Bxd6
{ White's advantage is close to winning. He has the bishop pair, and of them is a monster. His queenside majority will soon start marching. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) 2...Nc6 with 4...d5"]
[Black "4...d5  #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 d5
{ Black strikes in the centre, but the practice has shown that it doesn't work well. }
5. exd5
{ Much stronger than the more popular alternative. In some chess books, the recommended move is  5.Bb5  with the point that White has a better endgame. After forcing sequence  5...dxe4  6.Nxc6  Qxd1  7.Kxd1  a6  8.Ba4  Bd7  9.Nc3  Bxc6  10.Bxc6+  bxc6  11.Nxe4  e5  12.Ke2  f5  13.Nd2  Nf6  14.Nc4  O-O-O!  White's advantage doesn't impress me. }
5... Qxd5 6. Be3
{ Protecting the knight and preparing to gain a tempo with 7. Nc3. Playing too early with the queen always has its drawbacks. Here, unlike in the Scandinavian, Black has to be extra careful about Nb5-Nc7 ideas. }
6... e6 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Qg4
{ The natural  8.Qd2  is also good, but  8.Qg4  looks stronger. It is basically a double threat: the g7-pawn is hanging, and the bishop on b4 isn't safe either. }
8... Qe5
{ Defending the g7 square.  8...Bxc3+  9.bxc3  Qe5  is a transposition. } 9.
O-O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3
{ Black's pieces are far away from the white king, so we shouldn't worry much about the pawn structure. More important is the bishop pair and developing advantage. }
10... Nge7 11. Bd3 { Sometimes the simplest moves are the best ones. } 11...
O-O 12. Rhe1
{ Developing the last piece. In the meanwhile, Black's queenside pieces are on their initial squares. }
12... Qa5 13. Nxc6
{ The exchange of knights removes another defender from the kingside. } 13...
Nxc6 14. Qh4 h5
{ If  14...f5  15.Kb2  , White's king is safe, and his attack will be continued. }
15. g4
{ There are simpler solutions, but this one is the strongest. White's attack is faster, as it should be since his pieces are better placed. }
15... Qxc3 16. gxh5
{ The opening of the g-file was crucial, and White's king is safe on c1. }
16... Nb4 17. h6 { Still not caring about opponents' threats. } 17... Nxa2+ 18.
Kb1 Qa3 { Black prepares mate in one. } 19. Bh7+
{ But White is faster, every move comes with check. } 19... Kxh7 20. hxg7+
{ Check. } 20... Kxg7 21. Rg1# { Checkmate! } *

