[White "15) 2...Nc6 - Grivas Sicilian"]
[Black "Grivas 7...Bb4  #18"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6
{ The Grivas variation. Personally, I'm always happy to see my opponent making an early queen move. Black wants to play some sort of classical Sicilian setup @@StartBracket@@d6, e6, a6 - b5, Nf6 - Nd7, Nc6, Be7, Qc7@@EndBracket@@.   Before placing the queen to c7 he provokes Nb3, dragging our knight from the centre. This, however is not that bad for White at all. Just to make my point I will mention that against Najdorf, move 6. Nb3 became popular recently. }
5. Nb3 Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. Qe2
{ Since the classical English attack setup @@StartBracket@@Be3, Qd2@@EndBracket@@ runs into Bb4 followed by a quick d5 White has to be more subtle. The text move is known as the right antidote to the Qb6 line. White is preparing to play e5. }
7... Bb4 8. Bd2 O-O
{ Alternatives are barely worth of mentioning or have no independent value. }
9. a3
{ Now Black has to decide, to give up the bishop or admit the 'mistake' and pretend it was all part of the plan to provoke a3. }
9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 e5 11. O-O-O Rd8
{ Used to be a main line, but White has a powerful sequence here. } 12. Rd6
{ Stopping d5 first and threatening 13. Ba5. } 12... Qc7 13. Rxf6
{ The whole point behind 12. Rd6. Black has no pieces around his king and the white dark-squared bishop will become even stronger. }
13... gxf6 14. Qg4+ Kf8 15. Qh4 { White takes a pawn. } 15... d6 16. Qxf6 Be6
17. Nd2 { White keeps attacking, Black's king is weak. } *

