[Black "Grivas 7...Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6
{ The Grivas variation. Personally, I'm always happy to see my opponent making an early queen move. Black wants to play some sort of classical Sicilian setup @@StartBracket@@d6, e6, a6 - b5, Nf6 - Nd7, Nc6, Be7, Qc7@@EndBracket@@.   Before placing the queen to c7 he provokes Nb3, dragging our knight from the centre. This, however is not that bad for White at all. Just to make my point I will mention that against Najdorf, move 6. Nb3 became popular recently. }
5. Nb3 Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. Qe2
{ Since the classical English attack setup @@StartBracket@@Be3, Qd2@@EndBracket@@ runs into Bb4 followed by a quick d5 White has to be more subtle. The text move is known as the right antidote to the Qb6 line. White is preparing to play e5. }
7... Be7
{ is unpopular since it allows  8.e5  . However, it is questionable whether  8.e5  the is best move for White. }
8. Be3
{ 8.e5  Nd5  9.Nxd5  exd5  Black will castle and play d6, and I'm not sure what White should do. }
8... Qc7 9. O-O-O { Finishing the development. } 9... d5
{ This is the only way for Black to take advantage of not playing a6. How good or bad it is, that's another question. }
10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 exd5
{ White shouldn't hurry with taking on d5 since it gives Black nice compensation. }
12. g4
{ A multipurpose move. It covers f5-square, helps White to develop the bishop, and starts a kingside attack. }
12... O-O 13. Bg2 Be6 14. Kb1 { Securing the king and the pawn on a2. } 14...
Rad8 15. Nd4
{ The 'isolani' on d5 remains there and White's attack on the kingside is potentially more dangerous than Black's queenside attack. }
*

