[White "15) 2...Nc6 - Grivas Sicilian"]
[Black "Grivas 7...d6  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6
{ The Grivas variation. Personally, I'm always happy to see my opponent making an early queen move. Black wants to play some sort of classical Sicilian setup @@StartBracket@@d6, e6, a6 - b5, Nf6 - Nd7, Nc6, Be7, Qc7@@EndBracket@@.   Before placing the queen to c7 he provokes Nb3, dragging our knight from the centre. This, however is not that bad for White at all. Just to make my point I will mention that against Najdorf, move 6. Nb3 became popular recently. }
5. Nb3 Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. Qe2
{ Since the classical English attack setup @@StartBracket@@Be3, Qd2@@EndBracket@@ runs into Bb4 followed by a quick d5 White has to be more subtle. The text move is known as the right antidote to the Qb6 line. White is preparing to play e5. }
7... d6 { Black goes for the classical setup. } 8. g4 a6
{ 8...Be7  9.g5  Nd7  10.Be3  Qc7  11.O-O-O  a6  12.f4  transposes tothis line. }
9. Be3 Qc7 10. g5 { White's moves are simple and good. } 10... Nd7 11. O-O-O b5
12. f4
{ Here Black has couple of different plans, but none of them gives him enough counterplay for equality. I've realized that Black should keep his bishop on c8 to keep pawn on e6 protected and his best chance to create some counterplay should be connected with b4-Rb8 etc.   Actually, it would even make some sense to stop my analysis here because White has so many different promising plans and moves that it was hard for me to pick one. }
12... Nb6 13. Qf2 { Shows the merits of the bishop being on f1. } 13... Nc4 14.
Bxc4 bxc4 15. Bb6 { An intermediate move which removes the queen from c-file. }
15... Qb8 16. Nd2
{ And White is completely winning. The pawn on c4 falls and probably d6 afterwards. }
*

