[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) 2...Nc6 - Loewenthal: 4...e5 5. Nb5 a6"]
[Black "Loewenthal 7...f5  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 a6
{ Black claims that White has played too many moves in the early stage with his knight and he doesn't care if his bishop from f8 gets traded. In return for the bishop pair Black gets a development advantage.   Other reasonable moves are  5...d6  which is covered in the next chapter, Kalashnikov variation, and  5...Nf6  6.N1c3  isSveshnikov variation. }
6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6
{ Black has a couple of choices, but only two of them are playable:  7...Qf6  or  7...Qe7  . Everything else is clearly worse for Black. }
7... f5 { Looks unnatural. } 8. Nc3 Qf6 9. Qd1
{ Going all the way back is the strongest response and very typical in this line. 10. Nd5 is a dangerous threat. }
9... Nge7 10. Qh5+
{ White has other good moves such as  10.Be3  but this one creates even more mess in Black's position. }
10... Qg6
{ 10...g6  is strongly answered by  11.Bg5!  when Black has terrible weaknesses on the dark squares, and the endgame doesn't help him much. }
11. Qxg6+ { Exchanging queens to emphasize weaknesses. } 11... hxg6 12. Be3
{ This is a dream endgame for White. The bishop pair, the better pawn structure and weaknesses in Black's camp should be enough for White to claim a winning advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
