[Round "?"]
[White "16) 2...Nc6 - Loewenthal: 4...e5 5. Nb5 a6"]
[Black "Loewenthal 7...Nf6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 a6
{ Black claims that White has played too many moves in the early stage with his knight and he doesn't care if his bishop from f8 gets traded. In return for the bishop pair Black gets a development advantage.   Other reasonable moves are  5...d6  which is covered in the next chapter, Kalashnikov variation, and  5...Nf6  6.N1c3  isSveshnikov variation. }
6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6
{ Black has a couple of choices, but only two of them are playable:  7...Qf6  or  7...Qe7  . Everything else is clearly worse for Black. }
7... Nf6
{ This natural move leads Black to an inferior version of the 7...Qe7 line. The problem is that he doesn't have the option of recapturing on e7 with the knight from g8. }
8. Nc3 Qe7 9. Qxe7+ { 9.Qd1  transposes, but why not punish Black. } 9... Nxe7
{ 9...Kxe7  10.Bg5  is worse for Black because Nd5 is unstoppable. } 10. Bg5 b5
11. O-O-O Bb7 12. f3 { Fortifying e4. } 12... Bc6
{ Black wants to play b4, and covers d7 pawn. } 13. a3 { Stops b4. } 13... O-O
14. g3
{ The light-squared bishop will go to h3. White's bishop pair is very strong. Also, Black hasn't solved the problem of the d-pawn. }
*

