{ Black claims that White has played too many moves in the early stage with his knight and he doesn't care if his bishop from f8 gets traded. In return for the bishop pair Black gets a development advantage.   Other reasonable moves are  5...d6  which is covered in the next chapter, Kalashnikov variation, and  5...Nf6  6.N1c3  isSveshnikov variation. }
6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6
{ Black has a couple of choices, but only two of them are playable:  7...Qf6  or  7...Qe7  . Everything else is clearly worse for Black. }
7... Qe7 8. Qd1
{ It is counterintuitive to return your queen to its initial square, but that is the only square which doesn't block the bishops. We want to have open diagonals.   Delaying  8...Nf6  is not advisable. }
