{ Black claims that White has played too many moves in the early stage with his knight and he doesn't care if his bishop from f8 gets traded. In return for the bishop pair Black gets a development advantage.   Other reasonable moves are  5...d6  which is covered in the next chapter, Kalashnikov variation, and  5...Nf6  6.N1c3  isSveshnikov variation. }
6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6
{ Black has a couple of choices, but only two of them are playable:  7...Qf6  or  7...Qe7  . Everything else is clearly worse for Black. }
7... Qe7 8. Qd1
{ It is counterintuitive to return your queen to its initial square, but that is the only square which doesn't block the bishops. We want to have open diagonals.   Delaying  8...Nf6  is not advisable. }
8... Nf6 9. Nc3 d6 10. Bg5 { Developing and planning Nd5 jump. } 10... Be6
{ Covering the d5 square. } 11. Nd5
{ If Black consolidates he will have a fine position, so White must react quickly.   Taking a pawn gives Black enough compensation after  11.Bxf6  Qxf6  12.Qxd6  Rd8  13.Qc5  Nd4  14.Bd3  Qg5  . }
11... Bxd5
{ 11...Qd8?!  12.Bxf6  gxf6  13.c3  and Black is left with a terrible pawn structure, and his king won't be safe either. }
12. exd5 Nb8
{ This is by far Black's best chance in the whole 7...Qe7 variation. } 13. Qf3
{ 13.Be2  or  13.c4  are played more often with castling kingside, but the text move seems more critical to me. }
13... Nbd7 14. O-O-O Rc8 { Black is not rushing into castling. } 15. Kb1
{ Improving the king. } 15... b5 { Black gains space on the queenside. } 16.
Be2 { Connecting the rooks. } 16... O-O 17. Rhe1
{ This is the most flexible move in the position. Before playing g4 and h4 White consolidates the centre and waits to see what setup will Black choose. The two bishops will give an advantage to White for a very long time. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) 2...Nc6 - Loewenthal: 4...e5 5. Nb5 a6"]
[Black "Loewenthal 7...Qf6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 a6
{ Black claims that White has played too many moves in the early stage with his knight and he doesn't care if his bishop from f8 gets traded. In return for the bishop pair Black gets a development advantage.   Other reasonable moves are  5...d6  which is covered in the next chapter, Kalashnikov variation, and  5...Nf6  6.N1c3  isSveshnikov variation. }
6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6
{ Black has a couple of choices, but only two of them are playable:  7...Qf6  or  7...Qe7  . Everything else is clearly worse for Black. }
7... Qf6 8. Qd2
{ My initial idea was  8.Qd1  , but the variation becomes just too long and complex.  8.Qd2  is a much simpler solution. White indeed blocks the bishop on c1, but his plan is to play b3-Bb2 and O-O-O and queens on d2 fits perfectly there.   8.Qxf6  Exchanging queens is another simple possibility and leads  to a quiet endgame where White puts his hopes into the bishop pair, while Black  parries it with harmonious piece setup. I believe Black can hold that position  without much worries.  8...Nxf6  9.Nc3  Nb4  10.Kd2  d6  11.a3  Nc6  12.Ke1  Be6  13.f3  Ke7  14.Be3  Rhc8  . }
8... Qg6 9. Nc3 Nf6 { Is quite bad for Black. } 10. Qd6
{ Black can't take on e4 since he loses a knight, trading queens with  10...Ng4  and leads to clearly inferior endgame. }
10... b5 11. Be3 b4 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5
{ with 14. O-O-O on next move. White has the bishop pair and the black d-pawn is weak. }
*

