[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) 2...Nc6 - Loewenthal: 4...e5 5. Nb5 a6"]
[Black "Loewenthal 7...Qf6  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 a6
{ Black claims that White has played too many moves in the early stage with his knight and he doesn't care if his bishop from f8 gets traded. In return for the bishop pair Black gets a development advantage.   Other reasonable moves are  5...d6  which is covered in the next chapter, Kalashnikov variation, and  5...Nf6  6.N1c3  isSveshnikov variation. }
6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6
{ Black has a couple of choices, but only two of them are playable:  7...Qf6  or  7...Qe7  . Everything else is clearly worse for Black. }
7... Qf6 8. Qd2
{ My initial idea was  8.Qd1  , but the variation becomes just too long and complex.  8.Qd2  is a much simpler solution. White indeed blocks the bishop on c1, but his plan is to play b3-Bb2 and O-O-O and queens on d2 fits perfectly there.   8.Qxf6  Exchanging queens is another simple possibility and leads  to a quiet endgame where White puts his hopes into the bishop pair, while Black  parries it with harmonious piece setup. I believe Black can hold that position  without much worries.  8...Nxf6  9.Nc3  Nb4  10.Kd2  d6  11.a3  Nc6  12.Ke1  Be6  13.f3  Ke7  14.Be3  Rhc8  . }
8... Qg6 9. Nc3 d5 10. Nxd5
{ 10.f3  might be even stronger, but Black has some attacking possibilities there, while after  10.Nxd5  White is the one attacking. }
10... Qxe4+ 11. Be2 Qxg2 12. Rf1
{ 12.Nc7+  Kf8  13.Rf1  is practically the same. } 12... Rb8 13. Nc7+ Kf8 14.
b3 Nf6
{ The only move,  14...Nge7?  is bad for Black  15.Ba3  Bf5  16.O-O-O  and White's attack is too strong. }
15. Ba3+ Kg8 16. O-O-O
{ Surprisingly White is not winning here, although it looks terrible for Black. }
16... h6 17. f4 Bg4
{ Again, the only move for Black which forces White to trade queens. } 18. Bxg4
Qxd2+ 19. Rxd2 Nxg4 20. Rg1
{ And White keeps attacking chances and the initiative despite having the queens off the board. }
