[Round "?"]
[White "17) 2...Nc6 - Kalashnikov: 7...Be6 and 7...Be7"]
[Black "Kalashnikov 7...Be6  #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6
{ The Kalashnikov variation. The younger brother of the more popular Sveshnikov. Black is flexible about the move Nf6 since he doesn't want to get pinned with Bg5 @@StartBracket@@which happens in the Svehnikov@@EndBracket@@. This however has some drawbacks, the obvious one is that it allows the Nd5 jump. }
6. N1c3
{ 6.c4  is another way to deal with Kalashnikov, but  6.N1c3  fits better in our repertoire. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ Here we have another branching point. Black can play  7...b5  to stop  8.Nc4  or he can play some developing move:   a@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  ,   b@@EndBracket@@  7...Be6  and   c@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7  . }
7... Be6 8. Nc4 { Improving our worst piece. } 8... Rb8
{ The newest invention from Black who would like to play Nf6, but he doesn't like Bg5, and playing b7-b5 is creating weaknesses on the queenside.   This is a semi-waiting move, it prevents Be3 because of b5 and waits for White response. Many strong players have tried it such as Radjabov, Dubov, Maghsoodloo, Anton Guijarro... }
9. a4 { Preventing b5 in some cases, and also waiting for Black to play Nf6. }
9... Nb4 { Black uses the available b4 square. } 10. Nd5
{ Connected with the pawn sacrifice idea, which is quite common in the Najdorf variation. }
10... Bxd5 11. exd5 Nf6
{ The pawn on d5 is hanging, if White plays  12.Ne3  Qa5  comes. White should however wait for Black to capture that pawn to open up his light-squared bishop. }
12. g3 { Bg2 is the idea.  Black can try to be smart with 12...Qc8 } 12... Qc8
13. Ne3 Nfxd5
{ The knight on e3 is overloaded, but this is boomerang tactics for Black. }
14. c3 Nxe3 15. Bxe3 Nc6 16. Bg2
{ For the price of a pawn White got full control over the light squares. }
16... Be7 17. b4 O-O 18. O-O
{ White has more than enough compensation, and Black will have trouble when defending the queenside. }
