1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6
{ The Kalashnikov variation. The younger brother of the more popular Sveshnikov. Black is flexible about the move Nf6 since he doesn't want to get pinned with Bg5 @@StartBracket@@which happens in the Svehnikov@@EndBracket@@. This however has some drawbacks, the obvious one is that it allows the Nd5 jump. }
6. N1c3
{ 6.c4  is another way to deal with Kalashnikov, but  6.N1c3  fits better in our repertoire. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ Here we have another branching point. Black can play  7...b5  to stop  8.Nc4  or he can play some developing move:   a@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  ,   b@@EndBracket@@  7...Be6  and   c@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7  . }
7... Be6 8. Nc4 { Improving our worst piece. } 8... Rc8 9. Be3
{ White is not afraid of the tactics on the c-file. 10. Nb6 is a threat, so the only thing we need to check is 9...Nd4. }
9... Nd4 10. Bxd4 Bxc4 { 10...exd4?  11.Qxd4  and White wins a pawn. } 11. Bxc4
Rxc4 12. Be3
{ The exchanges were clearly in White's favour. He is just one move from finishing development and the d5 square is still big problem for Black. }
12... Nf6 13. Qd3 Qc7
{ 13...Qc8  14.Bg5  Rd4  15.Qe2  and White will soon jump on d5. } 14. O-O Be7
15. Bg5 { Attacking the last defender of the d5-square. } 15... Rd4 16. Qf3 Qc6
{ 16...Nxe4  17.Be3!  wins the exchange for White. } 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Nd5
{ With monster knight on d5, White gets the most typical advantage in this structure. }
