[Black "Kalashnikov 7...Be6  #21"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6
{ The Kalashnikov variation. The younger brother of the more popular Sveshnikov. Black is flexible about the move Nf6 since he doesn't want to get pinned with Bg5 @@StartBracket@@which happens in the Svehnikov@@EndBracket@@. This however has some drawbacks, the obvious one is that it allows the Nd5 jump. }
6. N1c3
{ 6.c4  is another way to deal with Kalashnikov, but  6.N1c3  fits better in our repertoire. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ Here we have another branching point. Black can play  7...b5  to stop  8.Nc4  or he can play some developing move:   a@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  ,   b@@EndBracket@@  7...Be6  and   c@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7  . }
7... Be6 8. Nc4 { Improving our worst piece. } 8... b5
{ Black should chase this knight immediately. } 9. Ne3 { The only square. }
9... Nf6 { 9...Be7  10.a4!?  b4  11.Ncd5  Nf6  12.Bd3  transposes to 9...Nf6. }
10. Bd3 { Covering the pawn on e4. } 10... Nb4
{ Covering d5 and attacking bishop at the same time. } 11. a4
{ The light-squared bishop is not that important. } 11... Qa5
{ Stopping axb5, but that's all this move does. } 12. O-O Nxd3 13. Qxd3 b4
{ Black will have to play this move at some point. } 14. Ncd5 Nxd5
{ Keeps the bishop pair, but loses time. } 15. exd5 Bd7 16. Nc4 Qc7 17. Be3
{ Is hopeless for Black. His lag in development is huge. } *

