[Black "Kalashnikov 7...Be7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6
{ The Kalashnikov variation. The younger brother of the more popular Sveshnikov. Black is flexible about the move Nf6 since he doesn't want to get pinned with Bg5 @@StartBracket@@which happens in the Svehnikov@@EndBracket@@. This however has some drawbacks, the obvious one is that it allows the Nd5 jump. }
6. N1c3
{ 6.c4  is another way to deal with Kalashnikov, but  6.N1c3  fits better in our repertoire. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ Here we have another branching point. Black can play  7...b5  to stop  8.Nc4  or he can play some developing move:   a@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  ,   b@@EndBracket@@  7...Be6  and   c@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7  . }
7... Be7
{ Black waits with Nf6 since he doesn't want to allow the pinning Bg5. } 8. Be3
{ An alternative way to fight against the Be7 line. The main move 8.Nc4 is covered in the next chapter. }
8... Nf6 { The critical response. } 9. Nc4 { Going for Nb6 jump. } 9... b5
{ 9...Be6  10.Nb6  Rb8  11.Be2  was covererd in the 7...Be6. } 10. Nb6
{ A forced move. } 10... Bg4
{ The text move is bad both positionally and tactically. } 11. f3
{ Two pieces are hanging in Black's camp. } 11... Rb8 12. fxg4
{ Simply taking material. } 12... Rxb6 13. g5
{ Getting the d5 square under control. } 13... Nd7 14. Bxb6 Nxb6 15. h4
{ Defending the pawn on g5. } 15... h6 16. a4
{ Should be winning for White who activated both rooks, which is very important when you are an exchange up. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) 2...Nc6 - Kalashnikov: 7...Be6 and 7...Be7"]
[Black "Kalashnikov 7...Be7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6
{ The Kalashnikov variation. The younger brother of the more popular Sveshnikov. Black is flexible about the move Nf6 since he doesn't want to get pinned with Bg5 @@StartBracket@@which happens in the Svehnikov@@EndBracket@@. This however has some drawbacks, the obvious one is that it allows the Nd5 jump. }
6. N1c3
{ 6.c4  is another way to deal with Kalashnikov, but  6.N1c3  fits better in our repertoire. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ Here we have another branching point. Black can play  7...b5  to stop  8.Nc4  or he can play some developing move:   a@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  ,   b@@EndBracket@@  7...Be6  and   c@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7  . }
7... Be7
{ Black waits with Nf6 since he doesn't want to allow the pinning Bg5. } 8. Be3
{ An alternative way to fight against the Be7 line. The main move 8.Nc4 is covered in the next chapter. }
8... Nf6 { The critical response. } 9. Nc4 { Going for Nb6 jump. } 9... b5
{ 9...Be6  10.Nb6  Rb8  11.Be2  was covererd in the 7...Be6. } 10. Nb6
{ A forced move. } 10... Rb8 11. Nxc8
{ White spent so many moves with his knight in the opening, 7 out of 11 total! In return, he created some weaknesses in Black's camp @@StartBracket@@d6,d5,a6@@EndBracket@@ and took off the light-squared bishop. What surprises me is the fact that White can still claim an advantage after all this 'jumping around'. }
11... Qxc8
{ Black captures with the queen so he doesn't have to worry about the a6 pawn. Also, the queen is more active on the c-file. }
12. Be2 { We need to finish our development. } 12... b4
{ The text move is premature. } 13. Nd5 Nxe4 14. Bxa6
{ The bishop is untouchable due to the Nc7 fork; this pawn exchange was bad for Black. White has a strong knight on d5, the control over the light squares, and a potentially passed pawn. }
*

