[White "17) 2...Nc6 - Kalashnikov: 7...Be6 and 7...Be7"]
[Black "Kalashnikov 7...Be7 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6
{ The Kalashnikov variation. The younger brother of the more popular Sveshnikov. Black is flexible about the move Nf6 since he doesn't want to get pinned with Bg5 @@StartBracket@@which happens in the Svehnikov@@EndBracket@@. This however has some drawbacks, the obvious one is that it allows the Nd5 jump. }
6. N1c3
{ 6.c4  is another way to deal with Kalashnikov, but  6.N1c3  fits better in our repertoire. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ Here we have another branching point. Black can play  7...b5  to stop  8.Nc4  or he can play some developing move:   a@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  ,   b@@EndBracket@@  7...Be6  and   c@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7  . }
7... Be7
{ Black waits with Nf6 since he doesn't want to allow the pinning Bg5. } 8. Be3
{ An alternative way to fight against the Be7 line. The main move 8.Nc4 is covered in the next chapter. }
8... Nf6 { The critical response. } 9. Nc4 { Going for Nb6 jump. } 9... b5
{ 9...Be6  10.Nb6  Rb8  11.Be2  was covererd in the 7...Be6. } 10. Nb6
{ A forced move. } 10... Rb8 11. Nxc8
{ White spent so many moves with his knight in the opening, 7 out of 11 total! In return, he created some weaknesses in Black's camp @@StartBracket@@d6,d5,a6@@EndBracket@@ and took off the light-squared bishop. What surprises me is the fact that White can still claim an advantage after all this 'jumping around'. }
11... Qxc8
{ Black captures with the queen so he doesn't have to worry about the a6 pawn. Also, the queen is more active on the c-file. }
12. Be2 { We need to finish our development. } 12... O-O 13. a3
{ 13...b4 is a threat and White has to prevent it.   If  13.O-O  b4  14.Nd5  Nxe4  15.Bf3  Nf6  16.Nxe7  Nxe7  17.Qxd6  Nf5  18.Qxe5  Re8=  Black takes the bishop pair and returns the pawn with an equal position. }
13... b4
{ Black plays it anyway. I guess the alternatives aren't satisfactory.   13...Nd8  With the idea to transfer the knight to  e6  .  14.Bg5  Ne6  16.Bxf6  Bxf6  17.Nd5  White obtains a typical advantage with the knight on  d5  . }
14. Nd5
{ New move. Threatening 15. axb4.   14.axb4  Nxb4  15.O-O  was played in one correspondence game, but Black can play  d5  @@StartBracket@@immediately or after  Rd8  @@EndBracket@@ and it seems to me that Black has enough activity to equalize. }
14... bxa3
{ 14...Nxe4??  15.axb4  is terrible for Black. He can't take on  b4  and the a6-pawn is falling with a tempo. }
15. Rxa3
{ Here Black has a choice between two moves and two completely different types of positions. }
15... Nxd5
{ Leads to an inferior opposite-coloured bishops endgame, but with good and patient defense Black should hold it. }
16. exd5 Nd4 17. Bxd4
{ The pawn on c2 was hanging, and White has to take that knight. } 17... exd4
18. b3 { The pawn was hanging. } 18... Qc3+
{ Creating some disbalance in White's camp. } 19. Qd2 Qb2 20. Rxa6
{ Taking the pawn. } 20... Rfc8 21. Rc6
{ Forced, if White wants to achieve something. } 21... Rxc6 22. dxc6 Qa1+ 23.
Bd1 { 23.Qd1  would lead only to a repetition after  23...Qc3+  . } 23... Qa6
{ Stopping 24. O-O and attacking the pawn. } 24. Qd3 Qxc6 25. O-O
{ Black regained the pawn, but he remains with the doubled pawns on d-file. White has a passed b-pawn which gives him better chances, and he is the only one who can enjoy this position. }
