{ 14...Nxe4??  15.axb4  is terrible for Black. He can't take on  b4  and the a6-pawn is falling with a tempo. }
15. Rxa3
{ Here Black has a choice between two moves and two completely different types of positions. }
15... Rxb2 { Taking the offered pawn, but complications are only starting. }
16. Rc3 { Seems like White is winning the material. } 16... Nxd5
{ 16...Bd8  17.Nxf6+  Bxf6  18.O-O!  Black loses either pawn on  d6  or  a6  .  18.Qxd6??  is a terrible mistake since it loses after  Rb1  and  Rd8 }
17. exd5
{ Black is losing a knight, or not?   17.Qxd5  Nb4!  18.Rxc8  Rxc8  19.Qd1  Nxc2+  20.Kf1  Nxe3+  21.fxe3  Rcc2  is another amazing line where Black saves his skin. }
17... Qb8 { This resource keeps Black in the game. } 18. Rxc6 Rb1 19. Bc1 Bg5
{ The trick Black had in mind. } 20. Bxg5 Rxd1+ 21. Kxd1
{ In general two bishops and a rook are much stronger than a queen, but here the clumsy position of the white pieces and a weak king allows Black to generate enough counterplay and collect some pawns. }
21... Qb2 22. f3 Qd4+ 23. Bd2 Qxd5 24. Rc4
{ I believe White's chances to win such a position are high, although computers claim this as equal. }
24... Rb8 { 24...Qb7 is best for Black. } 25. Bd3
{ Allowing the rook's check on b1. } 25... Rb1+ 26. Ke2 Rxh1
{ Black of course cannot take the rook. } 27. Rc8#
{ The classical back-rank mate. } *

