[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) 2...Nc6 - Kalashnikov: 7...Be6 and 7...Be7"]
[Black "Kalashnikov 7...Nf6 8.Nc4  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6
{ The Kalashnikov variation. The younger brother of the more popular Sveshnikov. Black is flexible about the move Nf6 since he doesn't want to get pinned with Bg5 @@StartBracket@@which happens in the Svehnikov@@EndBracket@@. This however has some drawbacks, the obvious one is that it allows the Nd5 jump. }
6. N1c3
{ 6.c4  is another way to deal with Kalashnikov, but  6.N1c3  fits better in our repertoire. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ Here we have another branching point. Black can play  7...b5  to stop  8.Nc4  or he can play some developing move:   a@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  ,   b@@EndBracket@@  7...Be6  and   c@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7  . }
7... Nf6
{ Or  7...Be7  8.Nc4  b5  9.Ne3  Nf6  , which is a more common move order. } 8.
Nc4
{ Playing  8.Bg5  would transpose into the Sveshnikov line which we don't want to play. }
8... b5 { Black has to include this move before playing Be7. } 9. Ne3 Be7
{ Black is developing, he wants to castle and decide later what to do with the light-squared bishop. }
10. Bd3 { Securing the pawn on e4, in order to play Ncd5 at some point. } 10...
O-O 11. O-O Nb4 { Attacking the bishop. } 12. Be2
{ This is a typical reaction, the knight on b4 stops Black from playing b4, and White can always kick it out with a3 also. }
12... Be6 13. a3 { Kicking out the knight. } 13... Nc6 14. Ned5
{ White has prepared everything for the knight jump. } 14... Nd4 15. Bd3
{ We need to keep this bishop. If Black takes on d5, the light-squared bishop will become important. }
15... Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Bg5
{ Black can trade the dark-squared bishops, which is his strategic idea, but this doesn't guarantee equal chances. }
17. c3 Bxc1 18. Rxc1 { Forced because of Nb3. } 18... Nc6 19. Ne3
{ The pawn on d6 is still weak. } *

