[Round "?"]
[White "18) 2...Nc6 - Kalashnikov: 7...b5"]
[Black "Kalashnikov 7...b5 8.Nd5 Be7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6
{ The Kalashnikov variation. Younger brother of the more popular Sveshnikov. Black is flexible about move Nf6 since he doesn't want to get pinned with Bg5 @@StartBracket@@which happens in Svehnikov@@EndBracket@@. This however has some drawbacks, obvious one is that it allows Nd5 jump. }
6. N1c3
{ 6.c4  is another way to deal with Kalashnikov, but  6.N1c3  fits better in our repertoire. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ Here we have another branching point. Black can play  7...b5  to stop  8.Nc4  or he can play some developing move:   a@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  transposes to Sveshnikov,   b@@EndBracket@@  7...Be6  and   c@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7  . }
7... b5 8. Nd5 { This is the starting point of the main line Kalashnikov. }
8... Be7 9. Be3 { With the Bb6 idea. } 9... Rb8 10. c4 b4 11. Nc2 Nf6 12. Bd3
{ 12.Qd3  is an interesting alternative, but the main move seems more natural, developing the bishop. }
12... b3
{ This is the right move when White plays 12. f3, now it doesn't work for Black. }
13. axb3 Rxb3 14. Ncb4 { And White wins the exchange. } *

