[Black "Kalashnikov 7...b5 8.Nd5 Nce7 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6
{ The Kalashnikov variation. Younger brother of the more popular Sveshnikov. Black is flexible about move Nf6 since he doesn't want to get pinned with Bg5 @@StartBracket@@which happens in Svehnikov@@EndBracket@@. This however has some drawbacks, obvious one is that it allows Nd5 jump. }
6. N1c3
{ 6.c4  is another way to deal with Kalashnikov, but  6.N1c3  fits better in our repertoire. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ Here we have another branching point. Black can play  7...b5  to stop  8.Nc4  or he can play some developing move:   a@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  transposes to Sveshnikov,   b@@EndBracket@@  7...Be6  and   c@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7  . }
7... b5 8. Nd5 { This is the starting point of the main line Kalashnikov. }
8... Nce7
{ If @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/5ppp/p1np4/1p1Np3/4P3/N7/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nf6  9.Bg5  transposes to the Sveshnikov. }
9. c4 Nxd5 10. exd5 bxc4 { The only move which doesn't give a pawn. } 11. Nxc4
f5 { Logical move, Black plays on the stronger side. } 12. a4 Nf6 13. a5
{ White got a very nice square @@StartBracket@@b6@@EndBracket@@ for his knight where it not only attacks and restricts Black's pieces, but also defends the d5-pawn. }
13... Be7 14. Nb6 Rb8 15. Qa4+
{ Before developing the bishop, White can first disrupt the black king. } 15...
Kf7 16. Bc4
{ White is clearly dominant on the queenside, eventually he will take the bishop pair, and the pawn on a6 and light squares will be weak. }
*

