{ Here we have another branching point. Black can play  7...b5  to stop  8.Nc4  or he can play some developing move:   a@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  transposes to Sveshnikov,   b@@EndBracket@@  7...Be6  and   c@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7  . }
7... b5 8. Nd5 { This is the starting point of the main line Kalashnikov. }
8... Nge7 9. Bd3
{ A relatively new idea with a small number of games. White doesn't give up the d4 square so easily and develops the bishop instead. The current state of theory suggest that the ball is in Black's court.   9.c4  is the main move where Black has a couple of ways to give up a pawn for quick development. }
9... Nxd5 10. exd5 { Black has to decide where to put his knight. } 10... Ne7
11. c4
{ Only now, when the black knight is on passive square, and far away from d4, White plays c4. Practically speaking, White has tricked Black with the 9. Bd3 move order.   After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/4nppp/p1np4/1p1Np3/4P3/N7/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.c4  Nxd5  10.exd5  no one puts the knight on e7. }
11... g6 12. O-O
{ White can also take on b5 first, but Black can't do anything about it anyways. }
12... Bg7 13. cxb5 O-O 14. Re1
{ Useful move before taking on a6. Here we should follow the example of the 1. b3 expert who sometimes tries the extravagant 1. e4.   14.bxa6  is the simplest move which gives  White advantage, but he can strive for more. }
14... Bb7 { Black doesn't have anything better. } 15. bxa6 Bxd5
{ Leaving the a6 pawn alive is not recommendable. } 16. Bf1 Be6 17. b4 d5 18.
b5 { Was already winning for White in Adhiban - Fawzy, Khanty-Mansiysk 2017. }
