[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6
{ The Kalashnikov variation. Younger brother of the more popular Sveshnikov. Black is flexible about move Nf6 since he doesn't want to get pinned with Bg5 @@StartBracket@@which happens in Svehnikov@@EndBracket@@. This however has some drawbacks, obvious one is that it allows Nd5 jump. }
6. N1c3
{ 6.c4  is another way to deal with Kalashnikov, but  6.N1c3  fits better in our repertoire. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ Here we have another branching point. Black can play  7...b5  to stop  8.Nc4  or he can play some developing move:   a@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  transposes to Sveshnikov,   b@@EndBracket@@  7...Be6  and   c@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7  . }
7... b5 8. Nd5 { This is the starting point of the main line Kalashnikov. }
8... Nge7 9. Bd3
{ A relatively new idea with a small number of games. White doesn't give up the d4 square so easily and develops the bishop instead. The current state of theory suggest that the ball is in Black's court.   9.c4  is the main move where Black has a couple of ways to give up a pawn for quick development. }
9... Nxd5 10. exd5 { Black has to decide where to put his knight. } 10... Nd4
{ An Active move, but runs into c3 tempo. } 11. c3 Nf5
{ It is not clear what is the knight doing on f5 since black's main idea is usually to push the f-pawn. }
12. Nc2
{ I prefer to improve the knight instead of playing  12.c4  which might be also good enough for the advantage. }
12... g6 13. Nb4 Bd7 14. a4
{ Undermining the black queenside pawns. This is very much in the spirit of the 7.Nd5 variation in the Sveshnikov where Black unnecessarily pushed the queenside pawns. }
14... bxa4 15. O-O Bg7 16. Nc6 Qc7 17. Bxf5
{ It might look a bit surprising to give up the bishop pair for no obvious reason. White wants to keep knight on c6 at all costs. }
17... gxf5 18. Rxa4 Bxc6 19. Rc4
{ Is an important resource that gives White a clear edge. } *

