14. Be3 O-O 15. Qd2 Qh4
{ Black activates his queen, attacks pawn on c4 and stops Bh6 ideas. In case of  15...Rc8  White simply plays  16.b3  . }
16. b3 e4 { Black must try something, to open up his bishop from g7. } 17. Bd4
{ Challenging the bishop. } 17... Bh6
{ Black has to avoid the trade of the bishops, especially now when his light-squared bishop is restricted by his own pawns. }
18. Qe1
{ White wants to play f4, and stop any kind of attacking ideas from Black. }
18... Bg5 { Guarding the queen. } 19. Be3 Bf6 20. Rc1
{ Preparing for the knight maneuvre. } 20... Rfe8 21. Ne2 Be5 22. f4 Qxe1 23.
Rfxe1
{ White has better chances in the endgame thanks to the pawn majority on the queenside. Endgame with opposite-coloured bishops can be very unpleasant for Black. }
