[Black "Sveshnikov 8...Ne7  #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ The Sveshnikov variation. Since many new ideas were found in the 70ies and the 80ies, it gained a reputation as one of the best Sicilians for Black.   It was a pet line of many top-class players, including two World champions: Magnus Carlsen and Vladimir Kramnik, who played it quite often before the unfortunate discovery of the Berlin defense. }
6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5
{ This move was never considered critical, but the World Championship match Caruana - Carlsen from 2018 has completely changed the course of the current theory. The main problem for White is that after  7.Bg5  Black was successfully equalizing in most of the lines, so White players were somehow forced to create something new.   The move  7.Nd5  gives up fight for the d5 square, which is a success for Black and leads to the pawn structures that are typical for the Najdorf. The positive side for White with the move Nd5 is that the knight from b5 doesn't have to retreat to the a3 square and quite often goes back to c3 after the pawn goes to c4. Also, Black has to decide where to place his knight. }
7... Nxd5 8. exd5 Ne7
{ The modern way of playing this position. It has brought many victories to the current World Champion. It seems as if Black is on the verge of losing a pawn in this line, but somehow always manages to find some compensation for it. }
9. c4 Ng6 { If Black could castle he would have a great position. } 10. Qa4
{ Creating a deadly threats. } 10... Bd7 { Only move. } 11. Qb4
{ White is annoying Black and constantly attacking some pawns. Here Black has choice between two approximately similar options: Bf5 and Qb8. }
11... Bf5
{ Black would like to place pawn on f5, but he needs to defend the pawn first. }
12. h4 h5 { Black should stop h5. } 13. Bg5 Qb8
{ Practically the only move,  13...Be7  looks quite dubious, after  14.Bxe7  Kxe7  15.c5  Black's king is wide open. }
14. Be2 { White develops. } 14... a6
{ Black must kick out this knight to include his rook and queen in the game. }
15. Nc3 Qc7 16. g3
{ Restricting the black knight, and overprotecting the pawn on h4. } 16... Be7
17. Be3
{ The exchange of the dark-squared bishops suits Black, and White needs this bishop. }
17... Nf8
{ Was played in the game K.Alekseenko - Y. Kuzubov, Konya 2019. White should choose the plan with Na4, O-O and Rc1, and the move order isn't that important. }
18. Na4 Nd7 19. O-O O-O 20. Rac1
{ White has a slight advantage thanks to the spatial advantage on the queenside. Black still has no counterplay. Taking the pawn on h5 allows Bd3 followed by e4 and Ne5 when Black gets enough counterplay on the light squares. }
*

