17. Be3
{ The exchange of the dark-squared bishops suits Black, and White needs this bishop. }
17... e4
{ Following the World Champion. Black is focused on the light squares. } 18.
Qa4+
{ We will see later, why this move is good.   If  18.O-O  then  O-O  19.Bxh5  Ne5  Was the introduction to a  horrible defeat for White in Karjakin - Carlsen, Shamkir 2019. White has to be very careful in the whole system when he grabs the pawn. }
18... Bd7 19. Qb3
{ Black doesn't have anything better than going back to f5 with the bishop.   And  19.Qd1  wins a pawn by force, but it is not the end of the world for Black.  19...O-O  20.Nxe4  Rae8  can become very messy. Black's pieces are nicely coordinated. }
19... Bf5 { So what is the big difference between the queen on b3 or b4? } 20.
O-O O-O
{ 20...Ne5  is too early because of  21.Qc2  when the pawn on e4 drops. } 21.
Bxh5 Ne5 22. Bd4
{ 22...Nd3  doesn't come with a tempo and that is why the queen is on the  b3  square. }
22... Qxc4 { Black regains the pawn. } 23. Qxc4 Nxc4 24. Rfe1
{ Attacking the e4 pawn. } 24... Nxb2 { Black took the pawn first. } 25. Reb1
{ Switching plans, White takes the b7 pawn, while the other on e4, will remain weak. }
25... Nd3 26. Rxb7 Bd8 27. Nd1
{ With Ne3 next, White has the advantage since Black's pawns are weak. } *

