1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ The Sveshnikov variation. Since many new ideas were found in the 70ies and the 80ies, it gained a reputation as one of the best Sicilians for Black.   It was a pet line of many top-class players, including two World champions: Magnus Carlsen and Vladimir Kramnik, who played it quite often before the unfortunate discovery of the Berlin defense. }
6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5
{ This move was never considered critical, but the World Championship match Caruana - Carlsen from 2018 has completely changed the course of the current theory. The main problem for White is that after  7.Bg5  Black was successfully equalizing in most of the lines, so White players were somehow forced to create something new.   The move  7.Nd5  gives up fight for the d5 square, which is a success for Black and leads to the pawn structures that are typical for the Najdorf. The positive side for White with the move Nd5 is that the knight from b5 doesn't have to retreat to the a3 square and quite often goes back to c3 after the pawn goes to c4. Also, Black has to decide where to place his knight. }
7... Nxd5 8. exd5
{ Black here has a choice between Nb8 and Ne7. The first one had a better reputation, but the World Champion revived the whole Ne7 line. }
8... Nb8 9. a4
{ White has two ways to solve the problem of the b5-knight, he can play  9.c4  and return the knight to c3, or play in a modern way  9.a4  and return the knight to a3 where it can reach his ideal square in this pawn structure, the c4 square. }
9... Be7
{ Black develops his kingside first, and is not in a hurry to play a6. } 10.
Be2 { White also develops, before pushing on the queenside with a5. } 10... O-O
11. Bd2
{ The most common move is  11.O-O  but after  11...Nd7  12.Bd2  a6  13.Na3  a5  practice has shown that Black has good chances there. With this move order @@StartBracket@@Bd2 before castling@@EndBracket@@ White fights against the mentioned plan @@StartBracket@@a6 followed by a5@@EndBracket@@ and doesn't spoil his position.   The bishop goes to d2, to guard the pawn on a5, or to attack the black pawn depending on our opponent's reaction. }
11... Nd7 { Black is flexible about pushing f5, instead he develops pieces. }
12. a5 { Time to gain space on the queenside. Also shows the point of Bd2. }
12... a6
{ If Black waited a bit more and played  12...Nf6  instead, White's reaction would be  13.Be3!  and suddenly a6 can't be played because of Bb6. This is possible because the black knight is behind the f-pawn and not in front. }
13. Na3 Nf6
{ Black keeps avoiding playing f5. His plan is to develop the bishop to f5, and quickly connect the rooks. }
14. Bb4
{ We have to defend the d5 pawn. The bishop is doing a nice job on the b4 square. }
14... Bf5 { Developing, quite logical move. } 15. Nc4
{ White must play this move. } 15... Be4 { Double attack. } 16. Ne3
{ Double defense. } 16... b5
{ Black must stop White from pushing the pawns on the queenside, otherwise he might get crushed without any resistance. }
17. c4 bxc4 18. Bxc4
{ White seems slightly better, due to Black's weaknesses on the queenside. } *

