{ Black here has a choice between Nb8 and Ne7. The first one had a better reputation, but the World Champion revived the whole Ne7 line. }
8... Nb8 9. a4
{ White has two ways to solve the problem of the b5-knight, he can play  9.c4  and return the knight to c3, or play in a modern way  9.a4  and return the knight to a3 where it can reach his ideal square in this pawn structure, the c4 square. }
9... Be7
{ Black develops his kingside first, and is not in a hurry to play a6. } 10.
Be2 { White also develops, before pushing on the queenside with a5. } 10... O-O
11. Bd2
{ The most common move is  11.O-O  but after  11...Nd7  12.Bd2  a6  13.Na3  a5  practice has shown that Black has good chances there. With this move order @@StartBracket@@Bd2 before castling@@EndBracket@@ White fights against the mentioned plan @@StartBracket@@a6 followed by a5@@EndBracket@@ and doesn't spoil his position.   The bishop goes to d2, to guard the pawn on a5, or to attack the black pawn depending on our opponent's reaction. }
11... f5
{ Usually, the best plan for Black is to play on the kingside, and postpone playing a6 as long as possible. }
12. a5 { Improving on the queenside and waiting for a reply. } 12... f4
{ I'm not impressed by such moves, especially when White hasn't castled yet. Black does gain some space on the kingside and prevents White from playing f4, but weakens the e4 square and the light squares in general. }
13. c4 { White ignores his opponents ideas, and continues with his plan. }
13... Bf5
{ This is very instructive line showing why the light squares are important. }
14. Bg4
{ Trying to trade light-squared bishops to emphasize the weaknesses in the black position. }
14... Bd3 { Attacking the pawn and preventing White from castling. } 15. Ra3
{ Very strong move, we don't care about one pawn. } 15... Bxc4 16. Be6+
{ Check. } 16... Kh8 17. Rh3
{ Suddenly White threatens mate in 2:  17...--  18.Rxh7  Kxh7  19.Qh5  . }
17... h6
{ The only playable way for Black to stop the mate, playing g6 is worse. } 18.
Na3
{ The knight was hanging, and it is important that White gains a tempo with this move. }
18... Ba6 { Only available square for the bishop. } 19. Qg4
{ The Queen joins the attack. Black will have big troubles defending this position. }
