{ White has two ways to solve the problem of the b5-knight, he can play  9.c4  and return the knight to c3, or play in a modern way  9.a4  and return the knight to a3 where it can reach his ideal square in this pawn structure, the c4 square. }
9... Be7
{ Black develops his kingside first, and is not in a hurry to play a6. } 10.
Be2 { White also develops, before pushing on the queenside with a5. } 10... O-O
11. Bd2
{ The most common move is  11.O-O  but after  11...Nd7  12.Bd2  a6  13.Na3  a5  practice has shown that Black has good chances there. With this move order @@StartBracket@@Bd2 before castling@@EndBracket@@ White fights against the mentioned plan @@StartBracket@@a6 followed by a5@@EndBracket@@ and doesn't spoil his position.   The bishop goes to d2, to guard the pawn on a5, or to attack the black pawn depending on our opponent's reaction. }
11... f5
{ Usually, the best plan for Black is to play on the kingside, and postpone playing a6 as long as possible. }
12. a5 { Improving on the queenside and waiting for reply. } 12... Nd7
{ Black continues with developing. } 13. O-O
{ An easy move for White, finishing the development. } 13... a6
{ If Black plays  13...Nf6  too soon, then  14.c4  is a strong reply, usually followed by Nc3 and pawn expansion on the queenside. }
14. Na3 e4 { Creating square for the knight. } 15. Nc4
{ Of course, the knight is on its ideal square. } 15... Ne5
{ Black challenges it. } 16. Nb6 { It is too early to trade those knights. }
16... Rb8 17. f4
{ White has to open up the position for his pieces on the kingside. } 17...
exf3 18. Bxf3
{ This position was reached via a different move order in the 8th game of the World Championship match Caruana - Carlsen, London 2018. The challenger was arguably having a winning advantage at some point which shows how tricky this position is for the Black side. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Rare 5th moves after 2...d6 / 2...e6 / 2..Nc6"]
[Black "5...Bd7  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bd7
{ Black wants to play some sort of improved Rauzer variation, but keeps the possibility of transposing into the Dragon setups, or Najdorf-like ideas with e5. }
6. f3
{ Might be the simplest way for White to fight for an advantage, since Black's best chance is to transpose into the Najdorf variation with 10...a5.   6.Bg5  e6  7.Qd2  a6  8.O-O-O  h6  is one of the main ideas for Black in this system. If White doesn't want to give up a pawn -because of Nxe4 tactics- he is forced to give up the dark-squared bishop, and Black won't have to spoil his pawn structure  9.Bh4  Nxe4  . }
6... e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3 { Just like in the Najdorf. } 8... O-O 9. Qd2 a5
{ Playing a6-b5 makes little sense with the bishop already being on d7, taking the square away from the knight. The only logical option for Black is to play a7-a5 at once, and develop the b8 knight to b4. }
10. a4 Bc6 11. O-O-O Qd7 12. Bb5
{ Black almost has nothing to attack on the queenside anymore. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Rare 5th moves after 2...d6 / 2...e6 / 2..Nc6"]
[Black "5...Bd7  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bd7
{ Black wants to play some sort of improved Rauzer variation, but keeps the possibility of transposing into the Dragon setups, or Najdorf-like ideas with e5. }
6. f3
{ Might be the simplest way for White to fight for an advantage, since Black's best chance is to transpose into the Najdorf variation with 10...a5.   6.Bg5  e6  7.Qd2  a6  8.O-O-O  h6  is one of the main ideas for Black in this system. If White doesn't want to give up a pawn -because of Nxe4 tactics- he is forced to give up the dark-squared bishop, and Black won't have to spoil his pawn structure  9.Bh4  Nxe4  . }
6... e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3 { Just like in the Najdorf. } 8... O-O 9. Qd2 a5
{ Playing a6-b5 makes little sense with the bishop already being on d7, taking the square away from the knight. The only logical option for Black is to play a7-a5 at once, and develop the b8 knight to b4. }
10. a4 Na6 11. O-O-O Qe8
{ This might be the only independent try for Black.  11...Be6  or  11...Nb4  12.g4  Be6  transposes to the Najdorf. }
12. Bb5 { Of course. } 12... Nc7 13. Bxd7 Qxd7 14. Bb6
{ We don't want to allow Black to play b5. White controls every side of the board, although he has to be careful and stop any attempt of counterplay for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Rare 5th moves after 2...d6 / 2...e6 / 2..Nc6"]
[Black "5...e5  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ Dubious line which gives White too many good options. } 6. Bb5+ Nbd7
{ 6...Bd7  7.Bxd7+  Qxd7  8.Nde2  important move, White just needs to avoid  8.Nf5  Nxe4  and that's it. Now Black has long-term weaknesses: the d5 square and the d6 pawn. }
7. Nf5
{ There is nothing wrong with  7.Nde2  followed by Bg5, but placing the knight on f5 is the most principled move. }
7... a6 { The pawn on d6 is hanging and Black must do something about it. } 8.
Ba4 b5 9. Bb3 Nc5
{ Doesn't seem bad at first sight for Black. Attacking the pawn on e4 and the bishop on b3. However, his light squares are still very weak. }
10. Bg5 { Control of the d5 square is important. } 10... Bxf5
{ Anything else is much worse for Black. } 11. exf5 Be7 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Qf3
{ White controls the light squares, while Black doesn't control anything. }
13... O-O 14. O-O-O
{ With the opposite coloured bishops, it is important to attack for a stronger side. }
14... b4 15. Ne4
{ Trading knights will only demonstrate the strength of the white bishop compared to his counterpart. }
15... Nxe4 16. Qxe4 a5 17. h4
{ Both sides are pushing. h4 is not only an attacking move, but also a positionally important one because it takes away squares from Black's bishop. }
17... a4 18. Bd5 Rb8
{ It looks like Black creates some counterplay against White's king. } 19. Kd2
{ The king goes to safety first. Afterwards, White might push the kingside pawns and/or attack the queenside pawns. }
19... h6 20. Ke2
{ White has a monster on d5, which is enough for a big advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Rare 5th moves after 2...d6 / 2...e6 / 2..Nc6"]
[Black "5...h5  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 h5
{ Black has only one idea with this move. Provoking White to play  6.Nxc6  bxc6  7.e5  Ng4  8.Qe2  Qa5  9.f4  d5  10.exd6  Rh6!  and suddenly White must be very careful. The only move which doesn't lose the game is Qf3, but Black is already doing ok. }
6. h3 { Simple chess, covering the g4 square in some variations. } 6... e5
{ Leads to a bad version of the Sveshnikov.   If  6...g6  7.Be3  White will go for the setup with Qd2 and O-O-O, a very good version of the English attack, since the pawn on h5 will be a target  once Black castles kingside. }
7. Ndb5 d6 8. Nd5
{ We play as if the pawns on h5 and h3 are on their initial squares. } 8...
Nxd5 9. exd5 Ne7
{ Placing the knight on b8 is now much worse than in the 'normal' Sveshnikov. }
10. c4 Nf5
{ The knight on g6 will be vulnerable after Bd3, so Black is kind of forced to play Nf5. }
11. Bd3 g6 12. O-O { Playing simple moves, finishing the development. } 12...
a6 13. Nc3 Bg7 14. a4 { White gains space on the queenside. } 14... O-O 15. a5
{ Black doesn't have enough counterplay on the kingside, while he is considerably worse on the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Rare 5th moves after 2...d6 / 2...e6 / 2..Nc6"]
[Black "5...g6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ An attempt to enter into the Accelerated Dragon without allowing White's Maroczy setup. }
6. Nxc6 bxc6 { This is very dubious. } 7. e5 Ng8 { Sad move for Black. } 8. Bc4
Bg7 9. Qf3 { Attacking the weakness. } 9... e6 10. Bf4
{ White keeps developing, while Black is still doing nothing. } 10... Qc7
{ Attacking the e5 pawn. } 11. O-O-O { Who cares about pawns? } 11... Bxe5 12.
Bxe5 Qxe5 13. Rhe1
{ White has a winning attack. Black has terribly weak dark squares. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Rare 5th moves after 2...d6 / 2...e6 / 2..Nc6"]
[Black "5...g6  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ An attempt to enter into the Accelerated Dragon without allowing White's Maroczy setup. }
6. Nxc6 dxc6 7. Qxd8+
{ One of the rare cases where queens are traded so early, but for a reason. White gets a much better endgame. }
7... Kxd8 8. Bc4
{ Taking the pawn on f7 is not a threat yet, because the bishop might get trapped after e6, but White prepares e4-e5. }
8... Ke8 9. e5 Nd7
{ 9...Ng4  10.f4  h5  11.h3  Nh6  12.Kf2  and White has huge spatial advantage. }
10. e6 { Important move which helps White to gain an advantage. } 10... fxe6
11. Bxe6
{ White has spoiled Black's pawn structure and created a long-term weakness in Black camp. }
11... Bg7 12. Be3 Nf8 13. Bb3 { Not in a hurry to trade bishops. } 13... Be6
14. O-O-O Bxb3 15. axb3
{ White has a very nice edge in this endgame. His pieces are more active, and he has no weaknesses. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) 2...d6 - Dragodorf"]
[Black "Dragodorf  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6
{ Playing a6 is almost never an idea for Black in the Dragon, so this opening looks like some hybrid between the Dragon and the Najdorf, which explains its name.   7...h5  has no independent value,  8.Qd2  will either transpose to h5-Dragon or the usual Dragodorf.  8...Nbd7  9.Be2  a6  10.h3  . }
8. Qd2 { A useful move for White, but also a waiting one. } 8... Nbd7
{ Whenever the knight from b8 lands on d7, White should play g4 if he can. } 9.
g4 { White should play g4 before castling to avoid the h5 response. } 9... b5
10. O-O-O b4 11. Na4 Qa5 { The only way to defend the pawn. } 12. b3 Ne5 13. g5
Nh5 14. a3 { Typical reaction, known from the Najdorf. } 14... Qc7 15. axb4 O-O
16. Be2 { Black doesn't have enough compensation. } *

