[Black "Dragodorf  #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6
{ Playing a6 is almost never an idea for Black in the Dragon, so this opening looks like some hybrid between the Dragon and the Najdorf, which explains its name.   7...h5  has no independent value,  8.Qd2  will either transpose to h5-Dragon or the usual Dragodorf.  8...Nbd7  9.Be2  a6  10.h3  . }
8. Qd2 { A useful move for White, but also a waiting one. } 8... Nbd7
{ Whenever the knight from b8 lands on d7, White should play g4 if he can. } 9.
g4 { White should play g4 before castling to avoid the h5 response. } 9... b5
10. O-O-O Bb7
{ 10...Nb6?  11.Nc6  Qc7  12.Nxe7!  Kxe7  13.e5!  dxe5  14.Nxb5!  axb5  15.Qb4+  Ke6  16.Bxb6  Qxb6  17.Bc4+  . }
11. h4 { Simple and good, the idea is h5 and h6. } 11... h5
{ 11...Ne5  12.h5  Rc8  13.h6  is a disaster for Black. } 12. g5
{ The black knight will have to go back. } 12... Nh7 13. f4
{ Very direct play. White is trying to breakthrough with f5. } 13... Nc5 14. f5
{ White can play the calm Bg2, but 14. f5 is much stronger and direct. } 14...
b4 15. fxg6 { Intermezzo, which opens the black king. } 15... bxc3 16. gxf7+
{ Black's king comes out. } 16... Kxf7 17. Qf2+
{ Not an easy move to spot. White just needs to focus on the black king. }
17... Bf6 { 17...Kg8  18.Bc4+  and no one can parry the bishop. } 18. Bc4+ Ke8
19. gxf6 Nxf6 20. e5 { Powerful play. White is completely winning. } 20...
cxb2+ 21. Kxb2 Bxh1 22. exf6 Be4 23. f7+ Kd7 24. Nb3 Nxb3 25. axb3 Qa5 26. Bc5
Rac8 27. Bxd6 exd6 28. Qf4 Rc6 29. Qxe4 Rxc4 30. Qxc4 Qe5+ 31. Kb1 Rf8 32. Rf1
{ 1-0 Overton - Sutton, ICCF email 2010. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) 2...d6 - Dragodorf"]
[Black "Dragodorf  #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6
{ Playing a6 is almost never an idea for Black in the Dragon, so this opening looks like some hybrid between the Dragon and the Najdorf, which explains its name.   7...h5  has no independent value,  8.Qd2  will either transpose to h5-Dragon or the usual Dragodorf.  8...Nbd7  9.Be2  a6  10.h3  . }
8. Qd2 { A useful move for White, but also a waiting one. } 8... b5
{ Black is not ready to play this. } 9. a4
{ White shifts plans, he will castle kingside, and play on the queenside. Playing a4 is almost always white response to b5 if he hasn't castled yet. }
9... b4 10. Na2 a5
{ Black defends the pawn, but leaves the b5-square chronically weak. } 11. Bb5+
{ Very good square for the bishop. } 11... Nbd7 12. c3
{ Undermining the queenside pawns. } 12... bxc3 13. Nxc3
{ White's pieces work in harmony. } 13... Bb7 14. O-O O-O
{ White here has control, thanks to the outpost on b5. There are many ways to continue, but I like the following move. }
15. Nb3
{ Stopping Nc5, eyeing the pawn on a5 and preparing to activate the rooks. The main problem for Black here is the lack of counterplay. }
*

