[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6
{ Playing a6 is almost never an idea for Black in the Dragon, so this opening looks like some hybrid between the Dragon and the Najdorf, which explains its name.   7...h5  has no independent value,  8.Qd2  will either transpose to h5-Dragon or the usual Dragodorf.  8...Nbd7  9.Be2  a6  10.h3  . }
8. Qd2 { A useful move for White, but also a waiting one. } 8... h5
{ This move is typical for modern chess. Black stops g4, gains some space on the kingside, and waits for white's response. }
9. h3
{ It is possible to start with  9.Be2  and after  9...Nbd7  play  10.h3  . }
9... Nbd7
{ If  9...Nc6  10.O-O-O  the knight on c6 and the pawn on a6 aren't compatible. }
10. Be2
{ White is playing semi-waiting moves. He keeps both castling options available and prepares for g2-g4 or f3-f4. }
10... b5 11. a4
{ Whenever Black plays b5 with White's king on e1, we should play a4. } 11...
b4 12. Na2 a5 13. c3 { The usual reaction. } 13... bxc3 14. Nxc3 Bb7 15. O-O
{ and similar tothe 8...b5 notes White has a nice advantage. Pawns on h5 and h3 don't change much. }
*

