[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6
{ Playing a6 is almost never an idea for Black in the Dragon, so this opening looks like some hybrid between the Dragon and the Najdorf, which explains its name.   7...h5  has no independent value,  8.Qd2  will either transpose to h5-Dragon or the usual Dragodorf.  8...Nbd7  9.Be2  a6  10.h3  . }
8. Qd2 { A useful move for White, but also a waiting one. } 8... h5
{ This move is typical for modern chess. Black stops g4, gains some space on the kingside, and waits for white's response. }
9. h3
{ It is possible to start with  9.Be2  and after  9...Nbd7  play  10.h3  . }
9... Nbd7
{ If  9...Nc6  10.O-O-O  and the knight on c6 and pawn on a6 aren't compatible. }
10. Be2
{ White is playing semi-waiting moves. He keeps both castling options available and prepares for g2-g4 or f3-f4. }
10... Qc7
{ Black can't castle kingside due to g4, so he must try some useful move instead. }
11. a4
{ Stopping b5.   11.O-O-O  b5  12.g4  Nb6  Is not that clear. The black knights might jump around. }
11... b6 12. Nd5
{ The only chance to play Nd5 is before Black plays Bb7. White has the positional idea of playing c4 and having a spatial advantage. }
12... Nxd5 13. exd5 Nf6 14. c4 { Guarding the pawn and gaining space. } 14...
O-O 15. O-O { Black has a hole on c6, so he needs to hit the d5-pawn. } 15...
Re8 16. Rfd1 { Preparing for the opening of the d-file. } 16... e6 17. dxe6
Bxe6 18. Bf2
{ Securing the bishop and avoiding possible tactical motifs on the e-file. White has a better structure and no pawn weaknesses. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) 2...d6 - Dragodorf"]
[Black "Dragodorf  #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 a6
{ Sooner or later Black will have to play Bg7, and I don't see much sense if Black avoids it.   7...Nbd7  is always responded with  8.g4!  b5  9.Qd2  Bb7  10.O-O-O  and we are back in the main line. }
7. f3 b5 8. Qd2 { Preparing to castle. } 8... Bb7 9. a4
{ White's pieces are not only prepared for queenside castling, but also for kingside castling. White changes the usual plan and decides to play more positionally since Black will have weaknesses on the queenside. }
9... e5
{ 9...bxa4  10.Nxa4  certainly favours White, he will continue Be2 and O-O, with an advantage on the queenside.   9...b4  10.Na2  e5  11.Nb3  is a transposition. }
10. Nb3 b4
{ Black is avoiding  10...bxa4  and trying to strike in the centre. } 11. Na2
d5 { 11...a5  12.c3  and Black can't really afford to give up the b5-square. }
12. Bg5 { Stops dxe4 and creates pressure on the d5-pawn. } 12... d4 13. Nxd4
{ Mini tactics help White to achieve his goal. } 13... exd4 14. e5
{ White will have an extra pawn. } *

