1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 a6
{ Sooner or later Black will have to play Bg7, and I don't see much sense if Black avoids it.   7...Nbd7  is always responded with  8.g4!  b5  9.Qd2  Bb7  10.O-O-O  and we are back in the main line. }
7. f3 b5 8. Qd2 { Preparing to castle. } 8... Bb7 9. a4
{ White's pieces are not only prepared for queenside castling, but also for kingside castling. White changes the usual plan and decides to play more positionally since Black will have weaknesses on the queenside. }
9... e5
{ 9...bxa4  10.Nxa4  certainly favours White, he will continue Be2 and O-O, with an advantage on the queenside.   9...b4  10.Na2  e5  11.Nb3  is a transposition. }
10. Nb3 b4
{ Black is avoiding  10...bxa4  and trying to strike in the centre. } 11. Na2
d5 { 11...a5  12.c3  and Black can't really afford to give up b5-square. } 12.
Bg5 { Stops dxe4 and creates pressure on the d5-pawn. } 12... Nbd7 13. exd5
{ Simply taking the pawn. } 13... Bxd5 14. Qxd5
{ 14.O-O-O  also looks promising, but this is the simplest. } 14... Nxd5 15.
Bxd8 Kxd8 { Forced recapture, since the pawn on a6 is hanging. } 16. O-O-O
{ Finishing development with tempo. The rook is perfect on the d-file. } 16...
Ne3 17. Rd3 Bh6 18. Kb1
{ The king is safe, and the pawn on b4 is under attack. } 18... a5 19. c3
{ White will win a pawn at least. The knight from a2 will be returned into the action and Black will have to give up some material. }
