[Black "Dragon 9.O-O-O Bd7  #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon variation. One of the most aggressive Sicilians, which was used by many great players in history including two of the greatest ones: Garry Kasparov and Magnus Carlsen.   Nowadays, it is not as popular as it used to be at the top level since White founds ways to soothe the Dragon. }
6. Be3
{ Going for the typical English attack setup, in this case known as the Yugoslav attack. }
6... Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O
{ The main move and the best one. Alternatives are not very promising. } 9.
O-O-O
{ Through the history there was a long debate whether White should play  9.Bc4  or  9.O-O-O  . In the early ages of the Dragon  9.Bc4  has always been considered as the critical move, since castling gave Black the opportunity to strike with  9...d5  .   However, the main difference between 9. Bc4 and 9. O-O-O is that if Black wants to create some counter chances he will have to comply with an inferior position in the 9. O-O-O line. }
9... Bd7
{ Before analyzing the main and the strongest move  9...d5  we will cover some other options for Black. }
10. g4 Rc8 { Here White has a pleasant choice between  11.h4  and  11.Kb1  . }
11. Kb1 { Typical useful move for White. } 11... Ne5
{ If  11...h5  12.h3  is strong, keeping both g5 and gxh5 as an option. It shows why Kb1 was a strong semi-waiting move. }
12. Be2 { Prevents some desperate sacrifices on f3 and c3 followed by Nxe4. }
12... Qc7 13. h4 { White has prepared everything for pushing pawns. } 13... b5
14. h5
{ We don't care about the pawns on the queenside, checkmating is more important. }
14... b4 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. exd5
{ The knight on d4 is a powerful defender, and White has free hands on the kingside. }
