1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. O-O-O d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4 Nxc3
{ Old line, connected with pawn sacrifice idea. } 13. Qxc3 Bh6+ 14. Be3 Bxe3+
15. Qxe3
{ Lot of light pieces have been exchanged. However, White controls the d-file, and Black pawns are weak. }
15... Qb6 16. Re1
{ Rejecting the pawn sacrifice gives White an easier task.   16.Qxe7  is played more often  16...Be6  17.Qa3  Rad8  18.Bd3  Rd5  and White can torture Black here also, but I'm afraid that the position will simplify too much. }
16... Qxe3+ { Black shouldn't trade queens yet. } 17. Rxe3 Be6 18. Ba6 Rad8 19.
Ra3 Rd6 20. Be2 Ra8 21. Rd1
{ White has clearly better endgame thanks to the more active rook, and compact pawn structure. }
