[White "23) 2...d6 - Dragon with 9.O-O-O d5"]
[Black "Dragon 9.O-O-O ... 12...Bxd4  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. O-O-O d5 { Literally, the only move. } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12.
Bd4
{ White shows his real intentions with this move. He wants to kill any counterplay Black has in this position, trade the dark-squared bishops, and play for the better endgame. }
12... Bxd4
{ This move was recommended by Gawain Jones in his books about the Dragon. Until recently @@StartBracket@@read Anish Giri's Dragon course@@EndBracket@@, the whole line has been considered as the best option for Black. }
13. Qxd4 Qc7 14. h4
{ White rarely takes pawn@@StartBracket@@s@@EndBracket@@ in this line, it is better for him to continue with the attack. }
14... e5 15. Qc5 Qb6 16. Na4 Qxc5 17. Nxc5 Rb8 18. a3
{ This is exact type of the position which Black should avoid. White has better pawn structure and controls every side of the board. }
*

