[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. O-O-O d5 { Literally, the only move. } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12.
Bd4
{ White shows his real intentions with this move. He wants to kill any counterplay Black has in this position, trade the dark-squared bishops, and play for the better endgame. }
12... Bxd4
{ This move was recommended by Gawain Jones in his books about the Dragon. Until recently @@StartBracket@@read Anish Giri's Dragon course@@EndBracket@@, the whole line has been considered as the best option for Black. }
13. Qxd4 Qc7 14. h4
{ White rarely takes pawn@@StartBracket@@s@@EndBracket@@ in this line, it is better for him to continue with the attack. }
14... Rd8 15. Bc4
{ 15.h5  Bf5!  16.hxg6  Bxg6  shows typical defensive resource for Black in Dragon. Bishop on g6 is a great defender and attacker too. }
15... Be6 16. Bxd5
{ White destroys the strong centralized knight. Black doesn't have a good way to recapture. }
16... cxd5
{ 16...Bxd5  17.Qc5  White dominates since his knight is stronger than bishop, his queen is more active, he has better pawn structure and safer king. }
17. h5 g5 { Otherwise, Black is in big trouble. } 18. Qe3 h6 19. Nb5
{ Improving the knight. } 19... Qc4 20. Nd4
{ Black doesn't have time to capture on a2. } 20... Rd6 21. Kb1
{ Looks positionally winning for White. His king is much safer. } *

