[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) 2...d6 - Dragon with 9.O-O-O d5"]
[Black "Dragon 9.O-O-O ... 12...Bxd4  #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. O-O-O d5 { Literally, the only move. } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12.
Bd4
{ White shows his real intentions with this move. He wants to kill any counterplay Black has in this position, trade the dark-squared bishops, and play for the better endgame. }
12... Bxd4
{ This move was recommended by Gawain Jones in his books about the Dragon. Until recently @@StartBracket@@read Anish Giri's Dragon course@@EndBracket@@, the whole line has been considered as the best option for Black. }
13. Qxd4 Qb6
{ Black generally doesn't want to trade queen unless it improves his pawn structure and opens the a-file. }
14. Na4 { Black wanted to take on d4 and c3, thus White has to react. } 14...
Qa5 15. b3 { Securing the knight and defending against threats on the b-file. }
15... Qc7
{ This can be a bit confusing since Black can place his queen on c7 on move 13th, 14th and 15th. Every time our reaction is different. }
16. c4 { I'd like to force matters. } 16... Nf4 17. g3 Ne6 18. Qe3 c5
{ 18...Ng7  19.g4  restricts black pieces. } 19. Bh3 { Connecting rooks. }
19... Nd4 20. Bxc8 Raxc8 21. Rhe1 { All White pieces are ideally placed. }
21... e6 22. f4
{ Knight on a4 may seem strange on the edge of the board, but it is actually stopping Black from developing any kind of the attack on the queenside. }
22... Rfd8 23. Rd2
{ We were following 3 corr. games which were all won by White. The plan is to slowly push pawns on the kingside to gain space and then use some tactics. }
23... Rd7 24. Red1 Rcd8 25. g4 Qc6 26. Nc3 Kf8 27. g5 Qc7 28. Kb2 a5 29. h4 Ke7
30. Na4 Ke8 31. Rd3 Ke7 32. a3 Qd6 33. Qe5 Qxe5 34. fxe5 Nf3 35. Rxd7+ Rxd7 36.
Rxd7+ Kxd7 37. Nxc5+ Ke7 38. Kc3 Nxe5 39. b4 axb4+ 40. axb4 Kd6 41. Nd3
{ 1-0 Klimakovs - Nemec, LSS email 2012. } *

