17. Bb3 { Defending c2. } 17... Nb6 18. Qe3 Nd5 19. Qg5 a5
{ Black must create some counterplay. } 20. g4
{ In a couple of correspondence games  20.h4  was played, but  20.g4  is more direct. Simply attacking the bishop. }
20... Qa7 21. Na4 Be6 22. h4 { White continues with his attack. } 22... Qf2
{ Seeking counterplay. } 23. h5 Ne3 24. Rxd8+ Rxd8 25. Qxa5
{ White picks up a pawn, and defends his king with tempo. } 25... Rf8 26. Qe1
Qxf3 27. hxg6 { Another reason behind Qe1. Black can't recapture on g6. } 27...
Rd8 { An intermediate move threatening Rd1+. } 28. Nc3 Bxb3 29. Qh4
{ Now White has the strong 'zwischenzug'. } 29... fxg6 30. Qxh7+ Kf8 31. cxb3
{ We want to have a passed pawn. } 31... Qg2 { Black threatens mate in 1. } 32.
Qh2 Qxh2 33. Rxh2
{ The smoke has cleared and White has an extra passed pawn in the endgame. } *

