Nc6 9. O-O-O d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4 e5 13. Bc5 Be6
{ The main move. Black develops the bishop and offers the exchange. } 14. Ne4
{ Improving the knight and preparing to play c4 at the right moment. White should definitely avoid  14.Bxf8?  which gives Black tremendous attacking possibilities after  14...Qxf8  , followed by Rb8, e4 or Bh6, etc. }
14... Rb8 15. Bc4
{ Useful attacking and defensive move. We should ignore rook on f8. } 15... Re8
{ Black doesn't have anything better than improving his rook. } 16. g4 a5 17.
h4 { Finally, we are pushing pawns. } 17... Nf4 18. Qc3
{ It is hard to say what does Black wants. The biggest problem for him in this line is that his dark-squared bishop is passive while white dark-squared bishop is doing excellent job. }
