{ Before, everyone was playing  13...Be6  inviting White to  14.Bxf8  . The problem with  13...Be6  is that if White doesn't accept the sacrifice he has an easy play.   Currently this move is gaining population and it will probably surpass 13...Be6 in the future. It is also the recommendation of Anish Giri in his excellent Dragon course. }
14. Ne4 Qc7 15. h4 { White needs to push the h-pawn. } 15... f5
{ Black must create counterplay fast.   15...h6  16.h5  g5  17.Bd6  Qb6  18.Bc4  Be6  19.Bc5  Qc7  20.g4  transposes  to the13...Be6 line. }
16. Nd6 Rd8 17. Nxc8 Raxc8
{ White took the bishop pair advantage, but lost a couple of tempi for it. Also, Black got rid of the bishop, which wasn't participating in the action anyway.   At first glance it may seem that Black will have troubles on the a2-g8 diagonal, but he has some hidden resources. }
18. h5 Nb6 19. Bxb6
{ The most forcing move, going for a slightly better endgame with bishops of opposite colour. }
19... axb6
{ This looks dangerous for Black. Keeping the queens on the board in a position with opposite-coloured bishops, only helps the stronger  @@StartBracket@@attacking@@EndBracket@@ side. }
20. Bc4+ Kf8 21. Qb4+ { White keeps checking. } 21... c5 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Qb3
{ Black has weak light squares. } 23... e4 24. Kb1 Qe5 25. c3
{ White has dangerous attacking ideas. The only question is, can Black save such position? }
*

