[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24) 2...d6 - Rauzer: Rare 6th moves"]
[Black "Rauzer 6...g6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Rauzer variation, known also as the Classical Sicilian. Black develops knights to the most natural squares, f6 and c6.   He will follow it up with e6, Be7, a6, Bd7 which seems as beginners way to play chess. However, this keeps flexibility and often Black castles queenside, or keeps king in the centre which makes typical English attack less effective.   Also,  6.Be3  is responded by Ng4, while  6.f3  e5  gives Black a more favourable position than in Najdorf. Unlike some other Sicilians, if White wants to achieve anything from the opening he must castle kingside. }
6. Bg5
{ Without any doubt, the most critical reply to the Classical variation. } 6...
g6
{ Few decades ago no one would consider this variation. Black's main idea is to force Bxf6 which White has to play if he wants to achieve anything.   Black gains the bishop pair advantage but compromises his pawn structure. Nevertheless, he is ready to sacrifice the pawn @@StartBracket@@on d6@@EndBracket@@ to obtain counterplay with the two bishops. }
7. Bb5 { Before taking on c6 White develops the  other bishop. } 7... Bd7
{ The only move. } 8. Bxf6
{ Practically forced, if Black plays Bg7 on the next move, White has nothing. }
8... exf6
{ Black obtained the bishop pair, but his pawn structure is far from perfect. In the whole Rauzer variation this is the only case when Black recaptures with the e-pawn. }
9. Qd2 { Developing and preparing for the queenside castling. } 9... a6
{ This move only helps White to improve his pieces. } 10. Bc4 Bg7 11. Nxc6
{ White wants to create pressure on the d6-pawn. } 11... Bxc6 12. O-O-O O-O 13.
Kb1
{ The pawn on d6 won't go anywhere. White first needs to improve his pieces. Taking on d6 allows Black to activate his bishops with f5 and obtain decent compensation. }
13... Rc8 14. Bb3
{ White has played all the preparatory moves, and is now ready to take some material. For example, playing f3 could be very useful since it restricts the black light-squared bishop and defends the e4-pawn. }
