[Black "Rauzer 6...Qa5  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Rauzer variation, known also as the Classical Sicilian. Black develops knights to the most natural squares, f6 and c6.   He will follow it up with e6, Be7, a6, Bd7 which seems as beginners way to play chess. However, this keeps flexibility and often Black castles queenside, or keeps king in the centre which makes typical English attack less effective.   Also,  6.Be3  is responded by Ng4, while  6.f3  e5  gives Black a more favourable position than in Najdorf. Unlike some other Sicilians, if White wants to achieve anything from the opening he must castle kingside. }
6. Bg5 Qa5
{ Playing for a trick,  7.Qd2  runs into  7...Nxe4!  and Black takes a pawn. }
7. Bb5
{ The bishop from f1 usually stays on the initial square, here White has concrete things in mind. }
7... Bd7 { Forced reply, everything else loses. } 8. Nb3 Qc7 9. Bxf6
{ White can now take on f6, because the queen on c7 will be attacked with gain of time. }
9... gxf6 10. Nd5 Qd8
{ Black has played too many moves with the queen which can't pass unpunished. }
11. Qf3 { Stopping e6. } 11... a6 12. Bxc6
{ Not allowing knight to jump on e5. } 12... bxc6 13. Ne3
{ White will castle kingside while Black king will stay in the centre. } 13...
Rb8 14. O-O Rg8 15. Rab1
{ The knight from b3 can now go to a better square. Black has a solid centre but his king remains in the middle of the board. His bishops are far away from their full potential, while the white knights can jump around and attack the black pawns. }
