1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Rauzer variation, known also as the Classical Sicilian. Black develops knights to the most natural squares, f6 and c6.   He will follow it up with e6, Be7, a6, Bd7 which seems as beginners way to play chess. However, this keeps flexibility and often Black castles queenside, or keeps king in the centre which makes typical English attack less effective.   Also,  6.Be3  is responded by Ng4, while  6.f3  e5  gives Black a more favourable position than in Najdorf. Unlike some other Sicilians, if White wants to achieve anything from the opening he must castle kingside. }
6. Bg5 Qb6
{ Double attack, the reply is obvious. On the other note, if Black wants to play Qb6 line it is smarter for him to include  6...e6  7.Qd2  , and only then to play  7...Qb6  . Later inthis variation we will see why. }
7. Nb3 e6
{ Black needs to cover d5 square.   If  7...a6  then  8.Bxf6  gxf6  9.Nd5  is the reason why. }
8. Bf4
{ 8.Qd2  Be7  would transpose to the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.Qd2  Qb6  8.Nb3  , but the text move is stronger and punishes Black for his move order. Before playing Be3, White is provoking Ne5 so he can play f2-f4 with a tempo. }
8... Qd8 { Too passive. } 9. Qd2 Be7 10. O-O-O { Pawn remains weak on d6. } *

