[Round "?"]
[White "24) 2...d6 - Rauzer: Rare 6th moves"]
[Black "Rauzer 6...h6  #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Rauzer variation, known also as the Classical Sicilian. Black develops knights to the most natural squares, f6 and c6.   He will follow it up with e6, Be7, a6, Bd7 which seems as beginners way to play chess. However, this keeps flexibility and often Black castles queenside, or keeps king in the centre which makes typical English attack less effective.   Also,  6.Be3  is responded by Ng4, while  6.f3  e5  gives Black a more favourable position than in Najdorf. Unlike some other Sicilians, if White wants to achieve anything from the opening he must castle kingside. }
6. Bg5 h6
{ I have never been fan of this move for Black, since White wants to take on f6 anyway.   6...Bd7  7.Qd2  h6  8.Bxf6  gxf6  is a different move order. }
7. Bxf6 gxf6 8. Qd2 { Getting ready for the long castle. } 8... Bd7
{ Black has to develop the queenside first. } 9. O-O-O Nxd4
{ White already can play Nf5 on the next move, so Black destroys the knight. }
10. Qxd4 Qa5 11. f4 { Must move for White in the Richter-Rauzer attack. } 11...
Rc8 12. Kb1
{ This calm move is always useful in Sicilians. Here it prevents exchange sacrifice ideas for Black @@StartBracket@@Rxc3@@EndBracket@@ . }
12... Qc5
{ With the bishop pair advantage and weak king Black would definitely love to trade queens. Actually this is one of the reasons why Classical Sicilian or Rauzer doesn't lose its popularity.   Black often has a very favourable endgame, and in the 90% of the cases when Black has bishop pair, White should avoid trade of the queens }
13. Qd3
{ White won't trade queens, and the only question is where does the queen go, d3 or d2? I prefer it on d3 since it is more useful on the third rank and more importantly, it doesn't stand on the c1-h6 diagonal which will be occupied by black bishop. }
13... Bg7 14. f5
{ Black wanted to play f5. This gives up the e5-square, but Black can hardly make good use of it. }
14... Qe5 { The queen looks nice on e5 indeed. } 15. Be2
{ Simply developing and connecting rooks. } 15... O-O 16. Qd4
{ One of those rare cases when White trades queens. Black has horrible bishop on g7 and White goes for a dominant endgame. }
16... Qxd4 17. Rxd4 Rc5 18. Nd5 Re8 19. Rf1
{ Stops e6. Black bishop on g7 is in the box. White will expand on the queenside with c3, b4 etc. }
