{ With the bishop pair advantage and weak king Black would definitely love to trade queens. Actually this is one of the reasons why Classical Sicilian or Rauzer doesn't lose its popularity.   Black often has a very favourable endgame, and in the 90% of the cases when Black has bishop pair, White should avoid trade of the queens }
13. Qd3
{ White won't trade queens, and the only question is where does the queen go, d3 or d2? I prefer it on d3 since it is more useful on the third rank and more importantly, it doesn't stand on the c1-h6 diagonal which will be occupied by black bishop. }
13... Bg7 14. f5
{ Black wanted to play f5. This gives up the e5-square, but Black can hardly make good use of it. }
14... h5 15. Qf3 { Targets h5 and opens rook and bishop. } 15... a6
{ Black must prevent Bb5. } 16. Bd3
{ Developing and covering white weakness, pawn on c2. Playing 16. h4 to fix pawn on h5 is also interesting. }
16... Bc6 17. Rhe1 { White brings last pieces into the action. } 17... h4 18.
Nd5
{ Opposite coloured bishops are clearly favoring White, because White king is safer and Black has more weaknesses @@StartBracket@@e7, h4, f7@@EndBracket@@. }
18... b5 19. Qg4 Kf8 20. c3
{ White is clearly better. I don't see any meaningful plan for Black besides waiting. On the other hand White can put his bishop to b3, or try to capture the h4-pawn. }
