1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Rauzer variation, known also as the Classical Sicilian. Black develops knights to the most natural squares, f6 and c6.   He will follow it up with e6, Be7, a6, Bd7 which seems as beginners way to play chess. However, this keeps flexibility and often Black castles queenside, or keeps king in the centre which makes typical English attack less effective.   Also,  6.Be3  is responded by Ng4, while  6.f3  e5  gives Black a more favourable position than in Najdorf. Unlike some other Sicilians, if White wants to achieve anything from the opening he must castle kingside. }
6. Bg5 Bd7 7. Qd2 Rc8
{ Old line which was the pet line of GM Alexey Dreev. To understand why Black is delaying e7-e6 we must see what happens if White plays the usual  8.O-O-O  . This is responded by  8...Nxd4  9.Qxd4  Qa5  10.f4  Rxc3!  typical exchange sacrifice in the Sicilian. After  11.bxc3  e5  12.Qb4  Qxb4  13.cxb4  Nxe4  Black got some typical compensation for the exchange.   However, each time computers gain strength this line becomes less and less playable. Currently, the main line   @@StartBracket@@or what it used to be@@EndBracket@@ leads Black to desperate position. White just has to study lines carefully. }
8. f4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Qa5 10. e5
{ That's the idea behind playing 8. f4 early. Not only White stops exchange sacrifice on c3 but he also plays e5 first and stops Black from doing the same. }
10... dxe5 { Only move, alternatives are clearly worse. } 11. fxe5 e6
{ Again, the only move for Black.   11...Bc6?  12.b4  and the queen must leave fifth rank.   11...Ng4?  12.O-O-O  Nxe5  13.Bf4  and Black loses the knight at least. }
12. O-O-O { Finishing development, and threatening to take the piece. } 12...
Bc6 13. Nb5
{ Another powerful move, which proved to be the best one. Idea is to prepare exf6 without losing bishop on g5. }
13... Bxb5
{ Only move.   13...Nd5  14.Qxa7  and White wins a pawn and a bishop pair.   13...Ne4?  14.Nxa7  Bc5  15.Nxc6  wins a piece. }
14. exf6 Ba4
{ Double attack doesn't seem that bad, but...   If  14...g6?  15.Qe5!  . } 15.
h4 { Pawn on c2 is meaningless. } 15... g6 16. Bd2
{ Black queen can't guard the bishop. } 16... Rxc2+ 17. Kb1 Rxd2 18. Qxd2
{ The simplest. } 18... Qxd2 19. Rxd2
{ White won an exchange and should win the game thanks to the control of the open files. }
*

