{ That's the idea behind playing 8. f4 early. Not only White stops exchange sacrifice on c3 but he also plays e5 first and stops Black from doing the same. }
10... dxe5 { Only move, alternatives are clearly worse. } 11. fxe5 e6
{ Again, the only move for Black.   11...Bc6?  12.b4  and the queen must leave fifth rank.   11...Ng4?  12.O-O-O  Nxe5  13.Bf4  and Black loses the knight at least. }
12. O-O-O { Finishing development, and threatening to take the piece. } 12...
Bc6 13. Nb5
{ Another powerful move, which proved to be the best one. Idea is to prepare exf6 without losing bishop on g5. }
13... Bxb5
{ Only move.   13...Nd5  14.Qxa7  and White wins a pawn and a bishop pair.   13...Ne4?  14.Nxa7  Bc5  15.Nxc6  wins a piece. }
14. exf6 Bc6 { Everything else loses quickly. } 15. h4 { Bishop was hanging. }
15... g6 { 15...Bc5  16.Qe5  g6  17.Bc4  transposes. } 16. Bc4
{ Bishop here is very good. Attacks e6, defends a2, and closes c-file. } 16...
Bc5
{ Only move again.   16...Qc5?  17.Qd3  and Black can't develop the kingside. }
17. Qe5 { Centralization. } 17... Bb6 { 17...O-O  18.h5  is crushing. } 18. Qd6
{ Forcing bishop back to c5 which keeps the c-file closed and queen cut off from the fifth rank. }
18... Bc5 19. Qg3 { The queen is well placed on g3. } 19... O-O 20. Bd2
{ Gaining tempo again. } 20... Qb6 21. h5 Bd4 { Double attack. } 22. Bc3
{ Defending vital pawns. } 22... Bf2 23. Qg4 Qe3+ 24. Kb1 Qe4
{ Black manages to force a queen trade, but it is too late. } 25. Qxe4 Bxe4 26.
Bd3
{ Pawn on g2 can't be taken because Black will lose two bishops for the rook. In other cases White can take on g6 and double the rooks on the h-file.   He has winning advantage thanks to the strong pawn on f6 and attack on the h-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25) 2...d6 - Rauzer with 6...e6 and 7...Qb6"]
[Black "Rauzer 7...Qb6 8.Nb3  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6
{ After observing sidelines @@StartBracket@@6...g6, 6...h6, 6...Bd7, etc.@@EndBracket@@ we have reached the best move for Black: 6...e6. It is the most natural and logical move in the position. Black doesn't want to spoil his pawn structure so early in the game and keeps flexibility with his bishops. }
7. Qd2
{ The most popular move in the position. Alternative  7.Qd3  became quite fashionable in the last couple of years, connected with Nxc6 and the queen transfer to g3, and idea which is often seen in Taimanov.   However, after  7...Bd7  it is not that clear to me how can White get the advantage. Therefore I'm recommending the old classical response 7. Qd2. }
7... Qb6 8. Nb3
{ The same reaction as it is in case of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qb6  . You can also checkthe line . The knight is not that bad on b3. Later we will see that Black will have difficulties with the pawn on d6. }
8... a6
{ Black covers the b5 square. You can hardly play the Sicilian without this move. }
9. O-O-O
{ The main thing you should know about Qb6 lines in general is: Don't hurry with Bxf6. It won't go away. Often it is preferable for White to leave this bishop alive and launch a kingside attack instead with f3-g4-h4 etc.  We are also waiting to see where Black wants to castle. A bishop on e7 usually means kingside castling, while a  bishop on d7 means queenside castling. }
9... Be7 10. Kb1
{ Another useful move before deciding where to push the f-pawn. } 10... h6
{ Loses a pawn or leaves Black with a bad structure. } 11. Na4 Qc7 12. Bxf6
gxf6 13. Qe3 { And Nb6 is the idea, which forces Black reply. } 13... Bd8 14.
Qg3 { White will win material. } *

