8... a6
{ Black covers the b5 square. You can hardly play the Sicilian without this move. }
9. O-O-O
{ The main thing you should know about Qb6 lines in general is: Don't hurry with Bxf6. It won't go away. Often it is preferable for White to leave this bishop alive and launch a kingside attack instead with f3-g4-h4 etc.  We are also waiting to see where Black wants to castle. A bishop on e7 usually means kingside castling, while a  bishop on d7 means queenside castling. }
9... Be7 10. Kb1
{ Another useful move before deciding where to push the f-pawn. } 10... Qc7
{ Sooner or later Black will have to put his queen on c7.   10...O-O  11.h4  Rd8  transposes to themain line which is often reached via @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp3ppp/1qnppn2/6B1/4P3/1NN5/PPPQ1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be7  9.O-O-O  O-O  10.h4  Rd8  11.Kb1  a6  . }
11. f4
{ If you like pawn grabbing you can take on f6 instead, but Black has some small compensation there. }
11... b5 12. Bxf6 gxf6
{ In Rauzer in most of the cases when Black takes gxf6 it is better for him to have the bishop on f8 which can later join the game via g7 or h6. On e7 this bishop defends pawns, but does nothing actively. White has many promising ways to proceed, but I like f5. }
13. f5 b4 14. Ne2 e5
{ Black should close the position, his is not ready for the opening yet. } 15.
c3 { If White's knight reaches the d5 square the game is over. } 15... a5 16.
cxb4 axb4 17. Nec1
{ The knight does an excellent defensive job here, and White has free hands on the kingside as well in the center. }
