{ This position can be also reached via the move order @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2nppn2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7  8.O-O-O  O-O  9.Nb3  Qb6  . }
10. h4
{ Securing the bishop. We will see this move quite often this move when Black castles kingside. }
10... Rd8
{ Black has to defend this pawn at some point. Also he might play d5 at the right moment. }
11. Kb1 { Semi-waiting move, but always useful. } 11... a6 12. g4
{ We don't even have to prepare g4. The pawn is untouchable, because Black will lose the piece on the g-file. }
12... Qc7
{ Trying to create counterplay with b5-b4 but it is clear that White is faster. }
13. Bxf6
{ White's pawns are so advanced that he doesn't care about the bishop pair. }
13... Bxf6 14. g5 Bxc3 15. Qxc3 e5 16. h5 { Looks even worse for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25) 2...d6 - Rauzer with 6...e6 and 7...Qb6"]
[Black "Rauzer 7...Qb6 8.Nb3  #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6
{ After observing sidelines @@StartBracket@@6...g6, 6...h6, 6...Bd7, etc.@@EndBracket@@ we have reached the best move for Black: 6...e6. It is the most natural and logical move in the position. Black doesn't want to spoil his pawn structure so early in the game and keeps flexibility with his bishops. }
7. Qd2
{ The most popular move in the position. Alternative  7.Qd3  became quite fashionable in the last couple of years, connected with Nxc6 and the queen transfer to g3, and idea which is often seen in Taimanov.   However, after  7...Bd7  it is not that clear to me how can White get the advantage. Therefore I'm recommending the old classical response 7. Qd2. }
7... Qb6 8. Nb3
{ The same reaction as it is in case of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qb6  . You can also checkthe line . The knight is not that bad on b3. Later we will see that Black will have difficulties with the pawn on d6. }
8... Be7 9. O-O-O { After almost every move White castles queenside. } 9... O-O
{ This position can be also reached via the move order @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2nppn2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7  8.O-O-O  O-O  9.Nb3  Qb6  . }
10. h4
{ Securing the bishop. We will see this move quite often this move when Black castles kingside. }
10... Rd8
{ Black has to defend this pawn at some point. Also he might play d5 at the right moment. }
11. Kb1 { Semi-waiting move, but always useful. } 11... a6 12. g4
{ We don't even have to prepare g4. The pawn is untouchable, because Black will lose the piece on the g-file. }
12... Qc7
{ Trying to create counterplay with b5-b4 but it is clear that White is faster. }
13. Bxf6
{ White's pawns are so advanced that he doesn't care about the bishop pair. }
13... Bxf6 14. g5 Be7 { Keeping the bishops } 15. f4 { Push them. } 15... b5
16. h5 { White has much faster attack. } *

