[Black "Rauzer 7...Be7 8.O-O-O O-O  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ Natural follow-up to 6...e6. This means Black will castle kingside. } 8.
O-O-O { As usual. } 8... h6 { Loses a pawn. } 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11.
Qxd6
{ The pawn on c6 will be weak, and Black will have zero compensation, even with the two bishops. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) 2...d6 - Rauzer with 6... e6 and 7...Be7"]
[Black "Rauzer 7...Be7 8.O-O-O O-O  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ Natural follow-up to 6...e6. This means Black will castle kingside. } 8.
O-O-O { As usual. } 8... O-O
{ 8...Bd7?  9.Ndb5  this is why Black has to play a6 before Bd7.   8...a6  9.Bxf6!   9.f4  Bd7  would transpose into a very fashionable line which I'm trying to avoid.  9...gxf6  10.f4  and Black will have to play  10...Nxd4  which will be  covered in theline 8...Nxd4. }
9. h4
{ My initial idea was to recommend  9.Nb3  but I realized that  9.h4  fits more into our repertoire. The idea behind this move is to secure the bishop on g5 and prevent possible tactics.   Also, it makes the move h6 less appealing for Black.  Black best replyis 8...Nxd4 which is covered later. }
9... h6 { White has instructive trick here. } 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. e5
{ The opening of the h-file should lead to checkmate, so Black has to capture on e5.  11...Nd5  has no independent value after  12.Bxh6! }
11... hxg5 12. exf6 { 12.exd6  is also very promising. } 12... Bxf6 13. hxg5
Bxc3 14. bxc3 { Black will have to give up many pawns to avoid checkmate. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) 2...d6 - Rauzer with 6... e6 and 7...Be7"]
[Black "Rauzer 7...Be7 8.O-O-O O-O  #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ Natural follow-up to 6...e6. This means Black will castle kingside. } 8.
O-O-O { As usual. } 8... O-O
{ 8...Bd7?  9.Ndb5  this is why Black has to play a6 before Bd7.   8...a6  9.Bxf6!   9.f4  Bd7  would transpose into a very fashionable line which I'm trying to avoid.  9...gxf6  10.f4  and Black will have to play  10...Nxd4  which will be  covered in theline 8...Nxd4. }
9. h4
{ My initial idea was to recommend  9.Nb3  but I realized that  9.h4  fits more into our repertoire. The idea behind this move is to secure the bishop on g5 and prevent possible tactics.   Also, it makes the move h6 less appealing for Black.  Black best replyis 8...Nxd4 which is covered later. }
9... h6 { White has instructive trick here. } 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. e5
{ The opening of the h-file should lead to checkmate, so Black has to capture on e5.  11...Nd5  has no independent value after  12.Bxh6! }
11... dxe5 12. Bxh6
{ That is the point. If Black captures the bishop, the game will finish quickly. The trade of queens is quite bad for him as well, due to his terrible pawn structure. }
12... Qxd2+ 13. Bxd2 Ng4 { Trying some pseudo active moves. } 14. Ne4 f5 15. f3
{ We don't retreat. } 15... Nf6
{ 15...fxe4  16.fxg4  is equal to resignation. } 16. Ng5
{ Excellent square for the knight. The pawn on e6 is weak as well. } 16... Nd5
17. Bc4 { Black's knight on d5 only brings him false hope. } 17... Bf6 18. Rhe1
{ Soon, Black will be left without any useful moves. } *

