[Black "Rauzer 7...Be7 8.O-O-O O-O  #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ Natural follow-up to 6...e6. This means Black will castle kingside. } 8.
O-O-O { As usual. } 8... O-O
{ 8...Bd7?  9.Ndb5  this is why Black has to play a6 before Bd7.   8...a6  9.Bxf6!   9.f4  Bd7  would transpose into a very fashionable line which I'm trying to avoid.  9...gxf6  10.f4  and Black will have to play  10...Nxd4  which will be  covered in theline 8...Nxd4. }
9. h4
{ My initial idea was to recommend  9.Nb3  but I realized that  9.h4  fits more into our repertoire. The idea behind this move is to secure the bishop on g5 and prevent possible tactics.   Also, it makes the move h6 less appealing for Black.  Black best replyis 8...Nxd4 which is covered later. }
9... a6 10. Nxc6
{ This reaction is more typical for Taimanov. Other normal moves are  10.f4  or  10.Kb1  . }
10... bxc6 11. Rh3 { The rook comes into the play. } 11... d5 12. Rg3 Rb8
{ A very natural move, but White here has a strong reply. } 13. e5 Nd7 14. Bh6
g6 15. f4
{ No need to take the rook yet, White can have a dangerous attack instead. He can parry Black's threats on the queenside with the simple b3. If Black takes the pawn on h4 then the h-file will be opened for the white rooks. }
*

