[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) 2...d6 - Rauzer with 6... e6 and 7...Be7"]
[Black "Rauzer 7...Be7 8.O-O-O Nxd4  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ Natural follow-up to 6...e6. This means Black will castle kingside. } 8.
O-O-O { As usual. } 8... Nxd4
{ One can say this is a more precise move order for Black than  8...O-O  since it avoids the  9.Nb3  line. }
9. Qxd4 a6
{ This line was popular in the 'old' days, and Vassily Ivanchuk played it a couple of times successfully. }
10. f4 b5 11. Bxf6 Bxf6
{ Is a well known mistake. Black is hoping for  12.Qxd6  but White has much stronger reply. }
12. e5 dxe5 13. Qe4 { Double attack. } 13... Bd7
{ It looks like Black is completely fine. Only one more move @@StartBracket@@O-O@@EndBracket@@ and he has everything. }
14. Rxd7 { Unfortunately for Black, White has a direct refutation. } 14... Kxd7
15. Bxb5+ axb5 16. Rd1+
{ Winning back the queen, and a few pawns afterwards, leaving White with a winning position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) 2...d6 - Rauzer with 6... e6 and 7...Be7"]
[Black "Rauzer 7...Be7 8.O-O-O Nxd4  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ Natural follow-up to 6...e6. This means Black will castle kingside. } 8.
O-O-O { As usual. } 8... Nxd4
{ One can say this is a more precise move order for Black than  8...O-O  since it avoids the  9.Nb3  line. }
9. Qxd4 a6
{ This line was popular in the 'old' days, and Vassily Ivanchuk played it a couple of times successfully. }
10. f4 b5 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Kb1
{ The main move was  12.e5  , but I think White should continue in typical Rauzer fashion. As I mentioned before, the bishop on e7 is not very happy with the pawns on f6 and d6. }
12... Qc7 13. f5 { Typical way to undermine the pawns. } 13... Bb7 14. Be2
{ Connecting the rooks. The bishop can later support the e4 pawn, or attack the Black pawns over the g4 and h5 squares. }
14... Qc5 15. Qd3 { White avoids the exchange of queens. } 15... h5
{ If the white bishop arrives on h5, then Black will have more troubles with his pawns. }
16. Rhe1
{ Including the last piece into the action. This looks deep, and you may think that the rook could be more useful on the f-file, but sooner or later the e-file will be opened. }
16... Rc8 17. fxe6 { We can exchange those pawns now. } 17... fxe6 18. Bf3 Qe5
{ Black has to stop the e4-e5 ideas. } 19. Ne2
{ The knight is heading towards a square where it can attack the queen @@StartBracket@@d3, f3, g6@@EndBracket@@. Black can hardly defend all those weaknesses. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) 2...d6 - Rauzer with 6... e6 and 7...Be7"]
[Black "Rauzer 7...Be7 8.O-O-O Nxd4  #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ Natural follow-up to 6...e6. This means Black will castle kingside. } 8.
O-O-O { As usual. } 8... Nxd4
{ One can say this is a more precise move order for Black than  8...O-O  since it avoids the  9.Nb3  line. }
9. Qxd4 O-O 10. h4
{ 10.f4  is by far the most popular move, but  10.h4  is trickier and I believe more precise. }
10... Qa5 11. Kb1
{ Here is the main difference between moves 10. f4 and 10. h4. The Black queen will soon be misplaced on a5.   When you compare this line withthe main line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2nppn2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...a6  8.O-O-O  Bd7  it is visible that Black got an inferior version of it, with early castling and will lose the whole tempo with Qa5-Qc7. }
11... Bd7 12. Qd2
{ The queen is a target on d4-square. On d2, the idea of playing Nd5 becomes possible. }
12... Rfd8 13. f3
{ It was too early for Nd5 since the pawn on e4 was hanging. Now, the threat becomes real. }
13... Qc7 { In case of  13...Rac8?  14.Nd5!  wins. } 14. g4
{ White's kingside attack is much faster. } *

