1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ Natural follow-up to 6...e6. This means Black will castle kingside. } 8.
O-O-O { As usual. } 8... Nxd4
{ One can say this is a more precise move order for Black than  8...O-O  since it avoids the  9.Nb3  line. }
9. Qxd4 O-O 10. h4
{ 10.f4  is by far the most popular move, but  10.h4  is trickier and I believe more precise. }
10... h6 11. f4 hxg5 { Exactly what White wants. } 12. hxg5 Ng4 13. Qd2
{ The most precise move. Anticipating e5 and Qb6. } 13... e5 14. g3
{ White plays a bit positionally. } 14... g6 { Black's king needs some air. }
15. Rh4 Kg7 16. Be2 { The knight has to be attacked. } 16... Rh8 17. Rxg4 Bxg4
18. Bxg4
{ This is positionally winning for White. Often you can see this type of material imbalance in the Sveshnikov variation, but here White also has a strong attack. }
