1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ Natural follow-up to 6...e6. This means Black will castle kingside. } 8.
O-O-O { As usual. } 8... Nxd4
{ One can say this is a more precise move order for Black than  8...O-O  since it avoids the  9.Nb3  line. }
9. Qxd4 O-O 10. h4
{ 10.f4  is by far the most popular move, but  10.h4  is trickier and I believe more precise. }
10... h6 11. f4 Qa5 12. Qe3
{ Avoiding e6-e5 which activates the bishop from c8 and preventing  12...Bd7?  due to  13.e5  .   Also  12...hxg5  13.hxg5  ends the game much quicker now than on the previous note because the queen can go to the h-file in one step. }
12... Qc5 13. Qe1
{ The endgame is definitely better for White, but why give Black any chance. }
13... b5
{ I guess the only move which can confuse the opponent.   13...Rd8  14.Bd3  and White keeps improving his pieces and preparing for the final blow. }
14. Bxb5 { We take the pawn. } 14... Rb8 15. Ba4
{ The bishop is heading to the b3 square where it guards the king. } 15... d5
16. Bb3 d4 17. Bxf6 { Simplifying. } 17... Bxf6 18. Na4 Qc6 19. g4
{ The pawns just go. } *

