1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ Natural follow-up to 6...e6. This means Black will castle kingside. } 8.
O-O-O { As usual. } 8... Nxd4
{ One can say this is a more precise move order for Black than  8...O-O  since it avoids the  9.Nb3  line. }
9. Qxd4 O-O 10. h4
{ 10.f4  is by far the most popular move, but  10.h4  is trickier and I believe more precise. }
10... Bd7
{ This move is preferred by the correspondence players, in other words, top chess engines. }
11. Kb1 { Rarely a bad move. } 11... h6 12. f3 b5
{ In case of some neutral move like  12...Rc8  13.Bc1  is simple and strong with g4-g5 next. }
13. Bd3
{ There is no need to take the material when you can try to checkmate. The bishop on d3 does a good defending and attacking task. }
13... e5 { 13...hxg5?  14.hxg5  Nh7  15.e5  finishes the game. } 14. Qg1
{ I like this move very much. The queen will support the g-pawn. } 14... b4 15.
Ne2 Be6 16. g4 { The bishop is still safe on g5, no need to retreat it yet. }
16... Qa5 17. b3
{ Black's threats are over, and White has just started having fun. } *

