1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ Natural follow-up to 6...e6. This means Black will castle kingside. } 8.
O-O-O { As usual. } 8... Nxd4
{ One can say this is a more precise move order for Black than  8...O-O  since it avoids the  9.Nb3  line. }
9. Qxd4 O-O 10. h4
{ 10.f4  is by far the most popular move, but  10.h4  is trickier and I believe more precise. }
10... Bd7
{ This move is preferred by the correspondence players, in other words, top chess engines. }
11. Kb1 { Rarely a bad move. } 11... Bc6 12. f3
{ Fortifying e4, and preparing g4. } 12... d5 { Doesn't work. } 13. exd5 Nxd5
14. Nxd5 Bxd5
{ 14...exd5  leaves Black with an isolated pawn and a bad bishop on c6, and  15.Bd3  gives White a huge advantage. }
15. Qe3
{ Black's queen can't protect both bishops and Black is forced to open up the h-file }
15... Bxa2+ 16. Kxa2 Qxd1 17. Bxe7
{ The two bishops are much stronger than the rook, even when Black gets two pawns. }
*

