1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6
{ Since we have seen that Black can't really get enough counterplay without a6-b5 plan it seems logical to start with this move. }
8. O-O-O h6
{ This line was popular until the discovery of 9. Nxc6. After that it was all going downhill for Black. The more popular andbetter 8...Bd7 will be part of this chapter. }
9. Nxc6
{ In case of  9.Bh4  Nxe4  is well known trick, although White can claim some compensation there. }
9... bxc6 10. Bf4
{ Forcing Black to play d5, since  10...e5?  loses a pawn to  11.Bxe5  . }
10... d5 11. Qe3
{ Avoiding a possible pin, and making the most out of the queen and the rook. White's queen is doing great job on the third rank.   White's next move is Be2 and he will have all his pieces developed by 12th move. If we look at the Black pieces, we see a completely different picture. }
11... Be7 12. Be2
{ Connecting rooks, and securing g4 and h5 squares which are important for the kingside attack. }
12... O-O 13. h4
{ White has a very simple plan @@StartBracket@@g4-g5@@EndBracket@@. It is hard to give a good advice for Black. }
13... Re8 14. g4 e5
{ Black tries to open up his pieces, however, White is better prepared. } 15.
Bxe5 Bb4
{ Taking on g4 will only help White to finish the attack over the g-file. } 16.
exd5 { Taking another pawn, and defending the bishop. } 16... Bxg4 17. Bxf6
Qxf6 18. Ne4 Qg6 19. f3
{ White has a material advantage which is enough for the victory. } *

