[Round "?"]
[White "27) 2...d6 - Rauzer with 6...e6 and 7...a6"]
[Black "Rauzer 7...a6 8.O-O-O h6  #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6
{ Since we have seen that Black can't really get enough counterplay without a6-b5 plan it seems logical to start with this move. }
8. O-O-O h6
{ This line was popular until the discovery of 9. Nxc6. After that it was all going downhill for Black. The more popular andbetter 8...Bd7 will be part of this chapter. }
9. Nxc6
{ In case of  9.Bh4  Nxe4  is well known trick, although White can claim some compensation there. }
9... bxc6 10. Bf4
{ Forcing Black to play d5, since  10...e5?  loses a pawn to  11.Bxe5  . }
10... d5 11. Qe3
{ Avoiding a possible pin, and making the most out of the queen and the rook. White's queen is doing great job on the third rank.   White's next move is Be2 and he will have all his pieces developed by 12th move. If we look at the Black pieces, we see a completely different picture. }
11... Qa5
{ Black activates his queen, and keeps flexibility with the dark-squared bishop. }
12. Be2 { White does the same as usual. } 12... dxe4
{ Black has some concrete ideas in mind which were refuted in practice. } 13.
Nxe4 Nd5
{ Obviously the idea behind 12...dxe4. Otherwise, Black is already lost. } 14.
Qg3
{ White has such nice position that the exchange sacrifice  14.Rxd5  cxd5  15.Nd6+  Bxd6  16.Bxd6  gave him excellent results thanks to the domination on the dark squares. The text move is simpler, because White doesn't have to give up material to prove superiority. }
14... Qxa2
{ Black took the pawn, but everything else in his position doesn't work. Here I was having troubles which move to recommend  15.Be5  ,  15.c4  or  15.Nd6  , since all give White an overwhelming advantage and almost winning position.  In the end I chose  15.Nd6  because it forces matters. }
15. Nd6+ { Taking the bishop pair. } 15... Bxd6 16. Bxd6 Qa1+
{ Black must at least take more pawns in return. } 17. Kd2 Qxb2 18. Be5
{ Attacking the queen again. } 18... Qb4+ 19. c3 Qb2+
{ Black must give checks to gain some time. } 20. Ke1
{ White's king is safe. Black can't castle and the g7 pawn is hanging. } 20...
Rg8 { Defending the pawn. } 21. c4 { Double attack. } 21... Qb4+ 22. Kf1
{ Finally, Black has run out of checks. } 22... Ne7 23. Bd6
{ Black is completely paralyzed. The bishop on d6 is a monster. When the rook from h1 enters into the attack the game will be finished. }
