1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6
{ Since we have seen that Black can't really get enough counterplay without a6-b5 plan it seems logical to start with this move. }
8. O-O-O h6
{ This line was popular until the discovery of 9. Nxc6. After that it was all going downhill for Black. The more popular andbetter 8...Bd7 will be part of this chapter. }
9. Nxc6
{ In case of  9.Bh4  Nxe4  is well known trick, although White can claim some compensation there. }
9... bxc6 10. Bf4
{ Forcing Black to play d5, since  10...e5?  loses a pawn to  11.Bxe5  . }
10... d5 11. Qe3
{ Avoiding a possible pin, and making the most out of the queen and the rook. White's queen is doing great job on the third rank.   White's next move is Be2 and he will have all his pieces developed by 12th move. If we look at the Black pieces, we see a completely different picture. }
11... Bb4
{ Over the last couple of years this moves gave Black the most success. } 12.
Be2 { Finishing development. } 12... Qa5
{ Looks logical, but it is refuted by } 13. Be5
{ The bishop attacks and defends. } 13... Bxc3
{ Objectively the best is  13...Be7  which means that Black gave a free tempo in already bad position. }
14. Bxc3 Qxa2
{ We will see that this pawn is completely meaningless. On the other hand, the dark squares in the black camp aren't. White's king is safe since it always has a square on d2, while Black's king has nowhere to go. }
15. Bd3
{ Preparing Qg3, I remember the first time I saw this line I was quite impressed by the move Bd3. }
15... dxe4 16. Qg3
{ This move reminds me of the Pin variation, where White gives a piece just to take on g7. }
16... exd3 17. Qxg7 { Double attack. Take a look at the dark squares. } 17...
Rg8 18. Qxf6 Qa1+ 19. Kd2 Qa4 20. Ke3
{ The final touch. White will finish off Black on the d-file. } *

