[White "27) 2...d6 - Rauzer with 6...e6 and 7...a6"]
[Black "Rauzer 7...a6 8.O-O-O h6  #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6
{ Since we have seen that Black can't really get enough counterplay without a6-b5 plan it seems logical to start with this move. }
8. O-O-O h6
{ This line was popular until the discovery of 9. Nxc6. After that it was all going downhill for Black. The more popular andbetter 8...Bd7 will be part of this chapter. }
9. Nxc6
{ In case of  9.Bh4  Nxe4  is well known trick, although White can claim some compensation there. }
9... bxc6 10. Bf4
{ Forcing Black to play d5, since  10...e5?  loses a pawn to  11.Bxe5  . }
10... d5 11. Qe3
{ Avoiding a possible pin, and making the most out of the queen and the rook. White's queen is doing great job on the third rank.   White's next move is Be2 and he will have all his pieces developed by 12th move. If we look at the Black pieces, we see a completely different picture. }
11... Bb4
{ Over the last couple of years this moves gave Black the most success. } 12.
Be2 { Finishing development. } 12... O-O 13. e5
{ Black has to decide where to put his knight. On d7 it looks more natural, but it blocks his bishop and prevents black's queenside from developing. }
13... Nd7 14. Qg3
{ The only move which keeps initiative.  14.h4  f6!  and Black gets a decent position. }
14... Kh8 15. Qh3
{ White is annoying Black with Bxh6 ideas, not giving him time to play f6. }
15... Bxc3
{ Black can't repeat the moves with  15...Kg8  since white's rook joins the action after  16.Rd3  . }
16. Qxc3
{ White has a pleasant choice between  16.Qxc3  which keeps the perfect pawn structure and  16.bxc3  which keeps the Bxh6 threat. I choose the first option since it gives less counterplay to opponent. }
16... Qb6 17. Qh3
{ Our queenside is safe, moves like  17...Rb8  are always responded by  18.b3  . With this last move White renews the threat. }
17... Qxf2 18. Bf3
{ The attack is too strong for the price of the pawn. The open f-file only helps White to create more threats. }
18... Nxe5
{ Using tactics to keep the game going.  19.Bxe5??  is bad due to  19...Qe3+  , but White has an intermediate move. }
19. Rd2 Qc5 20. Bxe5
{ Winning the piece. Two pawns shouldn't be enough to save Black. } *

