{ The only move which keeps initiative.  14.h4  f6!  and Black gets a decent position. }
14... Qc7 15. a3
{ Black has created some counterplay because of the e5 pawn, but we can take the bishop pair. }
15... Bxc3 16. Qxc3 f6 { Black will take the pawn on e5. } 17. Qg3
{ On the other hand White wins the pawn on h6. Yes, the central pawns are usually more important than the ones on the edge of the board, but White's dark-squared bishop has no opponent which is more than enough for White to claim advantage. }
17... Nxe5 18. Bxh6 c5 19. h4 { White has much easier play. } 19... Ra7 20. Bf4
{ The knight is pinned, and Black decided to give up a pawn. } 20... Qb6 21.
Bxe5 fxe5 22. Qxe5
{ We were following correspondence game Galliano - Boesenberg, ICCF email 2017. White is a clear pawn up. Capturing on f2 isn't possible due to a few reasons. First White can play Bf3 and trap the rook, secondly it only opens the f-file and weakens black's king further. }
