{ Over the last couple of years this moves gave Black the most success. } 12.
Be2 { Finishing development. } 12... O-O 13. e5
{ Black has to decide where to put his knight. On d7 it looks more natural, but it blocks his bishop and prevents black's queenside from developing. }
13... Nh7
{ The knight is very strange on h7 indeed, but Black is planning to create quick counterplay with Bd7, connect his rooks and combine attacking ideas with the f7-f6 pawn break. }
14. a3
{ White should now play positionally to take advantage of the misplaced knight. }
14... Be7 15. Ne4
{ Stopping c5, the knight will land somewhere @@StartBracket@@c5 or d6@@EndBracket@@ in Black's camp. }
15... a5
{ Trying to exchange his bad bishop might be Black's best option.   In case of  15...f5  16.Nd6  the knight lands on d6. White's next move is 17. h4 and he shouldn't be afraid of  16...g5  17.Qg3  when his bishop is secured. }
16. h4
{ Typical move, including the rook into the action, and controlling the g5 square. }
16... Ba6 17. Bxa6
{ White can also avoid the exchange of bishops by playing  17.c4!?  . } 17...
Rxa6 18. Bxh6 { The tactical justification of the previous moves. } 18... gxh6
19. Qxh6 f6
{ Only move, Black can't give up the queen because the rook from h1 will join the attack. }
20. g4 { Surprisingly fast. } 20... Rf7 { The only way for Black to defend. }
21. g5 { White has two threats, taking on f6 and g6. } 21... Qf8 22. Qxf8+
{ White can now trade queens because he gets a lot of pawns for the piece. }
22... Kxf8 23. exf6
{ It is also possible to take on f6 with the knight, but I would prefer to play against the knight, not the bishop. }
23... Nxf6 24. Nxf6 Bxf6 25. gxf6
{ Leaves White with an extra passed pawn in the endgame. } *

