[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27) 2...d6 - Rauzer with 6...e6 and 7...a6"]
[Black "Rauzer 7...a6 8.O-O-O Bd7  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O Bd7
{ We have reached the main move in the Rauzer. Since after  8...Be7  9.Bxf6  Black has to recapture with the pawn on f6, Black first develops his light-squared bishop. And he is ready to play b5. }
9. Kb1
{ Before explaining why I'm choosing 9. Kb1 I have to mention the main move and the most aggressive one,  9.f4  . After  9.f4  Black has two different options, one is to play  9...b5  which has always been considered as the main line. Another one is  9...Be7  , modern way of handling the position.   In both cases White can claim some advantage according to the computers, but the variations are long and complicated, and sometimes difficult to understand.   Also, White gives his dark-squared bishop in order to compromise the black pawn structure, which means that Black always has some counter chances, even in dubious positions. The move  9.Kb1  is very similar to  9.f3  , and often we will just transpose to the 9. f3 lines, with a few small differences which favour White in my opinion.   For example, in case of  9.f3  Nxd4  10.Qxd4  h6  11.Be3  Bc6  12.Qd2  d5  13.e5  Nd7  14.f4  g5!  15.f5  Qc7  Black gets enough counterplay. Also, we are freeing the c1 square for the dark-squared bishop in some lines. 9. Kb1 has been tried more than once by Giri, Dominguez Perez and Nakamura. }
9... h6 10. Be3
{ Now with the bishop being on e3, White doesn't need to take on c6, since he can recapture on d4 with the bishop. His plan remains the same, f3-g4-h4. }
10... Ng4 { Going for the dark-squared bishop doesn't work well. } 11. Nxc6
Bxc6 12. Bd4 { White is ready to kick out the knight. } 12... e5 13. Be3
{ Black will take the bishop, but he paid a big price for it. The d5 square is much more important and White has a clear advantage. }
*

