11. f3
{ Fortifying e4, and preparing for the kingside attack. White light squared bishop is best placed on the d3, g and h pawns must be pushed as far as possible.   The knight on c3 is placed well there, but sooner or later Black will attack it with b5-b4, and then we move it to e2 where it go to centre @@StartBracket@@d4@@EndBracket@@, defend queenside @@StartBracket@@c1@@EndBracket@@ or to the kingside @@StartBracket@@f4, g3 later h5@@EndBracket@@ to join the attack. }
11... O-O
{ 11...h6  12.Be3  only makes job easier for White. Now playing  12...d5  not even remotely good as if it was in case of 9. f3. Black will probably have to keep his king in the centre and play h5 at some moment to stop White pawns. }
12. h4
{ We had a very similar position in the7...Be7 8.O-O-O Nxd4 line with the inclusion of a6 which doesn't change much. }
12... d5 { Again, doesn't work. } 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Qe3
{ The key move again. } 15... Bxa2+ 16. Kxa2 Qxd1 17. Bxe7
{ The bishops are much stronger than a rook. } *

