{ Before explaining why I'm choosing 9. Kb1 I have to mention the main move and the most aggressive one,  9.f4  . After  9.f4  Black has two different options, one is to play  9...b5  which has always been considered as the main line. Another one is  9...Be7  , modern way of handling the position.   In both cases White can claim some advantage according to the computers, but the variations are long and complicated, and sometimes difficult to understand.   Also, White gives his dark-squared bishop in order to compromise the black pawn structure, which means that Black always has some counter chances, even in dubious positions. The move  9.Kb1  is very similar to  9.f3  , and often we will just transpose to the 9. f3 lines, with a few small differences which favour White in my opinion.   For example, in case of  9.f3  Nxd4  10.Qxd4  h6  11.Be3  Bc6  12.Qd2  d5  13.e5  Nd7  14.f4  g5!  15.f5  Qc7  Black gets enough counterplay. Also, we are freeing the c1 square for the dark-squared bishop in some lines. 9. Kb1 has been tried more than once by Giri, Dominguez Perez and Nakamura. }
9... Be7 10. Nxc6 { The usual. } 10... Bxc6
{ With bishop on d7, it makes no sense for Black to capture on c6 with a pawn. }
11. f3
{ Fortifying e4, and preparing for the kingside attack. White light squared bishop is best placed on the d3, g and h pawns must be pushed as far as possible.   The knight on c3 is placed well there, but sooner or later Black will attack it with b5-b4, and then we move it to e2 where it go to centre @@StartBracket@@d4@@EndBracket@@, defend queenside @@StartBracket@@c1@@EndBracket@@ or to the kingside @@StartBracket@@f4, g3 later h5@@EndBracket@@ to join the attack. }
11... b5 12. h4
{ Advancing kingside pawns, and securing the bishop. White has to be careful and not fall into the trap by playing  12.Ne2??  too early because of  12...Nxe4!  trick. }
12... Rc8 13. Ne2 { Before doing anything, White improves his knight. } 13...
Bb7 14. Nd4 h6 15. Be3 Nd7
{ Black tries to postpone kingside castling which could postpone White attack. }
16. g4 Qc7 17. Bd3 { Finishing development and overprotecting pawns. } 17... d5
18. g5
{ The simplest reaction. Other promising move is  18.Bf4  provoking e5 which weakens the f5 square. Black is forced to open up the h-file because everything else is clearly worse for him. }
