[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27) 2...d6 - Rauzer with 6...e6 and 7...a6"]
[Black "Rauzer 7...a6 8.O-O-O Bd7  #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O Bd7
{ We have reached the main move in the Rauzer. Since after  8...Be7  9.Bxf6  Black has to recapture with the pawn on f6, Black first develops his light-squared bishop. And he is ready to play b5. }
9. Kb1
{ Before explaining why I'm choosing 9. Kb1 I have to mention the main move and the most aggressive one,  9.f4  . After  9.f4  Black has two different options, one is to play  9...b5  which has always been considered as the main line. Another one is  9...Be7  , modern way of handling the position.   In both cases White can claim some advantage according to the computers, but the variations are long and complicated, and sometimes difficult to understand.   Also, White gives his dark-squared bishop in order to compromise the black pawn structure, which means that Black always has some counter chances, even in dubious positions. The move  9.Kb1  is very similar to  9.f3  , and often we will just transpose to the 9. f3 lines, with a few small differences which favour White in my opinion.   For example, in case of  9.f3  Nxd4  10.Qxd4  h6  11.Be3  Bc6  12.Qd2  d5  13.e5  Nd7  14.f4  g5!  15.f5  Qc7  Black gets enough counterplay. Also, we are freeing the c1 square for the dark-squared bishop in some lines. 9. Kb1 has been tried more than once by Giri, Dominguez Perez and Nakamura. }
9... Nxd4
{ This move is played way less than the others  9...b5  ,  9...h6  and  9...Be7  . In the whole line there is always some sort of psychological battle when considering who will force trade of knights, White with Nxc6 or Black with Nxd4. My conclusion is that Black should trade these knights immediately, therefore this line is his best chance. }
10. Qxd4 h6
{ Before doing anything else, Black asks White where does he puts his bishop. }
11. Bc1
{ The main idea of 9. Kb1, returning bishop to other squares is possible @@StartBracket@@d2 or e3@@EndBracket@@, but on c1 it doesn't block other pieces and still does its main task, control of the c1-h6 diagonal. It is also notable that guards b2, and sometimes bishop can be fianchettoed. }
11... Rc8
{ Black can start with  11...Qc7  12.f4  , but will have to play Rc8 anyway. }
12. f4 Qc7 { Immediately creating pressure over the c-file and c2 pawn. } 13.
Qe3
{ Black idea was to play Qc5, trade queens and enter into the endgame which would turn king on e8 into a strong piece.   After  13.Qe3  Qc5  White can simply move away his queen to f3 or e1 and continue with the same plan: Bd3 and e5. }
13... b5 14. Bd3
{ 14...b4  was a threat, and we know that bishop should go to d3, guarding pawns. White is now threatening 15. e5. }
14... b4 15. Ne2 Be7
{ And e5 is no longer a threat since black knight has outpost on d5. However, White can improve his knight. }
16. Nd4 d5
{ Following Gelfand's play. Alternatives seems worse.  16...O-O  17.e5!  followed by Qe4 puts lot of questions, while  16...e5  leaves f5 square weak and  17.Nf5  forces Black to give up bishop pair. }
17. e5
{ Entering into the French type pawn structure.  17.exd5  Nxd5  18.Qe4  with f5 ideas in mind also gives White some advantage. }
17... Ne4 { Black must sacrifice the pawn. } 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. Qxe4
{ Simply taking the pawn. } 19... Bc5 20. Rd2
{ Protecting c2, and preparing for doubling of the rooks. } 20... O-O 21. Rhd1
{ White is better here, after all he has an extra pawn. I will just mention one more natural move from Black which White could effectively punish. }
21... Rfd8
{ This logical move is mistake, it was played in a blitz game Dominguez Perez - Gelfand, Chess.com 2021. }
22. Nc6 { Forcing massive exchanges and leaving White with a winning endgame. }
