{ This move is played way less than the others  9...b5  ,  9...h6  and  9...Be7  . In the whole line there is always some sort of psychological battle when considering who will force trade of knights, White with Nxc6 or Black with Nxd4. My conclusion is that Black should trade these knights immediately, therefore this line is his best chance. }
10. Qxd4 Be7
{ Unlike h6 this is a must move for Black.   If  10...b5?  then  11.f4  and 12. e5 is unstoppable threat. }
11. f3 { According to plan. } 11... Qc7 12. Qd2
{ Some sort of prophylaxis. Avoiding all kinds of attacks on the queen, covering c2 and preparing g4.   In case of  12.g4  h5!  13.gxh5  Nxh5  I failed to find anything convincing for White. This move also prepares some tricks . }
12... b5
{ 12...h5?  is a loss of time,  13.Bf4  and the pawn is hanging, and   12...O-O?  loses on the spot after  13.e5  . }
13. g4 h5 { Trying to activate the rook and stop the Be3-g5 plan. } 14. gxh5
Rxh5 15. Bd3 { Finishing development. } 15... Rxg5
{ Worth of trying, but no more than that. } 16. Qxg5 Nxe4 17. Qxg7
{ Grabbing a pawn and defending on c3. } 17... Bf8 18. Qh8
{ Staying on the long diagonal. } 18... Nxc3+ 19. Qxc3 Qxc3 20. bxc3
{ White is exchange up, but has messed up pawn structure on the queenside. However, the h-pawn is his strength. }
*

