[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) 2...d6 - Najdorf English Attack: Rare Black Setups"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.f3 Nbd7  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf. One of the most popular and best systems against 1. e4 in general. There is hardly any modern World Champion who hasn't played the Najdorf. It was the first choice against 1. e4 of many great players in history, such as Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov, Veselin Topalov...   Nowadays people usually connect the Najdorf with the name of Maxime Vachier-Lagrave who plays it almost exclusively. I also have to mention that the Najdorf is currently the first choice against the 1. e4 of your author. }
6. f3
{ White has tried almost every legal move against the Najdorf. It wasn't an easy call to decide what to recommend against 'my own opening'.  6.Bg5  is the most aggressive and principled move, but it requires White to know a ton of theory, and in majority of lines such as  7...Qb6  theory tends to lead into forced draw.   I decided to go for the classical English attack setup, starting with  6.f3  . When comparing  6.f3  and  6.Be3  , the latter one is more flexible against  6...e6  and  6...e5  since it gives White more options.   But  6.f3  has one major plus. It avoids  6...Ng4  variation where White failed to prove any advantage as far as I know. To conclude, I choose  6.f3  because it leads to fighting play, and it is one of the most principled setups. }
6... Nbd7
{ Black is trying to be flexible with something, but it hardly has any effect against the move 6. f3. }
7. Be3 Qc7
{ 7...b5  is dubious because of  8.a4  , now  8...b4  loses pawn to  9.Nc6  drawback of the move Nbd7 and Nxb4. Taking on a4 is traditionally bad for Black when White hasn't weakened his kingside with g4, because White will simply castle kingside and create pressure on the a-pawn. }
8. g4 { Going for the g5. Black must lose time to stop it. } 8... h6 9. Qd2
{ This is typical, and very easy to remember. White almost always plays in the same manner. }
9... b5 10. a3
{ Not necessary now, White can also castle first, but the easiest move. } 10...
Bb7 11. O-O-O
{ In these systems black queen is a bit misplaced on c7, which is quite untypical for the Sicilians. The drawback is that piece sacrifice on b5 often comes with the tempo and White can get 3 pawns for the piece, which is thematic resource for White. }
*

