[Black "Najdorf 6.f3 Qb6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf. One of the most popular and best systems against 1. e4 in general. There is a hardly any modern World Champion who hasn't played the Najdorf. It was a first choice against 1. e4 of many great players in history, such as Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov, Veselin Topalov...   Nowadays people usually connect the Najdorf with the name of Maxime Vachier-Lagrave who plays it almost exclusively. I also have to mention that the Najdorf is currently the first choice against 1. e4 of your author. }
6. f3
{ White has tried almost every legal move against the Najdorf. It wasn't an easy call to decide what to recommend against 'my own opening'.  6.Bg5  is the most aggressive and principled move, but it requires White to know a ton of theory, and in majority of lines such as  7...Qb6  theory tends to lead into forced draw.   I decided to go for the classical English attack setup, starting with  6.f3  . When comparing  6.f3  and  6.Be3  , the latter one is more flexible against  6...e6  and  6...e5  since it gives White more options.   But  6.f3  has one major plus. It avoids  6...Ng4  variation where White failed to prove any advantage as far as I know. To conclude, I choose  6.f3  because it leads to fighting play, and it is one of the most principled setups. }
6... Qb6
{ Preventing  7.Be3  . Black is trying to punish White for playing f3 instead of Be3. }
7. g4 { Preparing g5. } 7... Nc6 8. Nb3 { White's typical reaction. } 8... e6
9. g5 { Or  9.Qe2  first. } 9... Nd7 10. Qe2 { Preparing 11. Be3. } 10... Qc7
11. Be3 b5 12. O-O-O
{ The position is very similar to theGrivas variation. White has played the move f3 which isn't that necessary, but still can keep better chances. }
12... Rb8 { Or  12...Nb6  13.Qf2  Rb8  . } 13. h4
{ White continues his attack on the  kingside. } 13... Nb6 14. Qf2
{ Getting the c4 square under control. } 14... b4
{ 14...Nc4?  15.Bxc4  bxc4  16.Nd2  this is structuraly bad for Black  16...Ne5  17.Ba7!  Rb7  18.Bd4  is winning for White. }
15. Ne2 Nc4 16. f4
{ Black will take the bishop on e3, but White has gained a lot of space  on the kingside which gives him an advantage. }
