8. Be3 Nc6
{ Before going to the main lines  8...Be7  ,  8...h5  or  8...Nbd7  we need to check what happens if Black develops the knight on another natural square c6, which isn't really typical for Najdorf. }
9. Nd5
{ Playing the usual  9.Qd2  would allow  9...d5  where Black is close to equality. Whenever there is knight on c6, playing Nd5 is an option since Black can't capture on d5 with the knight. }
9... Bxd5
{ Black must take on d5, and not allow White to play c4 which would be the case after 10...Rc8 for example. }
10. exd5 Ne7 11. c4 { The pawn was hanging. } 11... Nf5
{ The knight will be target on f5. } 12. Bf2 g6
{ Almost an only move.  12...e4?  13.Qe2  with O-O-O next is horrible for Black.   And  12...Be7?  loses material on the spot after  13.g4  . }
13. Bd3 Bh6 14. Bxf5
{ Transformation of the advantage. White gives up the bishop pair to weaken opponents' pawn structure. }
14... gxf5 15. Qd3 { Targetting the weak pawn. } 15... Rc8 16. O-O
{ White's advantage is huge, Black's kingside is considerably weak. } *

