11. O-O-O
{ White can play  11.g5  but after  11...b4  12.Ne2  Nh5  Black creates some counterplay on the queenside. }
11... Nb6 12. g5 Nfd7 { This knight setup is too passive. } 13. Na5 b4
{ In case of  13...Qc7  White can play  14.Kb1  . } 14. Nd5
{ After b4, playing Nd5 usually costs White a piece, but the black knight on d7 makes this move possible. }
14... Nxd5 15. exd5 Qxa5 16. dxe6 { Black doesn't have time to capture on a2. }
16... fxe6 17. Kb1
{ White is pawn down, but Black has a very weak pawn on e6, and weak light squares too. }
17... O-O 18. Qg2 { Black can hardly survive this position. } *

