{ The best move for Black is to castle and transpose into themain line. Black shouldn't try to 'improve' the main line. }
11. O-O-O
{ White can play  11.g5  but after  11...b4  12.Ne2  Nh5  Black creates some counterplay on the queenside. }
11... b4
{ If Black doesn't want to enter the main line, playing b4 is the only real alternative. }
12. Nd5 { Forced, but good enough. } 12... Bxd5 13. exd5 Nb6
{ A typical reaction from Black, attacking the d5 pawn. } 14. Na5
{ White takes advantage of the weak c6 square.  14.Qxb4?  would only lead to equality. }
14... Nbxd5 { The main move, and the safer one. } 15. Nc6
{ Returning the pawn immediately.  15.Nc4  is an alternative that looks too smart for my taste. }
15... Qc7 16. Nxb4 { Taking the pawn. } 16... Nxb4 17. Qxb4
{ Material is equal but White has the bishop pair. } 17... O-O 18. Qb6
{ Changing the queens would emphasize the strength of the bishops. } 18... Qc8
19. g5
{ The knight controls the d5 square, and the move 19. g5 also opens the h3-c8 diagonal for the white bishop. }
19... Nd7 20. Qa5 Rb8 { Black activates the rook. } 21. Rg1
{ Everyone is playing  21.h4  but after Qb7 it is more useful for White to have rook on g1 than a pawn on h4. }
21... Qb7 22. b3 Qxf3 23. Rg3
{ The most logical move attacking the queen. In one correspondence game, White played  23.Qd2  which I don't understand. }
23... Qh5 { Black attacks the pawn. } 24. Qc7
{ White's queen is doing a great job on c7. } 24... Rfd8 25. Bxa6
{ Taking the pawn and controlling the c8 square. } 25... Qxh2
{ Black is a pawn up, but his queen is cut off from the queenside. White's pawns are also faster than black ones. For example, the pawn on g5 stops 3 black pawns. }
26. Rgg1 { The rooks communicate best when connected. } 26... Qh3 27. Rge1 Qg3
28. Kb1
{ White has great compensation for the pawn. It is not easy for Black to find a move.  28...Bxg5?  loses after  29.Bxg5  Qxg5  30.Rxd6  Nf8  31.Rf1!  . }
