[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. Be3
Be7 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O Nbd7
{ Black develops the knight on d7, to its natural square with the idea to push the b-pawn. }
11. g4
{ Pushing the pawns on the kingside here is primarily used to deflect the black knight from d5 square. }
11... b5 12. g5 b4
{ This was the main line for ages. White has two choices now, he can trade knights with  13.gxf6  or keep them on the board with  13.Ne2  . }
13. Ne2 { Aimed against Nh5 and supporting f3-f4 also. } 13... Nh5
{ Pseudo active move which invites troubles. } 14. Ng3
{ White is immediately asking some questions:  14...g6  is structurally bad, so Black can either play  14...Nf4  , where the knight has no future or open the h-file with  14...Nxg3  which looks extremely dangerous. }
14... Nf4 15. h4 { Defending the pawn on g5. } 15... a5
{ Black is trying to create some counterplay. } 16. Kb1
{ Not giving the bishop pair advantage. } 16... a4 17. Nd4
{ That was the point of waiting with Bxf4, White will keep his bishop. } 17...
exd4 18. Bxf4 { Black's pawns are weak. } 18... b3 19. cxb3
{ Typical way to deal against b3 pushing and close the a file. } 19... axb3 20.
a3
{ Both a-file and b-file are closed and Black's only hope is the c2 square, which White can cover with his rooks or the light-squared bishop. }
