Be7 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O Nbd7
{ Black develops the knight on d7, to its natural square with the idea to push the b-pawn. }
11. g4
{ Pushing the pawns on the kingside here is primarily used to deflect the black knight from d5 square. }
11... b5 12. g5 b4
{ This was the main line for ages. White has two choices now, he can trade knights with  13.gxf6  or keep them on the board with  13.Ne2  . }
13. Ne2 { Aimed against Nh5 and supporting f3-f4 also. } 13... Nh5
{ Pseudo active move which invites troubles. } 14. Ng3
{ White is immediately asking some questions:  14...g6  is structurally bad, so Black can either play  14...Nf4  , where the knight has no future or open the h-file with  14...Nxg3  which looks extremely dangerous. }
14... Nxg3 15. hxg3
{ When I first saw this position I was under the impression that White is completely winning due to the Qh2 threat, however Qh2 wins 'only' a pawn. }
15... a5 16. Kb1 { Securing the queenside first, Qh2 won't go anywhere. } 16...
a4 17. Nc1 Qc7 18. Bd3
{ Defending c2, connecting the rooks, and creating the nasty threat of Rxh7. Much stronger than  18.Qh2  h6  . }
18... Nc5 { Loses spectacularly. } 19. Rxh7
{ 19.f4  Nxd3  20.Rxh7!!  is also winning, but  19.Rxh7  seems more forcing. }
19... Kxh7 20. Qh2+ Kg6
{ 20...Kg8  21.Rh1  f5  @@StartBracket@@or f6@@EndBracket@@  22.g6  and White checkmates. }
21. f4
{ Black was prepared to challenge the queen on the h-file, but White attacks Black's king from another side. }
21... Nxd3 22. f5+ { We can't lose any time. } 22... Bxf5 23. exf5+ Kxf5 24.
Qh3+ { Stopping the king from reaching the safe squares e6 and d7. } 24... Kg6
{ The only move, after  24...Ke4  25.Nxd3  Black can't avoid checkmate. } 25.
g4 { Threatening mate in one. } 25... Rh8 26. Qf3
{ Black can't defend both checks on the diagonal, if the king runs  26...Kh7  27.Qxf7  and Rh1 is checkmate. }
26... Qc8 { Covers the f5 square. } 27. Qe4+
{ The only check, but it's good enough. } 27... f5 28. gxf6+ Kf7
{ If  28...Kxf6  29.Nxd3  Black will have to give up more material to avoid checkmate. }
29. fxe7
{ White is completely winning. Black can't take on c1 because of Qd5+ } *

