Be7 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O Nbd7
{ Black develops the knight on d7, to its natural square with the idea to push the b-pawn. }
11. g4
{ Pushing the pawns on the kingside here is primarily used to deflect the black knight from d5 square. }
11... b5 12. g5 b4
{ This was the main line for ages. White has two choices now, he can trade knights with  13.gxf6  or keep them on the board with  13.Ne2  . }
13. Ne2 { Aimed against Nh5 and supporting f3-f4 also. } 13... Ne8
{ Looks passive, but this knight has a future, as on c7 it supports the d5-break. }
14. f4 { Timing is very important here. } 14... a5 { Black should also push. }
15. f5 a4 16. fxe6
{ The alternative is  16.Nbd4  which was heavily analyzed a few years ago, almost till the end.  16.fxe6  is also heavily analyzed but White's moves are much simpler and easier to understand. }
16... axb3 17. cxb3 { White must take this pawn. } 17... fxe6 18. Bh3
