[Black "Najdorf 6.f3 e5 ... 12...Nh5  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. Be3
Be7 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O Nbd7
{ Black develops the knight on d7, to its natural square with the idea to push the b-pawn. }
11. g4
{ Pushing the pawns on the kingside here is primarily used to deflect the black knight from d5 square. }
11... b5 12. g5 Nh5
{ The variation which is gaining popularity in last couple of years, and has probably surpassed the oldmain line 12...b4. It leads to double-edged positions, and the Najdorf expert MVL uses it regularly. }
13. Kb1
{ There is a big question for White, to jump with  13.Nd5  immediately or to play  13.Kb1  ?   I failed to find any meaningful advantage for White after  13.Nd5  Bxd5  14.exd5  f6  15.gxf6  Bxf6  . }
13... Nb6 { Black doesn't have a better and more useful move than this one. }
14. Nd5
{ 14.Na5  Rc8  15.a3  g6  16.h4  Ng3  17.Rh2  Nxf1  18.Rxf1  Na4  19.Nxa4  bxa4  is another tabiya where Black seems to be doing fine. }
14... Nxd5
{ 14...Bxd5  15.exd5  would transpose into one of thementioned lines where White enjoys a nice advantage. }
15. exd5 Bf5 { The bishop needs to be active. } 16. Na5 f6
{ Black has to open up the kingside, to include his rook and knight into the game. }
17. Nc6 Qd7 18. h4
{ White's knight on c6 is stronger than the black bishop, and exchanging it is not an option. }
18... Ng3 { Or  18...fxg5  19.hxg5  Ng3  . } 19. Rh2 Nxf1
{ Black takes the bishop pair. He finally got rid of the knight on the edge of the board which was problematic in a majority of the lines. }
20. Rxf1 fxg5 21. hxg5
{ The position is almost 0.00 according to the engines, but I believe there is one major difference between the two sides. White has a meaningful plan: b3, Kb2, @@StartBracket@@Rhf2 to defend the f3 pawn@@EndBracket@@ Ra1, a4 while Black is only shuffling pieces and preparing to anticipate White's threats. }
21... Rae8
{ Black can also play  21...Bg6  or  21...Rf7  , but White's plan remains the same. }
22. b3
{ Black should objectively draw this position, but only White can try something. }
*

