[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. Be3
Be7 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O Nbd7
{ Black develops the knight on d7, to its natural square with the idea to push the b-pawn. }
11. g4
{ Pushing the pawns on the kingside here is primarily used to deflect the black knight from d5 square. }
11... b5 12. g5 Nh5
{ The variation which is gaining popularity in last couple of years, and has probably surpassed the oldmain line 12...b4. It leads to double-edged positions, and the Najdorf expert MVL uses it regularly. }
13. Kb1
{ There is a big question for White, to jump with  13.Nd5  immediately or to play  13.Kb1  ?   I failed to find any meaningful advantage for White after  13.Nd5  Bxd5  14.exd5  f6  15.gxf6  Bxf6  . }
13... Nb6 { Black doesn't have a better and more useful move than this one. }
14. Nd5
{ 14.Na5  Rc8  15.a3  g6  16.h4  Ng3  17.Rh2  Nxf1  18.Rxf1  Na4  19.Nxa4  bxa4  is another tabiya where Black seems to be doing fine. }
14... Nxd5
{ 14...Bxd5  15.exd5  would transpose into one of thementioned lines where White enjoys a nice advantage. }
15. exd5 Bd7 16. Na5 { The usual response. The knight is going to c6. } 16...
Qc7 17. Rg1 { Anticipating f6 or f5. } 17... g6
{ Useful move for Black, securing the  knight. } 18. c4 f6
{ The most often played move, to my eye it looks quite dubious.  18...bxc4  19.Bxc4  this is exactly what White wants. }
19. Rc1 { Targetting the queen on c7. } 19... Bf5+ 20. Ka1 Bd8 21. Nc6 fxg5 22.
Nxd8 { With the idea to pick up a few pawns. } 22... Qxd8 23. cxb5
{ Novelty according to my database. Maybe both me and my engine are missing something. White players were previously choosing  23.Bxg5  Qd7  where Black might be OK. }
23... axb5 24. Bxb5 { White picks up a pawn. } 24... Rxa2+
{ Otherwise  White is pawn up and has the bishop pair advantage. } 25. Kxa2
Qa8+ 26. Kb3 Rb8 27. Qb4 { The only move, but good enough. } 27... Nf6
{ 27...Qxd5+  28.Bc4  and White exchanges queens.   27...Bd3  28.Bxd3  Rxb4+  29.Kxb4  and White is having too much material for the queen. }
28. Rgd1
{ Protecting the d5 pawn.  28...Nxd5  runs into the  29.Rxd5  and 30. Bc4. }
28... Bd7 29. Ra1 Qb7 30. Ra7
{ White trades off queens and ends up in a winning position. } *

