Be7 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O Nbd7
{ Black develops the knight on d7, to its natural square with the idea to push the b-pawn. }
11. g4
{ Pushing the pawns on the kingside here is primarily used to deflect the black knight from d5 square. }
11... Qc7
{ Black can postpone playing b5, but it is unclear what he gains from it. } 12.
g5 { Securing the d5 square. } 12... Nh5 13. Kb1 { Always useful. } 13... b5
14. Nd5 Bxd5 15. exd5 { Creating an outpost on c6 for the horsey. } 15... Nb6
16. Na5
{ With the idea of Nc6. This positional pawn sacrifice is quite typical. }
16... Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Qxa5
{ Black has won a pawn, but his light squares are chronically weak. } 18. Bd3
{ Developing. } 18... g6 19. Qb7
{ White queens enters into the black territory, creating chaos.  19.c4  is interesting also. }
19... Rfe8 20. Be4 Rab8 21. Qa7
{ White has more than enough compensation for the pawn. The bishops are monsters. }
