[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. Be3
h5 9. Nd5 { More precise than  9.Qd2  Nbd7  10.Nd5  because ofthe Nxd5 line. }
9... Bxd5 10. exd5 Nbd7
{ Black can't play this position without the move Nbd7. } 11. Qd2 Be7
{ Objectively this variation can be considered slightly dubious, but on the other hand it is very tricky for White if he doesn't know what to do. Black can also start with  11...Qc7  12.O-O-O  Be7  13.c4  . }
12. O-O-O Qc7
{ 12...Nb6  doesn't work because of  13.Qa5  when White defends the pawn. } 13.
c4
{ The only chance for White to fight for an advantage. The typical  13.Kb1  would be imprecise because of  13...Nb6  14.Qa5  Rc8!  15.c3  Bd8  and White has to give up a pawn or the dark-squared bishop. }
13... a5
{ Black tries to create chaos around the white king.  13...b5  14.Na5  only helps White.   And  13...Nb6  doesn't work now:  14.Qa5  Bd8  15.Kb1  and Black is not in time with Rc8. }
14. Kb1 O-O { The most flexible for Black. } 15. Na1
