[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30) 2...d6 - Najdorf English Attack: Main with 8...h5"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.f3 e5 ... 8...h5  11...g6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. Be3
h5 9. Nd5 { More precise than  9.Qd2  Nbd7  10.Nd5  because ofthe Nxd5 line. }
9... Bxd5 10. exd5 Nbd7
{ Black can't play this position without the move Nbd7. } 11. Qd2 g6
{ 11...Be7  12.O-O-O  or   11...Qc7  12.O-O-O  would transpose into theBe6-Be7-h5 line. }
12. O-O-O
{ More direct than the positional  12.Be2  .   12...b5?  is premature,  13.Na5!  Nb6   13...Bg7  allows White to play both  14.c4  and Nc6 with a huge advantage.  14.Qc3!  the crushing move. 15. Qc6 is the strong idea, and Black is in trouble. }
12... Qc7
{ Or  12...Bg7  13.Kb1  when Black doesn't have anything better than transpose to 12...Qc7. }
13. Kb1 Bg7
{ I tried this move a couple of times myself, but I'm not eager to repeat it. }
14. Be2 { Connecting rooks and preparing to play g4 one day. } 14... O-O
{ 14...a5  is too early, it weakens the b5 square. After  15.a4  O-O  16.Bb5  Black has no counterplay on the queenside. }
15. g4 { Not wasting time. White should try to open up the kingside. } 15...
hxg4 16. fxg4 Nb6
{ Is a very concrete idea from Black, but White doesn't care about the d5 pawn when he's pushing the h-pawn. }
17. h4 Nc4 { Only move, Black doesn't have time to capture on d5. } 18. Bxc4
Qxc4 { The awn on g4 is weak. } 19. g5 Nh5 20. Na5
{ We were following the correspondence game Brinkmann - Hoeppenstein from 2017. White has better chances, but the question is whether he can break through. }
*

