14. Be2 { Connecting rooks and preparing to play g4 one day. } 14... O-O
{ 14...a5  is too early, it weakens the b5 square. After  15.a4  O-O  16.Bb5  Black has no counterplay on the queenside. }
15. g4 { Not wasting time. White should try to open up the kingside. } 15...
Rfc8
{ Definitely a move that Black needs to play.  15...a5?  16.g5  Ne8  17.a4  shows exactly why. There is no communication between the black rooks, and he can only wait. }
16. Rc1
{ We need to cover the c2 pawn,  16.g5??  would lose pawns and the game after  16...Nxd5  17.Qxd5  Qxc2+  18.Ka1  Qxe2  . }
16... a5 { Was my try against Leko but it didn't end well for Black. } 17. g5
Ne8 18. a4 { The problem of Black's position is the lack of space. } 18... Qd8
19. Bb5 { The usual. } 19... Nc7 { Trying to get rid of the bad knight. } 20.
c4 Nxb5 21. cxb5
{ Occurred in thegame Leko-Saric, EU-chT Heraklion 2017. The only move for Black is }
21... f5 { To get e4 square under control. } 22. Bf2
{ White still keeps an edge, and his position is easier to play. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30) 2...d6 - Najdorf English Attack: Main with 8...h5"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.f3 e5 ... 8...h5  11...g6  #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. Be3
h5 9. Nd5 { More precise than  9.Qd2  Nbd7  10.Nd5  because ofthe Nxd5 line. }
9... Bxd5 10. exd5 Nbd7
{ Black can't play this position without the move Nbd7. } 11. Qd2 g6
{ 11...Be7  12.O-O-O  or   11...Qc7  12.O-O-O  would transpose into theBe6-Be7-h5 line. }
12. O-O-O
{ More direct than the positional  12.Be2  .   12...b5?  is premature,  13.Na5!  Nb6   13...Bg7  allows White to play both  14.c4  and Nc6 with a huge advantage.  14.Qc3!  the crushing move. 15. Qc6 is the strong idea, and Black is in trouble. }
12... Bg7 13. Kb1 b5
{ Black wants to play Nb6 and capture on d5.   13...O-O   13...Qc7  14.Be2  transposesto 12...Qc7 line.  14.h3!   The usual  14.Be2  allows  14...b5  15.g4  Nb6  where Black creates counterplay against the d5 pawn.  14...b5   14...e4  prevents g4 but gives White some extra possibilities:  15.f4  h4  16.Be2  White has ideas of pushing the f5 pawn or the g4 pawn, to open up the kingside.   14...Qc7  now is worse compared to the 12...Qc7 line,  15.g4  Rfc8  16.Rh2!  the rook protects the c2 pawn, while the other rook on d1 keeps an active placement.  15.g4  Nb6  16.Bg5!  it is important that hxg4 is never a good option for Black with the White pawn on h3, which is not the case if White plays 14. Be2. Black is in  trouble. }
14. Na5 { Going for the c6 square. The typical reaction against b5. } 14... Nb6
15. Nc6 Qc7 16. Bxb6
{ Unfortunately, White  has to give up the bishop to keep the d5-pawn alive. }
16... Qxb6 17. Bd3
{ Black can never capture on d5 in a good way because after Be4 he will lose the d6 pawn and have big issues on the light squares. White has a dominating knight on c6 which secures him slightly better chances, but the position is far from simple. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30) 2...d6 - Najdorf English Attack: Main with 8...h5"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.f3 e5 ... 8...h5  11...g6  #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. Be3
h5 9. Nd5 { More precise than  9.Qd2  Nbd7  10.Nd5  because ofthe Nxd5 line. }
9... Bxd5 10. exd5 Nbd7
{ Black can't play this position without the move Nbd7. } 11. Qd2 g6
{ 11...Be7  12.O-O-O  or   11...Qc7  12.O-O-O  would transpose into theBe6-Be7-h5 line. }
12. O-O-O
{ More direct than the positional  12.Be2  .   12...b5?  is premature,  13.Na5!  Nb6   13...Bg7  allows White to play both  14.c4  and Nc6 with a huge advantage.  14.Qc3!  the crushing move. 15. Qc6 is the strong idea, and Black is in trouble. }
12... Nb6
{ The best move according to the current state of theory. Black attacks the pawn on d5, and White is willing to sacrifice it. }
13. Kb1
{ 13.c4  Rc8  doesn't save the pawn, while   13.Qa5  allows Black to trade bishops with  13...Bh6  . White plays a useful move, preparing c4, and waits for Black to capture on d5. }
13... Nbxd5
{ Capturing with the knight from b6 allows White to pin the other knight. } 14.
Bg5 Be7 { The only move. } 15. Bd3
{ White has many interesting ways to play for compensation, but we will follow the main line. }
15... Qc7
{ A typical Sicilian move, Black removes his queen from the d-file and prepares for some sort of counterplay on the c-file. }
16. Rhe1 { Finishing the development. All white pieces are looking good. }
16... Nb6
{ Black should refrain from castling, either side.  16...O-O-O  is bad because of  17.c4  , while   16...O-O  17.g4  looks scary. }
17. Qf2 { Running away from Nc4 and eyeing both black knights. } 17... Rc8
{ If Black tries to simplify matters by playing  17...Ne4  18.Rxe4  Bxg5  , there is a strong response  19.f4  followed by f5 and troubles on the light squares are just beginning.   And  17...Rc8  happened in a very recent game Aronian - Yilmaz, Grand Swiss 2021, instead of direct  18.f4  that I like. }
18. c3 { Waiting for Black's reply. White has enough compensation. } *

