Be7 { or  8...h5  9.Qd2  Be7  . } 9. Qd2 h5 10. Be2
{ The main line is  10.Nd5  which is heavily covered in Anish Giri's Najdorf course. With the Be2 move White is aiming to obtain the bishop-pair advantage. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nd5 { Now it is time to jump. } 11... Bxd5 12. exd5 Qc7
{ The most flexible move for Black. Black wants to play Nb6.   12...Nb6  is premature. After  13.c4  White will place a knight on its ideal square, the  a5  where it defends on  c4  and attacks on  b7  . This gives White full control on the queenside. }
13. Rc1
{ 13.Na5  would be premature while  13.c4  a5  is usually good for Black. With his last move White is waiting for Nb6 to play c4. }
13... h4 { It is interesting for Black to gain some space on the kingside. }
14. O-O { White should finish development. } 14... Nh5 15. Rfd1
{ Creating a safe square for the bishop on f1. } 15... O-O 16. a4
{ Before playing c4 White would like to fix the black pawn with a5. } 16... b6
17. a5 Bd8 18. c4
{ Thanks to the bishop pair white can claim some small plus. } *

