1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. Be3
Be7 { or  8...h5  9.Qd2  Be7  . } 9. Qd2 h5 10. Be2
{ The main line is  10.Nd5  which is heavily covered in Anish Giri's Najdorf course. With the Be2 move White is aiming to obtain the bishop-pair advantage. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nd5 { Now it is time to jump. } 11... Bxd5 12. exd5 Qc7
{ The most flexible move for Black. Black wants to play Nb6. } 13. Rc1
{ 13.Na5  would be premature while  13.c4  a5  is usually good for Black. With his last move White is waiting for Nb6 to play c4. }
13... O-O { Following Giri's recommendation. } 14. c4
{ We are not in a hurry to castle. Sometimes White can even play g3 and open up the h-file. }
14... a5
{ With the knight on b3 Black should avoid at all costs playing  14...e4  and allowing  15.Nd4  .   If Black plays some useful neutral move such as  14...b6  White should continue with the knight rerouting  15.Na1  . }
15. Na1 { Improving the knight first. The most typical reaction after a5. }
15... h4 { Is an interesting try. } 16. Nc2 Nh5 17. Na3
{ Both sides are improving their knights. } 17... Nc5 18. Nb5 Qd7 19. O-O
{ The presence of the bishop pair can be felt already. Besides  19.O-O  it is worth considering to play  19.Kd1!?  with the idea Kc2 and Kb1, hiding the king on the queenside, and going for a kingside attack. }
