[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Valente, D. vs. Dreisch, J. - W-ch WS/M/579 email, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 c5 4. dxc5 Qa5+ 5. c3 Qxc5 6. Na3 Nf6 7. Nb5 O-O 8.
Be3 Qc6 9. Nfd4 Qxe4 10. Nc7 Nd5 11. Nxa8 Nxe3 12. fxe3 Qxe3+ 13. Qe2 Qg5 14.
Nf3 Qa5 15. Qxe7
{ Up to this moment we are followingthe course. White has the winning position since he has an extra rook, but things aren't that simple. Black has a few pawns for it and he will try to trap the a8-knight.   White continues to collect material. It may seem a bit counterintuitive to leave the king without protection but this move opens up the bishop from f1.   15.Qb5  is my recommendation in the course to keep an extra rook. }
15... Bxc3+
{ Black is returning some material.   15...Nc6  16.Qd6  the inlcusion of the last two moves only help White to secure his king.  16...Bxc3+  17.bxc3  Qxc3+  18.Kf2  Qxa1  19.Nc7  Qxa2+  20.Kg3  White's king on g3 is safe, he will include the bishop into the action and the pieces are stronger than the pawns in the middlegame. }
16. bxc3 Qxc3+ 17. Kf2 Qxa1 18. Qd6
{ Keeping the bishop on c8 in the box.  18.Kg3  and  18.Nc7  were alternatives. }
18... Qxa2+ 19. Kg3 Na6 { Black is trying to prevent the Nc7-Nd5 idea. } 20.
Bxa6 { Of course. } 20... Qxa6
{ Trading queens is Black's best chance. However, White has too many pieces and the material hasn't been reduced completely. }
21. Qxa6 bxa6 22. Rb1 { Restricting the black bishop again. } 22... a5 23. Nc7
a6 24. Rb6 { The technique is quite instructive. } 24... a4 25. Nxa6
{ White will eventualy collect the pawns on the d and the a-file. } 25... d6
26. Nc7 h5 27. Rxd6 Bb7 28. Rb6 Bxf3 29. Kxf3 Rd8 30. Ra6 Rd3+ 31. Ke2 Ra3
{ It looks like Black has managed to create some counterplay. } 32. h3 Ra2+ 33.
Kf1 Ra1+ 34. Kf2 Ra2+ 35. Kg1 Ra1+ 36. Kh2 Kg7 37. Nb5 h4 38. Nc3 a3 39. Nb5
{ The a-pawn falls. } 39... Rb1 40. Nxa3 Ra1 41. Ra7 { With the Nb5 idea. }
41... g5 42. Ra5 f6 43. Nc4 Re1 44. Ra3 Re4 45. Ne3 Kf7 46. Kg1
{ The king comes into the centre. } 46... Kg6 47. Kf2 Re6 48. Ra5 Rb6 49. Kf3
Rb3 50. Ra6 Kg7 51. Ra2 Kg6 52. Ke4 Rb4+ 53. Kd5 Rb6 54. Ng4 Rb5+ 55. Kd6 Rb6+
56. Kc7 Rb1 57. Ra6 Rf1 58. Kd6 Kf7 59. Ra7+ Kg6 60. Ke7 Re1+ 61. Kf8 Re6
{ 61...Re2  62.Ra6 } 62. Rg7+ Kf5 63. Re7 Ra6 64. Kg7 Ra2 65. Rf7
{ Black can't capture on g2 because he loses the rook after Ne3+. White will collect all the pawns and keep the pawn on h3 alive. }
