[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Maghsoodloo, P. vs. Adly, A. - Sharjah Masters 4th, 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 Nxc3 5. dxc3 Nc6 6. Bf4 Qc7
{ This is an inferior version for Black compared to the main  6...Qb6  , but nevertheless it doesn't change the character of the position.  So far we have been following the theoreticalchapter. }
7. h4 { White can start with  7.Bd3  , but we will transpose. } 7... h6 8. h5
e6 9. Bd3 b6 10. Qe2 Bb7 11. Rh3
{ White can also castle queenside first. The idea is to create pressure on g7 pawn. }
11... d5 12. exd6 Bxd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Rg3 Kf8
{ This is a serious positional mistake. The black rooks will remain disconnected for a long time.   14...O-O  The only move for Black.  15.Qe3  Kh8  16.O-O-O  White keeps good attacking chances on the kingside. }
15. O-O-O Qf4+ 16. Kb1 Rd8 17. Re1
{ White is planning Be4 followed by Bxc6 and Ne5 which will create pressure on the f7 pawn. }
17... Rd5 18. Rh3
{ Defending the pawn and preparing to kick out the black queen. White is completely winning here. Black is playing without the rook, and his king is weak. }
18... Ke7 19. Rh4 Qf6 20. g3 { Securing the rook and preparing Rf4. } 20... Kd8
21. Be4 Rd6 22. Bxc6
{ The simplest winning plan. The White knight now becomes dominant. } 22...
Bxc6 23. Ne5 Rf8 24. Rf4 Qe7 25. Nxc6+ Rxc6 26. Qe5
{ Double attack, both king and pawn on g7 are in trouble. } 26... Rd6 27. Qxg7
f5 28. Qe5 Kc8 29. b3
{ The rest is easy for White with a pawn up since he has a safer king and better pawn structure. }
29... Qd7 30. g4 Kb7 31. Kb2 Kc6 32. Rf3 Qf7 33. Qf4 Qf6 34. gxf5 exf5 35. Rfe3
Rf7 36. Qf3+ Kb5 37. Qe2+ Kc6 38. Qa6 Rc7 39. Re8 Qf7 40. Rb8 c4 41. Qa4+ Kd5
42. Qb5+ *

