1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 Nxd5 8.
exd5 Nb8 9. a4 Be7 10. Be2 O-O
{ So far we have been following the theoreticalchapter. } 11. O-O Nd7 12. Bd2
f5 13. a5 a6 14. Na3 e4 15. Nc4 Ne5 16. Nb6 Rb8 17. f4 exf3 18. Bxf3 g5
{ Too optimistic. A safer option for Black is  18...Bf6  19.c3  although White still looks preferable. }
19. c4
{ Black is pushing the kingside pawn, White is pushing the queenside pawns. }
19... f4 20. Bc3 { With the idea of playing c5. } 20... Bf5
{ 20...Bf6  21.c5!  quite typical positional pawn sacrifice. White gets the passed d-pawn, the d5 square and opens the diagonals for the bishop and the queen @@StartBracket@@a2-g8, and h1-a8@@EndBracket@@.  21...dxc5  22.d6  Nxf3+  23.gxf3  taking with the rook is also good.  23...Bxc3  24.bxc3  Be6  25.Re1  when White is strategically winning. The knight on b6 and the pawn on d6 fully dominate. }
21. c5 Nxf3+ { If Black rejects the pawn sacrifice, 22. c6 is coming. } 22.
Qxf3 dxc5 23. Rad1
{ The most natural move.  23.g4!  is a very powerful move. It kicks away Black's bishop from its ideal square on f5. After  23...Bg6   23...fxg3  24.Qxg3  is just game over for Black. White has too many threats.  24.Rad1!  Bd6  25.Rfe1  Black cannot defend against Re6. Nc4 is another huge threat.  25...c4  26.Re6  Qc7  27.Qh3  Rxg6 is undefendable threat.   23.Rae1  Bf6  24.h4  also looks promising. }
23... Bd6 24. h3
{ This spoils everything White has done so far.  24.Qh5  looks like a natural move to me.  24...Bg6  25.Qh3  Bf5  is replied by the typical  26.g4!  Bg6  27.Rfe1  f3  28.Re6  and now Rxg6 is a threat. Once the white rook gets to e6 Black's defences fall apart. }
24... Qe8 { Black got that one extra tempo which he needed. } 25. Nc4 Qg6
{ The rooks are connected, the bishops are safe, and the d6 square is under control. }
26. Nxd6 Qxd6 27. h4 gxh4 28. Qxf4 Qxf4 29. Rxf4 h5
{ The last precise move. It secures the g4 square. } 30. Re1 Bg4 31. Rf6 Rxf6
32. Bxf6 Kf7 33. Bxh4 Re8 34. Rf1+ Kg8 35. Rf6 Re2 36. Rg6+ Kf8 37. d6 Rd2 38.
Rg5 *

