g6 9. Nc3 Bg7 10. Rd1 O-O 11. Be3 Nbd7 12. Rac1 b6 13. f3 Bb7 14. Qf2 Rac8 15.
Bf1 Rfe8 16. b4 Qb8 17. Nb3 d5 18. exd5 exd5 19. c5
{ The game follows my recommendation in thecourse. It is instructive to see how White successfully converted his adavantage. }
19... bxc5 20. bxc5 Rcd8
{ Strange move to my eye. Black should keep control of the c-pawn.   20...Ne5  Seems like the most logical move for Black.  21.Bg5!?  White had a couple of interesting options. White immediately creates pressure on the d5 pawn.  21...h6  22.Bh4  Keeping the edge. }
21. Na5 Ba8 22. c6 { Of course. } 22... Ne5 23. Na4
{ With the idea of playing c7. The knights on the edge of the board are usually bad, but here they control important squares. }
23... Qb4 24. c7 Rc8 25. Nb6 Qxa5 { Black has picked up a knight. } 26. Bd2 Qa3
27. Nxc8 Rxc8 28. Qb6
{ Two pieces are usually stronger than a rook, but here White has a powerful passed pawn which changes the entire evaluation. }
28... Ne8 29. Bf4 { White pieces are too active. } 29... Nc6 30. Kh1
{ Securing the king before capturing on a6. } 30... Qa4 31. Bg3 Be5 32. Bxe5
Nxe5 { Black wants to play Rxc7. } 33. Re1 Nc4 34. Bxc4 dxc4 35. Qb8 Qd7 36.
Rcd1 { White finally wins material. } 36... Nxc7 37. Qxa8 Rxa8 38. Rxd7 Ne6 39.
Rc1
{ Extra exchange and active rooks are more than enough advantage for White to win the game. }
39... Rc8 40. Rd3 Rc5 41. Rdc3 Ra5 42. R1c2 Nd4 43. Rd2 Nb3 44. Rd8+ Kg7 45.
