1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. e5 Nd5 8.
Ne4 Qc7 9. f4 Qb6 10. c4 Ne3 11. Qd3 Bb4+ 12. Bd2 O-O 13. Rc1 a5 14. Bxb4 Qxb4+
15. Rc3 Nxf1 16. Rxf1 Qxb2 17. Rf2 Qa1+ 18. Qd1 Qxd1+ 19. Kxd1
{ The last moment which is mentioned in thecourse. White obviously has a nice positional compensation for the pawn thanks to the strong knight, the active rooks and the domination on the dark squares. }
19... Ba6
{ Black is trying to activate his bishop. However, this is a wrong square for the bishop. He should instead open the long diagonal @@StartBracket@@h1-a8@@EndBracket@@ even if it costs the pawn.   19...a4!?  Might be Black's best chance. He can continue with Ra5 and f6 or c5. }
20. Rd2 { Attacking the weak pawn. } 20... Rfd8 21. Kc1
{ Improving the king and controlling the squares on the b-file.   21.Nc5!?  Forcing the bishop back to c8 looks interesting. }
21... Kf8 22. Nd6
{ The knight on d6 paralyzes the black bishop. In general Black should aim to play c5 whenever possible with the idea of playing Rb8, followed by Bb7 activating the bishop. }
22... Rdb8 23. Ra3 Bc8 24. Rf2
{ Preparing for the opening of the f-file. Note how the White rooks easily participate on both sides of the board while the Black rooks are desperately passive. }
24... g6 25. g4 { Going for the f5. } 25... Rb4 26. f5 exf5 27. gxf5 Kg8 28. f6
{ Fixing weakness on f7. The Black king is also very weak. White is completely winning. }
28... Rab8 { Otherwise White plays Rb2. } 29. Rxa5 Rb1+ 30. Kd2
{ The pawn on a2 does the important job preventing checks on b3. } 30... h5 31.
Kc3 Bb7 32. Rd2 Rc1+ 33. Kd3 Rb1 34. Kc2 Re1 35. Ra7 Bc8 36. Rc7 Ba6 37. Rxd7
Rxe5 38. Rxf7 Re6 39. Ra7 Rd8 40. c5 *

