1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a3 Qc7 7. Be3 b5 8. Nxc6
Qxc6 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. Qd2 Rc8 { 10...Qc7  Is the critcal move. } 11. f3
{ And we transpose to theTaimanov's lines. } 11... Bc5 12. Bxc5 Qxc5 13. O-O-O
Nf6 14. Rhe1 { Developing the last piece. The threat is 15. e5. } 14... d6 15.
f4
{ 15.Bf1!?  Was my intial idea and the best move probably. After  15...Ke7!  I wasn't sure exactly what to do.  16.Re3!?  The rook will be very useful on the third rank, where it defends and attacks simultaneusly.  16...Rhd8  17.Rd3  Ne8  This knight is usually happier on d7 from where it can jump to e5 and c4 afterwards.  18.Kb1  With the plan to push kingside pawns. White has advantage since Black doesn't have a good way to attack on the quuenside. }
15... O-O 16. e5 { Concrete play. } 16... dxe5 17. fxe5 Ng4
{ 17...Nd5  18.Ne4  Qc7  19.Nd6  Is better for White. } 18. Qf4
{ Intentionally allowing Nf2. } 18... Nf2 19. Bxh7+
{ That was my idea. The knight has no squares from f2. } 19... Kxh7 20. Rd2 f6
{ 20...f5!  Was practically the only move for Black.  21.Qh4+  Kg8  22.Qxf2  Qxf2  23.Rxf2  g5!  Not allowing h4 secures Black equal chances and decent compensation for the pawn. }
21. Rxf2
{ 21.Qg3!!  Was even stronger. White has another threat, Rd7 and Black has no time to escape with the knight which means White will be able to recapture on f2 with the rook keeping the attacking chances. }
21... fxe5 22. Qh4+ Kg8 23. Rfe2
{ Material is equal but Black pawns are weak. } 23... Qc4
{ The endgame is bad for Black. } 24. Qxc4 Rxc4 25. g3
{ Securing the pawn and the f4 square. } 25... Rf6 26. Rxe5 Kf7 27. Nd1
{ Improving the knight. } 27... Rd4 28. Rc5 { Now improving the rook. } 28...
Kg6 29. Rc7 Re4 30. Kd2 { If White king reaches the e-file the rest is easy. }
30... e5 31. Rxe4 Bxe4 32. Ke3 Bg2 33. Nf2 e4
{ Black has a concrete idea in his mind. } 34. Re7 Rf3+ 35. Ke2 Kf6 36. Re8 Kf7
37. Re5 Bf1+ 38. Ke1 { 38.Kxf1  e3  Is something what Black wants. } 38... e3
39. Ng4 e2 40. Re3 { 40.Rxb5  Is the simplest. } 40... Rf5 41. Rf3
{ Forcing the trade of the rooks. } 41... Rxf3 42. Ne5+ Ke6 43. Nxf3 Kd5 44.
Nd2 { The e2 pawn will fall and White will have 2 extra pawns. } 44... Bh3 45.
Kxe2 Bf5 46. c3 g5 47. h4 gxh4 48. gxh4 Ke5 49. Ke3 Bg6 50. b3 Bf7 51. c4 bxc4
52. bxc4 Bh5 53. Nf3+ Kd6 54. Ke4 Kc5 55. Ne5 Be2 56. Ke3 Bh5 57. Kd3 Bd1 58.
