1. e4
{ This is the game which shows all the merits of plaing the Dragon with the White pieces. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2
O-O 9. O-O-O d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 Qb6 14. Na4
Qc7 15. Bc4 Rd8 16. Nc5 Bf5 17. Bb3 Nf4 18. Qf2 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Rd8 20. Re1 Nd5
21. g3 h5 22. a3
{ The last move mentioned in ourcourse. White enjoys small but stable advantage thanks to the better pawn structure on the queenside. }
22... Qb6 23. Qd4 { Centralization. } 23... Nf6 24. Qc3 Qc7
{ 24...Nd5?  Loses pawn.  25.Bxd5  Rxd5  26.Rxe7  Because of the back rank issues Balck can't take the knight. }
25. Qe5 { Forcing trade of the queens. } 25... Qxe5 26. Rxe5 Kf8 27. Nb7
{ White already has a big advantage, one would say close to winning. } 27...
Rc8 28. Ra5 { Attacking the weak pawn. } 28... Rc7 29. Nc5 Bc8 30. Kd2
{ Improving the king, White plays by the typical endgame principles. } 30... e6
{ Black covers the f7 square so he can improve his king, but the bishop on c8 is not happy with the last move. }
31. c4 { Time to push the queenside pawns. } 31... Ke7 32. Bc2 Nd7 33. Nxd7
{ White doesn't mind to trade pair of the knights. } 33... Bxd7 34. b4 Kd6 35.
f4 { Stopping e5. White is positionally winning. } 35... Be8 36. Kc3 f6 37. h4
e5 38. fxe5+ fxe5 39. Be4 { All black pawns are weak! } 39... Bf7 40. Ra6 Be8
41. a4 Ke7 42. Kd3 Rd7+ 43. Ke3 Rc7 44. b5 { White is slowly making progress. }
44... Kd6 45. bxc6
{ 45.Bxc6!  Bxc6  46.a5!  Important nuance before going into the pawn endgame.  46...Kc5  47.Rxc6+  Rxc6  48.bxc6  Kxc6  49.Ke4  Wins. }
45... Kc5 46. Ra5+ Kxc4 47. Bd5+ Kb4 48. Rb5+ Kxa4 49. Rb7
{ Black has collected some pawns but his king is out of play. } 49... Rc8 50.
c7 Bd7 51. Ke4 Re8 52. Rb8 Bf5+ 53. Ke3 Rc8 54. Rxc8 Bxc8 55. Ke4 Kb5 56. Kxe5
Kb6 57. Kd6 a5 58. Bc6 Ka7 59. Ke7 Kb6 60. Kd8 Ba6 61. Be8
{ Quite instructive game from White. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Swiercz, D. vs. Naroditsky, D. - USA-ch, 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2
O-O 9. O-O-O d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4 e5 13. Bc5 Re8 14. Ne4 Qc7
{ Following the current state of the theory. } 15. h4 f5 16. Nd6 Rd8 17. Nxc8
Raxc8 18. h5 Nb6 19. Bxb6 Rxd2 20. Bc4+ Kf8 21. Bxc7 Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 Rxc7 23.
hxg6 Bh6+ 24. Kb1 hxg6 25. Rd6 Kg7
{ Modern theory develops fast. Up to here nowadays it is allwell known. I brieflly mentioned couple of interesting moves White can try to test out the Black. }
26. b4
{ Creating a rouite for the White king and advancing the pawn majority. } 26...
Bf4
{ I'm not sure if this is the best for Black.  Black can create counterplay with his e-pawn.   26...e4!?  27.fxe4  fxe4  28.Kb2  Bf4  29.Re6  e3  White is still better, but objectively Black should hold. }
27. Re6 { Stopping e4. } 27... Rb7 28. a3 a5 29. Kb2 axb4 30. a4
{ White has created a passed pawn for the price of his own pawn. } 30... Ra7
31. Kb3 c5
{ The last couple of moves starting from 27...Rb7 were forced. here White has couple of moves available. }
32. Bb5 { Defends pawn on a4 and prepares for the king infiltration. } 32...
Kf7
{ Not giving White time to improve the king. If rook moves from the e-file Black will create a passed e-pawn. }
33. Bc4 Kg7 34. Bd3 Bg3
{ Funnily enough this move is a novelty!  Earliear in the same year Black has played   34...Kf7  35.Rb6  Ra5  36.Bc4+  Kg7  37.Bb5  e4  38.fxe4  fxe4  39.Re6  e3  40.Kc4  Ra7  41.Kxc5  Rc7+  42.Bc6  Kf7  43.Re4  g5  44.a5  Re7  45.Rxe7+  Kxe7  46.Bf3  Kd7?   46...Bd6+!  Was still drawing.  47.Kb6  Be5!  48.Kb5  Bc3  49.a6  Bd4  50.Kxb4  Kd6  51.Kc4  Ba7  52.Kd3  Ke5  I don't see a way for White to make a progress.  47.Kxb4  e2  48.Bxe2  White eventually won in game Kollars - Blomqvist, Stavanger 2021. }
35. Rc6 Ra5
{ 35...Bf2  Is stronger for Black.  36.g4  c4+!  Excellent example of the deflection.  37.Bxc4  e4! }
36. Bb5 Ra7
{ This is a mistake, Black needs to keep his queenside pawns alive.   36...Bf2  Is Black's only chance, but he probably didn't like  37.Re6  Bd4  38.Be8  When White wins the pawn back.  38...g5!  39.Bg6  g4  40.Bxf5  gxf3  41.gxf3  Kf7  This position should be defendable for Black. }
37. Rxc5 e4 38. fxe4 fxe4 39. Rc6
{ White bishop on b5 stops the e-pawn White no one can stop white kingside pawns. }
39... Rc7 40. Kxb4 Rxc6 41. Bxc6 e3 42. Bf3
{ Unlike in the aline arising after 34...Kf7 in the game Kollars - Blomqvist here Black king is too far and White c-pawn will cross the critical point. }
42... Kf6 43. a5 Ke7 44. Kc5 Kd7 45. a6 Kc7 46. Kd5 Kb6 47. Be2 Bh4 48. Ke6 Bd8
49. Kf7 g5 50. Kg6 Ka7 51. Kf5 Be7 52. Ke4 Bc5 53. Kd5 Bb6 54. c4 Kb8 55. c5
Ba7 56. Kd6 Kc8 57. Bg4+ Kd8 58. c6 Bb8+ 59. c7+ *

