[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Saric, Ivan vs. Shirov, Alexei - EU-chT, 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3
Be7 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O a5 11. a4 Nc6 12. Kb1 Nb4 13. g4 Rc8 14. g5 Nd7
{ Black probably has to go for the  14...Nh5  to stop White from playing  15.f4  . }
15. f4
{ This forces Black to capture on f4 and lose control of the d4 square which comese quite handy for the White pieces, especially the passive knight from b3. }
15... exf4 16. Bxf4 { So far we have been following the theoreticalchapter. }
16... Bxb3
{ Not allowing Nd4, but at the same time losing attacking motifs on the queenside and weakning his own king and the light squares. White light-sqaured bishop turns into the monster now. }
17. cxb3 Ne5 18. h4 f6 { Trying to activate his rook. } 19. Bh3 Rc6 20. Qe2
{ Stopping Nd3 ideas and preparing for the Qh5 in some lines. } 20... Qe8 21.
Bxe5
{ The right exchange. White transforms his bishop pair advantage into the advantage of the stronger bishop in the position with the opposite coloured bishops. There is a rule which goes something along the lines: The side which is attacking in the positions with the opposite coloured bishops usually attacks with an extra piece. }
21... fxe5 { 21...dxe5  22.Bd7  Wins exchange. } 22. Rhf1
{ Taking the f-file under control. Note how Black rook fro mc6 can't get back into the action to help in defense. }
22... Kh8 23. Rxf8+ Qxf8 24. Rf1 Qd8 25. Qf3
{ I wanted to place my queen on f7.   25.Rf7  Rc7  26.Qh5  Was also strong. }
25... g6 26. Be6 Rc7 27. Nb5 Rc2 28. h5
{ I had calculated everthing till the end. } 28... Bxg5 29. hxg6 Bf4 30. Qh5
Rh2 31. g7+ Kxg7 32. Rg1+ Kh8 33. Nxd6 { And Black gets checkmated. } *

